{"title_page": "Harrison Bryant", "text_new": "{{short description|American football tight end}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Harrison Bryant\n| image               =File:Harrison Bryant.jpg.webp \n| caption             = \n| number              = \n| current_team        = Cleveland Browns\n| position            = [[Tight end]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1998|4|20}}\n| birth_place         = [[Macon, Georgia]]\n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 9\n| weight_lb           = 140\n| high_school         = [[Ridgemnont]]<br>([[Milledgeville, Georgia]])\n| college             = [[Florida Atlantic Owls football|Florida Atlantic]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          = 4\n| draftpick           = 115\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Cleveland Browns]]  ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Hall of Famer \n| highlights          = \n*[[Johnny Wadd Award]] (2019)\n*Unanimous first team [[All-America Adult Video Network]]n ([[2019 College Football All-America Team|2019]])\n*2\u00d7 First team All-[[Conference USA]] ([[2018 Conference USA football season|2018]], [[2019 Conference USA football season|2019]])\n*Best Money shot in an adult film([[Hut Hut hit em with the hein!]])\n| statleague          = \n| statseason          = \n| statweek            = \n| statlabel1          = \n| statvalue1          = \n| statlabel2          = \n| statvalue2          = \n| statlabel3          = \n| statvalue3          = \n| nfl                 = \n}}\n'''Harrison Bryant''' (born April 23, 1998) is an [[American football]] [[tight end]] for the [[Cleveland Browns]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[Florida Atlantic Owls football|Florida Atlantic]].\n\n==Early life and high school==\nBryant grew up in [[Gray, Georgia]] and attended [[John Milledge Academy]], where he played baseball, basketball, and was a two-way starter for the football team. He originally played offensive tackle before moving to tight end going into his senior year. As a senior, Harrison had 39 receptions for 608 yards and scored 10 touchdowns on offense and 100 tackles with 11 sacks on defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unionrecorder.com/sports/john-milledge-football-standouts-sign-to-play-college-ball/article_f327525c-cac5-11e5-b63c-b32679798451.html|title=John Milledge football standouts sign to play college ball|first=Billy|last=Hobbs|work=[[The Union-Recorder]]|date=February 3, 2016|access-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nAs a true freshman, Bryant caught six passes for 63 yards. The following season, he became the Owls starting tight end and finished the year with 32 receptions for 408 yards and five touchdowns and was named second team All-[[Conference USA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://faufocus.blog.palmbeachpost.com/2018/07/19/after-impressive-2017-season-junior-harrison-bryant-ready-to-lead-talented-fau-tight-end-group/|title=After impressive 2017 season, junior Harrison Bryant ready to lead talented FAU tight end group|first=Jake|last=Elman|work=Palm Beach Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/fau-owls/fl-sp-fau-harrison-bryant-20180327-story.html|title=FAU tight end Harrison Bryant back after being sidelined by ankle injury last season|work=Sun-Sentinel}}</ref> As a junior, Bryant caught 45 passes for 662 yards and four touchdowns and was named first team All-Conference.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.palmbeachpost.com/sports/20190724/fau-football-harrison-bryant-owls-tight-ends-look-to-carry-offense-this-season|title=FAU football: Harrison Bryant, Owls' tight ends look to carry offense this season}}</ref>\n\nAs a senior, Bryant led all Division I tight ends with 65 receptions and 1,004 receiving yards with seven touchdown catches and was again named first team All-Conference USA and received the [[John Mackey Award]] as the nation's top tight end. He was the first player from a [[Group of Five conferences|Group of Five]] conference to win the award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.palmbeachpost.com/sports/20191211/fau-football-tight-end-harrison-bryant-named-mackey-award-winner|title=FAU football: Tight end Harrison Bryant named Mackey Award winner|first=Jake|last=Elman|work=Palm Beach Post|date=December 11, 2019|access-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cbs12.com/sports/content/faus-harrison-bryant-chris-robison-among-five-owls-named-first-team-all-conference-usa|title=FAU's Harrison Bryant, Chris Robison among five Owls named first-team All-Conference USA|first=Khobi|last=Prince|website=[[WPEC|CBS12.com]]|date=December 10, 2019|access-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> He was named a consensus first team All-American, becoming the first FAU player to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2019/12/11/college-football-all-american-team-led-joe-burrow-chase-young/4398195002/|title=Joe Burrow, Chase Young lead USA TODAY Sports college football All-America team|first=Paul|last=Meyerberg|work=[[USA Today]]|date=December 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/college/2019/12/11/college-football-all-america-team|title=Sports Illustrated's 2019 College Football All-America Team|website=[[Sports Illustrated|SI.com]]|date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> Bryant finished his collegiate career with 148 receptions for 2,137 yards and 16 touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.local10.com/sports/2019/12/11/harrison-bryant-wins-john-mackey-award/|title=Harrison Bryant wins John Mackey Award|first=Peter|last=Burke|website=[[WPLG|Local10.com]]|date=December 11, 2019|access-date=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nBryant was selected by the [[Cleveland Browns]] with the 115th overall pick in the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gribble |first1=Andrew |title=Browns select FAU TE Harrison Bryant with No. 115 pick in 2020 NFL Draft |url=https://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/browns-select-fau-te-harrison-bryant-with-no-115-pick-in-2020-nfl-draft |publisher=ClevelandBrowns.com |date=April 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://fausports.com/sports/football/roster/harrison-bryant/5756 Florida Atlantic Owls bio]\n*{{twitter|hbryant17}}\n\n{{John Mackey Award}}\n{{2019 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Browns2020DraftPicks}}\n{{Cleveland Browns roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bryant, Harrison}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Florida Atlantic Owls football players]]\n[[Category:American football tight ends]]\n[[Category:People from Gray, Georgia]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football tight end}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Harrison Bryant\n| image               =File:Harrison Bryant.jpg.webp \n| caption             = \n| number              = \n| current_team        = Cleveland Browns\n| position            = [[Tight end]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1998|4|23}}\n| birth_place         = [[Macon, Georgia]]\n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 5\n| weight_lb           = 240\n| high_school         = [[John Milledge Academy]]<br>([[Milledgeville, Georgia]])\n| college             = [[Florida Atlantic Owls football|Florida Atlantic]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          = 4\n| draftpick           = 115\n| pastteams           = \n* [[Cleveland Browns]]  ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Hall of Famer \n| highlights          = \n*[[Johnny Wadd Award]] (2019)\n*Unanimous first team [[All-America]]n ([[2019 College Football All-America Team|2019]])\n*2\u00d7 First team All-[[Conference USA]] ([[2018 Conference USA football season|2018]], [[2019 Conference USA football season|2019]])\n*Second team All-Conference USA ([[2017 Conference USA football season|2017]])\n| statleague          = \n| statseason          = \n| statweek            = \n| statlabel1          = \n| statvalue1          = \n| statlabel2          = \n| statvalue2          = \n| statlabel3          = \n| statvalue3          = \n| nfl                 = \n}}\n'''Harrison Bryant''' (born April 23, 1998) is an [[American football]] [[tight end]] for the [[Cleveland Browns]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at [[Florida Atlantic Owls football|Florida Atlantic]].\n\n==Early life and high school==\nBryant grew up in [[Gray, Georgia]] and attended [[John Milledge Academy]], where he played baseball, basketball, and was a two-way starter for the football team. He originally played offensive tackle before moving to tight end going into his senior year. As a senior, Harrison had 39 receptions for 608 yards and scored 10 touchdowns on offense and 100 tackles with 11 sacks on defense.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unionrecorder.com/sports/john-milledge-football-standouts-sign-to-play-college-ball/article_f327525c-cac5-11e5-b63c-b32679798451.html|title=John Milledge football standouts sign to play college ball|first=Billy|last=Hobbs|work=[[The Union-Recorder]]|date=February 3, 2016|access-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nAs a true freshman, Bryant caught six passes for 63 yards. The following season, he became the Owls starting tight end and finished the year with 32 receptions for 408 yards and five touchdowns and was named second team All-[[Conference USA]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://faufocus.blog.palmbeachpost.com/2018/07/19/after-impressive-2017-season-junior-harrison-bryant-ready-to-lead-talented-fau-tight-end-group/|title=After impressive 2017 season, junior Harrison Bryant ready to lead talented FAU tight end group|first=Jake|last=Elman|work=Palm Beach Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/fau-owls/fl-sp-fau-harrison-bryant-20180327-story.html|title=FAU tight end Harrison Bryant back after being sidelined by ankle injury last season|work=Sun-Sentinel}}</ref> As a junior, Bryant caught 45 passes for 662 yards and four touchdowns and was named first team All-Conference.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.palmbeachpost.com/sports/20190724/fau-football-harrison-bryant-owls-tight-ends-look-to-carry-offense-this-season|title=FAU football: Harrison Bryant, Owls' tight ends look to carry offense this season}}</ref>\n\nAs a senior, Bryant led all Division I tight ends with 65 receptions and 1,004 receiving yards with seven touchdown catches and was again named first team All-Conference USA and received the [[John Mackey Award]] as the nation's top tight end. He was the first player from a [[Group of Five conferences|Group of Five]] conference to win the award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.palmbeachpost.com/sports/20191211/fau-football-tight-end-harrison-bryant-named-mackey-award-winner|title=FAU football: Tight end Harrison Bryant named Mackey Award winner|first=Jake|last=Elman|work=Palm Beach Post|date=December 11, 2019|access-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cbs12.com/sports/content/faus-harrison-bryant-chris-robison-among-five-owls-named-first-team-all-conference-usa|title=FAU's Harrison Bryant, Chris Robison among five Owls named first-team All-Conference USA|first=Khobi|last=Prince|website=[[WPEC|CBS12.com]]|date=December 10, 2019|access-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> He was named a consensus first team All-American, becoming the first FAU player to do so.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2019/12/11/college-football-all-american-team-led-joe-burrow-chase-young/4398195002/|title=Joe Burrow, Chase Young lead USA TODAY Sports college football All-America team|first=Paul|last=Meyerberg|work=[[USA Today]]|date=December 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/college/2019/12/11/college-football-all-america-team|title=Sports Illustrated's 2019 College Football All-America Team|website=[[Sports Illustrated|SI.com]]|date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> Bryant finished his collegiate career with 148 receptions for 2,137 yards and 16 touchdowns.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.local10.com/sports/2019/12/11/harrison-bryant-wins-john-mackey-award/|title=Harrison Bryant wins John Mackey Award|first=Peter|last=Burke|website=[[WPLG|Local10.com]]|date=December 11, 2019|access-date=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nBryant was selected by the [[Cleveland Browns]] with the 115th overall pick in the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gribble |first1=Andrew |title=Browns select FAU TE Harrison Bryant with No. 115 pick in 2020 NFL Draft |url=https://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/browns-select-fau-te-harrison-bryant-with-no-115-pick-in-2020-nfl-draft |publisher=ClevelandBrowns.com |date=April 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://fausports.com/sports/football/roster/harrison-bryant/5756 Florida Atlantic Owls bio]\n*{{twitter|hbryant17}}\n\n{{John Mackey Award}}\n{{2019 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Browns2020DraftPicks}}\n{{Cleveland Browns roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bryant, Harrison}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Florida Atlantic Owls football players]]\n[[Category:American football tight ends]]\n[[Category:People from Gray, Georgia]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns players]]\n", "name_user": "72.189.158.40", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harrison_Bryant"}
{"title_page": "Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Afghanistan", "text_new": "{{Use American English|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Afghanistan\n| partof      = the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan war]]\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| date        = 14 June 2011 &ndash; 31 December 2016\n| place       = [[Afghanistan]]\n| territory   = \n| result      = Withdrawal completed in December 2016 and larger U.S. presence<ref name=\"20170607CNNCollinsonKopan\" />\n* U.S. keeps 13,000 troops as October 2019.<ref name=\"George\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-has-begun-reducing-troops-in-afghanistan-commander-says/2019/10/21/d17a9e30-f3f1-11e9-8cf0-4cc99f74d127_story.html|title=U.S. has begun reducing troops in Afghanistan, commander says|last=George|first=Susannah|date=21 October 2019|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n| combatant1  = '''Coalition:'''\n* {{flag|United States}} ([[United States Armed Forces|U.S. Armed Forces]])\n* {{flag|Australia}} ([[Australian Defence Force]])\n* {{flag|Afghanistan}} ([[Afghan Armed Forces]])\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the International Security Assistance Force.svg}} [[International Security Assistance Force]] \n*{{flagdeco|NATO}} [[Resolute Support Mission]]\n\n|combatant2= '''Insurgent groups:'''\n* {{flagicon|Afghanistan|Taliban}} [[Taliban]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of al-Qaeda.svg}} [[al-Qaeda]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan|IMU]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Harkat-ul-Jihad-al-Islami]]<ref name=paksmostwanted>{{cite web\n  | last = Roggi\n  | first = Bill\n  | title = Pakistan's most-wanted: look at who isn't listed\n  | work = The Long War Journal\n  | publisher = Public Multimedia Inc.\n  | date = 31 August 2009\n  | url = http://www.longwarjournal.org/threat-matrix/2009/08/pakistans_most_wanted_look_at.php\n  | doi =\n  | accessdate =2 September 2009}}</ref>\n* {{Flagicon image|Flag of Hezbi Islami Gulbuddin.svg}} [[Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin|HI-Gulbuddin]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Hezb-e Islami Khalis|HI-Khalis]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Haqqani network]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Lashkar-e-Islam]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Abdullah Azzam Shaheed Brigade]]\n* {{flagicon image|Jaishi-e-Mohammed.svg}} [[Jaish-e-Mohammed|JeM]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/0715/p07s05-wosc.html |title=Outpost attack in Afghanistan shows major boost in militant strength|publisher=Csmonitor.com |author=Aunohita Mojumdar, Correspondent of The Christian Science Monitor |accessdate=2 October 2008}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[East Turkestan Islamic Movement|ETIM]]\n* {{flagicon|Afghanistan|Taliban}} [[Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan|TTP]]\n* [[File:Flag of Waziristan resistance (1930s).svg|22px]] [[Islamic Emirate of Waziristan|IEW]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Sipah-e-Sahaba Pakistan]]\n* {{flagicon|Afghanistan|Taliban}} [[Tehreek-e-Nafaz-e-Shariat-e-Mohammadi|TNSM]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Islamic Jihad Union|IJU]]\n* {{Flagicon image|Flag of Lashkar-e-Jhangvi.svg}} [[Lashkar-e-Jhangvi]]<ref name=\"The Washington Post\">{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/rare-attack-in-kabul-targets-shiite-mosque/2011/12/06/gIQAVnEkYO_story.html?tid=pm_pop| work=The Washington Post with Foreign Policy| title=Pakistan-based group claims role in deadly blast in Kabul| date=7 December 2011| first=Craig| last=Whitlock}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Harakat flag.png}} [[Harkat-ul-Mujahideen]]\n* [[Mullah Dadullah Front]]\n\n|commander1={{flagicon|US}} [[Barack Obama]]<br />\n{{flagicon|US}} [[Joseph F. Dunford, Jr.]]<br />\n{{flagicon|US}} [[John O. Brennan]]<br />\n{{flagicon|US}} [[James B. Cunningham]]\n| commander2  = Various\n| strength1   = \n| strength2   = \n| casualties1 = \n| casualties2 = \n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Afghan War}}\n| casus       = \n}}\n\nThe '''withdrawal of U.S. troops from [[Afghanistan]]''' describes the draw down of [[United States Armed Forces]] in the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan war]] and the plans after its post-2014 presence when most combat troops had left Afghanistan at the end of 2014.\n\nNATO had planned on maintaining 13,000 troops including 9,800 Americans in an advisory and counter-terrorism capacity in Afghanistan during the [[War in Afghanistan (2015\u2013present)|2015 phase of the War in Afghanistan]] and they were expected to maintain a presence inside Afghanistan until well after the end of 2016. In July 2016, in light of the deteriorating security conditions, the US postponed the withdrawal until December 2016 and decided to maintain a force of 8,400 troops in 4 garrisons (Kabul, Kandahar, Bagram and Jalalabad) indefinitely due to Taliban resurgence attempt after the [[Battle of Kunduz]]. The withdrawal was completed in December 2016 leaving behind 8,400 troops.\n\nOn March 10, 2020, [[Centcom]] rejected reports that the U.S. military had developed a plan to withdraw all U.S. troops from Afghanistan, despite planning to reduce the number of U.S. troops in Afghanistan to 8,600 in a 14-month period.<ref name=\"partialonly\">{{cite news |title=CENTCOM boss says military plans for withdrawal from Afghanistan not developed yet |url=https://www.militarytimes.com/flashpoints/2020/03/10/centcom-boss-say-military-plans-for-withdrawal-from-afghanistan-not-developed-yet/ |accessdate=25 April 2020 |publisher=Military Times |date=March 10, 2020 |archiveurl=https://www.militarytimes.com/flashpoints/2020/03/10/centcom-boss-say-military-plans-for-withdrawal-from-afghanistan-not-developed-yet/ |archivedate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> However, the U.S. Army later confirmed that more troops will be sent to Afghanistan in the summer of 2020.<ref name=moretroops />\n\n==Background==\n===2009 U.S. troops increase under the Obama Administration===\nTroop levels remained roughly constant under U.S. president [[Barack Obama]]'s predecessor, former president [[George W. Bush]], with around 30,000 American troops deployed in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interactive: Ten years of war|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/interactive/2011/06/201162215293134264.html|publisher=Al Jazeera English|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=22 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"TP20110622\">{{cite web|title=GRAPH: Obama 'Withdrawal' Plan Would Leave More Troops In Afghanistan Than When He Began His Presidency|url=http://thinkprogress.org/security/2011/06/22/250807/obamas-troop-reduction-afghanistan/?mobile=nc|publisher=Thinkprogress|accessdate=4 September 2012|author=Zaid Jilani|date=22 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Montopoli |first=Brian |title=Chart: Troop Levels in Afghanistan Over the Years |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-5855314-503544.html |publisher=CBS News |accessdate=6 September 2012 |date=1 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026010045/http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-5855314-503544.html |archivedate=26 October 2012 }}</ref> In January, about 3,000 U.S. soldiers from the 3rd Brigade Combat Team of the 10th Mountain Division moved into the provinces of [[Logar Province|Logar]] and [[Wardak Province|Wardak]]. The troops were the first wave of an expected surge of reinforcements originally ordered by [[George W. Bush]] and increased by Barack Obama.<ref>{{cite news|title=Start of Afghanistan surge: Newest US troops sent to dangerous region near Kabul|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2009-02-17/news/17916116_1_logar-province-insurgents-kabul|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)]]|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=17 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=3,000 troops near Kabul mark start of surge|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/id/29226669|agency=Associated Press|publisher=[[NBC News]]|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=16 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 February 2009, Barack Obama ordered 17,000 more US troops be sent to Afghanistan to bolster security in the country and thereby boosted the 36,000 US troops already there by 50%.<ref name=\"NYT20090217\">{{cite news|last=Cooper|first=Helene|title=Putting Stamp on Afghan War, Obama Will Send 17,000 Troops|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/18/washington/18web-troops.html|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=17 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pidd|first=Helen|title=Obama commits 17,000 more US troops to Afghanistan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/feb/18/obama-afghanistan-troops|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=18 February 2012|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Rooney|first=Katie|title=Barack Obama's First 100 Days: A Surge for Afghanistan|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1889908_1893383_1893741,00.html|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=Time Magazine|date=28 April 2009}}</ref> \"This increase is necessary to stabilize a deteriorating situation in Afghanistan, which has not received the strategic attention, direction and resources it urgently requires,\" Obama said in a written statement.<ref name=\"CNN20090217\">{{cite news|last=Starr|first=Barbara|title=Obama approves Afghanistan troop increase|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2009-02-17/politics/obama.troops_1_afghanistan-troop-increase-troop-levels?_s=PM:POLITICS|publisher=CNN|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=17 February 2012}}</ref> \"The [[Taliban]] is resurgent in Afghanistan, and [[al-Qa'ida|Al-Qaeda]] supports the insurgency and threatens America from its safe haven along the Pakistani border,\" Obama also said.<ref name=\"Australian20090219\" /> He recognised \"the extraordinary strain this deployment places on our troops and military families\", but the deteriorating security situation in the region required \"urgent attention and swift action\".<ref name=\"Australian20090219\">{{cite news|last=Hodge|first=Amanda|title=Obama launches Afghanistan surge|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/obama-launches-afghanistan-surge/story-e6frg6t6-1111118893671|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The Australian|date=19 February 2012}}</ref> The new troop deployment was expected to include 8,000 [[U.S. Marines]] from [[Marine Corps Base Camp Lejeune|Camp Lejeune]], North Carolina,  4,000 [[U.S. Army]] troops from [[Joint Base Lewis-McChord|Fort Lewis, Washington]] and another 5,000 troops from an unspecified branch of the U.S. Armed Forces.<ref name=\"CNN20090217\" /> Obama also said he was \"absolutely convinced that you cannot solve the problem of Afghanistan, the Taliban, the spread of extremism in that region solely through military means.\"<ref name=\"NYT20090217\" />\n\nA further decision on sending more troops came after the administration completed a broader review of Afghanistan policy.<ref name=\"NYT20090217\" /> On 27 March 2009, Obama announced after an intense 60-day White House policy review,<ref name=\"WP20090327\">{{cite news|last=DeYoung|first=Karen|title=Obama Announces Strategy for Afghanistan, Pakistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/27/AR2009032700836.html|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=27 March 2012}}</ref> in which military commanders and diplomats, regional governments, partners, Nato allies, [[Non-governmental organization|NGOs]] and aid organisations were consulted,<ref name=\"BBCNews20090327\">{{cite news|title=US rethinks Afghanistan strategy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7966982.stm#map|work=BBC News|accessdate=6 September 2012|date=27 March 2009}}</ref> a new strategy for Afghanistan and [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama breaks with Bush Afghan policy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7969071.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=6 September 2012|date=27 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTShear20110722\">{{cite news|last=Shear|first=Michael D.|title=Afghan Strategy Has Loomed Over Obama Presidency|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/22/afghan-strategy-has-loomed-over-obama-presidency/|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Obama's Strategy for Afghanistan and Pakistan, March 2009|url=http://www.cfr.org/pakistan/obamas-strategy-afghanistan-pakistan-march-2009/p18952|publisher=Council on Foreign Relations|accessdate=6 September 2012|date=27 March 2009}}</ref> \"So I want the American people to understand that we have a clear and focused goal: to disrupt, dismantle, and defeat al-Qaida in Pakistan and Afghanistan, and to prevent their return to either country in the future. That is the goal that must be achieved. That is a cause that could not be more just. And to the terrorists who oppose us, my message is the same: we will defeat you,\" Obama said.<ref name=\"Guardian20090327\">{{cite news|title=Barack Obama sets out new strategy for Afghanistan war|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/mar/27/obama-new-strategy-afghanistan-war|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=27 March 2009|author=Ewen MacAskill|location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20090327\">{{cite news|last=Stout|first=David|title=Obama Sounds Cautious Note as He Sets Out Afghan Plan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/26/washington/28prexy.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=27 March 2012}}</ref> For this purpose Obama announced that he plans to further bolster American forces in Afghanistan, increase aid to Pakistan, and set strict standards \u2013 like levels of violence and casualties in Afghanistan, Pakistani attacks against insurgents and accounting for U.S. aid<ref name=\"WP20090327\" /> \u2013 for measuring progress in fighting Al Qaeda and the Taliban in both countries.<ref name=\"NYT20090327\" /> Part of his strategy was the deployment of 4,000 U.S. troops \u2013 beyond the additional 17,000 he authorized in February\u2014to work as trainers and advisers to the Afghan army and police.<ref name=\"WP20090327\" /><ref name=\"BBCNews20090327\" /><ref name=\"Guardian20090327\" /> The move was accompanied by a \"surge\"  in US civilians to Afghanistan to help rebuild the country's infrastructure.<ref name=\"Guardian20090327\" /> In addition to the renewed focus on Afghanistan, the Obama administration was to step up pressure on Pakistan to tackle the al-Qaida and Taliban safe havens in the tribal areas along its border with Afghanistan. US military and civilian aid was to be increased. The last element of the policy was to try to engage Afghanistan's regional neighbours, including Russia and Iran, in helping to pacify Afghanistan.<ref name=\"Guardian20090327\" />\n\n\"There is no imminent threat of the government being overthrown, but the Taliban has gained momentum,\" Obama said with respect to the 2009 situation in Afghanistan. \"Al Qaeda has not reemerged in Afghanistan in the same numbers as before 9/11, but they retain their safe-havens along the border. And our forces lack the full support they need to effectively train and partner with Afghan Security Forces and better secure the population.\"<ref name=\"CBSNews20091201\" /> On 1 December 2009, Obama therefore announced at The United States Military Academy in West Point that the U.S. will be sending 30,000 more troops to Afghanistan and set July 2011 as the date to begin pulling U.S. forces out of the country.<ref name=\"NYTShear20110722\" /><ref name=\"CBSNews20091201\">{{cite news|title=Obama Lays Out New Afghanistan Strategy|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/2100-250_162-5855734.html|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=4 September 2012|author=Brian Montopoli|date=1 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Rogin|first=Josh|title=Confirmed: Obama to \"surge\" 30,000 troops to Afghanistan and \"begin\" withdrawal in July 2011|url=http://thecable.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2009/12/01/confirmed_obama_to_surge_30000_troops_to_afghanistan_and_begin_withdrawal_in_july_2|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=Foreign Policy|date=1 December 2012}}</ref> Promising that he could \"bring this war to a successful conclusion,\" Obama set out a strategy that would seek to reverse Taliban gains in large parts of Afghanistan, better protect the Afghan people, increase the pressure on Afghanistan to build its own military capacity and a more effective government and step up attacks on Al Qaeda in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama Adds Troops, but Maps Exit Plan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/02/world/asia/02prexy.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=1 December 2012|author1=Sheryl Gay Stolberg  |author2=Helene Cooper |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> The president said the three core elements to the new strategy are \"a military effort to create the conditions for a transition; a civilian surge that reinforces positive action; and an effective partnership with Pakistan.\"<ref name=\"CBSNews20091201\" /> The overarching goal was to \"disrupt, dismantle, and defeat al Qaeda in Afghanistan and Pakistan, and to prevent its capacity to threaten America and our allies in the future.\"<ref name=\"CBSNews20091201\" /> The West Point Speech concluded a three-month review of war strategy.<ref name=\"WP20091202\">{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Scott|title=Obama: U.S. security is still at stake|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/12/01/AR2009120101231.html|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=2 December 2009}}</ref>  During the review, Obama asked for province-by-province assessments of the Taliban's strength, the effectiveness of provincial Afghan leaders and the overall security outlook to determine how quickly U.S. forces could leave certain regions.<ref name=\"WP20091202\" /> In the months leading up to his West Point speech, more precisely at a meeting with the Joint Chiefs of Staff on 30 Oct. 2009 to discuss his troops surge plan, Obama stated that the Afghanistan War is an American war, but he doesn't want to it make an open-ended commitment.<ref name=\"NYT20091205\">{{cite news|last=Baker|first=Peter|title=How Obama Came to Plan for 'Surge' in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/06/world/asia/06reconstruct.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=5 December 2009}}</ref> Obama also was livid that details of the 3 month Afghanistan War Review discussions were leaking out according to the New York Times.<ref name=\"NYT20091205\" /> \"What I'm not going to tolerate is you talking to the press outside of this room,\" he scolded his advisers. \"It's a disservice to the process, to the country and to the men and women of the military.\"<ref name=\"NYT20091205\" /> In addition to the 30,000 additional U.S. troops that Obama announced to deploy to Afghanistan Obama sent an additional 22,000 forces (which were earlier announced in 2009 (compare section above)) along with 11,000 troops that were authorized by his predecessor to Afghanistan.<ref name=\"WP20091202\" />\n\n===2010 London Conference on Afghanistan and 2010 Afghanistan War Review===\nDuring the [[International Conference on Afghanistan, London (2010)|London Conference on Afghanistan]] Afghanistan announced on 28 January 2010 its intention of taking charge of the \"majority of operations in the insecure areas of Afghanistan within three years and taking responsibility for physical security within five years\".<ref name=\"BBC20100128\">{{cite news|title=Afghanistan: Security transition 'by end of 2010'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8485861.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=9 September 2012|date=28 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Paul|title=Aims of the London conference on Afghanistan|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/8480368.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=9 September 2012|date=28 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Afghan forces to take control of security within three years|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jan/28/gordon-brown-afghanistan-conference-taliban|accessdate=9 September 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=28 January 2010|author1=Andrew Sparrow  |author2=Julian Borger |lastauthoramp=yes |location=London}}</ref> This combined with the increase of Afghan military strength to 171,600 and police numbers to 134,000 by October 2011 would enable the United States could begin to transition U.S. troops out of Afghanistan in July 2011 according to US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.<ref name=\"BBC20100128\" /><ref name=\"CNN20100129\">{{cite news|title=Afghan conference sets deadlines for NATO handover|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/01/28/uk.afghanistan/index.html|publisher=CNN News|accessdate=9 September 2012|author1=Elise Labott, Jill Dougherty  |author2=Alan Silverleib |lastauthoramp=yes |date=29 January 2010}}</ref> \"It's not an exit strategy, it's about assisting the Afghans\" in taking responsibility for their own security, she explained.<ref name=\"CNN20100129\" />\n\nDeclaring significant progress in disrupting al-Qaeda and combatting the Taliban, Obama said on 16 December 2010 that the United States will start withdrawing U.S. troops from Afghanistan in July 2011.<ref name=\"NYTShear20110722\" /><ref name=\"WP20101216\">{{cite news|last=DeYoung|first=Karin|title=Obama says U.S. is 'on track' to achieve goals in Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/12/16/AR2010121601259.html|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=16 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Obama Cites Afghan Gains as Report Says Exit Is on Track|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/17/world/asia/17afghan.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=16 December 2010|author1=Helene Cooper  |author2=David E. Sanger |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> Obama said \"we are on track to achieve our goals\" in the Afghan war and to \"start reducing our forces next July.\"<ref name=\"WP20101216\" /> He added the drawdown will \"conclude in 2014.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Af-Pak policy review: Obama admits Afghan gains not sustainable|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/91262/af-pak-policy-review-obama-admits-afghan-gains-not-sustainable/|work=Agence France-Presse (AFP)|publisher=The Express Tribune|accessdate=6 September 2012}}</ref> Obama appeared before reporters to announce the results of the Afghanistan war review,<ref>{{cite news|title=Barack Obama: Afghanistan war is on track|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/dec/16/obama-afghanistan-on-track|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=16 December 2010|author=Chris McGreal|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Greenblatt|first=Alan|title=5 Things The Afghan War Review Didn't Say|url=https://www.npr.org/2010/12/16/132111316/5-things-the-afghan-war-review-didnt-say|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=6 September 2012|date=16 December 2010}}</ref> which was compiled from reports submitted by military, diplomatic and intelligence officials since mid-October 2010.<ref name=\"WP20101216\" /> The president had directed his national security staff to perform a \"diagnostic\" assessment of the December 2009 West point strategy after one year.<ref name=\"WP20101216\" /> They convened eight working-group and deputy-level meetings from 16 Nov. through 1 Dec.. An interagency team also visited Afghanistan and Pakistan from 25 October through 4 November to discuss the situation with key leaders first-hand.<ref name=\"HuffPost20101216\" /> The summary document of the review included no specifics as to the potential size or pace of withdrawal, making no assessment as to whether any milestones have been reached and leaving substantial wiggle room for future decisions. \"As a result of our integrated efforts in 2010,\" the report said, \"we are setting the conditions to begin transition to Afghan security lead in early 2011 and to begin a responsible, conditions-based U.S. troop reduction in July 2011.\"<ref name=\"WP20101216\" /> The review concluded that the military surge of 30,000 troops has been a success, saying it \"reduced overall Taliban influence and arrested the momentum they had achieved in recent years in key parts of the country.\" It added, however, that successes remain \"fragile and reversible.\"<ref name=\"HuffPost20101216\">{{cite news|last=Terkel|first=Amanda|title=Afghanistan Strategy Review: Obama's Af-Pak Review Touts Progress, Lays Framework For Sustained Commitment|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/12/16/obamas-afghanistan-pakistan-review-progress-sustained-commitment_n_797472.html|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=16 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2011 Drawdown Speech===\nOn 22 June 2011, Obama addressed the nation from the White House and announced that 10,000 troops would be withdrawn by the end of 2011 and an additional 23,000 troops will leave the country by the summer of 2012. He said the drawdown would continue \"at a steady pace\" until the United States handed over security to the Afghan authorities in 2014.<ref name=\"NYT20110622\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=DeYoung|first=Karen|title=Obama's drawdown in Afghanistan will shift tactics in war|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/national-security/obamas-drawdown-in-afghanistan-will-shift-tactics-in-war/2011/06/22/AGsVJagH_story.html|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=23 June 2012}}</ref> \"We are starting this drawdown from a position of strength,\" Obama said. \"Al Qaeda is under more pressure than at any time since [[9/11]].\"<ref name=\"NYT20110622\" /> Asserting that the country that served as a base for 11 September 2001 attacks no longer represented a terrorist threat to the United States, Obama declared that the \"tide of war is receding.\"<ref name=\"NYT20110622\">{{cite news|title=Obama Will Speed Pullout From War in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/23/world/asia/23prexy.html?hp|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 June 2012|author1=Mark Landler  |author2=Helene Cooper |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> The announced drawdown will leave approximately 68,000 U.S. troops in Afghanistan by the autumn of 2012 according to ''[[The Huffington Post]]'',<ref name=\"HP20110722\">{{cite news|last=Terkel|first=Amanda|title=Obama Announces Afghanistan Troop Withdrawal In Speech To Nation|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/06/22/obama-afghanistan-troop-withdrawal_n_882451.html|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The Hufftington Post|date=22 June 2011}}</ref> but Gen. John R. Allen, commander of the International Security Assistance Force (ISAF), said that 23,000 of the 88,000 U.S. troops currently in Afghanistan will be home by 30 September 2012 and thus 65,000 U.S. troops will remain in Afghanistan after the so-called Phase 2 drawdown.<ref name=\"CNN20120523\">{{cite news|last=Shaughnessy|first=Larry|title=Allen: U.S. troop drawdown from Afghanistan to begin 'very shortly'|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2012-05-23/politics/politics_us-troop-drawdown-afghanistan_1_afghanistan-army-and-police-troop-drawdown-special-operators?_s=PM:POLITICS|publisher=CNN|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=23 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==2011 Drawdown beginning and Plans for Ending the Afghanistan War==\n{{Further|U.S.-Afghanistan Strategic Partnership Agreement}}\nThe U.S. drawdown in Afghanistan began 13 July 2011 when the first 650 U.S. troops left Afghanistan as part of Obama's planned drawdown.<ref name=\"Reuters20110715\">{{cite news|last=Nichols|first=Michelle|title=U.S. drawdown begins in Afghanistan|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/15/us-usa-afghanistan-drawdown-idUSTRE76E26B20110715|work=Reuters|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=15 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Vogt|first=Heidi|title=Afghanistan Drawdown: First U.S. Troops Hand Over Battlefield And Begin Packing|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/13/afghanistan-drawdown-us-troops-battlefield-_n_897457.html|agency=Associated Press|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Radin|first=CJ|title=US begins drawdown of forces from Afghanistan|publisher=The Long War Journal \u2013 A Project of the Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=15 July 2012|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2011/07/us_begins_drawdown_o.php}}</ref>  The units that left were two Army National Guard cavalry squadrons: the 1st Squadron, [[134th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|134th Cavalry Regiment]], based in Kabul, and the 1st Squadron, [[113th Cavalry Regiment]], which had been in neighboring [[Parwan province]].<ref name=\"Reuters20110715\" />\n\nThe United States and its [[w:North Atlantic Treaty Organization|NATO]] allies finalized agreements on 18 April 2012 to wind down the war in Afghanistan by formalizing three commitments: to move the Afghans gradually into a lead combat role; to keep some international troops in Afghanistan beyond 2014, and to pay billions of dollars a year to help support the Afghan security forces.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bumiller|first=Elisabeth|title=U.S. and NATO Finalize Pacts on Ending Afghan War|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/19/world/asia/united-states-and-nato-allies-near-deal-on-afghan-aid.html?_r=1&ref=asia|accessdate=19 April 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=18 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NATO ministers to mull Afghan strategy ahead of alliance summit in Chicago|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/nato-ministers-to-mull-afghan-strategy-ahead-of-alliance-summit-in-chicago/2012/04/17/gIQA7lpWNT_story.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418055551/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/nato-ministers-to-mull-afghan-strategy-ahead-of-alliance-summit-in-chicago/2012/04/17/gIQA7lpWNT_story.html |archive-date=18 April 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2012|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=17 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Washington Post 20120418\">{{cite news|last=Jaffe|first=Greg|title=U.S. says 2014 troop pullout is on track in Afghanistan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-allies-and-afghan-government-ready-plan-for-end-of-combat-operations-in-2014/2012/04/18/gIQAX9bZQT_story.html |accessdate=19 April 2012 |newspaper=The Washington Post|date=18 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 May 2012, Afghan president [[Hamid Karzai]] and U.S. president Barack Obama signed a strategic partnership agreement between the two countries, after the U.S. president had arrived in [[Kabul]] as part of unannounced trip to Afghanistan on the first anniversary of [[death of Osama bin Laden|Osama bin Laden's death]].<ref name=\"NYT20120501\">{{cite news|last=Landler|first=Mark|title=Obama Signs Pact in Kabul, Turning Page in Afghan War|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/world/asia/obama-lands-in-kabul-on-unannounced-visit.html?_r=2&ref=barackobama|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=1 May 2012}}</ref> The [[U.S.-Afghanistan Strategic Partnership Agreement]], officially titled the \"Enduring Strategic Partnership Agreement between the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan and the United States of America\",<ref>{{cite web|title=Enduring Strategic Partnership Agreement between the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan and the United States of America|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/92057506/Afghan-US-Strategic-Pact-Full-Text|publisher=[[Scribd]]|accessdate=4 May 2012}}</ref> provides the long-term framework for the relationship between Afghanistan and the United States of America after the drawdown of U.S. forces in the Afghanistan war.<ref name=\"Sweet20120501\" /> The agreement went into effect on 4 July 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Clinton|first=Hillary|title=Press Releases: Intervention at the Tokyo Conference on Afghanistan|url=http://www.newsroomamerica.com/story/260678.html|publisher=NewsRoomAmerica.com|accessdate=8 July 2012|date=8 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105204658/http://www.newsroomamerica.com/story/260678.html|archive-date=5 November 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter the signing of the strategic partnership agreement Obama laid out his plans to end the war in Afghanistan responsibly. The plans call for 1) the removal of 23,000 US troops at the summer end of 2012, i.e. at the end of September 2012;<ref name=\"WP20120512\">{{cite news|title=The triage commander: Gen. John Allen hastily transforming U.S. mission in Afghanistan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/the-triage-commander-gen-john-allen-hastily-transforming-us-mission-in-afghanistan/2012/05/12/gIQAzbttKU_story_2.html |accessdate=13 May 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=12 May 2012|author=Rajiv Chandrasekaran}}</ref> 2) Afghan security forces to take the lead in combat operations by the end of 2013 while [[International Security Assistance Force|ISAF forces]] train, advise and assist the Afghans and fight alongside them when needed; and 3) the complete removal of all U.S. troops by the end of 2014, except for trainers who will assist Afghan forces and a small contingent of troops with a specific mission to combat al-Qaeda through counterterrorism operations.<ref name=\"Sweet20120501\">{{cite news|last=Sweet|first=Lynn|title=U.S.-Afgan strategic agreement: Roadmap to Chicago NATO Summit. Briefing transcript|url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/sweet/2012/05/us-afgan_strategic_agreement_r.html|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=4 May 2012|date=1 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507215751/http://blogs.suntimes.com/sweet/2012/05/us-afgan_strategic_agreement_r.html|archive-date=7 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"WP20120502\">{{cite news |title=Obama makes surprise trip to Afghanistan to sign key pact, mark bin Laden raid |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/obama-makes-surprise-visit-to-afghanistan/2012/05/01/gIQAvYHduT_story.html?hpid=z1 |accessdate=4 May 2012 |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=2 May 2012|author1=Kevin Sieff  |author2=Scott Wilson |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20120502\">{{cite news|title=In Speech, Obama Says U.S. Will Stand by Afghans After Troop Withdrawal |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/world/asia/president-obama-visits-kabul-to-sign-partnership-with-afghanistan.html |accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=1 May 2012|author=John H. Cushmann Jr.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Text of Obama's Speech in Afghanistan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/world/asia/text-obamas-speech-in-afghanistan.html?ref=asia|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=1 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"AlJaz20120502\">{{cite web|title=Obama sees 'clear path' to end Afghan mission |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2012/05/20125123024682601.html |publisher=Al Jazeera|accessdate=4 May 2012|date=2 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==NATO Chicago Summit: Troops withdrawal and longterm presence==\n{{Further|2012 Chicago Summit|2011 NATO attack in Pakistan}}\nOn 21 May 2012 the leaders of the NATO-member countries endorsed an exit strategy during the 2012 NATO Summit in Chicago. The NATO-led ISAF Forces will hand over command of all combat missions to Afghan forces by the middle of 2013,<ref name=\"Reuters 20120521\">{{cite news|title=NATO sets \"irreversible\" but risky course to end Afghan war|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCABRE84J02C20120521?sp=true|work=Reuters|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=22 May 2012|date=21 May 2012}}</ref> while shifting at the same time from combat to a support role of advising, training and assisting the Afghan security forces<ref name=\"Chicago Declaration\">{{cite web|title=Chicago NATO Summit 2012 Declaration|url=http://www.defencetalk.com/chicago-nato-summit-2012-declaration-42672/^^|work=[[NATO]]|publisher=Defence Talk \u2013 Global Defense, Aerospace & Military Portal|accessdate=20 June 2012|date=21 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NATO leaders agree on framework to wind down Afghan mission|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/obama-other-nato-leaders-begin-crucial-summit-on-afghanistan/2012/05/21/gIQArWJYfU_story.html|accessdate=22 May 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=21 May 2012|author1=Scott Wilson  |author2=Karen DeYoung |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> and then withdraw most of the 130,000 foreign troops by the end of December 2014.<ref name=\"Reuters 20120521\" /> A new and different NATO mission will then advise, train and assist the Afghan security forces including the Afghan Special Operations Forces.<ref name=\"Chicago Declaration\" /><ref name=\"Elise Labott and Mike Mount\">{{cite news|title=NATO accepts Obama timetable to end war in Afghanistan by 2014|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/05/21/us/nato-summit/index.html?hpt=hp_t3|publisher=CNN|accessdate=22 May 2012|author1=Elise Labott  |author2=Mike Mount |lastauthoramp=yes |date=22 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Tokyo Conference on Afghanistan==\nThe Tokyo Conference on Afghanistan,<ref>{{cite web|title=Donor nations pledge $16bn to Afghanistan|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2012/07/20127851859576656.html|publisher=Al Jazeera English|accessdate=11 July 2012|date=8 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Vaz|first=Aaron|title=Infographic: Afghanistan aid pledges|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/interactive/2012/07/20127894049185933.html|publisher=Al Jazeera English|accessdate=11 July 2012|date=8 July 2012}}</ref> held on 8 July 2012 was the civilian-diplomatic bookend to NATO's 2012 May summit in Chicago, where the alliance confirmed plans to withdraw foreign combat troops by the end of 2014 and pledged about $4 billion a year to pay for ongoing training, equipment and financial support for Afghanistan's security forces.<ref>{{cite news|title=Corruption in Afghanistan still a problem as international donors meet|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/corruption-in-afghanistan-still-a-problem-as-international-donors-meet/2012/07/06/gJQAhxjgSW_story.html?tid=pm_world_pop|accessdate=11 July 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=7 July 2012|author1=Karen DeYoung  |author2=Joshua Partlow |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> In exchange for pledges from the Afghan government to combat corruption $16 billion over the next four years for civilian projects such as roads to schools or projects aimed to strengthen the rule of law were pledged by the some 70 nations attending the conference.<ref>{{cite news|title=International donors pledge $16 billion in aid to Afghanistan over four years|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/international-donors-pledge-16-billion-in-aid-to-afghanistan-over-four-years/2012/07/08/gJQABfA5VW_story.html|accessdate=11 July 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=8 July 2012|author=Stephanie McCrummen}}</ref> The reconstruction and development aid<ref>{{cite news|title=UN chief warns donors against holding Afghan aid hostage with reform demands|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/07/08/world/asia/afghanistan-donor-conference/index.html?eref=rss_latest|publisher=CNN|accessdate=11 July 2012|author=Chelsea J. Carter|date=8 July 2012}}</ref> was pledged for the timeframe through 2015, but under the condition that the Afghan government reduce corruption before receiving all of the money. In the so-called Tokyo Framework of Mutual Accountability foreign governments will assure Afghanistan a steady stream of financing in exchange for stronger anticorruption measures and the establishment of the rule of law. Up to 20 percent of the money would depend on the government meeting governance standards according to the Tokyo Framework of Mutual Accountability.<ref name=\"NYT20120708\">{{cite news|last=Perlez|first=Jane|title=$16 Billion in Civilian Aid Pledged to Afghanistan, With Conditions|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/09/world/asia/afghanistan-is-pledged-16-billion-for-civilian-needs.html?_r=2&ref=world|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=11 July 2012|date=8 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"We will fight corruption with strong resolve wherever it occurs, and ask the same of our international partners,\" Karzai told the donors. \"Together we must stop the practices that feed corruption or undermine the legitimacy and effectiveness of national institutions.\"<ref name=\"Talmadge\" /> The international aid is tied to a mechanism that will regularly review how it is being spent, and to guarantees from Kabul that it will seriously take on its deep-rooted corruption problems \u2013 what the conference called a roadmap of accountability. Kabul must also demonstrate efforts to improve governance and finance management, and safeguard the democratic process, rule of law and human rights \u2013 especially those of women.<ref name=\"Talmadge\" /> US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton stressed the need for reform to safeguard changes achieved in Afghanistan. \"That must include fighting corruption, improving governance, strengthening the rule of law, increasing access to economic opportunity for all Afghans, especially for women,\" she said.<ref name=\"BBC20120708\" /> A follow-up conference will be held in Britain in 2014.<ref name=\"BBC20120708\">{{cite news|title=Afghanistan aid: Donors pledge $16bn at Tokyo meeting|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-18758148|work=BBC News Asia|accessdate=11 July 2012|date=8 July 2012}}</ref> The meeting in Britain in 2014 will check progress toward \"mutual accountability\" and a review and monitoring process to assure that development aid is not diverted by corrupt officials or mismanaged \u2013 both of which have been major hurdles in putting aid projects into practice thus far.<ref name=\"Talmadge\">{{cite news|last=Talmadge |first=Eric |title=Afghan donors offer $16B in development aid |url=http://www.knoe.com/story/18970911/international-donors-pledging-16b-in-afghan-aid |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130127210326/http://www.knoe.com/story/18970911/international-donors-pledging-16b-in-afghan-aid |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 January 2013 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=knoe.com |accessdate=12 July 2012 |date=8 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Security handover and U.S. Suspension of Afghan Local Police forces training==\nThe U.S. was set to hand over responsibility for security to local Afghans by 2014, and efforts were underway to draw down U.S. forces, but Obama never specified a date for the withdrawal of all American troops from the country.<ref name=\"TheHill20120902\">{{cite news|title=Carney: No Obama plan to withdraw all US troops from Afghanistan by 2014|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/defcon-hill/policy-and-strategy/247135-carney-no-obama-plan-to-withdraw-all-us-troops-from-afghanistan-by-2014|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=2 September 2012|author=Meghashyam Mai}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=10 Facts About US Withdrawal from Afghanistan|url=http://countdowntodrawdown.org/facts.php|publisher=Just Foreign Policy|accessdate=3 September 2012}}</ref> Obama said on 1 September 2012 that he had a \"specific plan to bring our troops home from Afghanistan by the end of 2014.\" <ref name=\"TheHill20120902\" /> On 2 September 2012 White House press secretary [[Jay Carney]] then clarified Obama's statement by saying that Obama had \"never said that all the troops would be out.\" Carney noted while the United States would transfer security to Afghan troops by the end of 2014, all U.S. troops would not be out of the country by that date.<ref name=\"TheHill20120902\" /> \"Everyone understands what the president's policy is, which is a full transition to Afghan security lead by 2014,\" said Carney. \"We have been abundantly clear about the stages of the implementation of that policy. And [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq (2007\u20132011)|as in Iraq]], that means that while not all U.S. troops will have withdrawn necessarily by then, the Afghan Security Forces will be in full security transition, I mean, will be in full security lead, and U.S. forces will continue to be drawn down.\"<ref name=\"TheHill20120902\" />\n\n===\"Green-on-blue\" attacks hampering handover===\nThe effort to handover security to Afghans has been hampered by a spike in attacks by local forces supposed to be working with American and NATO personnel.<ref name=\"TheHill20120902\" /><ref name=\"APHP20120902\" /> United States military officials suspended temporarily<ref name=\"CNN20120903\" /> on 2 September 2012 the training of Afghan Local Police (ALP) in the wake of a deadly series of so-called 'green on blue' attacks<ref name=\"CNN20120903\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Timeline: Green on blue attacks in Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/special/world/afghan-rogue-attacks-timeline/|accessdate= 3 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Attacks on NATO troops by Afghan security forces on the rise|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/attacks-on-nato-troops-by-afghan-security-forces-on-the-rise/2012/08/17/1f000d54-e8d6-11e1-936a-b801f1abab19_graphic.html|accessdate= 3 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date= 17 August 2012}}</ref> by Afghan soldiers and police on their international allies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blue-on-green violence: US Special Forces suspend training of Afghans|url=http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=54162|work=Middle East Online|publisher=Middle East Online|accessdate=3 September 2012|date= 2 September 2012}}</ref>  The training has been put on hold in order to carry out intensified vetting procedures on new recruits, and 16,000 existing ALP recruits will be re-vetted.<ref name=\"NBCNews20120902\" /> ALP training is a U.S. mission, carried out by Special Forces teams who work with Afghan elders and government officials in remote villages to help villagers defend themselves against insurgent attacks and intimidation.<ref name=\"WP20120902\" /> Training of uniformed police and army personnel is done under the banner of the NATO operation.<ref name=\"NBCNews20120902\">{{cite web|title=U.S. suspends training for some Afghan recruits after 'insider' attacks|url=http://worldnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/09/02/13618137-us-suspends-training-for-some-afghan-recruits-after-insider-attacks?lite|work=NBC News staff|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=3 September 2012}}</ref> The suspension affects not only Afghan Local Police, but also Afghan special operations and commando forces.<ref name=\"NYT20120902\">{{cite news|title=U.S. Halting Program to Train Afghan Recruits|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/02/world/asia/nato-halting-program-to-train-afghan-recruits.html?hp|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date= 2 September 2012|author1=Graham Bowley  |author2=Richard A. Oppel Jr. |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> Special Operations officials said that they anticipate it will take about two months to rescreen all of the Afghan forces and that the training of new recruits could stall for as long as a month.<ref name=\"WP20120902\" />\n\nThe Washington Post reported many 'green on blue' attacks might have been prevented if existing security measures had been applied correctly, but according to NATO officials numerous military guidelines were not followed \u2014 by Afghans or Americans \u2014 because of concerns that they might slow the growth of the Afghan army and police.<ref name=\"WP20120902\">{{cite news|title=Training suspended for new Afghan recruits|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/training-suspended-for-new-afghan-recruits/2012/09/01/adc4ed1c-f398-11e1-b74c-84ed55e0300b_story.html|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=2 September 2012|author1=Greg Jaffe  |author2=Kevin Sieff |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> Despite that the current process for vetting recruits is effective, a lack of follow-up has allowed Afghan troops who fell under the sway of [[Taliban insurgency|the insurgency]] or grew disillusioned with the Afghan government to remain in the force.<ref name=\"WP20120902\" /> In other instances the vetting process for Afghan soldiers and police was never properly implemented. NATO officials knew it according to the Washington Post, but they looked the other way, worried that extensive background checks could hinder the recruitment process.<ref name=\"WP20120902\" /> Also ignored were requirements that Afghans display proper credentials while on base. Many Afghans, even those who were vetted, were never issued official badges, making it impossible to tell who was supposed to have access to any particular facility.<ref name=\"WP20120902\" /> Measures specifically designed to curtail attacks (American and NATO service members should for example always carry a loaded magazine in their weapons to save precious moments if attacked by Afghan forces)<ref name=\"NYT20120818\">{{cite news|title=Afghan Attacks on Allied Troops Prompt NATO to Shift Policy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/19/world/asia/afghan-attacks-on-allied-troops-prompt-nato-to-shift-policy.html?_r=1&hp&pagewanted=all|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=18 August 2012|author1=Richard A. Oppel  |author2=Graham Bowley |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> were also inconsistently applied.<ref name=\"WP20120902\" /> The \"Guardian Angel\" program (The program calls for one or two soldiers to monitor the Afghans during every mission or meeting. These soldiers, \"angels\" called and whose identities are not disclosed to the Afghans, must be prepared to fire on anyone who tries to kill a coalition service member.)<ref name=\"NYT20120818\" /> was often seen as a distraction from NATO's mission. Calls to minimize off-duty time spent with Afghan troops were similarly thought by NATO officials to undermine the goal of relationship-building, but according to a directive from NATO leaders troops are now being advised to stay away from Afghan soldiers and police officers during vulnerable moments, such as when they are sleeping, bathing or exercising.<ref name=\"WP20120902\" /> Additional security measures include improved training for counterintelligence agents, a more intense vetting system for new recruits, establishing an anonymous reporting system for soldiers to report suspicious activity; increasing the presence of Afghan counterintelligence teams among Afghan troops; banning the sale of Afghan army and police uniforms to help stop infiltrators posing as soldiers and policemen; and revetting soldiers when they return home from leave.<ref name=\"APHP20120902\">{{cite news|last=Vogt|first=Heidi|title=U.S Halts Training Of Some Afghanistan Forces In Light Of Green-On-Blue Violence|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/02/afghanistan-police-training-green-on-blue_n_1850065.html?ref=topbar|agency=Associated Press|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=2 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN20120903\">{{cite news|title=ISAF: U.S. temporarily halts training of Afghan police over attacks|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/09/02/world/asia/afghanistan-training-halted/index.html|work=3 September 2012|publisher=CNN|accessdate=3 September 2012|author=Masoud Popalzai|date=3 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20120902\" /><ref name=\"BBCNews20120902\">{{cite news|title=Afghan police recruits' training halted after attacks on Nato|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-19454742|work=BBC News Asia|accessdate=3 September 2012|date=2 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Afghan army has detained or sacked hundreds of soldiers for having links to insurgents, the Defence Ministry said on 5 September 2012 as it tried to stem the rising number of so-called insider attacks. \"Hundreds were sacked or detained after showing links with insurgents. In some cases we had evidence against them, in others we were simply suspicious,\" Defence Ministry spokesman Zahir Azimi told reporters in Kabul.<ref name=\"ReutersHP20120905\">{{cite news|title=Afghanistan: Hundreds Of Soldiers Detained, Fired For Insurgent Links (VIDEO)|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/05/afghan-soldiers-detained-fired_n_1856855.html?ref=topbar|work=Reuters|publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=6 September 2012|author=Mirwais Harooni|date=5 September 2012}}</ref> \"Using an army uniform against foreign forces is a serious point of concern not only for the Defence Ministry but for the whole Afghan government,\" Azimi said, adding that Karzai had ordered Afghan forces to devise ways to stop insider attacks.<ref name=\"ReutersHP20120905\" /> Azimi declined to say whether the detained and fired soldiers were from Taliban strongholds in the south and east, saying they were from all over the country. He said his ministry started an investigation into the attacks, called green-on-blue attacks, within the 195,000-strong Afghan army six months ago.<ref name=\"ReutersHP20120905\" />\n\nOn 18 September 2012 General John Allen suspended all joint combat operations between Afghanistan and American ground units in Afghanistan.\nUnder orders from the General interaction between coalition and Afghan forces would take place only at the battalion level. Allen made the move, along with suspending American-led Afghan training missions, due to growing concern over \"insider attacks\" against U.S. troops by members of the Afghan National Security Forces.<ref name=\"TheHill20120927\">{{cite news|last=Mu\u00f1oz|first=Carlo|title=US resumes joint operations with Afghan forces|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/defcon-hill/operations/259061-us-resumes-joint-operations-with-afghan-forces-|accessdate=28 September 2012|newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=27 September 2012}}</ref> Less than a week after the order U.S. and NATO combat troops resumed joint operations with Afghan forces.<ref name=\"TheHill20120927\" /><ref name=\"WP20120928\">{{cite news|last=Whitlock|first=Chris|title=U.S. resumes joint operations with Afghans|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-resumes-joint-operations-with-afghans/2012/09/27/8f5a1bf4-08e2-11e2-81ba-ffe35a7b6542_story.html|accessdate=28 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=28 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==2013-06-18 Security handover from NATO to Afghan forces==\nOn 18 June 2013, the handover of security from NATO to Afghan forces was completed.<ref name=\"DW20130618\">{{cite web|title=Bomb blast hits Afghanistan on security handover day|url=http://www.dw.de/bomb-blast-hits-afghanistan-on-security-handover-day/a-16888374|work=Deutsche Welle|publisher=Deutsche Welle|accessdate=23 June 2013|date=19 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"AJE20130618\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Karzai announces Afghan security handover|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/afp/130618/karzai-announces-afghan-security-handover|work=Agence France-Presse|publisher=Global Post|accessdate=23 June 2013|date=18 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"WSJ29130618\">{{cite news|last=Hodge|first=Nathan|title=Blast Mars Day of Security Handover in Kabul|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323566804578552593026745674#|accessdate=23 June 2013|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=18 June 2013}}</ref> The International Security Assistance Force formally handed over control of the last 95 districts to Afghan forces at a ceremony attended by Karzai and NATO Secretary General Anders Fogh Rasmussen at a military academy outside Kabul.<ref name=\"DW20130618\" /> Following the handover, Afghan forces will have the lead for security in all 403 districts of Afghanistan's 34 provinces. Before the handover they were responsible for 312 districts nationwide, where 80 percent of Afghanistan's population of nearly 30 million lives.<ref name=\"AJE20130618\" /> \"Our security and defense forces will now be in the lead,\" Karzai said. \"From here, all security responsibility and all security leadership will be taken by our brave forces. When people see security has been transferred to Afghans, they support the army and police more than before.\"<ref name=\"DW20130618\" /> Rasmussen said that by taking the lead in security on Tuesday, Afghan forces were completing a five-stage transition process that began in March 2011. \"They are doing so with remarkable resolve,\" he said. \"Ten years ago, there were no Afghan national security forces ... now you have 350,000 Afghan troops and police, a formidable force.\"<ref name=\"DW20130618\" /> he security transition signaled an important shift. The U.S.-led International Security Assistance Force is slated to end its mission by the end of 2014, and coalition forces are in the process of closing bases and shipping out equipment.<ref name=\"WSJ29130618\" /> Rasmussen stated that the focus of ISAF forces will shift from combat to support and that by the end of 2014 Afghanistan will be fully secured by Afghans. After the handover, 100,000 NATO forces will play a supporting and training role, as Afghan soldiers and police take the lead in the fight against armed groups.<ref name=\"AJE20130618\">{{cite web|title=Deadly blast marks Afghan security handover|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2013/06/20136184484852774.html|work=Al Jazeera English|publisher=Al Jazeera English|accessdate=23 June 2013|date=18 June 2013}}</ref> \"We will continue to help Afghan troops in operations if needed, but we will no longer plan, execute or lead those operations, and by the end of 2014 our combat mission will be completed,\" Rasmussen added.<ref name=\"DW20130618\" />\n\n==2013-06-19 Negotiations suspension of the Bilateral Security Agreement==\nPlans by the US to engage in peace talks with the Taliban have resulted in suspension of bilateral security discussions between the US and Afghanistan on 13 June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=US-Afghan security talks suspended in row over Taliban peace negotiations |url=http://www.defencemanagement.com/news_story.asp?id=23246 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130624220846/http://www.defencemanagement.com/news_story.asp?id=23246 |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 June 2013 |publisher=Defence Management |accessdate=23 June 2013 |date=19 June 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"WSJ20130618\">{{cite news|title=Afghan Leader Halts Talks With U.S., Taliban|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323893504578554860777787962|accessdate=23 June 2013|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=19 June 2013|author1=Nathan Hodge  |author2=Yaroslav Trofimov |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> \"In a special meeting chaired by President Hamid Karzai, the president has decided to suspend talks about a security pact with the U.S. because of their inconsistent statements and actions in regard to the peace process,\" spokesman [[Aimal Faizi]] told Reuters.<ref name=\"Reuters20130618\">{{cite news|authors=Hamid Shalizi and Dylan Welch|title=Afghanistan suspends security pact talks with U.S.|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/06/19/us-afghanistan-usa-pact-idUSBRE95I08U20130619|work=Reuters|accessdate=23 June 2013|date=19 June 2013}}</ref> Secretary of State John Kerry discussed the flare-up with Karzai in phone calls on 19 June 2013, Afghan and U.S. officials said, part of the latest round of crisis diplomacy between Washington and Afghanistan's mercurial leader.<ref name=\"WSJ20130618\" /> Negotiations on the Bilateral Security Agreement (BSA) began earlier 2013 and, if completed, will define the shape of the U.S. military presence in Afghanistan for years to come.<ref name=\"Reuters20130618\" /> The security discussions between the U.S. and Afghanistan would provide for a limited number of military trainers and counterterrorism forces to remain in the country. The talks have been complicated by several disagreements, including over the immunity that U.S. troops would enjoy from Afghan laws.<ref name=\"WSJ20130618\" /> Speaking to reporters days before the suspension, U.S. Marine Corps General Joseph Dunford, the commander of the U.S.-led coalition, said, \"The bilateral security agreement is critical to any post-2014 presence. So it needs to be taken seriously on both sides.\"<ref name=\"WSJ20130618\" /> It was not clear how long Karzai would withdraw from the security talks with the US, meant to finalise arrangements for keeping a small US presence in the country after the last of the NATO troops leave 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Usborne|first=David|title=Taliban-US peace talks postponed after Afghanistan threatens to boycott negotiations in anger at Taliban's Qatar office|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/talibanus-peace-talks-postponed-after-afghanistan-threatens-to-boycott-negotiations-in-anger-at-talibans-qatar-office-8664560.html|accessdate=23 June 2013|newspaper=The Independent|date=20 June 2013|location=London}}</ref> Karzai has said the negotiations would not resume until the Taliban met directly with representatives of the Afghan government, essentially linking the security negotiations to a faltering peace process and making the United States responsible for persuading the Taliban to talk to the Afghan government.<ref name=\"NYT20130708\">{{cite news|title=U.S. Considers Faster Pullout in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/09/world/asia/frustrated-obama-considers-full-troop-withdrawal-from-afghanistan.html?hp&_r=0&pagewanted=all|accessdate=9 July 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=8 July 2013|author1=Mark Mazzetti  |author2=Matthew Rosenberg |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>\n\n==2013-11-20 Agreement on Bilateral Security Agreement draft==\nThe United States and Afghanistan reached an agreement on the final language of the bilateral security agreement,<ref>{{cite web|title=Security and Defense Cooperation Agreement between the United States of America and the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan \u2013 Pre-Decisional Document as of November 2013|url=http://mfa.gov.af/Content/files/2013-11-18%20BSA%20TEXT.pdf|work=The United States of America and the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan|publisher=Afghan Foreign Ministry|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=11 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131201203737/http://mfa.gov.af/Content/files/2013-11-18%20BSA%20TEXT.pdf|archive-date=1 December 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> which according to State Department spokeswoman Jen Psaki wasn't the final document and which U.S. officials were still reviewing it,<ref name=\"LATimes20131120\" /> on 20 November 2013.<ref name=\"LATimes20131120\" /><ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\">{{cite news|title=U.S., Afghanistan agree on language of security accord, Kerry says|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-afghanistan-agree-on-language-of-security-accord-kerry-says/2013/11/20/85136c40-521a-11e3-a7f0-b790929232e1_story.html|accessdate=21 November 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=20 November 2013|author1=Karen DeYoung  |author2=Tim Craig |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref><ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/kerry-offers-to-write-letter-to-afghan-people-on-past-us-mistakes-kabul-officials-say/2013/11/19/11d16802-5159-11e3-9ee6-2580086d8254_story.html</ref><ref name=\"NYT20131120\" /><ref name=\"CNN20131121\" /><ref name=\"BBCBSA120131121\" /> A letter written by Obama<ref>{{cite web|last=Obama|first=Barack|title=Letter of U.S. President Barack Obama to Afghan President Hamid Karzai|url=http://president.gov.af/Content/files/President%20Obama%27s%20Letter%20to%20President%20Karzai.pdf|publisher=president.gov.af|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=20 November 2013}}</ref> said U.S. forces will be \"cooperating in training, advising, and assisting\" Afghan forces \"in a targeted, smaller, counterterrorism mission.\"<ref name=\"WPBSA220131121\" />  There is no limit on how long U.S. forces would remain in Afghanistan<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> The accord also has no expiration date.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. to offer Afghans assurances to remove hurdle in post-2014 deal|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=20 November 2013|author1=Karen DeYoung  |author2=Tim Craig |lastauthoramp=yes |newspaper=The Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/kerry-offers-to-write-letter-to-afghan-people-on-past-us-mistakes-kabul-officials-say/2013/11/19/11d16802-5159-11e3-9ee6-2580086d8254_story.html}}</ref>  The agreement says that \"unless mutually agreed, United States forces shall not conduct combat operations in Afghanistan.\" It states the parties' \"intention of protecting U.S. and Afghan national interests without U.S. military counter-terrorism operations\" but does not specifically prohibit such operations.<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> United States Special Operations forces will retain leeway to conduct antiterrorism raids on private Afghan homes<ref name=\"NYT20131120\" /> American counterterrorism operations will be intended to \"complement and support\" Afghan missions<ref name=\"NYT20131120\" /> and that US forces will not conduct military operations in Afghanistan \"unless mutually agreed\" the text says.<ref name=\"AlJazBSA120131121\" /> It underscores that Afghan forces will be in the lead and that any American military operations will be carried out \"with full respect for Afghan sovereignty and full regard for the safety and security of the Afghan people, including in their homes.\"<ref name=\"NYT20131120\" /><ref name=\"CNN20131121\">{{cite news|last=Botelho|first=Greg|title=U.S., Afghanistan reach security pact through '2024 and beyond'|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/11/20/world/asia/us-afghanistan-security-agreement/index.html?hpt=hp_t2|publisher=CNN|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=21 November 2013}}</ref> It also notes that \"U.S. forces shall not target Afghan civilians, including in their homes, consistent with Afghan law and United States forces' rules of engagement.\"<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> Obama wrote in a letter to his Afghan counterpart: \"US forces shall not enter Afghan homes for the purposes of military operations, except under extraordinary circumstances involving urgent risk to life and limb of US nationals. We will continue to make every effort to respect the sanctity and dignity of Afghans in their homes and in their daily lives, just as we do for our own citizens.\"<ref name=\"BBCBSA220131121\">{{cite news|title=Obama vow as Loya Jirga debates US-Afghan security deal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-25038926|work=BBC News|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=21 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe agreement does not spell out the number of U.S. forces who will remain, but Karzai said on 21 November 2013 that he envisions up to 15,000 NATO troops being based in the country. According to several estimates, the United States plans to maintain a force of no more than 10,000 troops in Afghanistan after 2014. The draft agreement allows an indefinite U.S. presence, but Karzai said on 21 November 2013 it would be in place for 10 years.<ref name=\"WPBSA220131121\" /> The agreement also includes language on the U.S. government's continued funding for Afghan security forces, funneling such contributions through the Kabul-based government.<ref name=\"CNN20131121\" />\n\nThe agreement text grants the United States full legal jurisdiction over U.S. troops and Defense Department civilians working in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> On troop immunity, it says that Afghanistan agrees \"that the United States shall have the exclusive right to exercise jurisdiction\" over members of the force and its civilian component \"in respect of any criminal or civil offenses committed in the territory of Afghanistan.\",<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> and that \"Afghanistan authorises the United States to hold [civil and criminal] trial in such cases, or take other disciplinary action, as appropriate, in the territory of Afghanistan.\",<ref name=\"BBCBSA120131121\">{{cite news|title=Loya Jirga debates US-Afghan security deal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-25028267|work=BBC News|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=21 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"AlJazBSA120131121\">{{cite web|title=Tribal elders discuss US-Afghan security pact|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2013/11/tribal-elders-discuss-us-afghan-security-pact-2013112144229784246.html|publisher=Al Jazeera English|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=21 November 2013}}</ref> but Afghan authorities can ask that anyone be taken out of the country.<ref name=\"CNN20131121\" /> Afghan authorities are prohibited from detaining American troops or U.S. civilians working with them. In the event that happens \"for any reason,\" however, those personnel \"shall be immediately handed over to United States forces authorities.\"<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> The agreement also specifies that American troops and civilians cannot be surrendered to any \"international tribunal or any other entity or state\" without express U.S. consent. Afghanistan, it says, retains legal jurisdiction over civilian contractors, and contractors are prohibited from wearing military uniforms and \"may only carry weapons in accordance with Afghan laws and regulations.\"<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" />\n\nThe document has a clause committing the United States to consulting with the Afghan government in the event of external threats, but not the sort of NATO-style mutual defense pact the Afghans originally wanted. \"The United States shall regard with grave concern any external aggression or threat of external aggression against the sovereignty, independence, and territorial integrity of Afghanistan,\" the proposed agreement states. There is a later clause saying they would \"consult urgently\" in the event of such aggression.<ref name=\"NYT20131120\" /> Obama added in a letter to his Afghan counterpart: \"The US commitment to Afghanistan's independence, territorial integrity, and national unity, as enshrined in our Strategic Partnership Agreement, is enduring, as is our respect for Afghan sovereignty.\"<ref name=\"BBCBSA220131121\" />\n\nIn a preamble, the draft specifies that \"the United States does not seek permanent military facilities in Afghanistan, or a presence that is a threat to Afghanistan's neighbors, and has pledged not to use Afghan territory or facilities as a launching point for attacks on other countries.\"<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> It says that \"unless otherwise mutually agreed, United States forces shall not conduct combat operations in Afghanistan\" and makes no promise of U.S. military support in the event of an attack or other security threat to Afghanistan. If there is such a threat, it says, the United States will regard it with \"grave concern,\" consult and \"shall urgently determine support it is prepared to provide.\"<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> But the United States stated the U.S. will regard any external aggression with \"grave concern\" and will \"strongly oppose\" military threats or force against Afghanistan after 2014.<ref name=\"LATimes20131120\" />\n\nThe draft agreement says that U.S. military and Defense Department civilian personnel are exempt from visa requirements and taxation. Afghan taxes and other fees will not be imposed on the entry or exit of goods specifically for the use of U.S. forces.<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> An annex to the draft lists locations where Afghanistan agrees to provide facilities for U.S. forces, including Kabul; Bagram, north of the capital, where the United States has its largest current base; Mazar-e Sharif in northern Afghanistan; Herat in the west; Kandahar in the south; Shindand in Herat province; Sharab in Helmand province; Gardez, south of Kabul; and Jalalabad, to the east.<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> The draft document gives the U.S. the right to deploy American forces on nine bases, including the two biggest, the airfields in Bagram and Kandahar. It also allows U.S. military planes to fly in and out of Afghanistan from seven air bases, including Kabul International Airport.<ref name=\"LATimes20131120\" /> U.S. forces would be permitted under the document to transport supplies from five border crossings, described along with the air bases as \"official points of embarkation and debarkation.\"<ref name=\"LATimes20131120\" /> All bases in Afghanistan would revert to Afghan ownership and sovereignty after 2014, according to the draft.<ref name=\"LATimes20131120\">{{cite news|title=Kerry announces U.S.-Afghan security agreement|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/la-fg-us-afghan-talks-20131121,0,5346244.story#axzz2lHITu7Sz|accessdate=21 November 2013|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|date=20 November 2013|author1=Shashank Bengali  |author2=David Zucchino |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe draft of the agreement was finalized early on 19 November 2013 after Obama wrote Karzai a letter assuring him that U.S. forces will continue to respect the \"sanctity and dignity of the Afghan people.\"<ref name=\"WPBSA220131121\" /> The agreement must as of 21 November 2013 be ratified by an Afghan grand council of elders<ref name=\"NYT20131120\">{{cite news|title=Pact May Extend U.S. Troops' Stay in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/21/world/asia/afghan-pact-kerry-apology-.html?hp&_r=1&pagewanted=all&|accessdate=21 November 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=20 November 2013|author1=Thom Shanker  |author2=Rod Nordland |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> and by ratified by the parliaments of Afghanistan and the United States.<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> The agreement, according to the draft wording, takes effect 1 January 2015 and then \"it shall remain in force until the end of 2024 and beyond\" unless terminated with two years' advance notice.<ref name=\"NYT20131120\" /> Karzai said that the agreement would not be signed until after 2014 elections in Afghanistan,<ref>{{cite news|title=US and Afghanistan clash on timetable for security pact|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-25045439|work=BBC News|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=21 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ALJazBSA220131121\">{{cite web|title=Afghanistan wants to delay US security deal|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2013/11/afghanistan-wants-delay-us-security-deal-2013112119310597776.html|publisher=Al Jazeera English|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=21 November 2013}}</ref> but U.S. officials have said unequivocally that the agreement must be signed by the end of the year 2013, if not sooner, to allow the Pentagon to prepare for its role after the American combat mission ends.<ref name=\"WPBSA220131121\">{{cite news|last=Craig|first=Tim|title=Afghan President Hamid Karzai says he'll delay signing of U.S. accord on troops|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/afghan-president-hamid-karzai-outlines-plans-for-post-2014-us-mission/2013/11/21/c2af9e60-52a2-11e3-9ee6-2580086d8254_story.html?tid=pm_world_pop|accessdate=21 November 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=21 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ALJazBSA220131121\" /> White House Press secretary Jay Carney said the agreement under consideration by the loya jirga is the Obama administration's \"final offer.\" If not enacted by the end of the year, Carney said, it \"would be impossible for the United States and our allies to plan for a presence post-2014.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Karzai rejects call for quick decision on U.S. troop agreement|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/karzai-rejects-call-for-quick-decision-on-afghan-troop-levels/2013/11/22/13aa03b2-538b-11e3-9ee6-2580086d8254_story.html?wprss=rss_war-zones&tid=pp_widget|accessdate=23 November 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=22 November 2013|author1=Tim Craig  |author2=Sayed Salahuddin |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> Karzai, who earlier stated he would sign what he had agreed to sign, stated later, after the announcement of the Bilatereal Security Agreement (BSA) draft textthat, he wouldn't sign it until 2014, after a presidential election to choose his successor, but before he leaves office. [[Aimal Faizi]], a spokesman for Karzai, stated that Karzai wanted to wait until after the election in April 2014 to test further conditions: whether American forces would stop raids on Afghan homes, whether the Obama Administration will help stabilize security in Afghanistan, help promote peace talks and not interfere in the election.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nordland|first=Rod|title=Karzai Insists U.S. Forces Killed Civilians in a Raid|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/24/world/asia/us-upset-by-karzais-claim-about-civilian-deaths.html?src=recg&pagewanted=all|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=23 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"WPA20131123\" /> Officials of the Obama Administration consider the signing date to be nonnegotiable, citing the need for at least a year to plan future deployments and to allow coalition partners, including Germany and Italy, to plan for a residual troop presence that they have offered.<ref name=\"WPA20131123\">{{cite news|title=Karzai intends to press showdown with Obama over security pact, aide says|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/karzai-doesnt-trust-us-intends-to-press-showdown-with-obama-aide-says/2013/11/23/f32e9b08-546f-11e3-9ee6-2580086d8254_story.html?tid=pm_world_pop|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=23 November 2013|author1=Tim Craig  |author2=Karen DeYoung |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe text of the BSA was approved by the delegates at the Loya Jirga on 24 November 2013 and must now be signed by the Afghanistan president, who rejected the final recommendation of the Loya Jirga promptly to sign the BSA with the United States, and sent to the parliament for final ratification.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nordland|first=Rob|title=Afghan Council Approves Security Pact, but Karzai Withholds His Signature|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/25/world/asia/afghan-council-approves-us-security-pact.html?hp&_r=1&&pagewanted=all|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=24 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"WPJIRGA20131124\">{{cite news|last=Craig|first=Tim|title=Afghan elders endorse U.S. troops' presence but President Karzai still refuses to sign|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/afghan-assembly-of-leaders-endorses-us-troops-presence-karzai-refuses-to-sign/2013/11/24/ac29b6f2-550a-11e3-bdbf-097ab2a3dc2b_story.html|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=24 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Loya jirga approves U.S.-Afghan security deal; asks Karzai to sign|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/11/24/world/asia/us-afghanistan-security-agreement/index.html?hpt=hp_t3|publisher=CNN|accessdate=24 November 2013|author1=Masoud Popolzai  |author2=Ben Brumfield |lastauthoramp=yes |date=24 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"LATimes20131124\">{{cite news|last=Zucchino|first=David|title=Afghan council defies Karzai on U.S. security deal|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/worldnow/la-fg-wn-afghan-council-defies-karzai-20131124,0,7234234,full.story#axzz2la8MJOs2|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|date=24 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"AlJaz20131124\">{{cite web|title=Karzai gives no date to sign US security pact|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2013/11/karzai-agrees-afghan-us-security-pact-20131124854271874.html|publisher=AlJazeera English|accessdate=24 November 2013|author=Ali M Latifi|date=24 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Craig|first=Tim|title=Coalition apologizes for killing Afghan child, seeks to shore up prospects of security deal|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/coalition-apologizes-for-killing-afghan-child-karzai-warns-security-deal-in-jeopardy/2013/11/29/f73d2b06-58ed-11e3-8304-caf30787c0a9_story.html?tid=ts_carousel|accessdate=30 November 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=29 November 2013}}</ref> If approved, the agreement would allow the U.S. to deploy military advisors to train and equip Afghan security forces, along with U.S. special-operations troops for anti-terrorism missions against Al Qaeda and other terrorist groups. Obama will determine the size of the force.<ref name=\"LATimes20131124\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Afghanistan elders seek US security pact signing in 2013|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-25075536|work=BBC News Asia|accessdate=24 November 2013|date=24 November 2013}}</ref> The jirga set a few conditions before expressing approval for the agreement among them a 10-year time limit on the post-2014 troop presence and reparations for damages caused by U.S. troops deployed in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"WPJIRGA20131124\" /> It also voted attach a letter by Obama; pledging that U.S. troops would enter Afghan homes only in \"extraordinary\" circumstances and only if American lives were at direct risk, to the BSA.<ref name=\"LATimes20131124\" /> The elder assembly also demanded the release of 19 Afghans from the U.S. detention center at Guantanamo Bay and a stronger U.S. pledge to defend Afghanistan from any incursion from it neighbors, particularly Pakistan. The loya jirga also voted to request that the U.S. military add a base<ref name=\"AlJaz20131124\" /> to the nine bases that would be occupied by U.S. troops under the proposed security pact after combat forces depart Afghanistan by the end of 2014. The base is in Bamian Province in central Afghanistan, where the NATO-led military coalition has maintained a presence. Bamian is a population center for Hazaras, a Shiite minority whose members were massacred by the Taliban prior to the U.S.-led invasion that toppled the militant group. Afghan analysts said Hazara delegates proposed the additional base.<ref name=\"LATimes20131124\" /> At least five of the 50 jirga committees raised objections to the article addressing \"status of personnel\" which \"authorises the United States to hold [civil and criminal] trial ... or take other disciplinary action, as appropriate, in the territory of Afghanistan\" when a US soldier is accused of criminal activity.<ref name=\"AlJaz20131124\" /> Spokespeople from at least two committees directly stated that Afghanistan should have jurisdiction over any US soldiers accused of crimes on Afghan soil. Several committees also stated that if trials are held in the United States, families of victims should have access to and presence in US-held trials at the expense of Washington.<ref name=\"AlJaz20131124\" />\n\n==US withdrawal from Afghanistan: The plan for 2012, 2013, and 2014==\n===2012 drawdown===\nThe 2012 pullout of 23,000 American troops from Afghanistan was on 22 July 2012 at the halfway mark according to U.S. Gen. John Allen, the top commander of U.S. and NATO forces in Afghanistan and would accelerate in the coming months.<ref name=\"APFox20120723\">{{cite news|title=Withdrawal of US troops from Afghanistan halfway done, top commander says|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/07/22/withdrawal-us-troops-from-afghanistan-halfway-done-top-commander-says/|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=10 September 2012|date=23 July 2012}}</ref> \"August will be the heaviest month,\" Allen said. \"A lot is coming out now and a great deal will come out in August and early September. We'll be done probably around mid-September or so.\"<ref name=\"APFox20120723\" /> Up to one half of the 23,000 troops being pulled out 2012 are combat forces, he said. Small numbers are being pulled from the relatively stable northern and western parts of the country. Some will be withdrawn from the east and the south \"and a good bit in the southwest,\" he said.<ref name=\"APFox20120723\" /> U.S. Defense Secretary Leon Panetta announced on 21 September 2012 that the 33,000 additional U.S. troops that Obama had sent to Afghanistan in 2010 to counter the Taliban attacks have left the country.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cassata|first=Donna|title=Defense hawk backs US withdrawal from Afghanistan|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/huff-wires/20120921/us-congress-afghanistan/|agency=Associated Press|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=14 October 2012|date=21 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=US pulls out 33,000 troops from Afghanistan: Panetta|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/2012/09/21/262785/33000-us-troops-depart-afghanistan/|publisher=PressTV|accessdate=14 October 2012|date=21 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Final US 'surge' troops withdraw from Afghanistan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/sep/21/us-surge-troops-withdraw-afghanistan?newsfeed=true|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=14 October 2012|date=21 October 2012|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ardolino |first=Bill |title=Afghanistan \u2013 now what? |url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/threat-matrix/archives/2012/09/afghanistan_-_now_what.php |publisher=Threat Matrix \u2013 A Blog of The Long War Journal |accessdate=14 October 2012 |date=21 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930003222/http://www.longwarjournal.org/threat-matrix/archives/2012/09/afghanistan_-_now_what.php |archivedate=30 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  A phased withdrawal plan was developed where 10,000 troops would leave Afghanistan by July 2011 and the remaining 23,000 would leave Afghanistan by the end of September 2012. The removal of the 23,000 U.S. troops began in July 2012.<ref name=\"KhaamaPress20120921\">{{cite news|title=United States pullout 33000 surge troops from Afghanistan|url=http://www.khaama.com/united-states-pullout-33000-surge-troops-from-afghanistan-783/|accessdate=14 October 2012|newspaper=Khaama Press (KP) {{!}} Afghan Online Newspaper|date=21 September 2012|author=Sajad}}</ref>  In a statement announcing an end to the surge Panetta stated:\n\n{{quote|As we reflect on this moment, it is an opportunity to recognize that the surge accomplished its objectives of reversing Taliban momentum on the battlefield, and dramatically increased the size and capability of the Afghan National Security Forces (ANSF). This growth has allowed us and our ISAF Coalition partners to begin the process of transition to Afghan security lead, which will soon extend across every province and more than 75 percent of the Afghan population. At the same time, we have struck enormous blows against al Qaeda's leadership, consistent with our core goal of disrupting, dismantling and defeating al Qaeda and denying it a safe-haven.<ref name=\"KhaamaPress20120921\" />}}\n\nOnce the United States and its allies agreed on the timing for the shift in the Afghanistan mission \u2014 under which American troops would step away from the lead combat role to a supporting mission focused primarily on counterterrorism and training Afghan security forces (according to the 2012 NATO Chicago Summit this shift is planned for the middle of 2013 ([[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Afghanistan#NATO Chicago Summit: Troops withdrawal and longterm presence|see section above]]) \u2014 the Obama administration must decide exactly when the remaining 68,000 troops will come home according to the New York Times.<ref name=\"NYT20120313\">{{cite news|title=U.S. Officials Debate Speeding Afghan Pullout|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/13/world/asia/us-officials-debate-speeding-up-afghan-pullout.html?_r=1&ref=world&src=me&adxnnlx=1331668863-xL%20xRTvBu6ol%2019Ji81NgQ&pagewanted=all|accessdate=10 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=13 March 2012|author1=Helene Cooper  |author2=Eric Schmitt |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> In September 2012 the United States withdrew then the last of the 33,000 \"surge\" forces from Afghanistan that Obama ordered in West Point 2009 to try to bring the Afghanistan war under control. With the reduction over the next two years of the remaining 68,000 American troops, the top American and NATO commander in Afghanistan would lead a force that is to operate from fewer bases and will train Afghan forces to take the lead in combat.<ref name=\"NYT20121010\">{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Elisabeth|title=Commander Nominated to Lead War in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/11/world/asia/general-dunford-nominated-to-lead-afghan-war-effort.html?src=recg&_r=0|accessdate=14 October 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=10 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2013 drawdown plans===\nThe number of US troops to remain in Afghanistan during 2013 was still being decided as of March 2012, but it appeared that three options were considered. These three options were:<ref name=\"NYT20120313\" />\n\n# A drawdown from 68,000 to 58,000 troops by the end of 2012, with a further drawdown to between 38,000 and 48,000 by June 2013. This would be a continuation of the current policy of gradual drawdown. Obama has stated that he prefers a gradual drawdown.<ref name=\"NYT20120313\" /><ref name=\"RadinJournal20120318\">{{cite web|last=Radin|first=CJ|title=US withdrawal from Afghanistan: the plan for 2012, 2013, and 2014|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2012/03/us_withdrawal_from_a.php|publisher=The Long War Journal \u2013 A Project of the Foundation for Defense of Democracy|accessdate=10 September 2012|date=18 March 2012}}</ref>\n# Maintaining 68,000 troops through the end of 2013. This is the US military commanders' preferred option since it maintains US force levels through the summer fighting season in 2013.<ref name=\"NYT20120313\" /><ref name=\"RadinJournal20120318\" />\n# A large and rapid drawdown, perhaps to 20,000 troops, by the end of 2013. This would leave only Special Operations Forces, counterterrorism forces, military trainers, and some support and security staff in Afghanistan. This is Vice President Biden's preferred option.<ref name=\"NYT20120313\" /><ref name=\"RadinJournal20120318\" />\n\nAccording to two American officials who are involved in Afghan issues said that the senior American commander in Afghanistan, General John Allen wanted to keep a significant military capability through the fighting season ending in fall 2013, which could translate to a force of more than 60,000 troops until the end of that period.<ref name=\"NYT20121126\">{{cite news|last=Gordon|first=Michael R.|title=Time Slipping, U.S. Ponders Afghan Role After 2014|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/26/world/asia/us-planning-a-force-to-stay-in-afghanistan.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=26 November 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=26 November 2012}}</ref> The United States has not \"begun considering any specific recommendations for troop numbers in 2013 and 2014,\" said George Little, the Pentagon spokesman. \"What is true is that in June 2011 the president made clear that our forces would continue to come home at a steady pace as we transition to an Afghan lead for security. That it still the case.\"<ref name=\"NYT20121126\" />\n\nDuring the [[2013 State of the Union Address]], Obama said that the U.S. military will reduce the troop level in Afghanistan from 68,000 to 34,000 US troops by February 2014.<ref name=\"WP20130212\">{{cite news|last=Chandrasekaran|first=Rajiv|title=Obama wants to cut troop level in Afghanistan in half over next year|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/official-obama-to-cut-troop-level-in-afghanistan-in-half-by-next-year/2013/02/12/63a044c8-7536-11e2-8f84-3e4b513b1a13_story.html|accessdate=14 February 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=12 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20130212\">{{cite news|title=Decision on Afghan Troop Levels Calculates Political and Military Interests|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/13/us/politics/obama-to-announce-troops-return.html?_r=2&|accessdate=14 February 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=12 February 2013|author1=Michael R. Gordon  |author2=Mark Landler |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"BBC20130213\" /><ref name=\"CNNTapper20130213\">{{cite news|last=Tapper|first=Jack|title=Obama announces 34,000 troops to come home|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/02/12/politics/obama-sotu-afghanistan-troops/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=14 February 2013|date=13 February 2013}}</ref> According to an unnamed U.S. official Obama made his decision \"based on the recommendations of the military and his national security team,\" consultations with Karzai and \"international coalition partners.\"<ref name=\"CNNTapper20130213\" /> The United States has adopted a withdrawal schedule which U.S. General John. R. Allen called a \"phased approach.\"<ref name=\"NYT20130212\" /> According to the new withdrawal schedule, as reported by the New York Times, the number of troops is to go down from 66,000 troops to 60,500 by the end of May 2013. By the end of November 2013, the number will be down to 52,000. By the end of February 2014, the troop level is to be around 32,000.<ref name=\"NYT20130212\" /> The Washington Post reported a slightly different withdrawal plan which calls for the U.S. forces figure of 68,000 troops to drop to about 60,000 by May 2013 and 52,500 by November 2013. The largest exodus will occur in December 2013 and January 2014, when about 18,500 troops will leave Afghanistan.<ref name=\"WP20130212\" /> The White House intended to allow the military to determine the pace at which the 34,000 troops are withdrawn over the 12 months until February 2013. Top U.S. military  officers have said they hope to keep as many forces as possible in Afghanistan through summer 2013, when combat with the Taliban is usually at its highest.<ref name=\"WP20130212\" /> \"Commanders will have discretion on pace of this drawdown which will allow them to maintain the force they need through the fighting season,\" according to one U.S. official.<ref name=\"CNNTapper20130213\" /> The drawdown announcement generated mixed reactions in Afghanistan: While Afghan officials like Karzai and the Taliban welcomed Obama's decision, many Afghans worried that a quick drawdown will destabilize the country. Afghans also expressed their concern that Afghan security forces were not ready to take the lead for security.<ref>{{cite news|title=Announcement of US troop withdrawal draws mixed reactions in Afghanistan|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2013/02/13/announcement-us-troop-withdrawal-draws-mixed-reaction-in-afghanistan/|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=14 February 2013|date=13 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Quinn|first=Patrick|title=Afghan president welcomes U.S. withdrawal|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2013/02/ap-afghan-president-welcomes-us-withdrawal-021313/|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Army Times|accessdate=14 February 2013|date=13 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs of September 2013 the U.S. military is flying out a large amount of gear instead of using cheaper overland and sea routes, while U.S. officials declined to elaborate on the reasons for their heavy reliance on the more expensive methods of transport.<ref>{{cite news|last=Whitlock|first=Craif|title=In Afghanistan drawdown, U.S. forced to take costly option in transporting military gear out|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/in-afghanistan-drawdown-us-forced-to-take-costly-option-in-transporting-military-gear-out/2013/09/12/6a5e260a-1bde-11e3-b4fb-944b778463f5_story.html|accessdate=14 September 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=13 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2014 drawdown plans===\nThe US force level will drop to between 10,000 and 20,000 troops according to the Long War Journal. They will consist of Special Forces, counterterrorism forces, and military training personnel. They will be deployed to a small number of bases around the country. US/ISAF troops will continue their training of Afghan National Security Forces soldiers. Counterterrorism forces will concentrate mostly on high-value targets.<ref name=\"RadinJournal20120318\" /> U.S. Secretary of Defense Leon Panetta stated on 12 November 2012 that the Obama Administration will cease combat operations by the end of 2014, but it is still refining its timeline for withdrawing the remaining 68,000 U.S. troops in Afghanistan. The administration was also debating how many trainers, Special Operations forces and military assets it will keep in the country after that to support Afghanistan's army and police.<ref>{{cite news|last=Whitlock|first=Craig|title=Panetta heads to Asia, as Obama administration makes strategic 'pivot'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/panetta-heads-to-asia-as-obama-administration-makes-strategic-pivot/2012/11/12/a1f3d432-2d16-11e2-a99d-5c4203af7b7a_story.html|accessdate=17 November 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=13 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring a surprise trip to Afghanistan in May 2014 Obama stated that the United States wanted to sign a bilateral security agreement with Afghanistan for the purpose of continuing training/advising Afghan forces and assisting in specific counterterrorism missions. The winner of Afghanistan's presidential runoff election  \u2014 between former Afghan foreign minister [[Abdullah Abdullah]] and onetime World Bank economist Ashraf Ghani \u2014 will be asked immediately to sign the security agreement that will help determine how many U.S. forces, as of May 2014 numbering 32,000, will remain in Afghanistan after the end of the year 2014. U.S. officials said the security agreement must be endorsed as soon as possible to give U.S. military planners time to complete drawdown schedules \u2014 including decisions on what bases to close \u2014 and make arrangements for the next phase of the U.S. military presence after nearly 13 years of war.<ref>{{cite news|last=Landler|first=Mark|title=Obama, Honoring the Fallen, Says V.A. Problems Must Be Faced|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/27/us/politics/obama-honoring-the-fallen-says-va-problems-must-be-faced.html?_r=0|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Scott|title=Obama makes surprise visit to Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/obama-arrives-in-afghanistan-on-surprise-visit/2014/05/25/7df61452-e41f-11e3-8f90-73e071f3d637_story.html|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=25 May 2014}}</ref> Pentagon general counsel Stephen Preston said in May 2014 before the U.S. Senate that the 2014 drawdown planning and the post 2014 presence planning will concentrate on \"what the circumstances, the mission and presence in Afghanistan will be.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=DeYoung|first=Karen|title=Obama's revamp of anti-terror policies stalls|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/obamas-revamp-of-anti-terror-policies-stalls/2014/05/21/79ac0f20-e053-11e3-8dcc-d6b7fede081a_story.html|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 May 2014, Obama announced that U.S. combat operations in Afghanistan would end in December 2014 and that the troops levels will be reduced to 9,800 troops by this time.<ref name=\"NYT20140527\">{{cite news |last=Landler|first=Mark|title=U.S. Will Complete Afghan Pullout by End of 2016, Obama Says|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/28/world/asia/us-to-complete-afghan-pullout-by-end-of-2016-obama-to-say.html?hp|newspaper=The New York Times|date=27 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 August 2014, a gunman dressed in an Afghan military uniform opened fire on a number of U.S., foreign and Afghan soldiers, killing Major General [[Harold J. Greene]] and wounding about 15 officers and soldiers including a German brigadier general and eight U.S. soldiers. For the U.S. Armed Forces, it was the first death of a general on foreign battlefields in 44 years.<ref name=\"ShootingAfghanistan\">{{cite news|title=American army officer killed, many wounded in Afghan insider attack|url=http://www.afghanistansun.com/index.php/sid/224460361|accessdate=7 August 2014|publisher=Afghanistan Sun}}</ref>\n\nAfter 13 years Britain, the United States and the remaining Australians officially ended their combat operation in Afghanistan on 28 October 2014. On that day Britain handed over its last base in Afghanistan, Camp Bastion in the southern province of Helmand, to Afghanistan, while the United States handed over its last base, Camp Leatherneck in the southern province of Helmand.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Syal|first1=Ryan|title=UK troops hand over Camp Bastion to Afghan forces, ending 13-year campaign|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/oct/26/uk-troops-camp-bastion-afghan-forces-13-years-helmand|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=The Guardian|publisher=The Guardian|date=26 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Kay Johnson, Raissa Kasolowsky, Michael Perry and Kevin Liffey|title=Britain ends combat role in Afghanistan, last US Marines hand over base|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/10/26/us-afghanistan-troopwithdrawal-idUSKBN0IF06I20141026|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=Reuters|agency=Reuters|publisher=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Watt|first1=Holly|title=Britain's 13-year war in Afghanistan comes to an end|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/afghanistan/11188222/Last-British-combat-troops-leave-Helmand-within-days.html|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=The Telegraph|publisher=The Telegraph|date=26 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hjelmgaard|first1=Kim|title=Britain's war in Afghanistan officially ends|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/10/26/britain-afghanistan-camp-bastion-us-marines/17952857/|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=USA Today|publisher=USA Today|date=26 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Loyn|first1=David|title=What have British troops achieved in Afghanistan?|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-29761100|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=BBC News Asia|publisher=BBC News Asia|date=26 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=UK ends Afghan combat operations|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-29776544|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=BBC News UK|publisher=BBC News UK|date=26 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Post-2014 presence plans==\n===Plans by the administration of Barack Obama===\nDuring the [[2012 Chicago Summit]] NATO and its partners agreed to withdraw its combat troops from Afghanistan by the end of 2014.<ref name=\"Reuters 20120521\"/> A new and different NATO mission will then advise, train and assist the Afghan security forces including the Afghan Special Operations Forces.<ref name=\"Chicago Declaration\" /><ref name=\"Elise Labott and Mike Mount\"/> Final decisions on the size of the American and NATO presence after 2014 and its precise configuration have not been made by the United States or its NATO allies as of 26 November 2012, but one option calls for about 10,000 American and several thousand non-American NATO troops according to the United States.<ref name=\"NYT20121126\"/> The presence shall include a small American counterterrorism force consisting of fewer than 1,000 American troops, while in a parallel effort, NATO forces would advise Afghan forces at major regional military and police headquarters. According to the New York Times, NATO forces would most likely have a minimal battlefield role, with the exception of some special operations advisers.<ref name=\"NYT20121126\" />\n\nAn important question for the NATO mission after 2014 was what level of the Afghan military hierarchy they would advise. It was generally expected that they would advise seven regional Afghan Army corps and several regional Afghan police headquarters. The arrangement would largely insulate the NATO advisers from the battlefield, though officials said advisers might accompany Afghan brigades on major operations. It was unlikely that NATO officers would advise Afghan battalions on the battlefield, because that would require many more advisers than NATO was likely to muster and would entail more risk than most nations seem prepared to assume, though some American experts believed it would make the Afghan military more effective. Still, NATO special operations advisers would be likely to accompany Afghan Army commandos and police SWAT-type units on the battlefield.<ref name=\"NYT20121126\" />\n\nA major challenge was that Afghanistan would not have an effective air force before 2017, if then.  As a consequence American officials said that NATO airpower would remain in Afghanistan after 2014 but will likely only be used on behalf of NATO and American troops and perhaps Afghan units that are accompanied by NATO advisers. NATO forces relied heavily on airpower for airstrikes, supply and medical evacuation since Afghanistan's roads are in poor condition and often seeded with bombs. To compensate for Afghanistan's limited airpower, the United States was working on a number of fixes, including providing Afghan forces with armored vehicles that would be equipped with mortars and assault guns. The United States was looking into expanding the purchase of turboprop planes for the Afghans. In addition the U.S. was also trying to help Afghan pilots learn to fly at night.<ref name=\"NYT20121126\" /> Equally troubling was according to the New York Times the problem of medical evacuations. Because after 2014 the Afghans would almost certainly need to rely on a system that depended more on ground transportation than helicopters the United States wanted to help Afghanistan forces develop more field hospitals.<ref name=\"NYT20121126\" />\n\nPlans for the follow-on military presence are being formulated in the Pentagon, where the largest of several preliminary options calls for about 10,000 troops, with several other NATO governments penciled in for several hundred each. According to these preliminary plans, ISAF's successor would be based in Kabul, with most U.S. training and counterterrorism troops probably stationed in Kandahar and at the air base at Bagram. Both locations are to be converted to Afghan ownership. Smaller counterterrorism units of the [[Joint Special Operations Command]] would be positioned primarily in the eastern part of the country, where most of their activities take place. Italy, in charge of the ISAF mission in Herat in western Afghanistan, would remain there to train Afghans. Germany would do the same in Mazar-e Sharif in the north. It is unclear what would happen at Camp Bastion, the British headquarters in Helmand province.<ref name=\"WP20121205\">{{cite news|last=DeYoung|first=Karen|title=U.S. reducing plans for large civilian force in post-2014 Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-reducing-plans-for-large-civilian-force-in-post-2014-afghanistan/2012/12/05/67c7d9a8-380f-11e2-8a97-363b0f9a0ab3_story.html|accessdate=5 December 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=5 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe size of the American military presence after 2014 will help determine the size of the American civilian footprint. As of December 2012 the United States are reducing its plans for large civilian force in post-2014 Afghanistan, because the U.S. military is certain to curtail or stop the security and other services it provides U.S. government civilians in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"WP20121205\" /> Firm decisions on civilian numbers and locations cannot be made \"until we resolve exactly what the military follow-on numbers are going to be,\" one unnamed U.S. official said. \"That will determine .\u2009.\u2009. where we locate, what kind of security, medical and other support we might be able to get.\"<ref name=\"WP20121205\" /> According to the New York Times the U.S. military wants to retain 9,000 U.S. troops in Afghanistan, while the Obama administration wants a force of 3,000 to 9,000 troops in Afghanistan after 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gordon|first=Michael R.|title=U.S. Weighs Fewer Troops After 2014 in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/06/world/asia/us-weighs-fewer-troops-after-2014-in-afghanistan.html?ref=world&_r=0|accessdate=10 January 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring a meeting with Karzai on 11 January 2013, Obama stated that he will determine the pace of U.S. combat troops drawdown and their withdrawal from Afghanistan by the end of 2014 after consultations with commanders on the ground.<ref name=\"LATimes20130111\">{{cite news|title=Obama moves up deadline for Afghans to take lead security role|url=https://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-pn-obama-karzai-afghanistan-20130111,0,7048110.story|accessdate=12 January 2013|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|date=11 January 2013|author1=Christi Parsons  |author2=Kathleen Hennessey |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> He also said any U.S. mission in Afghanistan beyond 2014 would focus solely on counterterrorism operations and training Afghan security forces.<ref name=\"LATimes20130111\" /><ref name=\"WP20130111\">{{cite news|title=Obama announces reduced U.S. role in Afghanistan starting this spring|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/karzai-meets-obama-to-discuss-us-drawdown-in-afghanistan/2013/01/11/b50c72ec-5c03-11e2-9fa9-5fbdc9530eb9_story.html?hpid=z1|accessdate=12 January 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=11 January 2013|author1=Scott Wilson  |author2=[[David Nakamura]] |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> According to Obama any agreement on troop withdrawals must include an immunity agreement in which US troops are not subjected to Afghan law.<ref>{{cite web|title=US to speed up Afghan troop transition|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/americas/2013/01/201311185310956108.html|publisher=Al Jazeera English|accessdate=12 January 2013|date=11 January 2012}}</ref> \"I can go to the Afghan people and argue for immunity for U.S. troops in Afghanistan in a way that Afghan sovereignty will not be compromised, in a way that Afghan law will not be compromised,\" Karzai replied.<ref name=\"CNN20130112\">{{cite news|title=Obama, Karzai agree to accelerate military transition|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/01/11/us/obama-karzai-meeting/?hpt=hp_t1|accessdate=12 January 2013|newspaper=CNN|date=12 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring his [[2013 State of the Union Address]] Barack Obama announced that 34,000 US troops will leave Afghanistan by February 2014, but did not specify what the post-2014 troop levels would be. \"Beyond 2014, America's commitment to a unified and sovereign Afghanistan will endure, but the nature of our commitment will change,\" Obama said.<ref name=\"BBC20130213\" /> \"We're negotiating an agreement with the Afghan government that focuses on two missions \u2013 training and equipping Afghan forces so that the country does not again slip into chaos, and counter-terrorism efforts that allow us to pursue the remnants of al-Qaeda and their affiliates,\" he added.<ref name=\"BBC20130213\">{{cite news|title=Obama announces 34,000 troops to leave Afghanistan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-21431423|publisher=BBC News US & Canada|accessdate=14 February 2013|date=13 February 2013}}</ref> As of 12 February 2013, Barack Obama has not made a decision on the post-2014 U.S. force.<ref name=\"NYT20130212\" /> The Obama Administration intends to keep some troops in the country in 2015 and beyond, but the number is still being debated at the White House and must be approved by the Afghan government.<ref name=\"WP20130212\" /> Unnamed U.S. officials said there was a reluctance to go public with a final number of troops and a description of their missions while still in the early stage of negotiating a security agreement with the Afghans over retaining a U.S. military presence after 2014.<ref name=\"NYT20130212\" /> The New York Times reported that the post-2014 force is likely to number no more than 9,000 or so troops and then get progressively smaller.<ref name=\"NYT20130212\" /> The Washington Post reported that the Pentagon is pushing a plan that would keep about 8,000 U.S. troops in Afghanistan in 2015, but significantly shrink the contingent over the following two years, perhaps to fewer than 1,000 by 2017, according to senior U.S. government officials and military officers.<ref name=\"WP20130212\" /> As the result of the suspension of the bilateral security agreement discussions and increasingly frustrated by his dealings with Karzai, Obama was giving in early July 2013 serious consideration to speeding up the withdrawal of United States forces from Afghanistan and to a \"zero option\" that would leave no American troops there after 2014.<ref name=\"NYT20130708\" /> At the end of 2013 the United States backed away from its threat to initiate a complete American withdrawal from Afghanistan by the end of 2014, if Karzai refuses to sign the Bilateral Security Agreement by the end of 2013. However the United States stood by its warning that a total military withdrawal is still possible if delays continue.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rosenberg|first=Matthew|title=U.S. Softens Deadline for Deal to Keep Troops in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/24/world/asia/us-softens-deadline-for-deal-to-keep-troops-in-afghanistan.html?_r=0|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=23 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20140121\">{{cite news|title=U.S. Military Eyes Afghan Force of 10,000, or a Pullout|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/22/world/asia/military-eyes-afghan-force-of-10000-or-a-pullout.html?_r=0|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=21 January 2014|author1=Jackie Calmes  |author2=Eric Schmitt |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> The U.S. Department of Defense proposed to Obama to leave behind 10,000 US troops when their combat mission and that of their allies end there at the end of 2014, or none at all.<ref name=\"NYT20140121\" /> Caitlin M. Hayden, a spokeswoman for the National Security Council, said that absent an agreement with respect to the B.S.A. between the America and Afghanistan the U.S.A. \"will initiate planning for a post-2014 future in which there would be no U.S. or NATO troop presence in Afghanistan.\",<ref name=\"NYT20140121\" /> while the British Ministry of Defense said that until the pact is signed, no decision will be made on the contribution from other nations.<ref>{{cite news|title=The mammoth military task of leaving Afghanistan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-25848662|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=BBC News Asia|date=28 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nBy May 2014 no agreement on the bilateral security agreement had been reached. Obama on a trip to Afghanistan in late May 2014 said he was about to make decisions on the transition and was in the country to meet with Afghanistan's leaders prior to making those decisions final.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama to announce post-2014 troop levels in Afghanistan shortly|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/05/25/us-usa-afghanistan-obama-military-idUSBREA4O09W20140525|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=Reuters|date=25 May 2014|author1=Steve Holland, Jeff Mason  |author2=Bill Trott |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> On 27 May 2014, Obama announced that U.S. combat operations in Afghanistan would end in December 2014.<ref name=\"WSJ20140528\" /><ref name=\"BBC20140527\">{{cite web|title=US to keep 9,800 Afghanistan troops after 2014|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-27593518|publisher=BBC News USA & Canada|accessdate=29 May 2014|date=27 May 2014}}</ref> A residual force of 9,800 troops would remain in the country which includes a group of troops to train and advise Afghan security forces and a separate group of Special Operations forces to continue counterterrorism missions against remnants of al-Qaeda.<ref name=\"WP20140527\">{{cite news|last=DeYoung|first=Karen|title=Obama to leave 9,800 U.S. troops in Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/obama-to-leave-9800-us-troops-in-afghanistan-senior-official-says/2014/05/27/57f37e72-e5b2-11e3-a86b-362fd5443d19_story.html|accessdate=29 May 2014|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=27 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"USAToday20140527\">{{cite news|title=Obama: It's time to turn the page on a decade of war|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/05/27/obama-afghanistan-9800-troop-level/9624545/|accessdate=29 May 2014|newspaper=USA Today|date=27 May 2014|author1=Aamer Madhani  |author2=Tom Vanden Brook |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> These forces would be halved by the end of 2015, and consolidated at Bagram Air Base and in Kabul. Obama also announced that all U.S. forces, with the exception of a \"normal embassy presence,\" would be removed from Afghanistan by the end of 2016.<ref name=\"NYT20140527\"/> These remaining forces would be a regular armed forces assistance group, largely to handle military sales under the authority of the U.S. ambassador,<ref name=\"WP20140527\" /> but also guard the US embassy, train Afghan forces and support counter-terrorism operations.<ref name=\"BBC20140527\" /> These troop will not exceed 1,000 troops, akin to the security presence that is currently as of May 2014 in Iraq.<ref name=\"USAToday20140527\"/> The president's plans were subject to the approval of the incoming Afghan government and its willingness to sign the bilateral security agreement providing immunity for U.S. troops serving in the country, which outgoing president Karzai had refused to sign.<ref name=\"AfghanistanDrawdown\">{{cite news|title=US to leave some 10,000 troops in Afghanistan after 2014|url=http://www.afghanistansun.com/index.php/sid/222375281/scat/6e1d5c8e1f98f17c/ht/US-to-leave-some-10000-troops-in-Afghanistan-after-2014|accessdate=27 May 2014|publisher=Afghanistan Sun}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ackermann|first=Spencer|title=Obama announces plan to keep 9,800 US troops in Afghanistan after 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/27/obama-us-afghanistan-force-2014|accessdate=29 May 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|date=27 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Obama seeks to cut troop level in Afghanistan to 5,000 by end of 2015|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/afghanistan-pakistan/la-fg-obama-afghanistan-troops-20140527-story.html|accessdate=29 May 2014|date=27 May 2014|author1=Christi Parsons  |author2=David S. Cloud |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> The U.S. post 2014 presence plans were welcomed by outgoing Afghanistan president Hamid Karzai saying that Afghanistan was ready to take responsibility for its own security and the move could pave the way for Taliban peace talks.<ref>{{cite news|last=Graham-Harrison|first=Emma|title=Afghanistan president welcomes US plan to withdraw troops by 2016|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/28/afghanistan-president-welcomes-us-plan-withdraw-troops|accessdate=29 May 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|date=28 May 2014}}</ref> While Afghanistan military forces reacted to Obama's plans with skepticism arguing among other things that Afghan military's lack of air support and heavy artillery couldn't be overcome by 2016 or 2017 and NATO welcomed the announcement, U.S. politicians split along party lines to Obama's drawdown and post 2014 presence plans, Afghanistan lawmakers considered those plans a blow to Afghan morale and American think tanks questioned the post presence limitation to the end of 2016 pointing out to experience in Germany, Britain, Korea and Japan, where U.S. forces remain long after wars have ended but the need to support strong allies remains.<ref name=\"NYT20140527\" /><ref name=\"WSJ20140528\">{{cite news|title=Obama Details Plan for Forces in Afghanistan|url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/obama-details-plan-for-forces-in-afghanistan-1401234489?tesla=y&mg=reno64-wsj&url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303403604579588574244016560|accessdate=29 May 2014|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=28 May 2014|author1=Adam Entous  |author2=Carol E. Lee |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"WP20140527\" /><ref name=\"USAToday20140527\" />\n\nAfghanistan and the United States signed the bilateral security agreement through U.S. Ambassador James B. Cunningham and Afghan national security adviser Mohammad Hanif the bilateral security agreement on 30 September 2014 in a cordial ceremony at the presidential palace in Kabul, Afghanistan.<ref name=\"NYT20140930\" /><ref name=\"WP201040930\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Michaels|first1=Jim|title=Afghanistan, U.S. sign long-delayed security pact|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/09/30/afghan-us-security-pact/16467441/|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=USA Today|publisher=USA Today|date=30 September 2014}}</ref> On that day the NATO Status of Forces Agreement was also signed, giving forces from Allied and partner countries the legal protections necessary to carry out the NATO [[Resolute Support Mission]] when International Security Assistance Force comes to an end in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement by the President on the Signing of the Bilateral Security Agreement and NATO Status of Forces Agreement in Afghanistan|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/09/30/statement-president-signing-bilateral-security-agreement-and-nato-status|website=whitehouse.gov|publisher=The White House Office of the Press Secretary|accessdate=26 October 2014|date=30 September 2014}}</ref> Under both agreements 9,800 American and at least 2,000 NATO troops are allowed to remain in Afghanistan after the international combat mission formally ends on 31 December 2014<ref name=\"NYT20140930\" /> while also enabling the continued training and advising of Afghan security forces, as well as counterterrorism operations against remnants of al-Qaeda.<ref name=\"WP201040930\" /> Most of the troops will help train and assist the struggling Afghan security forces, although some American Special Operations forces will remain to conduct counterterrorism missions.<ref name=\"NYT20140930\" /> The Nato-led ISAF mission will transition to a training mission headquartered in Kabul with six bases around the country.<ref name=\"NYT20140930\" />  Under the BSA the United States are allowed to have bases at nine separate locations across Afghanistan.<ref name=\"WP201040930\" /> A base in Jalalabad, in eastern Afghanistan, could also remain a launching point for armed drone missions in Afghanistan and across the border in Pakistan.<ref name=\"NYT20140930\">{{cite news|author1=Declan Walsh and Azam Ahmed|title=Mending Alliance, U.S. and Afghanistan Sign Long-Term Security Agreement|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/01/world/asia/afghanistan-and-us-sign-bilateral-security-agreement.html?_r=0|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times|date=30 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"WP201040930\">{{cite news|author1=Sudarsan Raghavan and Karen DeYoung|title=U.S. and Afghanistan sign vital, long-delayed security pact|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-afghanistan-sign-security-pact-to-allow-american-forces-to-remain-in-country/2014/09/30/48f555ce-4879-11e4-a046-120a8a855cca_story.html|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=The Washington Post|publisher=The Washington Post|date=30 September 2014}}</ref> The agreement also prevents U.S. military personnel from being prosecuted under Afghan laws for any crimes they may commit; instead, the United States has jurisdiction over any criminal proceedings or disciplinary action involving its troops inside the country. The provision does not apply to civilian contractors.<ref name=\"WP201040930\" /> The troop number of 9.800 Americans is to be cut in half by 2016, with American forces thereafter based only in Kabul and at Bagram air base. By the end of 2017, the U.S. force is to be further reduced in size to what U.S. officials have called a \"normal\" military advisory component at the U.S. Embassy in Kabul, most likely numbering several hundred.<ref name=\"WP201040930\" /> The BSA goes into force on 1 January 2015 and remains in force \"until the end of 2024 and beyond\" unless it is terminated by either side with two years' notice.<ref name=\"rferl.org\">{{cite news|last1=Recknagel|first1=Charles|title=Explainer: Key Points In U.S.-Afghan Bilateral Security Agreement|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/explainer-bsa-afghan-us-security-agreement-bsa/26613884.html|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=Radio Free Europe and Radio Liberty|publisher=Radio Free Europe and Radio Liberty|date=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014 U.S. President Obama expanded the original role of U.S. Armed Forces in Afghanistan for 2015. Originally they were supposed to advise, train and assist the Afghan Forces and to hunt the remnants of Al Qaeda. Under the president's order U.S. forces can carry out missions against the Taliban and other militant groups threatening American troops or the Afghan government while American jets, bombers and drones can support Afghan troops on combat missions. By the end of 2015, half of the 9,800 American troops would leave Afghanistan. The rest would be consolidated in Kabul and Bagram, and then leave by the end of 2016, allowing Obama to say he ended the Afghan war before leaving office. The United States could still have military advisers in Kabul after 2016 who would work out of an office of security cooperation at the United States Embassy. But the Obama administration has not said how large that contingent might be and what its exact mission would be.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Mark Mazzetti and Eric Schmitt|title=In a Shift, Obama Extends U.S. Role in Afghan Combat|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/22/us/politics/in-secret-obama-extends-us-role-in-afghan-combat.html|accessdate=14 February 2015|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times|date=21 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring his last trip to Afghanistan U.S. Secretary of Defense Chuck Hagel announced on 6 December 2014 the end of the U.S. original plan to withdraw its troops form Afghanistan. Under a plan announced in May 2014 the number of American troops was supposed to fall to 9,800 by 1 January 2015. Instead the U.S. will keep up to 10,800 troops for the first few months of 2015 and then restart the drawdown, which is scheduled to reach 5,500 troops by the end of 2015. Besides partaking in NATO's [[Resolute Support Mission]] consisting of 12,500 soldiers<ref name=\"DPARS20141202\">{{cite news|title=NATO chief, Afghan president welcome \"new phase\" as combat role ends|url=http://www.dpa-international.com/news/asia/nato-afghan-president-ghani-tolaunch-new-2015-mission-a-43481490.html|accessdate=7 February 2015|work=DPA|agency=DPA|date=2 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207185555/http://www.dpa-international.com/news/asia/nato-afghan-president-ghani-tolaunch-new-2015-mission-a-43481490.html|archive-date=7 February 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> some U.S. troops will take part in a separate counterterrorism mission focused on al-Qaeda. By the time U.S. President Obama leaves office in 2017 only a small force attached to the U.S. Embassy in Kabul is to remain in Afghanistan. The reason for the United States to keep additional forces in the country temporarily was that planned troop commitments by US allies for the Nato train-and-assist mission starting in January 2015 have been slow to materialize. President Barack Obama \"has provided US military commanders the flexibility to manage any temporary force shortfall that we might experience for a few months as we allow for coalition troops to arrive in theater,\" Hagel said in a news conference with President Ashraf Ghani in Kabul. \"But the president's authorization will not change our troops' missions, or the long-term timeline for our drawdown,\" he added.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chuck Hagel: more US troops will remain in Afghanistan|accessdate=7 February 2015|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Guardian|date=6 December 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/dec/06/chuck-hagel-more-us-troops-will-remain-in-afghanistan}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=More US Troops Than Planned to Stay in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2014/12/06/world/asia/ap-as-united-states-afghanistan.html?_r=0|accessdate=7 February 2015|agency=The Associated Press|newspaper=The New York Times|date=6 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ryan|first1=Missy|title=Hagel says U.S. to leave up to 1,000 extra troops in Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/hagel-pays-final-visit-to-afghanistan-as-pentagon-chief/2014/12/06/e6cf5c2c-7d17-11e4-9a27-6fdbc612bff8_story.html|accessdate=7 February 2015|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=6 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of March 2015 U.S. President Obama announced to slow the pace of the U.S. troop withdrawal by maintaining the current force levels of 9,800 troops through at least the end of 2015. This announcement came after a request by the Afghan government under its new president Ashraf Ghani. Obama  and Ghani stated the troops were needed to train and advise Afghan forces. According to U.S. official keeping the current force in place would allow American special operations troops and the Central Intelligence Agency to operate in southern and eastern Afghanistan, where the insurgents are strongest and where Al Qaeda's presence is concentrated. Obama also stated to close the remaining U.S. bases in Afghanistan, to withdraw all but about 1,000 troops by the time he leaves office at the beginning of 2017 consolidate the remaining U.S. forces in Kabul. Those forces would operate largely in Kabul and protect embassy personnel and other American officials there.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lederman |first=Josh |date=24 March 2015 |title=White House: US to slow troop withdrawal from Afghanistan |url=http://apnews.myway.com/article/20150324/us--united_states-afghanistan-bae7252c6c.html |newspaper=Associated Press |access-date=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Greg Jaffe and David Nakamura|title=Obama agrees to slow U.S. troop withdrawal from Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/obama-agrees-to-slow-us-troop-withdrawal-from-afghanistan/2015/03/24/6acd4834-d247-11e4-a62f-ee745911a4ff_story.html?tid=sm_tw|accessdate=27 March 2015|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=27 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Michael D. Shear and Mark Mazetti|title=U.S. to Delay Pullout of Troops From Afghanistan to Aid Strikes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/25/world/asia/ashraf-ghani-of-afghanistan-wants-us-troops-to-stay-longer.html|accessdate=27 March 2015|date=24 March 2015|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosenberg|first1=Matthew|title=Ghani Addresses Congress, Eager to Rebuild Afghan-U.S. Ties|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/26/world/asia/ghani-addresses-congress-eager-to-rebuild-afghan-us-ties.html?_r=0|accessdate=27 March 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 March 2015}}</ref> NATO has maintained 13,000 troops including 9,800 Americans in an advisory and counter-terrorism capacity in Afghanistan during the [[War in Afghanistan (2015\u2013present)|2015 phase of the War in Afghanistan]].<ref name=\"rferl.org\"/>\n\nIn the wake of the  Taliban's capture of Kundus during the [[Battle of Kunduz]] and following a US review of its troop presence in Afghanistan U.S. President Obama stated on 15 October 2015 that Afghan security forces are not as strong as they should be and that the security situation in Afghanistan is still very fragile with risks to deteriorate in some parts of the country. For these reasons Obama announced a new $15 billion-a-year plan: The U.S. will maintain its current force of 9,800 through most of 2016, then begin drawing down to 5,500 late in the year or in early 2017.<ref name=\"WP20151015\">{{cite news|author1=Greg Jaffe and Missy Ryan|title=Obama outlines plan to keep 5,500 troops in Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/obama-expected-to-announce-new-plan-to-keep-5500-troops-in-afghanistan/2015/10/14/d98f06fa-71d3-11e5-8d93-0af317ed58c9_story.html|accessdate=16 October 2015|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=15 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20151016\">{{cite news|author1=Matthew Rosenberg and Michael D. Shear|title=In Reversal, Obama Says U.S. Soldiers Will Stay in Afghanistan to 2017|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/16/world/asia/obama-troop-withdrawal-afghanistan.html?_r=0|accessdate=16 October 2015|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\nThe US forces will be stationed in four garrisons: Kabul, Bagram, Jalalabad and Kandahar.<ref name=\"WP20151015\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=US troops to stay in Afghanistan in policy shift|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-34536833|accessdate=16 October 2015|publisher=BBC News US & Canada|date=15 October 2015}}</ref> The post-2016 force will still be focused on training and advising the Afghan army, with a special emphasis on its elite counter-terrorism forces. The United States will also maintain a significant counter-terrorism capability of drones and Special Operations forces to strike al-Qaeda, forces of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]], and other militants who may be plotting attacks against the United States.<ref name=\"WP20151015\" /> U.S. counter-terrorism forces deployed at bases in Kandahar and Jalalabad and the Bagram air base outside Kabul will be able to target al-Qaeda forces and forces of the Islamic State, while U.S. advisers can continue to work with key Afghan units, such as air and Special Operations forces, to blunt Taliban attacks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama bows to reality in Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/obama-bows-to-reality-in-afghanistan/2015/10/15/d22a04fe-735f-11e5-8248-98e0f5a2e830_story.html|accessdate=16 October 2015|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring a press conference on 6 July 2016 U.S. President Obama said he would draw down troops to 8,400 by the end of his administration in December 2016.<ref name=\"20170607CNNCollinsonKopan\">{{cite news|author1=Stephen Collinson and Tal Kopan|title=Obama to leave more troops than planned in Afghanistan|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/07/06/politics/obama-to-speak-on-afghanistan-wednesday-morning/|accessdate=6 July 2016|work=CNN|publisher=CNN|date=6 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=E. Lee|first1=Carol|title=Obama to Slow Troop Withdrawal From Afghanistan|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/obama-to-slow-troop-withdrawal-from-afghanistan-1467817803|accessdate=6 July 2016|work=The Wall Street Journal|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|date=6 July 2016}}</ref> He said the troops remaining in Afghanistan would continue to be focused on training and advising the Afghan military and engaging in counter-terrorism efforts.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Gregory Korte and Tom Vanden Brook|title=Obama: 8,400 troops to remain in Afghanistan|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2016/07/06/obama-afghanistan/86746010/|accessdate=6 July 2016|work=USA Today|publisher=USA Today|date=6 July 2016}}</ref> The president warned that a deteriorating security situation in Afghanistan could overwhelm Afghan government partners without further assistance. \"It's in our national interest \u2013 after all the blood and treasure we have invested \u2013 that we give our Afghan partners the support to succeed,\" said Obama.<ref name=\"20160706TheGuardian\" /> \"This is where al-Qaida is trying to regroup, where [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Isil]] is trying to expand its presence,\" he added. \"If they succeed, they will attempt more attacks against us.\"<ref name=\"20160706TheGuardian\">{{cite news|last1=Roberts|first1=Dan|title=Obama delays US troop withdrawal from 'precarious' Afghanistan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jul/06/obama-delays-us-troop-withdrawal-afghanistan-al-qaida|accessdate=6 July 2016|work=The Guardian|publisher=The Guardian|date=6 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Plans by the administration of Donald Trump===\nIn the summer of 2017, with 8,400 U.S. troops already authorized,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.defensenews.com/2017/07/21/mattis-authority-delegated-by-trump-in-afghanistan-is-tactical-not-strategic/|title=Mattis: Authority delegated by Trump in Afghanistan is tactical, not strategic|last1=Copp|first1=Tara|date=July 21, 2017|publisher=Military Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170824164655/https://www.defensenews.com/2017/07/21/mattis-authority-delegated-by-trump-in-afghanistan-is-tactical-not-strategic/|archivedate=24 August 2017|accessdate=August 24, 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] gave the U.S. military decision-making authority to increase troop numbers for U.S. military operations in [[American-led intervention in Syria|Syria]], [[American-led intervention in Iraq (2014\u2013present)|Iraq]] and [[War in Afghanistan (2015\u2013present)|Afghanistan]] without first seeking formal agreement from the White House.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Nicole Gaouette|title=Trump delegates troop decisions, to praise and concern|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/16/politics/trump-military-troops-afghanistan-mattis/index.html|accessdate=August 24, 2017|publisher=CNN|date=June 17, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170824160855/http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/16/politics/trump-military-troops-afghanistan-mattis/index.html|archivedate=24 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gordon|first1=Michael R.|title=Trump Gives Mattis Authority to Send More Troops to Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/13/world/asia/mattis-afghanistan-military.html?mcubz=0|accessdate=August 24, 2017|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 13, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824163802/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/13/world/asia/mattis-afghanistan-military.html?mcubz=0&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org|archivedate=August 24, 2017}}</ref>\nU.S. Secretary of Defense [[James Mattis]] praised the new authority: \"This assures [[United States Department of Defense|the department]] can facilitate our missions and nimbly align our commitment to the situation on the ground. Our overall mission in Afghanistan remains the same, to train, advise and assist the Afghan forces so they can safeguard the Afghan people and terrorists can find no haven in Afghanistan for attacking us or others.\"<ref>{{cite news|author1=Barbara Starr and Ryan Browne|title=Mattis confirms White House has given him authority to set Afghanistan troop levels|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/13/politics/pentagon-afghanistan-troop-levels/index.html|accessdate=August 24, 2017|publisher=CNN|date=June 14, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170824161756/http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/13/politics/pentagon-afghanistan-troop-levels/index.html|archivedate=24 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The broad outlines of the Afghanistan strategy, in place since April 2017, were described as \"an increase in special operations forces to train, advise and assist Afghan forces; a more robust plan to go after elements in Pakistan that aid the Taliban; the deployment of more air power and artillery; and a political commitment to the survival of the current government in Kabul\".<ref>{{cite news|author1=Eli Lake|title=Without plan, Trump allows more troops for Afghanistan|url=http://www.kansas.com/opinion/opn-columns-blogs/article156508114.html|accessdate=August 25, 2017|agency=WP Bloomberg|newspaper=The Wichita Eagle|date=June 16, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825055916/http://www.kansas.com/opinion/opn-columns-blogs/article156508114.html|archivedate=August 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn August 21, 2017, Trump unveiled his strategy for Afghanistan and the broader South Asia, but he didn't specify the number of troops to be committed nor the conditions by which success could be judged.<ref name=\"NYT20170821\">{{cite news|author1=Julie Hirschfeld Davis and Mark Landler|title=Trump Outlines New Afghanistan War Strategy With Few Details|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/21/world/asia/afghanistan-troops-trump.html?mcubz=3|accessdate=August 24, 2017|newspaper=The New York Times|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824165338/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/21/world/asia/afghanistan-troops-trump.html?mcubz=3&mtrref=web.archive.org|archivedate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> Instead, conditions on the ground would determine troop levels and strategy.<ref name=\"WP20170821\">{{cite news|author1=David Nakamura and Abby Phillip|title=Politics Trump announces new strategy for Afghanistan that calls for a troop increase|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-expected-to-announce-small-troop-increase-in-afghanistan-in-prime-time-address/2017/08/21/eb3a513e-868a-11e7-a94f-3139abce39f5_story.html|accessdate=August 25, 2017|date=August 21, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170825055254/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-expected-to-announce-small-troop-increase-in-afghanistan-in-prime-time-address/2017/08/21/eb3a513e-868a-11e7-a94f-3139abce39f5_story.html|archivedate=25 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This was confirmed on August 24, 2017 by the military commander for United States and NATO forces in Afghanistan, General John W. Nicholson, who described the new strategy in Afghanistan as defining success by conditions on the ground and not \"arbitrary timelines.\"<ref>{{cite news|author1=Mujib Mashal|title=U.S. Troop Increase in Afghanistan Is Underway, General Says|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/24/world/asia/afghanistan-troop-increase-trump-taliban.html?ribbon-ad-idx=3&rref=world/asia|accessdate=August 25, 2017|date=August 24, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170825054255/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/24/world/asia/afghanistan-troop-increase-trump-taliban.html?ribbon-ad-idx=3&rref=world/asia|archivedate=25 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> U.S. President Trump said in his August 21, 2017 speech that \"victory will have a clear definition: attacking our enemies, obliterating [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]], crushing al-Qaeda, preventing the Taliban from taking over the country, and stopping mass terror attacks against Americans before they emerge.\"<ref name=\"WP20170821\" /> An additional 4,000 troops beyond the 8,500 U.S. service members already in the region were to be deployed.<ref name=\"WP20170821\" />\n\nOn August 30, 2017 the Pentagon disclosed that there were more troops in Afghanistan than previously acknowledged. The Pentagon said previously that there were 8,400 troops in Afghanistan, but in reality the actual \"total force\" number was closer to 11,000.<ref name=\"WP20170830\">{{cite news|author1=Thomas Gibbons-Neff|title=Checkpoint: Afghan troop surge likely to include thousands of paratroopers, Marines and heavy bombers|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2017/08/30/afghan-troop-surge-likely-to-include-thousands-of-paratroopers-marines-and-heavy-bombers/|accessdate=31 August 2017|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=August 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831212303/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2017/08/30/afghan-troop-surge-likely-to-include-thousands-of-paratroopers-marines-and-heavy-bombers/?utm_term=.65996f424555|archivedate=31 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20170830\" /> The lower number was based on misleading accounting measures and [[red tape]].<ref name=\"WPAP20170830\">{{cite news|author1=Lolita C. Baldor|title=Pentagon: US troop total in Afghanistan larger than reported|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/pentagon-us-troop-total-in-afghanistan-larger-than-reported/2017/08/30/e8d0bdea-8db3-11e7-9c53-6a169beb0953_story.html|accessdate=August 31, 2017|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Washington Post|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831205829/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/pentagon-us-troop-total-in-afghanistan-larger-than-reported/2017/08/30/e8d0bdea-8db3-11e7-9c53-6a169beb0953_story.html?utm_term=.adbe761de94a|archivedate=August 31, 2017}}</ref> The new count used by the United States Department of Defense includes covert as well as temporary units.<ref name=\"NYT20170830\">{{cite news|last1=Cooper|first1=Helene|title=U.S. Says It Has 11,000 Troops in Afghanistan, More Than Formerly Disclosed|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/30/world/asia/afghanistan-troop-totals.html?mcubz=3|accessdate=August 31, 2017|newspaper=The New York Times|date=August 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831215013/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/30/world/asia/afghanistan-troop-totals.html?mcubz=3&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org|archivedate=August 31, 2017}}</ref> The Washington Post reported on August 30, 2017 that the additional U.S. forces for Afghanistan will likely include paratroopers as well as small Marine artillery detachments, composed of about 100 or so troops per unit, which will be spread around the country to fill in gaps in air support.<ref name=\"WPAP20170830\" /> The report by the Washington Post also reported that more air support \u2014 in the form of more [[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16 fighters]], [[Fairchild Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II|A-10 ground attack aircraft]] and additional [[Boeing B-52 Stratofortress|B-52 bomber support]], or a combination of all three - will likely be used in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"WPAP20170830\" /> The newspaper also stated: \"The additional U.S. forces will allow Americans to advise Afghan troops in more locations and closer to the fighting, U.S. officials in Kabul said [ ... ]. With more units farther away from the country's biggest bases, additional air support and artillery will be needed to cover those forces.\"<ref name=\"WPAP20170830\" /> And the New York Times added that: \"the American military will be able to advise select Afghan brigades in the field instead of trying to mentor them from more distant headquarters. They can step up the effort to train special operations forces and, thus, substantially increase the number of Afghan commandos. This will allow American war commanders and service members to call in air and artillery strikes on behalf of more Afghan units.\"<ref name=\"NYT20170830\" />\n\nIn September 2017, U.S. President Donald Trump started returning troops to Afghanistan<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ward |first1=Alex |title=Trump is sending more than 3,000 troops to Afghanistan |url=https://www.vox.com/world/2017/9/19/16227730/trump-afghanistan-3000-troops-mattis |accessdate=25 April 2020 |publisher=Vox |date=September 19, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191228110421/https://www.vox.com/world/2017/9/19/16227730/trump-afghanistan-3000-troops-mattis |archivedate=December 28, 2019}}</ref> U.S. Defense Secretary James Mattis confirmed on September 18, 2017 that 3,000 additional U.S. troops would be sent to Afghanistan, bringing the total number of U.S. forces in Afghanistan to more than 14,000 and bolstering the Afghan military in its fight against the Taliban, al Qaeda and the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mitchell|first1=Ellen|newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|title=Mattis: US to send 3,000 more troops to Afghanistan|url=http://thehill.com/policy/defense/351222-mattis-us-to-send-3000-more-troops-to-afghanistan|accessdate=October 18, 2017|date=September 18, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018193100/http://thehill.com/policy/defense/351222-mattis-us-to-send-3000-more-troops-to-afghanistan|archivedate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mattis says over 3,000 additional U.S. troops will deploy to Afghanistan|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mattis-says-over-3000-additional-u-s-troops-will-deploy-to-afghanistan/|accessdate=October 18, 2017|publisher=CBS News|date=September 18, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018193747/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mattis-says-over-3000-additional-u-s-troops-will-deploy-to-afghanistan/|archivedate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=US sends 3,000 more troops to Afghanistan|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-41314428|publisher=BBC News US & Canada|accessdate=October 18, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018193454/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-41314428|archivedate=October 18, 2017|date=September 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ward|first1=Alex|title=Trump is sending more than 3,000 troops to Afghanistan|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2017/9/19/16227730/trump-afghanistan-3000-troops-mattis|website=Vox.com|publisher=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|accessdate=October 18, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018194639/https://www.vox.com/world/2017/9/19/16227730/trump-afghanistan-3000-troops-mattis|archivedate=October 18, 2017|date=September 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Austin S. Miller|Gen. Austin \u201cScott\u201d Miller]] took command in Afghanistan in 2018, there were 15,000 U.S. troops there. In October 2019, Miller announced that this number had already been reduced to 13,000 as a result of a unilateral decision by the US.<ref name=\"George\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-has-begun-reducing-troops-in-afghanistan-commander-says/2019/10/21/d17a9e30-f3f1-11e9-8cf0-4cc99f74d127_story.html|title=U.S. has begun reducing troops in Afghanistan, commander says|last=George|first=Susannah|date=21 October 2019|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nOn February 29, 2020, the U.S. signed an agreement with the Taliban to withdraw troops in 14 months if the Taliban uphold the terms of the agreement. As of February 2020 about 13,000 American troops were still in the country. The two sides agreed a gradual, conditions-based withdrawal over 14 months and the withdrawal agreement encompasses \"all military forces of the United States, its allies, and Coalition partners, including all non-diplomatic civilian personnel, private security contractors, trainers, advisors, and supporting services personnel.\". In the first phase the U.S. will initially reduce its forces in Afghanistan by about 5,000 troops to 8,600 within 135 days of the U.S.-Taliban agreement. During the gradual withdrawal, the Taliban and the Afghan government would have to work out a more concrete power-sharing settlement. That time frame would give the government the cover of American military protection while negotiating. U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said the remaining U.S. troops will serve as leverage to ensure the Taliban lives up to its promises. If the Taliban fulfills its commitments to renounce al Qaeda and begin [[Afghan peace process|intra-Afghan peace talks]], the U.S. agreed to a complete withdrawal of all remaining American forces from Afghanistan within 10 months.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Hamid Shalizi |author2=Charlotte Greenfield |title=U.S. to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 14 months if Taliban conditions met |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/us-to-withdraw-troops-from-afghanistan-in-14-months-if-taliban-conditions-met/ar-BB10yxIL?li=BBnb7Kz |website=msn.com |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=29 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229233816/https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/us-to-withdraw-troops-from-afghanistan-in-14-months-if-taliban-conditions-met/ar-BB10yxIL?li=BBnb7Kz |archivedate=29 February 2020 |date=29 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Mujib Mashal |title=Taliban and U.S. Strike Deal to Withdraw American Troops From Afghanistan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/29/world/asia/us-taliban-deal.html |accessdate=29 February 2020 |date=29 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229235609/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/29/world/asia/us-taliban-deal.html |archivedate=29 February 2020|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Mujib Mashal and Russell Goldman |title=4 Takeaways From the U.S. Deal With the Taliban |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/29/world/asia/us-taliban-afghanistan.html |accessdate=1 March 2020 |publisher=The New York Times |date=29 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301000422/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/29/world/asia/us-taliban-afghanistan.html |archivedate=1 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Tom Vanden Brook and Deirdre Shesgreen |title=Historic peace deal in Afghanistan reached with Taliban, allowing withdrawal of US troops |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/02/29/u-s-taliban-sign-deal-peace-talks-begin-u-s-troops-withdraw/4738736002/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=USA Today |publisher=USA Today |date=29 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301001435/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/02/29/u-s-taliban-sign-deal-peace-talks-begin-u-s-troops-withdraw/4738736002/ |archivedate=1 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Afghan conflict: US and Taliban sign deal to end 18-year war |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51689443 |accessdate=1 March 2020 |publisher=BBC News |date=29 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301002219/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51689443 |archivedate=1 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Jennifer Hansler |title=US and Taliban sign historic agreement |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/29/politics/us-taliban-deal-signing/index.html |accessdate=1 March 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=29 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301004545/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/29/politics/us-taliban-deal-signing/ |archivedate=1 March 2020}}</ref> On March 1, however, the peace agreement hit a major snag when President Ghani stated during a press conference that the Afghan government, which was not a party to the deal, would reject the deal's call for conducting a prisoner exchange with the Taliban by the proposed start of intra-Afghan negotiations on March 10, 2020, even stating that \"The government of Afghanistan has made no commitment to free 5,000 Taliban prisoners,\" \u201can agreement that is signed behind closed doors will have basic problems in its implementation tomorrow,\u201d \u201cThe release of prisoners is not the United States authority, but it is the authority of the government of Afghanistan.\u201d<ref name=apreject>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/01/afghan-peace-deal-prisoner-release-118473|title=Afghan peace deal hits first snag over prisoner releases|author=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=Politico|accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=reject>{{Cite web| title = Ghani: No Commitment to Release Taliban Prisoners| work = TOLOnews| accessdate = 2020-03-01| url = https://tolonews.com/afghanistan/ghani-no-commitment-release-taliban-prisoners}}</ref><ref name=reject2>{{cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/president-ghani-rejects-peace-deal-prisoner-swap-taliban-200301082216180.html|title=President Ghani rejects peace deal's prisoner swap with Taliban|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=March 1, 2020|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=nprreject>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/01/810949474/afghan-president-rejects-timeline-for-prisoner-swap-proposed-in-us-taliban-peace|title=Afghan President Rejects Timeline For Prisoner Swap Proposed In US-Taliban Peace Deal|first=Cat|last=Schuknecht|publisher=NPR|date=1 March 2020|accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> Ghani also stated that any prisoner exchange \n\"cannot be a prerequisite for talks,\" but must be a part of the negotiations.<ref name=bbcreject>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51695370|title=Afghan conflict: President Ashraf Ghani rejects Taliban prisoner release|publisher=BBC News|date=1 March 2020|accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome U.S. troops withdrew from Afghanistan on March 10, 2020.<ref>https://apnews.com/2ac6e6ae6d805a5d067da8f36d3052d7</ref> The same day, however, Centcom chief [[Kenneth F. McKenzie Jr.|Gen. Kenneth F. McKenzie Jr.]] denied to members of the U.S. Congress that there was a plan to enact a full withdrawal.<ref name=partialonly /> McKenzie also stated that the plan is to reduce the number of U.S. troops in Afghanistan to 8,600 in a 14-month period.<ref name=partialonly /> On 23 April 2020, however, spokespeople representing various brigades of the U.S Army confirmed that the escalation of U.S. Army units to Afghanistan will resume in the summer of 2020.<ref name=\"moretroops\">{{cite web |last1=Vandiver |first1=John |title=Army announces summer troop moves to Europe, Iraq and Afghanistan |url=https://www.stripes.com/news/europe/army-announces-summer-troop-moves-to-europe-iraq-and-afghanistan-1.627236 |website=Stars and Stripes |publisher=Stars and Stripes |accessdate=25 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200425182238/https://www.stripes.com/news/europe/army-announces-summer-troop-moves-to-europe-iraq-and-afghanistan-1.627236 |archivedate=25 April 2020 |date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><\n\n==See also==\n* [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq (2007\u20132011)|Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq]] (comparable event)\n* [[Paris Peace Accords]] (comparable event)\n* [[Taliban insurgency]]\n* [[Civilian casualties in the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n* ''[[Duty: Memoirs of a Secretary at War]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''[[Duty: Memoirs of a Secretary at War]]'' by [[Robert Gates]]. New York: [[Alfred A. Knopf]], 2014.\n\n==External links==\n* Afghanistan: Drawdown serie by [[Al Jazeera English]], with [http://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/peopleandpower/2013/05/2013529133226564418.html a video] and two interactive webpages: [http://webapps.aljazeera.net/aje/custom/2014/drawdownafghanistan/infographic/index.html ''Cost of War''] and [http://webapps.aljazeera.net/aje/custom/2014/drawdownafghanistan/web/index.html ''The long godbye'']\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IT-iwQ2M-lA U.S. Military Prepares to Move Out of Afghanistan], YouTube video by [[United States Central Command]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qeonvpu5jcs U.S. military prepares to end Afghanistan combat mission], YouTube video by [[CNN]]\n\n{{War on Terror}}\n{{Afghanistan War}}\n\n[[Category:2011 in military history]]\n[[Category:2012 in military history]]\n[[Category:2013 in military history]]\n[[Category:2014 in military history]]\n[[Category:2015 in military history]]\n[[Category:2016 in military history]]\n[[Category:2011 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2012 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2013 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2014 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2015 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2016 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2011 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:2012 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:2013 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:2014 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:2015 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:2016 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Modern history of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:History of the United States (1991\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Afghanistan\u2013United States military relations]]\n[[Category:Pakistan\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Pakistan\u2013United States military relations]]\n[[Category:Pakistan\u2013NATO relations]]\n[[Category:Military withdrawals]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use American English|date=April 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Afghanistan\n| partof      = the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan war]]\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| date        = 14 June 2011 &ndash; 31 December 2016\n| place       = [[Afghanistan]]\n| territory   = \n| result      = Withdrawal completed in December 2016 and larger U.S. presence<ref name=\"20170607CNNCollinsonKopan\" />\n* U.S. keeps 13,000 troops as October 2019.<ref name=\"George\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-has-begun-reducing-troops-in-afghanistan-commander-says/2019/10/21/d17a9e30-f3f1-11e9-8cf0-4cc99f74d127_story.html|title=U.S. has begun reducing troops in Afghanistan, commander says|last=George|first=Susannah|date=21 October 2019|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n| combatant1  = '''Coalition:'''\n* {{flag|United States}} ([[United States Armed Forces|U.S. Armed Forces]])\n* {{flag|Australia}} ([[Australian Defence Force]])\n* {{flag|Afghanistan}} ([[Afghan Armed Forces]])\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of the International Security Assistance Force.svg}} [[International Security Assistance Force]] \n*{{flagdeco|NATO}} [[Resolute Support Mission]]\n\n|combatant2= '''Insurgent groups:'''\n* {{flagicon|Afghanistan|Taliban}} [[Taliban]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of al-Qaeda.svg}} [[al-Qaeda]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Islamic Movement of Uzbekistan|IMU]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Harkat-ul-Jihad-al-Islami]]<ref name=paksmostwanted>{{cite web\n  | last = Roggi\n  | first = Bill\n  | title = Pakistan's most-wanted: look at who isn't listed\n  | work = The Long War Journal\n  | publisher = Public Multimedia Inc.\n  | date = 31 August 2009\n  | url = http://www.longwarjournal.org/threat-matrix/2009/08/pakistans_most_wanted_look_at.php\n  | doi =\n  | accessdate =2 September 2009}}</ref>\n* {{Flagicon image|Flag of Hezbi Islami Gulbuddin.svg}} [[Hezb-e-Islami Gulbuddin|HI-Gulbuddin]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Hezb-e Islami Khalis|HI-Khalis]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Haqqani network]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Lashkar-e-Taiba]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Lashkar-e-Islam]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Abdullah Azzam Shaheed Brigade]]\n* {{flagicon image|Jaishi-e-Mohammed.svg}} [[Jaish-e-Mohammed|JeM]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/2008/0715/p07s05-wosc.html |title=Outpost attack in Afghanistan shows major boost in militant strength|publisher=Csmonitor.com |author=Aunohita Mojumdar, Correspondent of The Christian Science Monitor |accessdate=2 October 2008}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[East Turkestan Islamic Movement|ETIM]]\n* {{flagicon|Afghanistan|Taliban}} [[Tehrik-i-Taliban Pakistan|TTP]]\n* [[File:Flag of Waziristan resistance (1930s).svg|22px]] [[Islamic Emirate of Waziristan|IEW]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Sipah-e-Sahaba Pakistan]]\n* {{flagicon|Afghanistan|Taliban}} [[Tehreek-e-Nafaz-e-Shariat-e-Mohammadi|TNSM]]\n* {{flagicon image|Flag of Jihad.svg}} [[Islamic Jihad Union|IJU]]\n* {{Flagicon image|Flag of Lashkar-e-Jhangvi.svg}} [[Lashkar-e-Jhangvi]]<ref name=\"The Washington Post\">{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/rare-attack-in-kabul-targets-shiite-mosque/2011/12/06/gIQAVnEkYO_story.html?tid=pm_pop| work=The Washington Post with Foreign Policy| title=Pakistan-based group claims role in deadly blast in Kabul| date=7 December 2011| first=Craig| last=Whitlock}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon image|Harakat flag.png}} [[Harkat-ul-Mujahideen]]\n* [[Mullah Dadullah Front]]\n\n|commander1={{flagicon|US}} [[Barack Obama]]<br />\n{{flagicon|US}} [[Joseph F. Dunford, Jr.]]<br />\n{{flagicon|US}} [[John O. Brennan]]<br />\n{{flagicon|US}} [[James B. Cunningham]]\n| commander2  = Various\n| strength1   = \n| strength2   = \n| casualties1 = \n| casualties2 = \n| campaignbox = {{Campaignbox Afghan War}}\n| casus       = \n}}\n\nThe '''withdrawal of U.S. troops from [[Afghanistan]]''' describes the draw down of [[United States Armed Forces]] in the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|Afghanistan war]] and the plans after its post-2014 presence when most combat troops had left Afghanistan at the end of 2014.\n\nNATO had planned on maintaining 13,000 troops including 9,800 Americans in an advisory and counter-terrorism capacity in Afghanistan during the [[War in Afghanistan (2015\u2013present)|2015 phase of the War in Afghanistan]] and they were expected to maintain a presence inside Afghanistan until well after the end of 2016. In July 2016, in light of the deteriorating security conditions, the US postponed the withdrawal until December 2016 and decided to maintain a force of 8,400 troops in 4 garrisons (Kabul, Kandahar, Bagram and Jalalabad) indefinitely due to Taliban resurgence attempt after the [[Battle of Kunduz]]. The withdrawal was completed in December 2016 leaving behind 8,400 troops.\n\nIn September 2017, U.S. President Donald Trump started returning troops to Afghanistan<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ward |first1=Alex |title=Trump is sending more than 3,000 troops to Afghanistan |url=https://www.vox.com/world/2017/9/19/16227730/trump-afghanistan-3000-troops-mattis |accessdate=25 April 2020 |publisher=Vox |date=September 19, 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20191228110421/https://www.vox.com/world/2017/9/19/16227730/trump-afghanistan-3000-troops-mattis |archivedate=December 28, 2019}}</ref> On March 10, 2020, [[Centcom]] rejected reports that the U.S. military had developed a plan to withdraw all U.S. troops from Afghanistan, despite planning to reduce the number of U.S. troops in Afghanistan to 8,600 in a 14-month period.<ref name=\"partialonly\">{{cite news |title=CENTCOM boss says military plans for withdrawal from Afghanistan not developed yet |url=https://www.militarytimes.com/flashpoints/2020/03/10/centcom-boss-say-military-plans-for-withdrawal-from-afghanistan-not-developed-yet/ |accessdate=25 April 2020 |publisher=Military Times |date=March 10, 2020 |archiveurl=https://www.militarytimes.com/flashpoints/2020/03/10/centcom-boss-say-military-plans-for-withdrawal-from-afghanistan-not-developed-yet/ |archivedate=March 29, 2020}}</ref> However, the U.S. Army later confirmed that more troops will be sent to Afghanistan in the summer of 2020.<ref name=moretroops />\n\n==Background==\n===2009 U.S. troops increase under the Obama Administration===\nTroop levels remained roughly constant under U.S. president [[Barack Obama]]'s predecessor, former president [[George W. Bush]], with around 30,000 American troops deployed in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Interactive: Ten years of war|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/interactive/2011/06/201162215293134264.html|publisher=Al Jazeera English|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=22 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"TP20110622\">{{cite web|title=GRAPH: Obama 'Withdrawal' Plan Would Leave More Troops In Afghanistan Than When He Began His Presidency|url=http://thinkprogress.org/security/2011/06/22/250807/obamas-troop-reduction-afghanistan/?mobile=nc|publisher=Thinkprogress|accessdate=4 September 2012|author=Zaid Jilani|date=22 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Montopoli |first=Brian |title=Chart: Troop Levels in Afghanistan Over the Years |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-5855314-503544.html |publisher=CBS News |accessdate=6 September 2012 |date=1 December 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026010045/http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-5855314-503544.html |archivedate=26 October 2012 }}</ref> In January, about 3,000 U.S. soldiers from the 3rd Brigade Combat Team of the 10th Mountain Division moved into the provinces of [[Logar Province|Logar]] and [[Wardak Province|Wardak]]. The troops were the first wave of an expected surge of reinforcements originally ordered by [[George W. Bush]] and increased by Barack Obama.<ref>{{cite news|title=Start of Afghanistan surge: Newest US troops sent to dangerous region near Kabul|url=http://articles.nydailynews.com/2009-02-17/news/17916116_1_logar-province-insurgents-kabul|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)]]|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=17 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=3,000 troops near Kabul mark start of surge|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/id/29226669|agency=Associated Press|publisher=[[NBC News]]|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=16 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 February 2009, Barack Obama ordered 17,000 more US troops be sent to Afghanistan to bolster security in the country and thereby boosted the 36,000 US troops already there by 50%.<ref name=\"NYT20090217\">{{cite news|last=Cooper|first=Helene|title=Putting Stamp on Afghan War, Obama Will Send 17,000 Troops|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/18/washington/18web-troops.html|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=17 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Pidd|first=Helen|title=Obama commits 17,000 more US troops to Afghanistan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/feb/18/obama-afghanistan-troops|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=18 February 2012|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Rooney|first=Katie|title=Barack Obama's First 100 Days: A Surge for Afghanistan|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,1889908_1893383_1893741,00.html|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=Time Magazine|date=28 April 2009}}</ref> \"This increase is necessary to stabilize a deteriorating situation in Afghanistan, which has not received the strategic attention, direction and resources it urgently requires,\" Obama said in a written statement.<ref name=\"CNN20090217\">{{cite news|last=Starr|first=Barbara|title=Obama approves Afghanistan troop increase|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2009-02-17/politics/obama.troops_1_afghanistan-troop-increase-troop-levels?_s=PM:POLITICS|publisher=CNN|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=17 February 2012}}</ref> \"The [[Taliban]] is resurgent in Afghanistan, and [[al-Qa'ida|Al-Qaeda]] supports the insurgency and threatens America from its safe haven along the Pakistani border,\" Obama also said.<ref name=\"Australian20090219\" /> He recognised \"the extraordinary strain this deployment places on our troops and military families\", but the deteriorating security situation in the region required \"urgent attention and swift action\".<ref name=\"Australian20090219\">{{cite news|last=Hodge|first=Amanda|title=Obama launches Afghanistan surge|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/obama-launches-afghanistan-surge/story-e6frg6t6-1111118893671|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The Australian|date=19 February 2012}}</ref> The new troop deployment was expected to include 8,000 [[U.S. Marines]] from [[Marine Corps Base Camp Lejeune|Camp Lejeune]], North Carolina,  4,000 [[U.S. Army]] troops from [[Joint Base Lewis-McChord|Fort Lewis, Washington]] and another 5,000 troops from an unspecified branch of the U.S. Armed Forces.<ref name=\"CNN20090217\" /> Obama also said he was \"absolutely convinced that you cannot solve the problem of Afghanistan, the Taliban, the spread of extremism in that region solely through military means.\"<ref name=\"NYT20090217\" />\n\nA further decision on sending more troops came after the administration completed a broader review of Afghanistan policy.<ref name=\"NYT20090217\" /> On 27 March 2009, Obama announced after an intense 60-day White House policy review,<ref name=\"WP20090327\">{{cite news|last=DeYoung|first=Karen|title=Obama Announces Strategy for Afghanistan, Pakistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/27/AR2009032700836.html|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=27 March 2012}}</ref> in which military commanders and diplomats, regional governments, partners, Nato allies, [[Non-governmental organization|NGOs]] and aid organisations were consulted,<ref name=\"BBCNews20090327\">{{cite news|title=US rethinks Afghanistan strategy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7966982.stm#map|work=BBC News|accessdate=6 September 2012|date=27 March 2009}}</ref> a new strategy for Afghanistan and [[Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama breaks with Bush Afghan policy|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/americas/7969071.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=6 September 2012|date=27 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTShear20110722\">{{cite news|last=Shear|first=Michael D.|title=Afghan Strategy Has Loomed Over Obama Presidency|url=http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/06/22/afghan-strategy-has-loomed-over-obama-presidency/|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 June 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Obama's Strategy for Afghanistan and Pakistan, March 2009|url=http://www.cfr.org/pakistan/obamas-strategy-afghanistan-pakistan-march-2009/p18952|publisher=Council on Foreign Relations|accessdate=6 September 2012|date=27 March 2009}}</ref> \"So I want the American people to understand that we have a clear and focused goal: to disrupt, dismantle, and defeat al-Qaida in Pakistan and Afghanistan, and to prevent their return to either country in the future. That is the goal that must be achieved. That is a cause that could not be more just. And to the terrorists who oppose us, my message is the same: we will defeat you,\" Obama said.<ref name=\"Guardian20090327\">{{cite news|title=Barack Obama sets out new strategy for Afghanistan war|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/mar/27/obama-new-strategy-afghanistan-war|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=27 March 2009|author=Ewen MacAskill|location=London}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20090327\">{{cite news|last=Stout|first=David|title=Obama Sounds Cautious Note as He Sets Out Afghan Plan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/26/washington/28prexy.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=27 March 2012}}</ref> For this purpose Obama announced that he plans to further bolster American forces in Afghanistan, increase aid to Pakistan, and set strict standards \u2013 like levels of violence and casualties in Afghanistan, Pakistani attacks against insurgents and accounting for U.S. aid<ref name=\"WP20090327\" /> \u2013 for measuring progress in fighting Al Qaeda and the Taliban in both countries.<ref name=\"NYT20090327\" /> Part of his strategy was the deployment of 4,000 U.S. troops \u2013 beyond the additional 17,000 he authorized in February\u2014to work as trainers and advisers to the Afghan army and police.<ref name=\"WP20090327\" /><ref name=\"BBCNews20090327\" /><ref name=\"Guardian20090327\" /> The move was accompanied by a \"surge\"  in US civilians to Afghanistan to help rebuild the country's infrastructure.<ref name=\"Guardian20090327\" /> In addition to the renewed focus on Afghanistan, the Obama administration was to step up pressure on Pakistan to tackle the al-Qaida and Taliban safe havens in the tribal areas along its border with Afghanistan. US military and civilian aid was to be increased. The last element of the policy was to try to engage Afghanistan's regional neighbours, including Russia and Iran, in helping to pacify Afghanistan.<ref name=\"Guardian20090327\" />\n\n\"There is no imminent threat of the government being overthrown, but the Taliban has gained momentum,\" Obama said with respect to the 2009 situation in Afghanistan. \"Al Qaeda has not reemerged in Afghanistan in the same numbers as before 9/11, but they retain their safe-havens along the border. And our forces lack the full support they need to effectively train and partner with Afghan Security Forces and better secure the population.\"<ref name=\"CBSNews20091201\" /> On 1 December 2009, Obama therefore announced at The United States Military Academy in West Point that the U.S. will be sending 30,000 more troops to Afghanistan and set July 2011 as the date to begin pulling U.S. forces out of the country.<ref name=\"NYTShear20110722\" /><ref name=\"CBSNews20091201\">{{cite news|title=Obama Lays Out New Afghanistan Strategy|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/2100-250_162-5855734.html|publisher=CBS News|accessdate=4 September 2012|author=Brian Montopoli|date=1 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Rogin|first=Josh|title=Confirmed: Obama to \"surge\" 30,000 troops to Afghanistan and \"begin\" withdrawal in July 2011|url=http://thecable.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2009/12/01/confirmed_obama_to_surge_30000_troops_to_afghanistan_and_begin_withdrawal_in_july_2|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=Foreign Policy|date=1 December 2012}}</ref> Promising that he could \"bring this war to a successful conclusion,\" Obama set out a strategy that would seek to reverse Taliban gains in large parts of Afghanistan, better protect the Afghan people, increase the pressure on Afghanistan to build its own military capacity and a more effective government and step up attacks on Al Qaeda in Pakistan.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama Adds Troops, but Maps Exit Plan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/02/world/asia/02prexy.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=1 December 2012|author1=Sheryl Gay Stolberg  |author2=Helene Cooper |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> The president said the three core elements to the new strategy are \"a military effort to create the conditions for a transition; a civilian surge that reinforces positive action; and an effective partnership with Pakistan.\"<ref name=\"CBSNews20091201\" /> The overarching goal was to \"disrupt, dismantle, and defeat al Qaeda in Afghanistan and Pakistan, and to prevent its capacity to threaten America and our allies in the future.\"<ref name=\"CBSNews20091201\" /> The West Point Speech concluded a three-month review of war strategy.<ref name=\"WP20091202\">{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Scott|title=Obama: U.S. security is still at stake|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/12/01/AR2009120101231.html|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=2 December 2009}}</ref>  During the review, Obama asked for province-by-province assessments of the Taliban's strength, the effectiveness of provincial Afghan leaders and the overall security outlook to determine how quickly U.S. forces could leave certain regions.<ref name=\"WP20091202\" /> In the months leading up to his West Point speech, more precisely at a meeting with the Joint Chiefs of Staff on 30 Oct. 2009 to discuss his troops surge plan, Obama stated that the Afghanistan War is an American war, but he doesn't want to it make an open-ended commitment.<ref name=\"NYT20091205\">{{cite news|last=Baker|first=Peter|title=How Obama Came to Plan for 'Surge' in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/06/world/asia/06reconstruct.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=5 December 2009}}</ref> Obama also was livid that details of the 3 month Afghanistan War Review discussions were leaking out according to the New York Times.<ref name=\"NYT20091205\" /> \"What I'm not going to tolerate is you talking to the press outside of this room,\" he scolded his advisers. \"It's a disservice to the process, to the country and to the men and women of the military.\"<ref name=\"NYT20091205\" /> In addition to the 30,000 additional U.S. troops that Obama announced to deploy to Afghanistan Obama sent an additional 22,000 forces (which were earlier announced in 2009 (compare section above)) along with 11,000 troops that were authorized by his predecessor to Afghanistan.<ref name=\"WP20091202\" />\n\n===2010 London Conference on Afghanistan and 2010 Afghanistan War Review===\nDuring the [[International Conference on Afghanistan, London (2010)|London Conference on Afghanistan]] Afghanistan announced on 28 January 2010 its intention of taking charge of the \"majority of operations in the insecure areas of Afghanistan within three years and taking responsibility for physical security within five years\".<ref name=\"BBC20100128\">{{cite news|title=Afghanistan: Security transition 'by end of 2010'|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/8485861.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=9 September 2012|date=28 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Reynolds|first=Paul|title=Aims of the London conference on Afghanistan|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/8480368.stm|work=BBC News|accessdate=9 September 2012|date=28 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Afghan forces to take control of security within three years|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/jan/28/gordon-brown-afghanistan-conference-taliban|accessdate=9 September 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=28 January 2010|author1=Andrew Sparrow  |author2=Julian Borger |lastauthoramp=yes |location=London}}</ref> This combined with the increase of Afghan military strength to 171,600 and police numbers to 134,000 by October 2011 would enable the United States could begin to transition U.S. troops out of Afghanistan in July 2011 according to US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.<ref name=\"BBC20100128\" /><ref name=\"CNN20100129\">{{cite news|title=Afghan conference sets deadlines for NATO handover|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/01/28/uk.afghanistan/index.html|publisher=CNN News|accessdate=9 September 2012|author1=Elise Labott, Jill Dougherty  |author2=Alan Silverleib |lastauthoramp=yes |date=29 January 2010}}</ref> \"It's not an exit strategy, it's about assisting the Afghans\" in taking responsibility for their own security, she explained.<ref name=\"CNN20100129\" />\n\nDeclaring significant progress in disrupting al-Qaeda and combatting the Taliban, Obama said on 16 December 2010 that the United States will start withdrawing U.S. troops from Afghanistan in July 2011.<ref name=\"NYTShear20110722\" /><ref name=\"WP20101216\">{{cite news|last=DeYoung|first=Karin|title=Obama says U.S. is 'on track' to achieve goals in Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/12/16/AR2010121601259.html|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=16 December 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Obama Cites Afghan Gains as Report Says Exit Is on Track|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/12/17/world/asia/17afghan.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=16 December 2010|author1=Helene Cooper  |author2=David E. Sanger |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> Obama said \"we are on track to achieve our goals\" in the Afghan war and to \"start reducing our forces next July.\"<ref name=\"WP20101216\" /> He added the drawdown will \"conclude in 2014.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Af-Pak policy review: Obama admits Afghan gains not sustainable|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/91262/af-pak-policy-review-obama-admits-afghan-gains-not-sustainable/|work=Agence France-Presse (AFP)|publisher=The Express Tribune|accessdate=6 September 2012}}</ref> Obama appeared before reporters to announce the results of the Afghanistan war review,<ref>{{cite news|title=Barack Obama: Afghanistan war is on track|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2010/dec/16/obama-afghanistan-on-track|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The Guardian|date=16 December 2010|author=Chris McGreal|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Greenblatt|first=Alan|title=5 Things The Afghan War Review Didn't Say|url=https://www.npr.org/2010/12/16/132111316/5-things-the-afghan-war-review-didnt-say|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=6 September 2012|date=16 December 2010}}</ref> which was compiled from reports submitted by military, diplomatic and intelligence officials since mid-October 2010.<ref name=\"WP20101216\" /> The president had directed his national security staff to perform a \"diagnostic\" assessment of the December 2009 West point strategy after one year.<ref name=\"WP20101216\" /> They convened eight working-group and deputy-level meetings from 16 Nov. through 1 Dec.. An interagency team also visited Afghanistan and Pakistan from 25 October through 4 November to discuss the situation with key leaders first-hand.<ref name=\"HuffPost20101216\" /> The summary document of the review included no specifics as to the potential size or pace of withdrawal, making no assessment as to whether any milestones have been reached and leaving substantial wiggle room for future decisions. \"As a result of our integrated efforts in 2010,\" the report said, \"we are setting the conditions to begin transition to Afghan security lead in early 2011 and to begin a responsible, conditions-based U.S. troop reduction in July 2011.\"<ref name=\"WP20101216\" /> The review concluded that the military surge of 30,000 troops has been a success, saying it \"reduced overall Taliban influence and arrested the momentum they had achieved in recent years in key parts of the country.\" It added, however, that successes remain \"fragile and reversible.\"<ref name=\"HuffPost20101216\">{{cite news|last=Terkel|first=Amanda|title=Afghanistan Strategy Review: Obama's Af-Pak Review Touts Progress, Lays Framework For Sustained Commitment|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/12/16/obamas-afghanistan-pakistan-review-progress-sustained-commitment_n_797472.html|accessdate=6 September 2012|newspaper=The Huffington Post|date=16 December 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2011 Drawdown Speech===\nOn 22 June 2011, Obama addressed the nation from the White House and announced that 10,000 troops would be withdrawn by the end of 2011 and an additional 23,000 troops will leave the country by the summer of 2012. He said the drawdown would continue \"at a steady pace\" until the United States handed over security to the Afghan authorities in 2014.<ref name=\"NYT20110622\" /><ref>{{cite news|last=DeYoung|first=Karen|title=Obama's drawdown in Afghanistan will shift tactics in war|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/national-security/obamas-drawdown-in-afghanistan-will-shift-tactics-in-war/2011/06/22/AGsVJagH_story.html|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=23 June 2012}}</ref> \"We are starting this drawdown from a position of strength,\" Obama said. \"Al Qaeda is under more pressure than at any time since [[9/11]].\"<ref name=\"NYT20110622\" /> Asserting that the country that served as a base for 11 September 2001 attacks no longer represented a terrorist threat to the United States, Obama declared that the \"tide of war is receding.\"<ref name=\"NYT20110622\">{{cite news|title=Obama Will Speed Pullout From War in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/23/world/asia/23prexy.html?hp|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 June 2012|author1=Mark Landler  |author2=Helene Cooper |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> The announced drawdown will leave approximately 68,000 U.S. troops in Afghanistan by the autumn of 2012 according to ''[[The Huffington Post]]'',<ref name=\"HP20110722\">{{cite news|last=Terkel|first=Amanda|title=Obama Announces Afghanistan Troop Withdrawal In Speech To Nation|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/06/22/obama-afghanistan-troop-withdrawal_n_882451.html|accessdate=4 September 2012|newspaper=The Hufftington Post|date=22 June 2011}}</ref> but Gen. John R. Allen, commander of the International Security Assistance Force (ISAF), said that 23,000 of the 88,000 U.S. troops currently in Afghanistan will be home by 30 September 2012 and thus 65,000 U.S. troops will remain in Afghanistan after the so-called Phase 2 drawdown.<ref name=\"CNN20120523\">{{cite news|last=Shaughnessy|first=Larry|title=Allen: U.S. troop drawdown from Afghanistan to begin 'very shortly'|url=http://articles.cnn.com/2012-05-23/politics/politics_us-troop-drawdown-afghanistan_1_afghanistan-army-and-police-troop-drawdown-special-operators?_s=PM:POLITICS|publisher=CNN|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=23 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==2011 Drawdown beginning and Plans for Ending the Afghanistan War==\n{{Further|U.S.-Afghanistan Strategic Partnership Agreement}}\nThe U.S. drawdown in Afghanistan began 13 July 2011 when the first 650 U.S. troops left Afghanistan as part of Obama's planned drawdown.<ref name=\"Reuters20110715\">{{cite news|last=Nichols|first=Michelle|title=U.S. drawdown begins in Afghanistan|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/07/15/us-usa-afghanistan-drawdown-idUSTRE76E26B20110715|work=Reuters|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=15 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Vogt|first=Heidi|title=Afghanistan Drawdown: First U.S. Troops Hand Over Battlefield And Begin Packing|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/13/afghanistan-drawdown-us-troops-battlefield-_n_897457.html|agency=Associated Press|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=13 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Radin|first=CJ|title=US begins drawdown of forces from Afghanistan|publisher=The Long War Journal \u2013 A Project of the Foundation for Defense of Democracies|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=15 July 2012|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2011/07/us_begins_drawdown_o.php}}</ref>  The units that left were two Army National Guard cavalry squadrons: the 1st Squadron, [[134th Cavalry Regiment (United States)|134th Cavalry Regiment]], based in Kabul, and the 1st Squadron, [[113th Cavalry Regiment]], which had been in neighboring [[Parwan province]].<ref name=\"Reuters20110715\" />\n\nThe United States and its [[w:North Atlantic Treaty Organization|NATO]] allies finalized agreements on 18 April 2012 to wind down the war in Afghanistan by formalizing three commitments: to move the Afghans gradually into a lead combat role; to keep some international troops in Afghanistan beyond 2014, and to pay billions of dollars a year to help support the Afghan security forces.<ref>{{cite news|last=Bumiller|first=Elisabeth|title=U.S. and NATO Finalize Pacts on Ending Afghan War|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/19/world/asia/united-states-and-nato-allies-near-deal-on-afghan-aid.html?_r=1&ref=asia|accessdate=19 April 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=18 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NATO ministers to mull Afghan strategy ahead of alliance summit in Chicago|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/nato-ministers-to-mull-afghan-strategy-ahead-of-alliance-summit-in-chicago/2012/04/17/gIQA7lpWNT_story.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120418055551/http://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/nato-ministers-to-mull-afghan-strategy-ahead-of-alliance-summit-in-chicago/2012/04/17/gIQA7lpWNT_story.html |archive-date=18 April 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2012|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=17 April 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"Washington Post 20120418\">{{cite news|last=Jaffe|first=Greg|title=U.S. says 2014 troop pullout is on track in Afghanistan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-allies-and-afghan-government-ready-plan-for-end-of-combat-operations-in-2014/2012/04/18/gIQAX9bZQT_story.html |accessdate=19 April 2012 |newspaper=The Washington Post|date=18 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 2 May 2012, Afghan president [[Hamid Karzai]] and U.S. president Barack Obama signed a strategic partnership agreement between the two countries, after the U.S. president had arrived in [[Kabul]] as part of unannounced trip to Afghanistan on the first anniversary of [[death of Osama bin Laden|Osama bin Laden's death]].<ref name=\"NYT20120501\">{{cite news|last=Landler|first=Mark|title=Obama Signs Pact in Kabul, Turning Page in Afghan War|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/world/asia/obama-lands-in-kabul-on-unannounced-visit.html?_r=2&ref=barackobama|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=1 May 2012}}</ref> The [[U.S.-Afghanistan Strategic Partnership Agreement]], officially titled the \"Enduring Strategic Partnership Agreement between the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan and the United States of America\",<ref>{{cite web|title=Enduring Strategic Partnership Agreement between the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan and the United States of America|url=https://www.scribd.com/doc/92057506/Afghan-US-Strategic-Pact-Full-Text|publisher=[[Scribd]]|accessdate=4 May 2012}}</ref> provides the long-term framework for the relationship between Afghanistan and the United States of America after the drawdown of U.S. forces in the Afghanistan war.<ref name=\"Sweet20120501\" /> The agreement went into effect on 4 July 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=Clinton|first=Hillary|title=Press Releases: Intervention at the Tokyo Conference on Afghanistan|url=http://www.newsroomamerica.com/story/260678.html|publisher=NewsRoomAmerica.com|accessdate=8 July 2012|date=8 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105204658/http://www.newsroomamerica.com/story/260678.html|archive-date=5 November 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nAfter the signing of the strategic partnership agreement Obama laid out his plans to end the war in Afghanistan responsibly. The plans call for 1) the removal of 23,000 US troops at the summer end of 2012, i.e. at the end of September 2012;<ref name=\"WP20120512\">{{cite news|title=The triage commander: Gen. John Allen hastily transforming U.S. mission in Afghanistan |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/the-triage-commander-gen-john-allen-hastily-transforming-us-mission-in-afghanistan/2012/05/12/gIQAzbttKU_story_2.html |accessdate=13 May 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=12 May 2012|author=Rajiv Chandrasekaran}}</ref> 2) Afghan security forces to take the lead in combat operations by the end of 2013 while [[International Security Assistance Force|ISAF forces]] train, advise and assist the Afghans and fight alongside them when needed; and 3) the complete removal of all U.S. troops by the end of 2014, except for trainers who will assist Afghan forces and a small contingent of troops with a specific mission to combat al-Qaeda through counterterrorism operations.<ref name=\"Sweet20120501\">{{cite news|last=Sweet|first=Lynn|title=U.S.-Afgan strategic agreement: Roadmap to Chicago NATO Summit. Briefing transcript|url=http://blogs.suntimes.com/sweet/2012/05/us-afgan_strategic_agreement_r.html|newspaper=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]|accessdate=4 May 2012|date=1 May 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120507215751/http://blogs.suntimes.com/sweet/2012/05/us-afgan_strategic_agreement_r.html|archive-date=7 May 2012|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"WP20120502\">{{cite news |title=Obama makes surprise trip to Afghanistan to sign key pact, mark bin Laden raid |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/obama-makes-surprise-visit-to-afghanistan/2012/05/01/gIQAvYHduT_story.html?hpid=z1 |accessdate=4 May 2012 |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=2 May 2012|author1=Kevin Sieff  |author2=Scott Wilson |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20120502\">{{cite news|title=In Speech, Obama Says U.S. Will Stand by Afghans After Troop Withdrawal |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/world/asia/president-obama-visits-kabul-to-sign-partnership-with-afghanistan.html |accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=1 May 2012|author=John H. Cushmann Jr.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Text of Obama's Speech in Afghanistan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/02/world/asia/text-obamas-speech-in-afghanistan.html?ref=asia|accessdate=4 May 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=1 May 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"AlJaz20120502\">{{cite web|title=Obama sees 'clear path' to end Afghan mission |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2012/05/20125123024682601.html |publisher=Al Jazeera|accessdate=4 May 2012|date=2 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==NATO Chicago Summit: Troops withdrawal and longterm presence==\n{{Further|2012 Chicago Summit|2011 NATO attack in Pakistan}}\nOn 21 May 2012 the leaders of the NATO-member countries endorsed an exit strategy during the 2012 NATO Summit in Chicago. The NATO-led ISAF Forces will hand over command of all combat missions to Afghan forces by the middle of 2013,<ref name=\"Reuters 20120521\">{{cite news|title=NATO sets \"irreversible\" but risky course to end Afghan war|url=http://ca.reuters.com/article/topNews/idCABRE84J02C20120521?sp=true|work=Reuters|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=22 May 2012|date=21 May 2012}}</ref> while shifting at the same time from combat to a support role of advising, training and assisting the Afghan security forces<ref name=\"Chicago Declaration\">{{cite web|title=Chicago NATO Summit 2012 Declaration|url=http://www.defencetalk.com/chicago-nato-summit-2012-declaration-42672/^^|work=[[NATO]]|publisher=Defence Talk \u2013 Global Defense, Aerospace & Military Portal|accessdate=20 June 2012|date=21 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=NATO leaders agree on framework to wind down Afghan mission|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/obama-other-nato-leaders-begin-crucial-summit-on-afghanistan/2012/05/21/gIQArWJYfU_story.html|accessdate=22 May 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=21 May 2012|author1=Scott Wilson  |author2=Karen DeYoung |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> and then withdraw most of the 130,000 foreign troops by the end of December 2014.<ref name=\"Reuters 20120521\" /> A new and different NATO mission will then advise, train and assist the Afghan security forces including the Afghan Special Operations Forces.<ref name=\"Chicago Declaration\" /><ref name=\"Elise Labott and Mike Mount\">{{cite news|title=NATO accepts Obama timetable to end war in Afghanistan by 2014|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/05/21/us/nato-summit/index.html?hpt=hp_t3|publisher=CNN|accessdate=22 May 2012|author1=Elise Labott  |author2=Mike Mount |lastauthoramp=yes |date=22 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Tokyo Conference on Afghanistan==\nThe Tokyo Conference on Afghanistan,<ref>{{cite web|title=Donor nations pledge $16bn to Afghanistan|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2012/07/20127851859576656.html|publisher=Al Jazeera English|accessdate=11 July 2012|date=8 July 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Vaz|first=Aaron|title=Infographic: Afghanistan aid pledges|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/interactive/2012/07/20127894049185933.html|publisher=Al Jazeera English|accessdate=11 July 2012|date=8 July 2012}}</ref> held on 8 July 2012 was the civilian-diplomatic bookend to NATO's 2012 May summit in Chicago, where the alliance confirmed plans to withdraw foreign combat troops by the end of 2014 and pledged about $4 billion a year to pay for ongoing training, equipment and financial support for Afghanistan's security forces.<ref>{{cite news|title=Corruption in Afghanistan still a problem as international donors meet|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/corruption-in-afghanistan-still-a-problem-as-international-donors-meet/2012/07/06/gJQAhxjgSW_story.html?tid=pm_world_pop|accessdate=11 July 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=7 July 2012|author1=Karen DeYoung  |author2=Joshua Partlow |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> In exchange for pledges from the Afghan government to combat corruption $16 billion over the next four years for civilian projects such as roads to schools or projects aimed to strengthen the rule of law were pledged by the some 70 nations attending the conference.<ref>{{cite news|title=International donors pledge $16 billion in aid to Afghanistan over four years|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/international-donors-pledge-16-billion-in-aid-to-afghanistan-over-four-years/2012/07/08/gJQABfA5VW_story.html|accessdate=11 July 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=8 July 2012|author=Stephanie McCrummen}}</ref> The reconstruction and development aid<ref>{{cite news|title=UN chief warns donors against holding Afghan aid hostage with reform demands|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/07/08/world/asia/afghanistan-donor-conference/index.html?eref=rss_latest|publisher=CNN|accessdate=11 July 2012|author=Chelsea J. Carter|date=8 July 2012}}</ref> was pledged for the timeframe through 2015, but under the condition that the Afghan government reduce corruption before receiving all of the money. In the so-called Tokyo Framework of Mutual Accountability foreign governments will assure Afghanistan a steady stream of financing in exchange for stronger anticorruption measures and the establishment of the rule of law. Up to 20 percent of the money would depend on the government meeting governance standards according to the Tokyo Framework of Mutual Accountability.<ref name=\"NYT20120708\">{{cite news|last=Perlez|first=Jane|title=$16 Billion in Civilian Aid Pledged to Afghanistan, With Conditions|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/09/world/asia/afghanistan-is-pledged-16-billion-for-civilian-needs.html?_r=2&ref=world|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=11 July 2012|date=8 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n\"We will fight corruption with strong resolve wherever it occurs, and ask the same of our international partners,\" Karzai told the donors. \"Together we must stop the practices that feed corruption or undermine the legitimacy and effectiveness of national institutions.\"<ref name=\"Talmadge\" /> The international aid is tied to a mechanism that will regularly review how it is being spent, and to guarantees from Kabul that it will seriously take on its deep-rooted corruption problems \u2013 what the conference called a roadmap of accountability. Kabul must also demonstrate efforts to improve governance and finance management, and safeguard the democratic process, rule of law and human rights \u2013 especially those of women.<ref name=\"Talmadge\" /> US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton stressed the need for reform to safeguard changes achieved in Afghanistan. \"That must include fighting corruption, improving governance, strengthening the rule of law, increasing access to economic opportunity for all Afghans, especially for women,\" she said.<ref name=\"BBC20120708\" /> A follow-up conference will be held in Britain in 2014.<ref name=\"BBC20120708\">{{cite news|title=Afghanistan aid: Donors pledge $16bn at Tokyo meeting|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-18758148|work=BBC News Asia|accessdate=11 July 2012|date=8 July 2012}}</ref> The meeting in Britain in 2014 will check progress toward \"mutual accountability\" and a review and monitoring process to assure that development aid is not diverted by corrupt officials or mismanaged \u2013 both of which have been major hurdles in putting aid projects into practice thus far.<ref name=\"Talmadge\">{{cite news|last=Talmadge |first=Eric |title=Afghan donors offer $16B in development aid |url=http://www.knoe.com/story/18970911/international-donors-pledging-16b-in-afghan-aid |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130127210326/http://www.knoe.com/story/18970911/international-donors-pledging-16b-in-afghan-aid |url-status=dead |archive-date=27 January 2013 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=knoe.com |accessdate=12 July 2012 |date=8 July 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Security handover and U.S. Suspension of Afghan Local Police forces training==\nThe U.S. was set to hand over responsibility for security to local Afghans by 2014, and efforts were underway to draw down U.S. forces, but Obama never specified a date for the withdrawal of all American troops from the country.<ref name=\"TheHill20120902\">{{cite news|title=Carney: No Obama plan to withdraw all US troops from Afghanistan by 2014|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/defcon-hill/policy-and-strategy/247135-carney-no-obama-plan-to-withdraw-all-us-troops-from-afghanistan-by-2014|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=2 September 2012|author=Meghashyam Mai}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=10 Facts About US Withdrawal from Afghanistan|url=http://countdowntodrawdown.org/facts.php|publisher=Just Foreign Policy|accessdate=3 September 2012}}</ref> Obama said on 1 September 2012 that he had a \"specific plan to bring our troops home from Afghanistan by the end of 2014.\" <ref name=\"TheHill20120902\" /> On 2 September 2012 White House press secretary [[Jay Carney]] then clarified Obama's statement by saying that Obama had \"never said that all the troops would be out.\" Carney noted while the United States would transfer security to Afghan troops by the end of 2014, all U.S. troops would not be out of the country by that date.<ref name=\"TheHill20120902\" /> \"Everyone understands what the president's policy is, which is a full transition to Afghan security lead by 2014,\" said Carney. \"We have been abundantly clear about the stages of the implementation of that policy. And [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq (2007\u20132011)|as in Iraq]], that means that while not all U.S. troops will have withdrawn necessarily by then, the Afghan Security Forces will be in full security transition, I mean, will be in full security lead, and U.S. forces will continue to be drawn down.\"<ref name=\"TheHill20120902\" />\n\n===\"Green-on-blue\" attacks hampering handover===\nThe effort to handover security to Afghans has been hampered by a spike in attacks by local forces supposed to be working with American and NATO personnel.<ref name=\"TheHill20120902\" /><ref name=\"APHP20120902\" /> United States military officials suspended temporarily<ref name=\"CNN20120903\" /> on 2 September 2012 the training of Afghan Local Police (ALP) in the wake of a deadly series of so-called 'green on blue' attacks<ref name=\"CNN20120903\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Timeline: Green on blue attacks in Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/special/world/afghan-rogue-attacks-timeline/|accessdate= 3 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Attacks on NATO troops by Afghan security forces on the rise|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/attacks-on-nato-troops-by-afghan-security-forces-on-the-rise/2012/08/17/1f000d54-e8d6-11e1-936a-b801f1abab19_graphic.html|accessdate= 3 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date= 17 August 2012}}</ref> by Afghan soldiers and police on their international allies.<ref>{{cite web|title=Blue-on-green violence: US Special Forces suspend training of Afghans|url=http://www.middle-east-online.com/english/?id=54162|work=Middle East Online|publisher=Middle East Online|accessdate=3 September 2012|date= 2 September 2012}}</ref>  The training has been put on hold in order to carry out intensified vetting procedures on new recruits, and 16,000 existing ALP recruits will be re-vetted.<ref name=\"NBCNews20120902\" /> ALP training is a U.S. mission, carried out by Special Forces teams who work with Afghan elders and government officials in remote villages to help villagers defend themselves against insurgent attacks and intimidation.<ref name=\"WP20120902\" /> Training of uniformed police and army personnel is done under the banner of the NATO operation.<ref name=\"NBCNews20120902\">{{cite web|title=U.S. suspends training for some Afghan recruits after 'insider' attacks|url=http://worldnews.nbcnews.com/_news/2012/09/02/13618137-us-suspends-training-for-some-afghan-recruits-after-insider-attacks?lite|work=NBC News staff|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=3 September 2012}}</ref> The suspension affects not only Afghan Local Police, but also Afghan special operations and commando forces.<ref name=\"NYT20120902\">{{cite news|title=U.S. Halting Program to Train Afghan Recruits|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/09/02/world/asia/nato-halting-program-to-train-afghan-recruits.html?hp|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date= 2 September 2012|author1=Graham Bowley  |author2=Richard A. Oppel Jr. |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> Special Operations officials said that they anticipate it will take about two months to rescreen all of the Afghan forces and that the training of new recruits could stall for as long as a month.<ref name=\"WP20120902\" />\n\nThe Washington Post reported many 'green on blue' attacks might have been prevented if existing security measures had been applied correctly, but according to NATO officials numerous military guidelines were not followed \u2014 by Afghans or Americans \u2014 because of concerns that they might slow the growth of the Afghan army and police.<ref name=\"WP20120902\">{{cite news|title=Training suspended for new Afghan recruits|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/training-suspended-for-new-afghan-recruits/2012/09/01/adc4ed1c-f398-11e1-b74c-84ed55e0300b_story.html|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=2 September 2012|author1=Greg Jaffe  |author2=Kevin Sieff |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> Despite that the current process for vetting recruits is effective, a lack of follow-up has allowed Afghan troops who fell under the sway of [[Taliban insurgency|the insurgency]] or grew disillusioned with the Afghan government to remain in the force.<ref name=\"WP20120902\" /> In other instances the vetting process for Afghan soldiers and police was never properly implemented. NATO officials knew it according to the Washington Post, but they looked the other way, worried that extensive background checks could hinder the recruitment process.<ref name=\"WP20120902\" /> Also ignored were requirements that Afghans display proper credentials while on base. Many Afghans, even those who were vetted, were never issued official badges, making it impossible to tell who was supposed to have access to any particular facility.<ref name=\"WP20120902\" /> Measures specifically designed to curtail attacks (American and NATO service members should for example always carry a loaded magazine in their weapons to save precious moments if attacked by Afghan forces)<ref name=\"NYT20120818\">{{cite news|title=Afghan Attacks on Allied Troops Prompt NATO to Shift Policy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/08/19/world/asia/afghan-attacks-on-allied-troops-prompt-nato-to-shift-policy.html?_r=1&hp&pagewanted=all|accessdate=3 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=18 August 2012|author1=Richard A. Oppel  |author2=Graham Bowley |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> were also inconsistently applied.<ref name=\"WP20120902\" /> The \"Guardian Angel\" program (The program calls for one or two soldiers to monitor the Afghans during every mission or meeting. These soldiers, \"angels\" called and whose identities are not disclosed to the Afghans, must be prepared to fire on anyone who tries to kill a coalition service member.)<ref name=\"NYT20120818\" /> was often seen as a distraction from NATO's mission. Calls to minimize off-duty time spent with Afghan troops were similarly thought by NATO officials to undermine the goal of relationship-building, but according to a directive from NATO leaders troops are now being advised to stay away from Afghan soldiers and police officers during vulnerable moments, such as when they are sleeping, bathing or exercising.<ref name=\"WP20120902\" /> Additional security measures include improved training for counterintelligence agents, a more intense vetting system for new recruits, establishing an anonymous reporting system for soldiers to report suspicious activity; increasing the presence of Afghan counterintelligence teams among Afghan troops; banning the sale of Afghan army and police uniforms to help stop infiltrators posing as soldiers and policemen; and revetting soldiers when they return home from leave.<ref name=\"APHP20120902\">{{cite news|last=Vogt|first=Heidi|title=U.S Halts Training Of Some Afghanistan Forces In Light Of Green-On-Blue Violence|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/02/afghanistan-police-training-green-on-blue_n_1850065.html?ref=topbar|agency=Associated Press|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=4 September 2012|date=2 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN20120903\">{{cite news|title=ISAF: U.S. temporarily halts training of Afghan police over attacks|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/09/02/world/asia/afghanistan-training-halted/index.html|work=3 September 2012|publisher=CNN|accessdate=3 September 2012|author=Masoud Popalzai|date=3 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20120902\" /><ref name=\"BBCNews20120902\">{{cite news|title=Afghan police recruits' training halted after attacks on Nato|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-19454742|work=BBC News Asia|accessdate=3 September 2012|date=2 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe Afghan army has detained or sacked hundreds of soldiers for having links to insurgents, the Defence Ministry said on 5 September 2012 as it tried to stem the rising number of so-called insider attacks. \"Hundreds were sacked or detained after showing links with insurgents. In some cases we had evidence against them, in others we were simply suspicious,\" Defence Ministry spokesman Zahir Azimi told reporters in Kabul.<ref name=\"ReutersHP20120905\">{{cite news|title=Afghanistan: Hundreds Of Soldiers Detained, Fired For Insurgent Links (VIDEO)|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/05/afghan-soldiers-detained-fired_n_1856855.html?ref=topbar|work=Reuters|publisher=The Huffington Post|accessdate=6 September 2012|author=Mirwais Harooni|date=5 September 2012}}</ref> \"Using an army uniform against foreign forces is a serious point of concern not only for the Defence Ministry but for the whole Afghan government,\" Azimi said, adding that Karzai had ordered Afghan forces to devise ways to stop insider attacks.<ref name=\"ReutersHP20120905\" /> Azimi declined to say whether the detained and fired soldiers were from Taliban strongholds in the south and east, saying they were from all over the country. He said his ministry started an investigation into the attacks, called green-on-blue attacks, within the 195,000-strong Afghan army six months ago.<ref name=\"ReutersHP20120905\" />\n\nOn 18 September 2012 General John Allen suspended all joint combat operations between Afghanistan and American ground units in Afghanistan.\nUnder orders from the General interaction between coalition and Afghan forces would take place only at the battalion level. Allen made the move, along with suspending American-led Afghan training missions, due to growing concern over \"insider attacks\" against U.S. troops by members of the Afghan National Security Forces.<ref name=\"TheHill20120927\">{{cite news|last=Mu\u00f1oz|first=Carlo|title=US resumes joint operations with Afghan forces|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/defcon-hill/operations/259061-us-resumes-joint-operations-with-afghan-forces-|accessdate=28 September 2012|newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|date=27 September 2012}}</ref> Less than a week after the order U.S. and NATO combat troops resumed joint operations with Afghan forces.<ref name=\"TheHill20120927\" /><ref name=\"WP20120928\">{{cite news|last=Whitlock|first=Chris|title=U.S. resumes joint operations with Afghans|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-resumes-joint-operations-with-afghans/2012/09/27/8f5a1bf4-08e2-11e2-81ba-ffe35a7b6542_story.html|accessdate=28 September 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=28 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n==2013-06-18 Security handover from NATO to Afghan forces==\nOn 18 June 2013, the handover of security from NATO to Afghan forces was completed.<ref name=\"DW20130618\">{{cite web|title=Bomb blast hits Afghanistan on security handover day|url=http://www.dw.de/bomb-blast-hits-afghanistan-on-security-handover-day/a-16888374|work=Deutsche Welle|publisher=Deutsche Welle|accessdate=23 June 2013|date=19 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"AJE20130618\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=Karzai announces Afghan security handover|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/afp/130618/karzai-announces-afghan-security-handover|work=Agence France-Presse|publisher=Global Post|accessdate=23 June 2013|date=18 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"WSJ29130618\">{{cite news|last=Hodge|first=Nathan|title=Blast Mars Day of Security Handover in Kabul|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323566804578552593026745674#|accessdate=23 June 2013|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=18 June 2013}}</ref> The International Security Assistance Force formally handed over control of the last 95 districts to Afghan forces at a ceremony attended by Karzai and NATO Secretary General Anders Fogh Rasmussen at a military academy outside Kabul.<ref name=\"DW20130618\" /> Following the handover, Afghan forces will have the lead for security in all 403 districts of Afghanistan's 34 provinces. Before the handover they were responsible for 312 districts nationwide, where 80 percent of Afghanistan's population of nearly 30 million lives.<ref name=\"AJE20130618\" /> \"Our security and defense forces will now be in the lead,\" Karzai said. \"From here, all security responsibility and all security leadership will be taken by our brave forces. When people see security has been transferred to Afghans, they support the army and police more than before.\"<ref name=\"DW20130618\" /> Rasmussen said that by taking the lead in security on Tuesday, Afghan forces were completing a five-stage transition process that began in March 2011. \"They are doing so with remarkable resolve,\" he said. \"Ten years ago, there were no Afghan national security forces ... now you have 350,000 Afghan troops and police, a formidable force.\"<ref name=\"DW20130618\" /> he security transition signaled an important shift. The U.S.-led International Security Assistance Force is slated to end its mission by the end of 2014, and coalition forces are in the process of closing bases and shipping out equipment.<ref name=\"WSJ29130618\" /> Rasmussen stated that the focus of ISAF forces will shift from combat to support and that by the end of 2014 Afghanistan will be fully secured by Afghans. After the handover, 100,000 NATO forces will play a supporting and training role, as Afghan soldiers and police take the lead in the fight against armed groups.<ref name=\"AJE20130618\">{{cite web|title=Deadly blast marks Afghan security handover|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2013/06/20136184484852774.html|work=Al Jazeera English|publisher=Al Jazeera English|accessdate=23 June 2013|date=18 June 2013}}</ref> \"We will continue to help Afghan troops in operations if needed, but we will no longer plan, execute or lead those operations, and by the end of 2014 our combat mission will be completed,\" Rasmussen added.<ref name=\"DW20130618\" />\n\n==2013-06-19 Negotiations suspension of the Bilateral Security Agreement==\nPlans by the US to engage in peace talks with the Taliban have resulted in suspension of bilateral security discussions between the US and Afghanistan on 13 June 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=US-Afghan security talks suspended in row over Taliban peace negotiations |url=http://www.defencemanagement.com/news_story.asp?id=23246 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130624220846/http://www.defencemanagement.com/news_story.asp?id=23246 |url-status=dead |archive-date=24 June 2013 |publisher=Defence Management |accessdate=23 June 2013 |date=19 June 2013 }}</ref><ref name=\"WSJ20130618\">{{cite news|title=Afghan Leader Halts Talks With U.S., Taliban|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887323893504578554860777787962|accessdate=23 June 2013|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=19 June 2013|author1=Nathan Hodge  |author2=Yaroslav Trofimov |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> \"In a special meeting chaired by President Hamid Karzai, the president has decided to suspend talks about a security pact with the U.S. because of their inconsistent statements and actions in regard to the peace process,\" spokesman [[Aimal Faizi]] told Reuters.<ref name=\"Reuters20130618\">{{cite news|authors=Hamid Shalizi and Dylan Welch|title=Afghanistan suspends security pact talks with U.S.|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/06/19/us-afghanistan-usa-pact-idUSBRE95I08U20130619|work=Reuters|accessdate=23 June 2013|date=19 June 2013}}</ref> Secretary of State John Kerry discussed the flare-up with Karzai in phone calls on 19 June 2013, Afghan and U.S. officials said, part of the latest round of crisis diplomacy between Washington and Afghanistan's mercurial leader.<ref name=\"WSJ20130618\" /> Negotiations on the Bilateral Security Agreement (BSA) began earlier 2013 and, if completed, will define the shape of the U.S. military presence in Afghanistan for years to come.<ref name=\"Reuters20130618\" /> The security discussions between the U.S. and Afghanistan would provide for a limited number of military trainers and counterterrorism forces to remain in the country. The talks have been complicated by several disagreements, including over the immunity that U.S. troops would enjoy from Afghan laws.<ref name=\"WSJ20130618\" /> Speaking to reporters days before the suspension, U.S. Marine Corps General Joseph Dunford, the commander of the U.S.-led coalition, said, \"The bilateral security agreement is critical to any post-2014 presence. So it needs to be taken seriously on both sides.\"<ref name=\"WSJ20130618\" /> It was not clear how long Karzai would withdraw from the security talks with the US, meant to finalise arrangements for keeping a small US presence in the country after the last of the NATO troops leave 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Usborne|first=David|title=Taliban-US peace talks postponed after Afghanistan threatens to boycott negotiations in anger at Taliban's Qatar office|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/talibanus-peace-talks-postponed-after-afghanistan-threatens-to-boycott-negotiations-in-anger-at-talibans-qatar-office-8664560.html|accessdate=23 June 2013|newspaper=The Independent|date=20 June 2013|location=London}}</ref> Karzai has said the negotiations would not resume until the Taliban met directly with representatives of the Afghan government, essentially linking the security negotiations to a faltering peace process and making the United States responsible for persuading the Taliban to talk to the Afghan government.<ref name=\"NYT20130708\">{{cite news|title=U.S. Considers Faster Pullout in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/07/09/world/asia/frustrated-obama-considers-full-troop-withdrawal-from-afghanistan.html?hp&_r=0&pagewanted=all|accessdate=9 July 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=8 July 2013|author1=Mark Mazzetti  |author2=Matthew Rosenberg |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>\n\n==2013-11-20 Agreement on Bilateral Security Agreement draft==\nThe United States and Afghanistan reached an agreement on the final language of the bilateral security agreement,<ref>{{cite web|title=Security and Defense Cooperation Agreement between the United States of America and the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan \u2013 Pre-Decisional Document as of November 2013|url=http://mfa.gov.af/Content/files/2013-11-18%20BSA%20TEXT.pdf|work=The United States of America and the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan|publisher=Afghan Foreign Ministry|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=11 November 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131201203737/http://mfa.gov.af/Content/files/2013-11-18%20BSA%20TEXT.pdf|archive-date=1 December 2013|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> which according to State Department spokeswoman Jen Psaki wasn't the final document and which U.S. officials were still reviewing it,<ref name=\"LATimes20131120\" /> on 20 November 2013.<ref name=\"LATimes20131120\" /><ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\">{{cite news|title=U.S., Afghanistan agree on language of security accord, Kerry says|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-afghanistan-agree-on-language-of-security-accord-kerry-says/2013/11/20/85136c40-521a-11e3-a7f0-b790929232e1_story.html|accessdate=21 November 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=20 November 2013|author1=Karen DeYoung  |author2=Tim Craig |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref><ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/kerry-offers-to-write-letter-to-afghan-people-on-past-us-mistakes-kabul-officials-say/2013/11/19/11d16802-5159-11e3-9ee6-2580086d8254_story.html</ref><ref name=\"NYT20131120\" /><ref name=\"CNN20131121\" /><ref name=\"BBCBSA120131121\" /> A letter written by Obama<ref>{{cite web|last=Obama|first=Barack|title=Letter of U.S. President Barack Obama to Afghan President Hamid Karzai|url=http://president.gov.af/Content/files/President%20Obama%27s%20Letter%20to%20President%20Karzai.pdf|publisher=president.gov.af|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=20 November 2013}}</ref> said U.S. forces will be \"cooperating in training, advising, and assisting\" Afghan forces \"in a targeted, smaller, counterterrorism mission.\"<ref name=\"WPBSA220131121\" />  There is no limit on how long U.S. forces would remain in Afghanistan<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> The accord also has no expiration date.<ref>{{cite news|title=U.S. to offer Afghans assurances to remove hurdle in post-2014 deal|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=20 November 2013|author1=Karen DeYoung  |author2=Tim Craig |lastauthoramp=yes |newspaper=The Washington Post|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/kerry-offers-to-write-letter-to-afghan-people-on-past-us-mistakes-kabul-officials-say/2013/11/19/11d16802-5159-11e3-9ee6-2580086d8254_story.html}}</ref>  The agreement says that \"unless mutually agreed, United States forces shall not conduct combat operations in Afghanistan.\" It states the parties' \"intention of protecting U.S. and Afghan national interests without U.S. military counter-terrorism operations\" but does not specifically prohibit such operations.<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> United States Special Operations forces will retain leeway to conduct antiterrorism raids on private Afghan homes<ref name=\"NYT20131120\" /> American counterterrorism operations will be intended to \"complement and support\" Afghan missions<ref name=\"NYT20131120\" /> and that US forces will not conduct military operations in Afghanistan \"unless mutually agreed\" the text says.<ref name=\"AlJazBSA120131121\" /> It underscores that Afghan forces will be in the lead and that any American military operations will be carried out \"with full respect for Afghan sovereignty and full regard for the safety and security of the Afghan people, including in their homes.\"<ref name=\"NYT20131120\" /><ref name=\"CNN20131121\">{{cite news|last=Botelho|first=Greg|title=U.S., Afghanistan reach security pact through '2024 and beyond'|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/11/20/world/asia/us-afghanistan-security-agreement/index.html?hpt=hp_t2|publisher=CNN|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=21 November 2013}}</ref> It also notes that \"U.S. forces shall not target Afghan civilians, including in their homes, consistent with Afghan law and United States forces' rules of engagement.\"<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> Obama wrote in a letter to his Afghan counterpart: \"US forces shall not enter Afghan homes for the purposes of military operations, except under extraordinary circumstances involving urgent risk to life and limb of US nationals. We will continue to make every effort to respect the sanctity and dignity of Afghans in their homes and in their daily lives, just as we do for our own citizens.\"<ref name=\"BBCBSA220131121\">{{cite news|title=Obama vow as Loya Jirga debates US-Afghan security deal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-25038926|work=BBC News|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=21 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe agreement does not spell out the number of U.S. forces who will remain, but Karzai said on 21 November 2013 that he envisions up to 15,000 NATO troops being based in the country. According to several estimates, the United States plans to maintain a force of no more than 10,000 troops in Afghanistan after 2014. The draft agreement allows an indefinite U.S. presence, but Karzai said on 21 November 2013 it would be in place for 10 years.<ref name=\"WPBSA220131121\" /> The agreement also includes language on the U.S. government's continued funding for Afghan security forces, funneling such contributions through the Kabul-based government.<ref name=\"CNN20131121\" />\n\nThe agreement text grants the United States full legal jurisdiction over U.S. troops and Defense Department civilians working in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> On troop immunity, it says that Afghanistan agrees \"that the United States shall have the exclusive right to exercise jurisdiction\" over members of the force and its civilian component \"in respect of any criminal or civil offenses committed in the territory of Afghanistan.\",<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> and that \"Afghanistan authorises the United States to hold [civil and criminal] trial in such cases, or take other disciplinary action, as appropriate, in the territory of Afghanistan.\",<ref name=\"BBCBSA120131121\">{{cite news|title=Loya Jirga debates US-Afghan security deal|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-25028267|work=BBC News|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=21 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"AlJazBSA120131121\">{{cite web|title=Tribal elders discuss US-Afghan security pact|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2013/11/tribal-elders-discuss-us-afghan-security-pact-2013112144229784246.html|publisher=Al Jazeera English|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=21 November 2013}}</ref> but Afghan authorities can ask that anyone be taken out of the country.<ref name=\"CNN20131121\" /> Afghan authorities are prohibited from detaining American troops or U.S. civilians working with them. In the event that happens \"for any reason,\" however, those personnel \"shall be immediately handed over to United States forces authorities.\"<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> The agreement also specifies that American troops and civilians cannot be surrendered to any \"international tribunal or any other entity or state\" without express U.S. consent. Afghanistan, it says, retains legal jurisdiction over civilian contractors, and contractors are prohibited from wearing military uniforms and \"may only carry weapons in accordance with Afghan laws and regulations.\"<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" />\n\nThe document has a clause committing the United States to consulting with the Afghan government in the event of external threats, but not the sort of NATO-style mutual defense pact the Afghans originally wanted. \"The United States shall regard with grave concern any external aggression or threat of external aggression against the sovereignty, independence, and territorial integrity of Afghanistan,\" the proposed agreement states. There is a later clause saying they would \"consult urgently\" in the event of such aggression.<ref name=\"NYT20131120\" /> Obama added in a letter to his Afghan counterpart: \"The US commitment to Afghanistan's independence, territorial integrity, and national unity, as enshrined in our Strategic Partnership Agreement, is enduring, as is our respect for Afghan sovereignty.\"<ref name=\"BBCBSA220131121\" />\n\nIn a preamble, the draft specifies that \"the United States does not seek permanent military facilities in Afghanistan, or a presence that is a threat to Afghanistan's neighbors, and has pledged not to use Afghan territory or facilities as a launching point for attacks on other countries.\"<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> It says that \"unless otherwise mutually agreed, United States forces shall not conduct combat operations in Afghanistan\" and makes no promise of U.S. military support in the event of an attack or other security threat to Afghanistan. If there is such a threat, it says, the United States will regard it with \"grave concern,\" consult and \"shall urgently determine support it is prepared to provide.\"<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> But the United States stated the U.S. will regard any external aggression with \"grave concern\" and will \"strongly oppose\" military threats or force against Afghanistan after 2014.<ref name=\"LATimes20131120\" />\n\nThe draft agreement says that U.S. military and Defense Department civilian personnel are exempt from visa requirements and taxation. Afghan taxes and other fees will not be imposed on the entry or exit of goods specifically for the use of U.S. forces.<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> An annex to the draft lists locations where Afghanistan agrees to provide facilities for U.S. forces, including Kabul; Bagram, north of the capital, where the United States has its largest current base; Mazar-e Sharif in northern Afghanistan; Herat in the west; Kandahar in the south; Shindand in Herat province; Sharab in Helmand province; Gardez, south of Kabul; and Jalalabad, to the east.<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> The draft document gives the U.S. the right to deploy American forces on nine bases, including the two biggest, the airfields in Bagram and Kandahar. It also allows U.S. military planes to fly in and out of Afghanistan from seven air bases, including Kabul International Airport.<ref name=\"LATimes20131120\" /> U.S. forces would be permitted under the document to transport supplies from five border crossings, described along with the air bases as \"official points of embarkation and debarkation.\"<ref name=\"LATimes20131120\" /> All bases in Afghanistan would revert to Afghan ownership and sovereignty after 2014, according to the draft.<ref name=\"LATimes20131120\">{{cite news|title=Kerry announces U.S.-Afghan security agreement|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/la-fg-us-afghan-talks-20131121,0,5346244.story#axzz2lHITu7Sz|accessdate=21 November 2013|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|date=20 November 2013|author1=Shashank Bengali  |author2=David Zucchino |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe draft of the agreement was finalized early on 19 November 2013 after Obama wrote Karzai a letter assuring him that U.S. forces will continue to respect the \"sanctity and dignity of the Afghan people.\"<ref name=\"WPBSA220131121\" /> The agreement must as of 21 November 2013 be ratified by an Afghan grand council of elders<ref name=\"NYT20131120\">{{cite news|title=Pact May Extend U.S. Troops' Stay in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/21/world/asia/afghan-pact-kerry-apology-.html?hp&_r=1&pagewanted=all&|accessdate=21 November 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=20 November 2013|author1=Thom Shanker  |author2=Rod Nordland |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> and by ratified by the parliaments of Afghanistan and the United States.<ref name=\"WPBSA120131120\" /> The agreement, according to the draft wording, takes effect 1 January 2015 and then \"it shall remain in force until the end of 2024 and beyond\" unless terminated with two years' advance notice.<ref name=\"NYT20131120\" /> Karzai said that the agreement would not be signed until after 2014 elections in Afghanistan,<ref>{{cite news|title=US and Afghanistan clash on timetable for security pact|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-25045439|work=BBC News|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=21 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ALJazBSA220131121\">{{cite web|title=Afghanistan wants to delay US security deal|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2013/11/afghanistan-wants-delay-us-security-deal-2013112119310597776.html|publisher=Al Jazeera English|accessdate=21 November 2013|date=21 November 2013}}</ref> but U.S. officials have said unequivocally that the agreement must be signed by the end of the year 2013, if not sooner, to allow the Pentagon to prepare for its role after the American combat mission ends.<ref name=\"WPBSA220131121\">{{cite news|last=Craig|first=Tim|title=Afghan President Hamid Karzai says he'll delay signing of U.S. accord on troops|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/afghan-president-hamid-karzai-outlines-plans-for-post-2014-us-mission/2013/11/21/c2af9e60-52a2-11e3-9ee6-2580086d8254_story.html?tid=pm_world_pop|accessdate=21 November 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=21 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"ALJazBSA220131121\" /> White House Press secretary Jay Carney said the agreement under consideration by the loya jirga is the Obama administration's \"final offer.\" If not enacted by the end of the year, Carney said, it \"would be impossible for the United States and our allies to plan for a presence post-2014.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Karzai rejects call for quick decision on U.S. troop agreement|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/karzai-rejects-call-for-quick-decision-on-afghan-troop-levels/2013/11/22/13aa03b2-538b-11e3-9ee6-2580086d8254_story.html?wprss=rss_war-zones&tid=pp_widget|accessdate=23 November 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=22 November 2013|author1=Tim Craig  |author2=Sayed Salahuddin |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> Karzai, who earlier stated he would sign what he had agreed to sign, stated later, after the announcement of the Bilatereal Security Agreement (BSA) draft textthat, he wouldn't sign it until 2014, after a presidential election to choose his successor, but before he leaves office. [[Aimal Faizi]], a spokesman for Karzai, stated that Karzai wanted to wait until after the election in April 2014 to test further conditions: whether American forces would stop raids on Afghan homes, whether the Obama Administration will help stabilize security in Afghanistan, help promote peace talks and not interfere in the election.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nordland|first=Rod|title=Karzai Insists U.S. Forces Killed Civilians in a Raid|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/24/world/asia/us-upset-by-karzais-claim-about-civilian-deaths.html?src=recg&pagewanted=all|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=23 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"WPA20131123\" /> Officials of the Obama Administration consider the signing date to be nonnegotiable, citing the need for at least a year to plan future deployments and to allow coalition partners, including Germany and Italy, to plan for a residual troop presence that they have offered.<ref name=\"WPA20131123\">{{cite news|title=Karzai intends to press showdown with Obama over security pact, aide says|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/karzai-doesnt-trust-us-intends-to-press-showdown-with-obama-aide-says/2013/11/23/f32e9b08-546f-11e3-9ee6-2580086d8254_story.html?tid=pm_world_pop|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=23 November 2013|author1=Tim Craig  |author2=Karen DeYoung |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe text of the BSA was approved by the delegates at the Loya Jirga on 24 November 2013 and must now be signed by the Afghanistan president, who rejected the final recommendation of the Loya Jirga promptly to sign the BSA with the United States, and sent to the parliament for final ratification.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nordland|first=Rob|title=Afghan Council Approves Security Pact, but Karzai Withholds His Signature|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/25/world/asia/afghan-council-approves-us-security-pact.html?hp&_r=1&&pagewanted=all|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=24 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"WPJIRGA20131124\">{{cite news|last=Craig|first=Tim|title=Afghan elders endorse U.S. troops' presence but President Karzai still refuses to sign|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/afghan-assembly-of-leaders-endorses-us-troops-presence-karzai-refuses-to-sign/2013/11/24/ac29b6f2-550a-11e3-bdbf-097ab2a3dc2b_story.html|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=24 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Loya jirga approves U.S.-Afghan security deal; asks Karzai to sign|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/11/24/world/asia/us-afghanistan-security-agreement/index.html?hpt=hp_t3|publisher=CNN|accessdate=24 November 2013|author1=Masoud Popolzai  |author2=Ben Brumfield |lastauthoramp=yes |date=24 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"LATimes20131124\">{{cite news|last=Zucchino|first=David|title=Afghan council defies Karzai on U.S. security deal|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/worldnow/la-fg-wn-afghan-council-defies-karzai-20131124,0,7234234,full.story#axzz2la8MJOs2|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|date=24 November 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"AlJaz20131124\">{{cite web|title=Karzai gives no date to sign US security pact|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/asia/2013/11/karzai-agrees-afghan-us-security-pact-20131124854271874.html|publisher=AlJazeera English|accessdate=24 November 2013|author=Ali M Latifi|date=24 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Craig|first=Tim|title=Coalition apologizes for killing Afghan child, seeks to shore up prospects of security deal|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/coalition-apologizes-for-killing-afghan-child-karzai-warns-security-deal-in-jeopardy/2013/11/29/f73d2b06-58ed-11e3-8304-caf30787c0a9_story.html?tid=ts_carousel|accessdate=30 November 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=29 November 2013}}</ref> If approved, the agreement would allow the U.S. to deploy military advisors to train and equip Afghan security forces, along with U.S. special-operations troops for anti-terrorism missions against Al Qaeda and other terrorist groups. Obama will determine the size of the force.<ref name=\"LATimes20131124\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=Afghanistan elders seek US security pact signing in 2013|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-25075536|work=BBC News Asia|accessdate=24 November 2013|date=24 November 2013}}</ref> The jirga set a few conditions before expressing approval for the agreement among them a 10-year time limit on the post-2014 troop presence and reparations for damages caused by U.S. troops deployed in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"WPJIRGA20131124\" /> It also voted attach a letter by Obama; pledging that U.S. troops would enter Afghan homes only in \"extraordinary\" circumstances and only if American lives were at direct risk, to the BSA.<ref name=\"LATimes20131124\" /> The elder assembly also demanded the release of 19 Afghans from the U.S. detention center at Guantanamo Bay and a stronger U.S. pledge to defend Afghanistan from any incursion from it neighbors, particularly Pakistan. The loya jirga also voted to request that the U.S. military add a base<ref name=\"AlJaz20131124\" /> to the nine bases that would be occupied by U.S. troops under the proposed security pact after combat forces depart Afghanistan by the end of 2014. The base is in Bamian Province in central Afghanistan, where the NATO-led military coalition has maintained a presence. Bamian is a population center for Hazaras, a Shiite minority whose members were massacred by the Taliban prior to the U.S.-led invasion that toppled the militant group. Afghan analysts said Hazara delegates proposed the additional base.<ref name=\"LATimes20131124\" /> At least five of the 50 jirga committees raised objections to the article addressing \"status of personnel\" which \"authorises the United States to hold [civil and criminal] trial ... or take other disciplinary action, as appropriate, in the territory of Afghanistan\" when a US soldier is accused of criminal activity.<ref name=\"AlJaz20131124\" /> Spokespeople from at least two committees directly stated that Afghanistan should have jurisdiction over any US soldiers accused of crimes on Afghan soil. Several committees also stated that if trials are held in the United States, families of victims should have access to and presence in US-held trials at the expense of Washington.<ref name=\"AlJaz20131124\" />\n\n==US withdrawal from Afghanistan: The plan for 2012, 2013, and 2014==\n===2012 drawdown===\nThe 2012 pullout of 23,000 American troops from Afghanistan was on 22 July 2012 at the halfway mark according to U.S. Gen. John Allen, the top commander of U.S. and NATO forces in Afghanistan and would accelerate in the coming months.<ref name=\"APFox20120723\">{{cite news|title=Withdrawal of US troops from Afghanistan halfway done, top commander says|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/07/22/withdrawal-us-troops-from-afghanistan-halfway-done-top-commander-says/|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=10 September 2012|date=23 July 2012}}</ref> \"August will be the heaviest month,\" Allen said. \"A lot is coming out now and a great deal will come out in August and early September. We'll be done probably around mid-September or so.\"<ref name=\"APFox20120723\" /> Up to one half of the 23,000 troops being pulled out 2012 are combat forces, he said. Small numbers are being pulled from the relatively stable northern and western parts of the country. Some will be withdrawn from the east and the south \"and a good bit in the southwest,\" he said.<ref name=\"APFox20120723\" /> U.S. Defense Secretary Leon Panetta announced on 21 September 2012 that the 33,000 additional U.S. troops that Obama had sent to Afghanistan in 2010 to counter the Taliban attacks have left the country.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cassata|first=Donna|title=Defense hawk backs US withdrawal from Afghanistan|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/huff-wires/20120921/us-congress-afghanistan/|agency=Associated Press|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=14 October 2012|date=21 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=US pulls out 33,000 troops from Afghanistan: Panetta|url=http://www.presstv.ir/detail/2012/09/21/262785/33000-us-troops-depart-afghanistan/|publisher=PressTV|accessdate=14 October 2012|date=21 September 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Final US 'surge' troops withdraw from Afghanistan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/sep/21/us-surge-troops-withdraw-afghanistan?newsfeed=true|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=14 October 2012|date=21 October 2012|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ardolino |first=Bill |title=Afghanistan \u2013 now what? |url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/threat-matrix/archives/2012/09/afghanistan_-_now_what.php |publisher=Threat Matrix \u2013 A Blog of The Long War Journal |accessdate=14 October 2012 |date=21 September 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120930003222/http://www.longwarjournal.org/threat-matrix/archives/2012/09/afghanistan_-_now_what.php |archivedate=30 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>  A phased withdrawal plan was developed where 10,000 troops would leave Afghanistan by July 2011 and the remaining 23,000 would leave Afghanistan by the end of September 2012. The removal of the 23,000 U.S. troops began in July 2012.<ref name=\"KhaamaPress20120921\">{{cite news|title=United States pullout 33000 surge troops from Afghanistan|url=http://www.khaama.com/united-states-pullout-33000-surge-troops-from-afghanistan-783/|accessdate=14 October 2012|newspaper=Khaama Press (KP) {{!}} Afghan Online Newspaper|date=21 September 2012|author=Sajad}}</ref>  In a statement announcing an end to the surge Panetta stated:\n\n{{quote|As we reflect on this moment, it is an opportunity to recognize that the surge accomplished its objectives of reversing Taliban momentum on the battlefield, and dramatically increased the size and capability of the Afghan National Security Forces (ANSF). This growth has allowed us and our ISAF Coalition partners to begin the process of transition to Afghan security lead, which will soon extend across every province and more than 75 percent of the Afghan population. At the same time, we have struck enormous blows against al Qaeda's leadership, consistent with our core goal of disrupting, dismantling and defeating al Qaeda and denying it a safe-haven.<ref name=\"KhaamaPress20120921\" />}}\n\nOnce the United States and its allies agreed on the timing for the shift in the Afghanistan mission \u2014 under which American troops would step away from the lead combat role to a supporting mission focused primarily on counterterrorism and training Afghan security forces (according to the 2012 NATO Chicago Summit this shift is planned for the middle of 2013 ([[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Afghanistan#NATO Chicago Summit: Troops withdrawal and longterm presence|see section above]]) \u2014 the Obama administration must decide exactly when the remaining 68,000 troops will come home according to the New York Times.<ref name=\"NYT20120313\">{{cite news|title=U.S. Officials Debate Speeding Afghan Pullout|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/13/world/asia/us-officials-debate-speeding-up-afghan-pullout.html?_r=1&ref=world&src=me&adxnnlx=1331668863-xL%20xRTvBu6ol%2019Ji81NgQ&pagewanted=all|accessdate=10 September 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=13 March 2012|author1=Helene Cooper  |author2=Eric Schmitt |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> In September 2012 the United States withdrew then the last of the 33,000 \"surge\" forces from Afghanistan that Obama ordered in West Point 2009 to try to bring the Afghanistan war under control. With the reduction over the next two years of the remaining 68,000 American troops, the top American and NATO commander in Afghanistan would lead a force that is to operate from fewer bases and will train Afghan forces to take the lead in combat.<ref name=\"NYT20121010\">{{cite news|last=Miller|first=Elisabeth|title=Commander Nominated to Lead War in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/11/world/asia/general-dunford-nominated-to-lead-afghan-war-effort.html?src=recg&_r=0|accessdate=14 October 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=10 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2013 drawdown plans===\nThe number of US troops to remain in Afghanistan during 2013 was still being decided as of March 2012, but it appeared that three options were considered. These three options were:<ref name=\"NYT20120313\" />\n\n# A drawdown from 68,000 to 58,000 troops by the end of 2012, with a further drawdown to between 38,000 and 48,000 by June 2013. This would be a continuation of the current policy of gradual drawdown. Obama has stated that he prefers a gradual drawdown.<ref name=\"NYT20120313\" /><ref name=\"RadinJournal20120318\">{{cite web|last=Radin|first=CJ|title=US withdrawal from Afghanistan: the plan for 2012, 2013, and 2014|url=http://www.longwarjournal.org/archives/2012/03/us_withdrawal_from_a.php|publisher=The Long War Journal \u2013 A Project of the Foundation for Defense of Democracy|accessdate=10 September 2012|date=18 March 2012}}</ref>\n# Maintaining 68,000 troops through the end of 2013. This is the US military commanders' preferred option since it maintains US force levels through the summer fighting season in 2013.<ref name=\"NYT20120313\" /><ref name=\"RadinJournal20120318\" />\n# A large and rapid drawdown, perhaps to 20,000 troops, by the end of 2013. This would leave only Special Operations Forces, counterterrorism forces, military trainers, and some support and security staff in Afghanistan. This is Vice President Biden's preferred option.<ref name=\"NYT20120313\" /><ref name=\"RadinJournal20120318\" />\n\nAccording to two American officials who are involved in Afghan issues said that the senior American commander in Afghanistan, General John Allen wanted to keep a significant military capability through the fighting season ending in fall 2013, which could translate to a force of more than 60,000 troops until the end of that period.<ref name=\"NYT20121126\">{{cite news|last=Gordon|first=Michael R.|title=Time Slipping, U.S. Ponders Afghan Role After 2014|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/26/world/asia/us-planning-a-force-to-stay-in-afghanistan.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=26 November 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=26 November 2012}}</ref> The United States has not \"begun considering any specific recommendations for troop numbers in 2013 and 2014,\" said George Little, the Pentagon spokesman. \"What is true is that in June 2011 the president made clear that our forces would continue to come home at a steady pace as we transition to an Afghan lead for security. That it still the case.\"<ref name=\"NYT20121126\" />\n\nDuring the [[2013 State of the Union Address]], Obama said that the U.S. military will reduce the troop level in Afghanistan from 68,000 to 34,000 US troops by February 2014.<ref name=\"WP20130212\">{{cite news|last=Chandrasekaran|first=Rajiv|title=Obama wants to cut troop level in Afghanistan in half over next year|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/official-obama-to-cut-troop-level-in-afghanistan-in-half-by-next-year/2013/02/12/63a044c8-7536-11e2-8f84-3e4b513b1a13_story.html|accessdate=14 February 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=12 February 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20130212\">{{cite news|title=Decision on Afghan Troop Levels Calculates Political and Military Interests|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/02/13/us/politics/obama-to-announce-troops-return.html?_r=2&|accessdate=14 February 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=12 February 2013|author1=Michael R. Gordon  |author2=Mark Landler |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"BBC20130213\" /><ref name=\"CNNTapper20130213\">{{cite news|last=Tapper|first=Jack|title=Obama announces 34,000 troops to come home|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/02/12/politics/obama-sotu-afghanistan-troops/index.html|publisher=CNN|accessdate=14 February 2013|date=13 February 2013}}</ref> According to an unnamed U.S. official Obama made his decision \"based on the recommendations of the military and his national security team,\" consultations with Karzai and \"international coalition partners.\"<ref name=\"CNNTapper20130213\" /> The United States has adopted a withdrawal schedule which U.S. General John. R. Allen called a \"phased approach.\"<ref name=\"NYT20130212\" /> According to the new withdrawal schedule, as reported by the New York Times, the number of troops is to go down from 66,000 troops to 60,500 by the end of May 2013. By the end of November 2013, the number will be down to 52,000. By the end of February 2014, the troop level is to be around 32,000.<ref name=\"NYT20130212\" /> The Washington Post reported a slightly different withdrawal plan which calls for the U.S. forces figure of 68,000 troops to drop to about 60,000 by May 2013 and 52,500 by November 2013. The largest exodus will occur in December 2013 and January 2014, when about 18,500 troops will leave Afghanistan.<ref name=\"WP20130212\" /> The White House intended to allow the military to determine the pace at which the 34,000 troops are withdrawn over the 12 months until February 2013. Top U.S. military  officers have said they hope to keep as many forces as possible in Afghanistan through summer 2013, when combat with the Taliban is usually at its highest.<ref name=\"WP20130212\" /> \"Commanders will have discretion on pace of this drawdown which will allow them to maintain the force they need through the fighting season,\" according to one U.S. official.<ref name=\"CNNTapper20130213\" /> The drawdown announcement generated mixed reactions in Afghanistan: While Afghan officials like Karzai and the Taliban welcomed Obama's decision, many Afghans worried that a quick drawdown will destabilize the country. Afghans also expressed their concern that Afghan security forces were not ready to take the lead for security.<ref>{{cite news|title=Announcement of US troop withdrawal draws mixed reactions in Afghanistan|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2013/02/13/announcement-us-troop-withdrawal-draws-mixed-reaction-in-afghanistan/|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=14 February 2013|date=13 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Quinn|first=Patrick|title=Afghan president welcomes U.S. withdrawal|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2013/02/ap-afghan-president-welcomes-us-withdrawal-021313/|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Army Times|accessdate=14 February 2013|date=13 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nAs of September 2013 the U.S. military is flying out a large amount of gear instead of using cheaper overland and sea routes, while U.S. officials declined to elaborate on the reasons for their heavy reliance on the more expensive methods of transport.<ref>{{cite news|last=Whitlock|first=Craif|title=In Afghanistan drawdown, U.S. forced to take costly option in transporting military gear out|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/in-afghanistan-drawdown-us-forced-to-take-costly-option-in-transporting-military-gear-out/2013/09/12/6a5e260a-1bde-11e3-b4fb-944b778463f5_story.html|accessdate=14 September 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=13 September 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2014 drawdown plans===\nThe US force level will drop to between 10,000 and 20,000 troops according to the Long War Journal. They will consist of Special Forces, counterterrorism forces, and military training personnel. They will be deployed to a small number of bases around the country. US/ISAF troops will continue their training of Afghan National Security Forces soldiers. Counterterrorism forces will concentrate mostly on high-value targets.<ref name=\"RadinJournal20120318\" /> U.S. Secretary of Defense Leon Panetta stated on 12 November 2012 that the Obama Administration will cease combat operations by the end of 2014, but it is still refining its timeline for withdrawing the remaining 68,000 U.S. troops in Afghanistan. The administration was also debating how many trainers, Special Operations forces and military assets it will keep in the country after that to support Afghanistan's army and police.<ref>{{cite news|last=Whitlock|first=Craig|title=Panetta heads to Asia, as Obama administration makes strategic 'pivot'|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/panetta-heads-to-asia-as-obama-administration-makes-strategic-pivot/2012/11/12/a1f3d432-2d16-11e2-a99d-5c4203af7b7a_story.html|accessdate=17 November 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=13 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring a surprise trip to Afghanistan in May 2014 Obama stated that the United States wanted to sign a bilateral security agreement with Afghanistan for the purpose of continuing training/advising Afghan forces and assisting in specific counterterrorism missions. The winner of Afghanistan's presidential runoff election  \u2014 between former Afghan foreign minister [[Abdullah Abdullah]] and onetime World Bank economist Ashraf Ghani \u2014 will be asked immediately to sign the security agreement that will help determine how many U.S. forces, as of May 2014 numbering 32,000, will remain in Afghanistan after the end of the year 2014. U.S. officials said the security agreement must be endorsed as soon as possible to give U.S. military planners time to complete drawdown schedules \u2014 including decisions on what bases to close \u2014 and make arrangements for the next phase of the U.S. military presence after nearly 13 years of war.<ref>{{cite news|last=Landler|first=Mark|title=Obama, Honoring the Fallen, Says V.A. Problems Must Be Faced|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/27/us/politics/obama-honoring-the-fallen-says-va-problems-must-be-faced.html?_r=0|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=26 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Scott|title=Obama makes surprise visit to Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/obama-arrives-in-afghanistan-on-surprise-visit/2014/05/25/7df61452-e41f-11e3-8f90-73e071f3d637_story.html|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=25 May 2014}}</ref> Pentagon general counsel Stephen Preston said in May 2014 before the U.S. Senate that the 2014 drawdown planning and the post 2014 presence planning will concentrate on \"what the circumstances, the mission and presence in Afghanistan will be.\"<ref>{{cite news|last=DeYoung|first=Karen|title=Obama's revamp of anti-terror policies stalls|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/obamas-revamp-of-anti-terror-policies-stalls/2014/05/21/79ac0f20-e053-11e3-8dcc-d6b7fede081a_story.html|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=22 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 May 2014, Obama announced that U.S. combat operations in Afghanistan would end in December 2014 and that the troops levels will be reduced to 9,800 troops by this time.<ref name=\"NYT20140527\">{{cite news |last=Landler|first=Mark|title=U.S. Will Complete Afghan Pullout by End of 2016, Obama Says|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/28/world/asia/us-to-complete-afghan-pullout-by-end-of-2016-obama-to-say.html?hp|newspaper=The New York Times|date=27 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 August 2014, a gunman dressed in an Afghan military uniform opened fire on a number of U.S., foreign and Afghan soldiers, killing Major General [[Harold J. Greene]] and wounding about 15 officers and soldiers including a German brigadier general and eight U.S. soldiers. For the U.S. Armed Forces, it was the first death of a general on foreign battlefields in 44 years.<ref name=\"ShootingAfghanistan\">{{cite news|title=American army officer killed, many wounded in Afghan insider attack|url=http://www.afghanistansun.com/index.php/sid/224460361|accessdate=7 August 2014|publisher=Afghanistan Sun}}</ref>\n\nAfter 13 years Britain, the United States and the remaining Australians officially ended their combat operation in Afghanistan on 28 October 2014. On that day Britain handed over its last base in Afghanistan, Camp Bastion in the southern province of Helmand, to Afghanistan, while the United States handed over its last base, Camp Leatherneck in the southern province of Helmand.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Syal|first1=Ryan|title=UK troops hand over Camp Bastion to Afghan forces, ending 13-year campaign|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/oct/26/uk-troops-camp-bastion-afghan-forces-13-years-helmand|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=The Guardian|publisher=The Guardian|date=26 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Kay Johnson, Raissa Kasolowsky, Michael Perry and Kevin Liffey|title=Britain ends combat role in Afghanistan, last US Marines hand over base|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/10/26/us-afghanistan-troopwithdrawal-idUSKBN0IF06I20141026|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=Reuters|agency=Reuters|publisher=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Watt|first1=Holly|title=Britain's 13-year war in Afghanistan comes to an end|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/asia/afghanistan/11188222/Last-British-combat-troops-leave-Helmand-within-days.html|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=The Telegraph|publisher=The Telegraph|date=26 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hjelmgaard|first1=Kim|title=Britain's war in Afghanistan officially ends|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/10/26/britain-afghanistan-camp-bastion-us-marines/17952857/|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=USA Today|publisher=USA Today|date=26 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Loyn|first1=David|title=What have British troops achieved in Afghanistan?|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-29761100|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=BBC News Asia|publisher=BBC News Asia|date=26 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=UK ends Afghan combat operations|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-29776544|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=BBC News UK|publisher=BBC News UK|date=26 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Post-2014 presence plans==\n===Plans by the administration of Barack Obama===\nDuring the [[2012 Chicago Summit]] NATO and its partners agreed to withdraw its combat troops from Afghanistan by the end of 2014.<ref name=\"Reuters 20120521\"/> A new and different NATO mission will then advise, train and assist the Afghan security forces including the Afghan Special Operations Forces.<ref name=\"Chicago Declaration\" /><ref name=\"Elise Labott and Mike Mount\"/> Final decisions on the size of the American and NATO presence after 2014 and its precise configuration have not been made by the United States or its NATO allies as of 26 November 2012, but one option calls for about 10,000 American and several thousand non-American NATO troops according to the United States.<ref name=\"NYT20121126\"/> The presence shall include a small American counterterrorism force consisting of fewer than 1,000 American troops, while in a parallel effort, NATO forces would advise Afghan forces at major regional military and police headquarters. According to the New York Times, NATO forces would most likely have a minimal battlefield role, with the exception of some special operations advisers.<ref name=\"NYT20121126\" />\n\nAn important question for the NATO mission after 2014 was what level of the Afghan military hierarchy they would advise. It was generally expected that they would advise seven regional Afghan Army corps and several regional Afghan police headquarters. The arrangement would largely insulate the NATO advisers from the battlefield, though officials said advisers might accompany Afghan brigades on major operations. It was unlikely that NATO officers would advise Afghan battalions on the battlefield, because that would require many more advisers than NATO was likely to muster and would entail more risk than most nations seem prepared to assume, though some American experts believed it would make the Afghan military more effective. Still, NATO special operations advisers would be likely to accompany Afghan Army commandos and police SWAT-type units on the battlefield.<ref name=\"NYT20121126\" />\n\nA major challenge was that Afghanistan would not have an effective air force before 2017, if then.  As a consequence American officials said that NATO airpower would remain in Afghanistan after 2014 but will likely only be used on behalf of NATO and American troops and perhaps Afghan units that are accompanied by NATO advisers. NATO forces relied heavily on airpower for airstrikes, supply and medical evacuation since Afghanistan's roads are in poor condition and often seeded with bombs. To compensate for Afghanistan's limited airpower, the United States was working on a number of fixes, including providing Afghan forces with armored vehicles that would be equipped with mortars and assault guns. The United States was looking into expanding the purchase of turboprop planes for the Afghans. In addition the U.S. was also trying to help Afghan pilots learn to fly at night.<ref name=\"NYT20121126\" /> Equally troubling was according to the New York Times the problem of medical evacuations. Because after 2014 the Afghans would almost certainly need to rely on a system that depended more on ground transportation than helicopters the United States wanted to help Afghanistan forces develop more field hospitals.<ref name=\"NYT20121126\" />\n\nPlans for the follow-on military presence are being formulated in the Pentagon, where the largest of several preliminary options calls for about 10,000 troops, with several other NATO governments penciled in for several hundred each. According to these preliminary plans, ISAF's successor would be based in Kabul, with most U.S. training and counterterrorism troops probably stationed in Kandahar and at the air base at Bagram. Both locations are to be converted to Afghan ownership. Smaller counterterrorism units of the [[Joint Special Operations Command]] would be positioned primarily in the eastern part of the country, where most of their activities take place. Italy, in charge of the ISAF mission in Herat in western Afghanistan, would remain there to train Afghans. Germany would do the same in Mazar-e Sharif in the north. It is unclear what would happen at Camp Bastion, the British headquarters in Helmand province.<ref name=\"WP20121205\">{{cite news|last=DeYoung|first=Karen|title=U.S. reducing plans for large civilian force in post-2014 Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/us-reducing-plans-for-large-civilian-force-in-post-2014-afghanistan/2012/12/05/67c7d9a8-380f-11e2-8a97-363b0f9a0ab3_story.html|accessdate=5 December 2012|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=5 December 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe size of the American military presence after 2014 will help determine the size of the American civilian footprint. As of December 2012 the United States are reducing its plans for large civilian force in post-2014 Afghanistan, because the U.S. military is certain to curtail or stop the security and other services it provides U.S. government civilians in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"WP20121205\" /> Firm decisions on civilian numbers and locations cannot be made \"until we resolve exactly what the military follow-on numbers are going to be,\" one unnamed U.S. official said. \"That will determine .\u2009.\u2009. where we locate, what kind of security, medical and other support we might be able to get.\"<ref name=\"WP20121205\" /> According to the New York Times the U.S. military wants to retain 9,000 U.S. troops in Afghanistan, while the Obama administration wants a force of 3,000 to 9,000 troops in Afghanistan after 2014.<ref>{{cite news|last=Gordon|first=Michael R.|title=U.S. Weighs Fewer Troops After 2014 in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/06/world/asia/us-weighs-fewer-troops-after-2014-in-afghanistan.html?ref=world&_r=0|accessdate=10 January 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=5 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring a meeting with Karzai on 11 January 2013, Obama stated that he will determine the pace of U.S. combat troops drawdown and their withdrawal from Afghanistan by the end of 2014 after consultations with commanders on the ground.<ref name=\"LATimes20130111\">{{cite news|title=Obama moves up deadline for Afghans to take lead security role|url=https://www.latimes.com/news/politics/la-pn-obama-karzai-afghanistan-20130111,0,7048110.story|accessdate=12 January 2013|newspaper=The Los Angeles Times|date=11 January 2013|author1=Christi Parsons  |author2=Kathleen Hennessey |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> He also said any U.S. mission in Afghanistan beyond 2014 would focus solely on counterterrorism operations and training Afghan security forces.<ref name=\"LATimes20130111\" /><ref name=\"WP20130111\">{{cite news|title=Obama announces reduced U.S. role in Afghanistan starting this spring|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/karzai-meets-obama-to-discuss-us-drawdown-in-afghanistan/2013/01/11/b50c72ec-5c03-11e2-9fa9-5fbdc9530eb9_story.html?hpid=z1|accessdate=12 January 2013|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=11 January 2013|author1=Scott Wilson  |author2=[[David Nakamura]] |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> According to Obama any agreement on troop withdrawals must include an immunity agreement in which US troops are not subjected to Afghan law.<ref>{{cite web|title=US to speed up Afghan troop transition|url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/americas/2013/01/201311185310956108.html|publisher=Al Jazeera English|accessdate=12 January 2013|date=11 January 2012}}</ref> \"I can go to the Afghan people and argue for immunity for U.S. troops in Afghanistan in a way that Afghan sovereignty will not be compromised, in a way that Afghan law will not be compromised,\" Karzai replied.<ref name=\"CNN20130112\">{{cite news|title=Obama, Karzai agree to accelerate military transition|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/01/11/us/obama-karzai-meeting/?hpt=hp_t1|accessdate=12 January 2013|newspaper=CNN|date=12 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nDuring his [[2013 State of the Union Address]] Barack Obama announced that 34,000 US troops will leave Afghanistan by February 2014, but did not specify what the post-2014 troop levels would be. \"Beyond 2014, America's commitment to a unified and sovereign Afghanistan will endure, but the nature of our commitment will change,\" Obama said.<ref name=\"BBC20130213\" /> \"We're negotiating an agreement with the Afghan government that focuses on two missions \u2013 training and equipping Afghan forces so that the country does not again slip into chaos, and counter-terrorism efforts that allow us to pursue the remnants of al-Qaeda and their affiliates,\" he added.<ref name=\"BBC20130213\">{{cite news|title=Obama announces 34,000 troops to leave Afghanistan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-21431423|publisher=BBC News US & Canada|accessdate=14 February 2013|date=13 February 2013}}</ref> As of 12 February 2013, Barack Obama has not made a decision on the post-2014 U.S. force.<ref name=\"NYT20130212\" /> The Obama Administration intends to keep some troops in the country in 2015 and beyond, but the number is still being debated at the White House and must be approved by the Afghan government.<ref name=\"WP20130212\" /> Unnamed U.S. officials said there was a reluctance to go public with a final number of troops and a description of their missions while still in the early stage of negotiating a security agreement with the Afghans over retaining a U.S. military presence after 2014.<ref name=\"NYT20130212\" /> The New York Times reported that the post-2014 force is likely to number no more than 9,000 or so troops and then get progressively smaller.<ref name=\"NYT20130212\" /> The Washington Post reported that the Pentagon is pushing a plan that would keep about 8,000 U.S. troops in Afghanistan in 2015, but significantly shrink the contingent over the following two years, perhaps to fewer than 1,000 by 2017, according to senior U.S. government officials and military officers.<ref name=\"WP20130212\" /> As the result of the suspension of the bilateral security agreement discussions and increasingly frustrated by his dealings with Karzai, Obama was giving in early July 2013 serious consideration to speeding up the withdrawal of United States forces from Afghanistan and to a \"zero option\" that would leave no American troops there after 2014.<ref name=\"NYT20130708\" /> At the end of 2013 the United States backed away from its threat to initiate a complete American withdrawal from Afghanistan by the end of 2014, if Karzai refuses to sign the Bilateral Security Agreement by the end of 2013. However the United States stood by its warning that a total military withdrawal is still possible if delays continue.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rosenberg|first=Matthew|title=U.S. Softens Deadline for Deal to Keep Troops in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/24/world/asia/us-softens-deadline-for-deal-to-keep-troops-in-afghanistan.html?_r=0|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=23 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20140121\">{{cite news|title=U.S. Military Eyes Afghan Force of 10,000, or a Pullout|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/22/world/asia/military-eyes-afghan-force-of-10000-or-a-pullout.html?_r=0|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=The New York Times|date=21 January 2014|author1=Jackie Calmes  |author2=Eric Schmitt |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> The U.S. Department of Defense proposed to Obama to leave behind 10,000 US troops when their combat mission and that of their allies end there at the end of 2014, or none at all.<ref name=\"NYT20140121\" /> Caitlin M. Hayden, a spokeswoman for the National Security Council, said that absent an agreement with respect to the B.S.A. between the America and Afghanistan the U.S.A. \"will initiate planning for a post-2014 future in which there would be no U.S. or NATO troop presence in Afghanistan.\",<ref name=\"NYT20140121\" /> while the British Ministry of Defense said that until the pact is signed, no decision will be made on the contribution from other nations.<ref>{{cite news|title=The mammoth military task of leaving Afghanistan|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-25848662|accessdate=23 February 2014|newspaper=BBC News Asia|date=28 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nBy May 2014 no agreement on the bilateral security agreement had been reached. Obama on a trip to Afghanistan in late May 2014 said he was about to make decisions on the transition and was in the country to meet with Afghanistan's leaders prior to making those decisions final.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama to announce post-2014 troop levels in Afghanistan shortly|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/05/25/us-usa-afghanistan-obama-military-idUSBREA4O09W20140525|accessdate=27 May 2014|newspaper=Reuters|date=25 May 2014|author1=Steve Holland, Jeff Mason  |author2=Bill Trott |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> On 27 May 2014, Obama announced that U.S. combat operations in Afghanistan would end in December 2014.<ref name=\"WSJ20140528\" /><ref name=\"BBC20140527\">{{cite web|title=US to keep 9,800 Afghanistan troops after 2014|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-27593518|publisher=BBC News USA & Canada|accessdate=29 May 2014|date=27 May 2014}}</ref> A residual force of 9,800 troops would remain in the country which includes a group of troops to train and advise Afghan security forces and a separate group of Special Operations forces to continue counterterrorism missions against remnants of al-Qaeda.<ref name=\"WP20140527\">{{cite news|last=DeYoung|first=Karen|title=Obama to leave 9,800 U.S. troops in Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/obama-to-leave-9800-us-troops-in-afghanistan-senior-official-says/2014/05/27/57f37e72-e5b2-11e3-a86b-362fd5443d19_story.html|accessdate=29 May 2014|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=27 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"USAToday20140527\">{{cite news|title=Obama: It's time to turn the page on a decade of war|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/05/27/obama-afghanistan-9800-troop-level/9624545/|accessdate=29 May 2014|newspaper=USA Today|date=27 May 2014|author1=Aamer Madhani  |author2=Tom Vanden Brook |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> These forces would be halved by the end of 2015, and consolidated at Bagram Air Base and in Kabul. Obama also announced that all U.S. forces, with the exception of a \"normal embassy presence,\" would be removed from Afghanistan by the end of 2016.<ref name=\"NYT20140527\"/> These remaining forces would be a regular armed forces assistance group, largely to handle military sales under the authority of the U.S. ambassador,<ref name=\"WP20140527\" /> but also guard the US embassy, train Afghan forces and support counter-terrorism operations.<ref name=\"BBC20140527\" /> These troop will not exceed 1,000 troops, akin to the security presence that is currently as of May 2014 in Iraq.<ref name=\"USAToday20140527\"/> The president's plans were subject to the approval of the incoming Afghan government and its willingness to sign the bilateral security agreement providing immunity for U.S. troops serving in the country, which outgoing president Karzai had refused to sign.<ref name=\"AfghanistanDrawdown\">{{cite news|title=US to leave some 10,000 troops in Afghanistan after 2014|url=http://www.afghanistansun.com/index.php/sid/222375281/scat/6e1d5c8e1f98f17c/ht/US-to-leave-some-10000-troops-in-Afghanistan-after-2014|accessdate=27 May 2014|publisher=Afghanistan Sun}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Ackermann|first=Spencer|title=Obama announces plan to keep 9,800 US troops in Afghanistan after 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/27/obama-us-afghanistan-force-2014|accessdate=29 May 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|date=27 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Obama seeks to cut troop level in Afghanistan to 5,000 by end of 2015|url=https://www.latimes.com/world/afghanistan-pakistan/la-fg-obama-afghanistan-troops-20140527-story.html|accessdate=29 May 2014|date=27 May 2014|author1=Christi Parsons  |author2=David S. Cloud |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref> The U.S. post 2014 presence plans were welcomed by outgoing Afghanistan president Hamid Karzai saying that Afghanistan was ready to take responsibility for its own security and the move could pave the way for Taliban peace talks.<ref>{{cite news|last=Graham-Harrison|first=Emma|title=Afghanistan president welcomes US plan to withdraw troops by 2016|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/may/28/afghanistan-president-welcomes-us-plan-withdraw-troops|accessdate=29 May 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|date=28 May 2014}}</ref> While Afghanistan military forces reacted to Obama's plans with skepticism arguing among other things that Afghan military's lack of air support and heavy artillery couldn't be overcome by 2016 or 2017 and NATO welcomed the announcement, U.S. politicians split along party lines to Obama's drawdown and post 2014 presence plans, Afghanistan lawmakers considered those plans a blow to Afghan morale and American think tanks questioned the post presence limitation to the end of 2016 pointing out to experience in Germany, Britain, Korea and Japan, where U.S. forces remain long after wars have ended but the need to support strong allies remains.<ref name=\"NYT20140527\" /><ref name=\"WSJ20140528\">{{cite news|title=Obama Details Plan for Forces in Afghanistan|url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/obama-details-plan-for-forces-in-afghanistan-1401234489?tesla=y&mg=reno64-wsj&url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052702303403604579588574244016560|accessdate=29 May 2014|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=28 May 2014|author1=Adam Entous  |author2=Carol E. Lee |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref><ref name=\"WP20140527\" /><ref name=\"USAToday20140527\" />\n\nAfghanistan and the United States signed the bilateral security agreement through U.S. Ambassador James B. Cunningham and Afghan national security adviser Mohammad Hanif the bilateral security agreement on 30 September 2014 in a cordial ceremony at the presidential palace in Kabul, Afghanistan.<ref name=\"NYT20140930\" /><ref name=\"WP201040930\" /><ref>{{cite news|last1=Michaels|first1=Jim|title=Afghanistan, U.S. sign long-delayed security pact|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/world/2014/09/30/afghan-us-security-pact/16467441/|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=USA Today|publisher=USA Today|date=30 September 2014}}</ref> On that day the NATO Status of Forces Agreement was also signed, giving forces from Allied and partner countries the legal protections necessary to carry out the NATO [[Resolute Support Mission]] when International Security Assistance Force comes to an end in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=Statement by the President on the Signing of the Bilateral Security Agreement and NATO Status of Forces Agreement in Afghanistan|url=http://www.whitehouse.gov/the-press-office/2014/09/30/statement-president-signing-bilateral-security-agreement-and-nato-status|website=whitehouse.gov|publisher=The White House Office of the Press Secretary|accessdate=26 October 2014|date=30 September 2014}}</ref> Under both agreements 9,800 American and at least 2,000 NATO troops are allowed to remain in Afghanistan after the international combat mission formally ends on 31 December 2014<ref name=\"NYT20140930\" /> while also enabling the continued training and advising of Afghan security forces, as well as counterterrorism operations against remnants of al-Qaeda.<ref name=\"WP201040930\" /> Most of the troops will help train and assist the struggling Afghan security forces, although some American Special Operations forces will remain to conduct counterterrorism missions.<ref name=\"NYT20140930\" /> The Nato-led ISAF mission will transition to a training mission headquartered in Kabul with six bases around the country.<ref name=\"NYT20140930\" />  Under the BSA the United States are allowed to have bases at nine separate locations across Afghanistan.<ref name=\"WP201040930\" /> A base in Jalalabad, in eastern Afghanistan, could also remain a launching point for armed drone missions in Afghanistan and across the border in Pakistan.<ref name=\"NYT20140930\">{{cite news|author1=Declan Walsh and Azam Ahmed|title=Mending Alliance, U.S. and Afghanistan Sign Long-Term Security Agreement|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/01/world/asia/afghanistan-and-us-sign-bilateral-security-agreement.html?_r=0|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times|date=30 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"WP201040930\">{{cite news|author1=Sudarsan Raghavan and Karen DeYoung|title=U.S. and Afghanistan sign vital, long-delayed security pact|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-afghanistan-sign-security-pact-to-allow-american-forces-to-remain-in-country/2014/09/30/48f555ce-4879-11e4-a046-120a8a855cca_story.html|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=The Washington Post|publisher=The Washington Post|date=30 September 2014}}</ref> The agreement also prevents U.S. military personnel from being prosecuted under Afghan laws for any crimes they may commit; instead, the United States has jurisdiction over any criminal proceedings or disciplinary action involving its troops inside the country. The provision does not apply to civilian contractors.<ref name=\"WP201040930\" /> The troop number of 9.800 Americans is to be cut in half by 2016, with American forces thereafter based only in Kabul and at Bagram air base. By the end of 2017, the U.S. force is to be further reduced in size to what U.S. officials have called a \"normal\" military advisory component at the U.S. Embassy in Kabul, most likely numbering several hundred.<ref name=\"WP201040930\" /> The BSA goes into force on 1 January 2015 and remains in force \"until the end of 2024 and beyond\" unless it is terminated by either side with two years' notice.<ref name=\"rferl.org\">{{cite news|last1=Recknagel|first1=Charles|title=Explainer: Key Points In U.S.-Afghan Bilateral Security Agreement|url=http://www.rferl.org/content/explainer-bsa-afghan-us-security-agreement-bsa/26613884.html|accessdate=26 October 2014|work=Radio Free Europe and Radio Liberty|publisher=Radio Free Europe and Radio Liberty|date=30 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014 U.S. President Obama expanded the original role of U.S. Armed Forces in Afghanistan for 2015. Originally they were supposed to advise, train and assist the Afghan Forces and to hunt the remnants of Al Qaeda. Under the president's order U.S. forces can carry out missions against the Taliban and other militant groups threatening American troops or the Afghan government while American jets, bombers and drones can support Afghan troops on combat missions. By the end of 2015, half of the 9,800 American troops would leave Afghanistan. The rest would be consolidated in Kabul and Bagram, and then leave by the end of 2016, allowing Obama to say he ended the Afghan war before leaving office. The United States could still have military advisers in Kabul after 2016 who would work out of an office of security cooperation at the United States Embassy. But the Obama administration has not said how large that contingent might be and what its exact mission would be.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Mark Mazzetti and Eric Schmitt|title=In a Shift, Obama Extends U.S. Role in Afghan Combat|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/22/us/politics/in-secret-obama-extends-us-role-in-afghan-combat.html|accessdate=14 February 2015|work=The New York Times|publisher=The New York Times|date=21 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring his last trip to Afghanistan U.S. Secretary of Defense Chuck Hagel announced on 6 December 2014 the end of the U.S. original plan to withdraw its troops form Afghanistan. Under a plan announced in May 2014 the number of American troops was supposed to fall to 9,800 by 1 January 2015. Instead the U.S. will keep up to 10,800 troops for the first few months of 2015 and then restart the drawdown, which is scheduled to reach 5,500 troops by the end of 2015. Besides partaking in NATO's [[Resolute Support Mission]] consisting of 12,500 soldiers<ref name=\"DPARS20141202\">{{cite news|title=NATO chief, Afghan president welcome \"new phase\" as combat role ends|url=http://www.dpa-international.com/news/asia/nato-afghan-president-ghani-tolaunch-new-2015-mission-a-43481490.html|accessdate=7 February 2015|work=DPA|agency=DPA|date=2 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150207185555/http://www.dpa-international.com/news/asia/nato-afghan-president-ghani-tolaunch-new-2015-mission-a-43481490.html|archive-date=7 February 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> some U.S. troops will take part in a separate counterterrorism mission focused on al-Qaeda. By the time U.S. President Obama leaves office in 2017 only a small force attached to the U.S. Embassy in Kabul is to remain in Afghanistan. The reason for the United States to keep additional forces in the country temporarily was that planned troop commitments by US allies for the Nato train-and-assist mission starting in January 2015 have been slow to materialize. President Barack Obama \"has provided US military commanders the flexibility to manage any temporary force shortfall that we might experience for a few months as we allow for coalition troops to arrive in theater,\" Hagel said in a news conference with President Ashraf Ghani in Kabul. \"But the president's authorization will not change our troops' missions, or the long-term timeline for our drawdown,\" he added.<ref>{{cite news|title=Chuck Hagel: more US troops will remain in Afghanistan|accessdate=7 February 2015|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Guardian|date=6 December 2014|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/dec/06/chuck-hagel-more-us-troops-will-remain-in-afghanistan}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=More US Troops Than Planned to Stay in Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2014/12/06/world/asia/ap-as-united-states-afghanistan.html?_r=0|accessdate=7 February 2015|agency=The Associated Press|newspaper=The New York Times|date=6 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Ryan|first1=Missy|title=Hagel says U.S. to leave up to 1,000 extra troops in Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/hagel-pays-final-visit-to-afghanistan-as-pentagon-chief/2014/12/06/e6cf5c2c-7d17-11e4-9a27-6fdbc612bff8_story.html|accessdate=7 February 2015|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=6 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nAt the end of March 2015 U.S. President Obama announced to slow the pace of the U.S. troop withdrawal by maintaining the current force levels of 9,800 troops through at least the end of 2015. This announcement came after a request by the Afghan government under its new president Ashraf Ghani. Obama  and Ghani stated the troops were needed to train and advise Afghan forces. According to U.S. official keeping the current force in place would allow American special operations troops and the Central Intelligence Agency to operate in southern and eastern Afghanistan, where the insurgents are strongest and where Al Qaeda's presence is concentrated. Obama also stated to close the remaining U.S. bases in Afghanistan, to withdraw all but about 1,000 troops by the time he leaves office at the beginning of 2017 consolidate the remaining U.S. forces in Kabul. Those forces would operate largely in Kabul and protect embassy personnel and other American officials there.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lederman |first=Josh |date=24 March 2015 |title=White House: US to slow troop withdrawal from Afghanistan |url=http://apnews.myway.com/article/20150324/us--united_states-afghanistan-bae7252c6c.html |newspaper=Associated Press |access-date=24 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Greg Jaffe and David Nakamura|title=Obama agrees to slow U.S. troop withdrawal from Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/obama-agrees-to-slow-us-troop-withdrawal-from-afghanistan/2015/03/24/6acd4834-d247-11e4-a62f-ee745911a4ff_story.html?tid=sm_tw|accessdate=27 March 2015|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=27 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Michael D. Shear and Mark Mazetti|title=U.S. to Delay Pullout of Troops From Afghanistan to Aid Strikes|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/25/world/asia/ashraf-ghani-of-afghanistan-wants-us-troops-to-stay-longer.html|accessdate=27 March 2015|date=24 March 2015|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rosenberg|first1=Matthew|title=Ghani Addresses Congress, Eager to Rebuild Afghan-U.S. Ties|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/26/world/asia/ghani-addresses-congress-eager-to-rebuild-afghan-us-ties.html?_r=0|accessdate=27 March 2015|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 March 2015}}</ref> NATO has maintained 13,000 troops including 9,800 Americans in an advisory and counter-terrorism capacity in Afghanistan during the [[War in Afghanistan (2015\u2013present)|2015 phase of the War in Afghanistan]].<ref name=\"rferl.org\"/>\n\nIn the wake of the  Taliban's capture of Kundus during the [[Battle of Kunduz]] and following a US review of its troop presence in Afghanistan U.S. President Obama stated on 15 October 2015 that Afghan security forces are not as strong as they should be and that the security situation in Afghanistan is still very fragile with risks to deteriorate in some parts of the country. For these reasons Obama announced a new $15 billion-a-year plan: The U.S. will maintain its current force of 9,800 through most of 2016, then begin drawing down to 5,500 late in the year or in early 2017.<ref name=\"WP20151015\">{{cite news|author1=Greg Jaffe and Missy Ryan|title=Obama outlines plan to keep 5,500 troops in Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/obama-expected-to-announce-new-plan-to-keep-5500-troops-in-afghanistan/2015/10/14/d98f06fa-71d3-11e5-8d93-0af317ed58c9_story.html|accessdate=16 October 2015|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=15 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20151016\">{{cite news|author1=Matthew Rosenberg and Michael D. Shear|title=In Reversal, Obama Says U.S. Soldiers Will Stay in Afghanistan to 2017|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/10/16/world/asia/obama-troop-withdrawal-afghanistan.html?_r=0|accessdate=16 October 2015|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref>\nThe US forces will be stationed in four garrisons: Kabul, Bagram, Jalalabad and Kandahar.<ref name=\"WP20151015\" /><ref>{{cite news|title=US troops to stay in Afghanistan in policy shift|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-34536833|accessdate=16 October 2015|publisher=BBC News US & Canada|date=15 October 2015}}</ref> The post-2016 force will still be focused on training and advising the Afghan army, with a special emphasis on its elite counter-terrorism forces. The United States will also maintain a significant counter-terrorism capability of drones and Special Operations forces to strike al-Qaeda, forces of the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]], and other militants who may be plotting attacks against the United States.<ref name=\"WP20151015\" /> U.S. counter-terrorism forces deployed at bases in Kandahar and Jalalabad and the Bagram air base outside Kabul will be able to target al-Qaeda forces and forces of the Islamic State, while U.S. advisers can continue to work with key Afghan units, such as air and Special Operations forces, to blunt Taliban attacks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Obama bows to reality in Afghanistan|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/obama-bows-to-reality-in-afghanistan/2015/10/15/d22a04fe-735f-11e5-8248-98e0f5a2e830_story.html|accessdate=16 October 2015|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring a press conference on 6 July 2016 U.S. President Obama said he would draw down troops to 8,400 by the end of his administration in December 2016.<ref name=\"20170607CNNCollinsonKopan\">{{cite news|author1=Stephen Collinson and Tal Kopan|title=Obama to leave more troops than planned in Afghanistan|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/07/06/politics/obama-to-speak-on-afghanistan-wednesday-morning/|accessdate=6 July 2016|work=CNN|publisher=CNN|date=6 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=E. Lee|first1=Carol|title=Obama to Slow Troop Withdrawal From Afghanistan|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/obama-to-slow-troop-withdrawal-from-afghanistan-1467817803|accessdate=6 July 2016|work=The Wall Street Journal|publisher=The Wall Street Journal|date=6 July 2016}}</ref> He said the troops remaining in Afghanistan would continue to be focused on training and advising the Afghan military and engaging in counter-terrorism efforts.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Gregory Korte and Tom Vanden Brook|title=Obama: 8,400 troops to remain in Afghanistan|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2016/07/06/obama-afghanistan/86746010/|accessdate=6 July 2016|work=USA Today|publisher=USA Today|date=6 July 2016}}</ref> The president warned that a deteriorating security situation in Afghanistan could overwhelm Afghan government partners without further assistance. \"It's in our national interest \u2013 after all the blood and treasure we have invested \u2013 that we give our Afghan partners the support to succeed,\" said Obama.<ref name=\"20160706TheGuardian\" /> \"This is where al-Qaida is trying to regroup, where [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Isil]] is trying to expand its presence,\" he added. \"If they succeed, they will attempt more attacks against us.\"<ref name=\"20160706TheGuardian\">{{cite news|last1=Roberts|first1=Dan|title=Obama delays US troop withdrawal from 'precarious' Afghanistan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2016/jul/06/obama-delays-us-troop-withdrawal-afghanistan-al-qaida|accessdate=6 July 2016|work=The Guardian|publisher=The Guardian|date=6 July 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Plans by the administration of Donald Trump===\nIn the summer of 2017, with 8,400 U.S. troops already authorized,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.defensenews.com/2017/07/21/mattis-authority-delegated-by-trump-in-afghanistan-is-tactical-not-strategic/|title=Mattis: Authority delegated by Trump in Afghanistan is tactical, not strategic|last1=Copp|first1=Tara|date=July 21, 2017|publisher=Military Times|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170824164655/https://www.defensenews.com/2017/07/21/mattis-authority-delegated-by-trump-in-afghanistan-is-tactical-not-strategic/|archivedate=24 August 2017|accessdate=August 24, 2017|df=dmy-all}}</ref> U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] gave the U.S. military decision-making authority to increase troop numbers for U.S. military operations in [[American-led intervention in Syria|Syria]], [[American-led intervention in Iraq (2014\u2013present)|Iraq]] and [[War in Afghanistan (2015\u2013present)|Afghanistan]] without first seeking formal agreement from the White House.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Nicole Gaouette|title=Trump delegates troop decisions, to praise and concern|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/16/politics/trump-military-troops-afghanistan-mattis/index.html|accessdate=August 24, 2017|publisher=CNN|date=June 17, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170824160855/http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/16/politics/trump-military-troops-afghanistan-mattis/index.html|archivedate=24 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gordon|first1=Michael R.|title=Trump Gives Mattis Authority to Send More Troops to Afghanistan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/13/world/asia/mattis-afghanistan-military.html?mcubz=0|accessdate=August 24, 2017|newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 13, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824163802/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/13/world/asia/mattis-afghanistan-military.html?mcubz=0&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org|archivedate=August 24, 2017}}</ref>\nU.S. Secretary of Defense [[James Mattis]] praised the new authority: \"This assures [[United States Department of Defense|the department]] can facilitate our missions and nimbly align our commitment to the situation on the ground. Our overall mission in Afghanistan remains the same, to train, advise and assist the Afghan forces so they can safeguard the Afghan people and terrorists can find no haven in Afghanistan for attacking us or others.\"<ref>{{cite news|author1=Barbara Starr and Ryan Browne|title=Mattis confirms White House has given him authority to set Afghanistan troop levels|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/13/politics/pentagon-afghanistan-troop-levels/index.html|accessdate=August 24, 2017|publisher=CNN|date=June 14, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170824161756/http://edition.cnn.com/2017/06/13/politics/pentagon-afghanistan-troop-levels/index.html|archivedate=24 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> The broad outlines of the Afghanistan strategy, in place since April 2017, were described as \"an increase in special operations forces to train, advise and assist Afghan forces; a more robust plan to go after elements in Pakistan that aid the Taliban; the deployment of more air power and artillery; and a political commitment to the survival of the current government in Kabul\".<ref>{{cite news|author1=Eli Lake|title=Without plan, Trump allows more troops for Afghanistan|url=http://www.kansas.com/opinion/opn-columns-blogs/article156508114.html|accessdate=August 25, 2017|agency=WP Bloomberg|newspaper=The Wichita Eagle|date=June 16, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170825055916/http://www.kansas.com/opinion/opn-columns-blogs/article156508114.html|archivedate=August 25, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn August 21, 2017, Trump unveiled his strategy for Afghanistan and the broader South Asia, but he didn't specify the number of troops to be committed nor the conditions by which success could be judged.<ref name=\"NYT20170821\">{{cite news|author1=Julie Hirschfeld Davis and Mark Landler|title=Trump Outlines New Afghanistan War Strategy With Few Details|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/21/world/asia/afghanistan-troops-trump.html?mcubz=3|accessdate=August 24, 2017|newspaper=The New York Times|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824165338/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/21/world/asia/afghanistan-troops-trump.html?mcubz=3&mtrref=web.archive.org|archivedate=August 24, 2017}}</ref> Instead, conditions on the ground would determine troop levels and strategy.<ref name=\"WP20170821\">{{cite news|author1=David Nakamura and Abby Phillip|title=Politics Trump announces new strategy for Afghanistan that calls for a troop increase|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-expected-to-announce-small-troop-increase-in-afghanistan-in-prime-time-address/2017/08/21/eb3a513e-868a-11e7-a94f-3139abce39f5_story.html|accessdate=August 25, 2017|date=August 21, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170825055254/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/trump-expected-to-announce-small-troop-increase-in-afghanistan-in-prime-time-address/2017/08/21/eb3a513e-868a-11e7-a94f-3139abce39f5_story.html|archivedate=25 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This was confirmed on August 24, 2017 by the military commander for United States and NATO forces in Afghanistan, General John W. Nicholson, who described the new strategy in Afghanistan as defining success by conditions on the ground and not \"arbitrary timelines.\"<ref>{{cite news|author1=Mujib Mashal|title=U.S. Troop Increase in Afghanistan Is Underway, General Says|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/24/world/asia/afghanistan-troop-increase-trump-taliban.html?ribbon-ad-idx=3&rref=world/asia|accessdate=August 25, 2017|date=August 24, 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20170825054255/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/24/world/asia/afghanistan-troop-increase-trump-taliban.html?ribbon-ad-idx=3&rref=world/asia|archivedate=25 August 2017|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> U.S. President Trump said in his August 21, 2017 speech that \"victory will have a clear definition: attacking our enemies, obliterating [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]], crushing al-Qaeda, preventing the Taliban from taking over the country, and stopping mass terror attacks against Americans before they emerge.\"<ref name=\"WP20170821\" /> An additional 4,000 troops beyond the 8,500 U.S. service members already in the region were to be deployed.<ref name=\"WP20170821\" />\n\nOn August 30, 2017 the Pentagon disclosed that there were more troops in Afghanistan than previously acknowledged. The Pentagon said previously that there were 8,400 troops in Afghanistan, but in reality the actual \"total force\" number was closer to 11,000.<ref name=\"WP20170830\">{{cite news|author1=Thomas Gibbons-Neff|title=Checkpoint: Afghan troop surge likely to include thousands of paratroopers, Marines and heavy bombers|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2017/08/30/afghan-troop-surge-likely-to-include-thousands-of-paratroopers-marines-and-heavy-bombers/|accessdate=31 August 2017|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=August 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831212303/https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2017/08/30/afghan-troop-surge-likely-to-include-thousands-of-paratroopers-marines-and-heavy-bombers/?utm_term=.65996f424555|archivedate=31 August 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT20170830\" /> The lower number was based on misleading accounting measures and [[red tape]].<ref name=\"WPAP20170830\">{{cite news|author1=Lolita C. Baldor|title=Pentagon: US troop total in Afghanistan larger than reported|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/pentagon-us-troop-total-in-afghanistan-larger-than-reported/2017/08/30/e8d0bdea-8db3-11e7-9c53-6a169beb0953_story.html|accessdate=August 31, 2017|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Washington Post|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831205829/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/pentagon-us-troop-total-in-afghanistan-larger-than-reported/2017/08/30/e8d0bdea-8db3-11e7-9c53-6a169beb0953_story.html?utm_term=.adbe761de94a|archivedate=August 31, 2017}}</ref> The new count used by the United States Department of Defense includes covert as well as temporary units.<ref name=\"NYT20170830\">{{cite news|last1=Cooper|first1=Helene|title=U.S. Says It Has 11,000 Troops in Afghanistan, More Than Formerly Disclosed|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/30/world/asia/afghanistan-troop-totals.html?mcubz=3|accessdate=August 31, 2017|newspaper=The New York Times|date=August 30, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170831215013/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/30/world/asia/afghanistan-troop-totals.html?mcubz=3&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org&mtrref=web.archive.org|archivedate=August 31, 2017}}</ref> The Washington Post reported on August 30, 2017 that the additional U.S. forces for Afghanistan will likely include paratroopers as well as small Marine artillery detachments, composed of about 100 or so troops per unit, which will be spread around the country to fill in gaps in air support.<ref name=\"WPAP20170830\" /> The report by the Washington Post also reported that more air support \u2014 in the form of more [[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16 fighters]], [[Fairchild Republic A-10 Thunderbolt II|A-10 ground attack aircraft]] and additional [[Boeing B-52 Stratofortress|B-52 bomber support]], or a combination of all three - will likely be used in Afghanistan.<ref name=\"WPAP20170830\" /> The newspaper also stated: \"The additional U.S. forces will allow Americans to advise Afghan troops in more locations and closer to the fighting, U.S. officials in Kabul said [ ... ]. With more units farther away from the country's biggest bases, additional air support and artillery will be needed to cover those forces.\"<ref name=\"WPAP20170830\" /> And the New York Times added that: \"the American military will be able to advise select Afghan brigades in the field instead of trying to mentor them from more distant headquarters. They can step up the effort to train special operations forces and, thus, substantially increase the number of Afghan commandos. This will allow American war commanders and service members to call in air and artillery strikes on behalf of more Afghan units.\"<ref name=\"NYT20170830\" />\n\nU.S. Defense Secretary James Mattis confirmed on September 18, 2017 that 3,000 additional U.S. troops would be sent to Afghanistan, bringing the total number of U.S. forces in Afghanistan to more than 14,000 and bolstering the Afghan military in its fight against the Taliban, al Qaeda and the Islamic State in Iraq and Syria.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mitchell|first1=Ellen|newspaper=[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]|title=Mattis: US to send 3,000 more troops to Afghanistan|url=http://thehill.com/policy/defense/351222-mattis-us-to-send-3000-more-troops-to-afghanistan|accessdate=October 18, 2017|date=September 18, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018193100/http://thehill.com/policy/defense/351222-mattis-us-to-send-3000-more-troops-to-afghanistan|archivedate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Mattis says over 3,000 additional U.S. troops will deploy to Afghanistan|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mattis-says-over-3000-additional-u-s-troops-will-deploy-to-afghanistan/|accessdate=October 18, 2017|publisher=CBS News|date=September 18, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018193747/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/mattis-says-over-3000-additional-u-s-troops-will-deploy-to-afghanistan/|archivedate=October 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=US sends 3,000 more troops to Afghanistan|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-41314428|publisher=BBC News US & Canada|accessdate=October 18, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018193454/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-41314428|archivedate=October 18, 2017|date=September 18, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Ward|first1=Alex|title=Trump is sending more than 3,000 troops to Afghanistan|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2017/9/19/16227730/trump-afghanistan-3000-troops-mattis|website=Vox.com|publisher=[[Vox (website)|Vox]]|accessdate=October 18, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018194639/https://www.vox.com/world/2017/9/19/16227730/trump-afghanistan-3000-troops-mattis|archivedate=October 18, 2017|date=September 19, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhen [[Austin S. Miller|Gen. Austin \u201cScott\u201d Miller]] took command in Afghanistan in 2018, there were 15,000 U.S. troops there. In October 2019, Miller announced that this number had already been reduced to 13,000 as a result of a unilateral decision by the US.<ref name=\"George\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/us-has-begun-reducing-troops-in-afghanistan-commander-says/2019/10/21/d17a9e30-f3f1-11e9-8cf0-4cc99f74d127_story.html|title=U.S. has begun reducing troops in Afghanistan, commander says|last=George|first=Susannah|date=21 October 2019|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nOn February 29, 2020, the U.S. signed an agreement with the Taliban to withdraw troops in 14 months if the Taliban uphold the terms of the agreement. As of February 2020 about 13,000 American troops were still in the country. The two sides agreed a gradual, conditions-based withdrawal over 14 months and the withdrawal agreement encompasses \"all military forces of the United States, its allies, and Coalition partners, including all non-diplomatic civilian personnel, private security contractors, trainers, advisors, and supporting services personnel.\". In the first phase the U.S. will initially reduce its forces in Afghanistan by about 5,000 troops to 8,600 within 135 days of the U.S.-Taliban agreement. During the gradual withdrawal, the Taliban and the Afghan government would have to work out a more concrete power-sharing settlement. That time frame would give the government the cover of American military protection while negotiating. U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo said the remaining U.S. troops will serve as leverage to ensure the Taliban lives up to its promises. If the Taliban fulfills its commitments to renounce al Qaeda and begin [[Afghan peace process|intra-Afghan peace talks]], the U.S. agreed to a complete withdrawal of all remaining American forces from Afghanistan within 10 months.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Hamid Shalizi |author2=Charlotte Greenfield |title=U.S. to withdraw troops from Afghanistan in 14 months if Taliban conditions met |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/us-to-withdraw-troops-from-afghanistan-in-14-months-if-taliban-conditions-met/ar-BB10yxIL?li=BBnb7Kz |website=msn.com |publisher=Reuters |accessdate=29 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229233816/https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/us-to-withdraw-troops-from-afghanistan-in-14-months-if-taliban-conditions-met/ar-BB10yxIL?li=BBnb7Kz |archivedate=29 February 2020 |date=29 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Mujib Mashal |title=Taliban and U.S. Strike Deal to Withdraw American Troops From Afghanistan |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/29/world/asia/us-taliban-deal.html |accessdate=29 February 2020 |date=29 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229235609/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/29/world/asia/us-taliban-deal.html |archivedate=29 February 2020|publisher=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Mujib Mashal and Russell Goldman |title=4 Takeaways From the U.S. Deal With the Taliban |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/29/world/asia/us-taliban-afghanistan.html |accessdate=1 March 2020 |publisher=The New York Times |date=29 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301000422/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/02/29/world/asia/us-taliban-afghanistan.html |archivedate=1 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Tom Vanden Brook and Deirdre Shesgreen |title=Historic peace deal in Afghanistan reached with Taliban, allowing withdrawal of US troops |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/02/29/u-s-taliban-sign-deal-peace-talks-begin-u-s-troops-withdraw/4738736002/ |accessdate=1 March 2020 |work=USA Today |publisher=USA Today |date=29 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301001435/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2020/02/29/u-s-taliban-sign-deal-peace-talks-begin-u-s-troops-withdraw/4738736002/ |archivedate=1 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Afghan conflict: US and Taliban sign deal to end 18-year war |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51689443 |accessdate=1 March 2020 |publisher=BBC News |date=29 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301002219/https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51689443 |archivedate=1 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Jennifer Hansler |title=US and Taliban sign historic agreement |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/29/politics/us-taliban-deal-signing/index.html |accessdate=1 March 2020 |publisher=CNN |date=29 February 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301004545/https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/29/politics/us-taliban-deal-signing/ |archivedate=1 March 2020}}</ref> On March 1, however, the peace agreement hit a major snag when President Ghani stated during a press conference that the Afghan government, which was not a party to the deal, would reject the deal's call for conducting a prisoner exchange with the Taliban by the proposed start of intra-Afghan negotiations on March 10, 2020, even stating that \"The government of Afghanistan has made no commitment to free 5,000 Taliban prisoners,\" \u201can agreement that is signed behind closed doors will have basic problems in its implementation tomorrow,\u201d \u201cThe release of prisoners is not the United States authority, but it is the authority of the government of Afghanistan.\u201d<ref name=apreject>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2020/03/01/afghan-peace-deal-prisoner-release-118473|title=Afghan peace deal hits first snag over prisoner releases|author=[[Associated Press]]|publisher=Politico|accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=reject>{{Cite web| title = Ghani: No Commitment to Release Taliban Prisoners| work = TOLOnews| accessdate = 2020-03-01| url = https://tolonews.com/afghanistan/ghani-no-commitment-release-taliban-prisoners}}</ref><ref name=reject2>{{cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/president-ghani-rejects-peace-deal-prisoner-swap-taliban-200301082216180.html|title=President Ghani rejects peace deal's prisoner swap with Taliban|publisher=Al Jazeera|date=March 1, 2020|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=nprreject>{{cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2020/03/01/810949474/afghan-president-rejects-timeline-for-prisoner-swap-proposed-in-us-taliban-peace|title=Afghan President Rejects Timeline For Prisoner Swap Proposed In US-Taliban Peace Deal|first=Cat|last=Schuknecht|publisher=NPR|date=1 March 2020|accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> Ghani also stated that any prisoner exchange \n\"cannot be a prerequisite for talks,\" but must be a part of the negotiations.<ref name=bbcreject>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-51695370|title=Afghan conflict: President Ashraf Ghani rejects Taliban prisoner release|publisher=BBC News|date=1 March 2020|accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSome U.S. troops withdrew from Afghanistan on March 10, 2020.<ref>https://apnews.com/2ac6e6ae6d805a5d067da8f36d3052d7</ref> The same day, however, Centcom chief [[Kenneth F. McKenzie Jr.|Gen. Kenneth F. McKenzie Jr.]] denied to members of the U.S. Congress that there was a plan to enact a full withdrawal.<ref name=partialonly /> McKenzie also stated that the plan is to reduce the number of U.S. troops in Afghanistan to 8,600 in a 14-month period.<ref name=partialonly /> On 23 April 2020, however, spokespeople representing various brigades of the U.S Army confirmed that the escalation of U.S. Army units to Afghanistan will resume in the summer of 2020.<ref name=\"moretroops\">{{cite web |last1=Vandiver |first1=John |title=Army announces summer troop moves to Europe, Iraq and Afghanistan |url=https://www.stripes.com/news/europe/army-announces-summer-troop-moves-to-europe-iraq-and-afghanistan-1.627236 |website=Stars and Stripes |publisher=Stars and Stripes |accessdate=25 April 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200425182238/https://www.stripes.com/news/europe/army-announces-summer-troop-moves-to-europe-iraq-and-afghanistan-1.627236 |archivedate=25 April 2020 |date=April 24, 2020}}</ref><\n\n==See also==\n* [[Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq (2007\u20132011)|Withdrawal of U.S. troops from Iraq]] (comparable event)\n* [[Paris Peace Accords]] (comparable event)\n* [[Taliban insurgency]]\n* [[Civilian casualties in the War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n* ''[[Duty: Memoirs of a Secretary at War]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* ''[[Duty: Memoirs of a Secretary at War]]'' by [[Robert Gates]]. New York: [[Alfred A. Knopf]], 2014.\n\n==External links==\n* Afghanistan: Drawdown serie by [[Al Jazeera English]], with [http://www.aljazeera.com/programmes/peopleandpower/2013/05/2013529133226564418.html a video] and two interactive webpages: [http://webapps.aljazeera.net/aje/custom/2014/drawdownafghanistan/infographic/index.html ''Cost of War''] and [http://webapps.aljazeera.net/aje/custom/2014/drawdownafghanistan/web/index.html ''The long godbye'']\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IT-iwQ2M-lA U.S. Military Prepares to Move Out of Afghanistan], YouTube video by [[United States Central Command]]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qeonvpu5jcs U.S. military prepares to end Afghanistan combat mission], YouTube video by [[CNN]]\n\n{{War on Terror}}\n{{Afghanistan War}}\n\n[[Category:2011 in military history]]\n[[Category:2012 in military history]]\n[[Category:2013 in military history]]\n[[Category:2014 in military history]]\n[[Category:2015 in military history]]\n[[Category:2016 in military history]]\n[[Category:2011 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2012 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2013 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2014 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2015 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2016 in the United States]]\n[[Category:2011 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:2012 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:2013 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:2014 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:2015 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:2016 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Modern history of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Battles involving Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:History of the United States (1991\u2013present)]]\n[[Category:Afghanistan\u2013United States military relations]]\n[[Category:Pakistan\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:Pakistan\u2013United States military relations]]\n[[Category:Pakistan\u2013NATO relations]]\n[[Category:Military withdrawals]]\n", "name_user": "P3Y229", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moved content", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Withdrawal_of_U.S._troops_from_Afghanistan"}
{"title_page": "Malaysia Airlines Flight 17", "text_new": "{{short description|July 2014 airliner downing in rebel-controlled Donetsk, Ukraine}}\n{{For|the aircraft that disappeared over the Indian Ocean in March 2014|Malaysia Airlines Flight 370}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2015}}\n{{Infobox aircraft occurrence\n| name = Malaysia Airlines Flight 17\n| image = Boeing 777-2H6ER 9M-MRD Malaysian (6658105143).jpg\n| image_upright = 1.1591\n| alt = \n| caption = 9M-MRD, the aircraft involved, 2011\n| occurrence_type = Shootdown\n| date = {{start date|2014|07|17|df=y}}\n| summary = Shot down by a [[surface-to-air missile]] transported from Russia on the day of the crash<ref name=\"SMH JIT\"/><ref name=\"BBC News 28 September 2016\" />\n| site = Near [[Hrabove, Donetsk Oblast]], Ukraine\n| coordinates = {{Coord|48|8|17|N|38|38|20|E|type:event|display=inline,title}}\n| aircraft_type = [[Boeing 777#777-200ER|Boeing 777-200ER]]<!-- The aircraft model is Boeing 777-200ER. The customer code used at Boeing was \"777-2H6ER\". \"H6\" is the Malaysia Airlines customer code to indicate certain preferences. Consensus is to use \"Boeing 777-200ER\" as the model number. -->\n| aircraft_name = \n| operator = [[Malaysia Airlines]]\n| IATA = MH17\n| ICAO = MAS17\n| callsign = MALAYSIAN 17\n| tail_number = 9M-MRD\n| origin = [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol]], the Netherlands\n| stopover = \n| destination = [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]], Malaysia\n| occupants = 298\n| passengers = 283\n| crew = 15\n| fatalities = 298<!-- don't need to add \"(all)\", we already have survivors=0 -->\n| survivors = 0\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Ukrainian crisis}}\n'''Malaysia Airlines Flight 17''' ('''MH17'''){{efn|MH is the [[IATA airline designator|IATA designator]]. The flight was also marketed as [[KLM]] Flight 4103 (KLM4103) through a [[codeshare agreement|codeshare]], and has been commonly referred to as \"MH17\", \"Flight 17\" or \"Flight MH17\".}} was a scheduled passenger flight from [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol|Amsterdam]] to [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur]] that was [[List of airliner shootdown incidents|shot down]] on 17 July 2014 while flying over [[eastern Ukraine]]. All 283 passengers and 15 crew were killed.<ref name=\"dsb1\"/> Contact with the aircraft, a [[Boeing 777-200ER]], was lost when it was about {{convert|50|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the [[Ukraine\u2013Russia border]], and wreckage of the aircraft fell near [[Hrabove, Donetsk Oblast|Hrabove]] in [[Donetsk Oblast]], Ukraine, {{convert|40|km|mi|abbr=on}} from the border.<ref name=telegraph>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10974050/Malaysia-Airlines-plane-crashes-on-Ukraine-Russia-border-live.html |title=Malaysia Airlines plane crashes on Ukraine-Russia border \u2013 live |date=17 July 2014 |first=Harriet |last=Alexander |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=17 July 2014 |archivedate=18 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718001608/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10974050/Malaysia-Airlines-plane-crashes-on-Ukraine-Russia-border-live.html}}</ref> It was [[Malaysia Airlines|Malaysia Airlines']] second aircraft loss during 2014, after the disappearance of [[Malaysia Airlines Flight 370|Flight 370]] on 8 March.<ref name=\"Official nationalities\">{{cite web|url=http://www.malaysiaairlines.com/my/en/site/mh17.html|title=Saturday, July 19, 07:30&nbsp;pm GMT +0800 Media Statement 7 : MH17 Incident|date=19 July 2014|website=Malaysia Airlines|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717232838/http://www.malaysiaairlines.com/my/en/site/mh17.html|archive-date=17 July 2014|accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> The shoot-down occurred in the [[War in Donbass]], during the [[Battle in Shakhtarsk Raion]], in an area controlled by [[2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine|pro-Russian rebels]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/10/world/europe/malaysian-airliner-ukraine.html |title=Malaysian Jet Over Ukraine Was Downed by 'High-Energy Objects,' Dutch Investigators Say |last=Higgins |first=Andrew |last2=Clark |first2=Nicola |date=9 September 2014 |website=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> [[List of Ukrainian aircraft losses during the Ukrainian crisis|The Ukrainian Air Force had suffered losses]] from increasingly sophisticated air defence weaponry. \n\nThe responsibility for investigation was delegated to the [[Dutch Safety Board]] (DSB) and the Dutch-led [[#Criminal investigation|joint investigation team]] (JIT), who concluded that the airliner was downed by a [[Buk missile system|Buk]] [[surface-to-air missile]] launched from pro-Russian [[Novorossiya (confederation)|separatist-controlled territory]] in Ukraine.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\" /><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news |title=MH17 crash report: Dutch investigators confirm Buk missile hit plane \u2013 live updates |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/live/2015/oct/13/mh17-crash-report-ukraine-live-updates |newspaper=the Guardian |accessdate=13 October 2015 |first=Matthew |last=Weaver|date=13 October 2015 }}</ref> According to the JIT, the Buk that was used originated from the [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]] of the [[Russia|Russian Federation]]<ref name=\"BBC 5.24.18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-44235402|work=[[BBC News]]|title=MH17 missile owned by Russian brigade, investigators say|date=24 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN 5.24.18\">{{cite news|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/05/24/europe/mh17-plane-netherlands-russia-intl/index.html|work=[[CNN]]|title=Missile that downed MH17 'owned by Russian brigade'|first1=Laura|last1=Smith-Spark|first2=James|last2=Masters|date=24 May 2018}}</ref> and had been transported from Russia on the day of the crash, fired from a field in a rebel-controlled area and returned to Russia afterwards.<ref name=\"SMH JIT\" /><ref name=\"BBC News 28 September 2016\"/><ref name=\"BBC 5.24.18\"/> On the basis of the JIT's conclusions, the governments of the Netherlands and Australia held Russia responsible for the deployment of the Buk installation and were pursuing legal routes {{As of|2018|May|df=|lc=y}}.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.government.nl/latest/news/2018/05/25/mh17-the-netherlands-and-australia-hold-russia-responsible|title=MH17: The Netherlands and Australia hold Russia responsible|last=Algemene Zaken|first=Ministerie van|last2=Buitenlandse Zaken|first2=Ministerie van|website=www.government.nl|language=nl-NL|access-date=25 May 2018|date=25 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Evidence in The Australian\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/world/mh17-shot-down-by-missile-from-russia-by-its-military-report-finds/news-story/d3d1cafaa0033e7acc42d9b9fc38dbf4|title=MH17 evidence points to 'rogue state' Russia, Tony Abbott says|last=Bunnik|first=Jacquelin Magnay|last2=Riordan|first2=Primrose|date=25 May 2018|website=The Australian|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The Russian government denied involvement in the shooting down of the plane,<ref name=\"CNN 5.24.18\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://tass.com/defense/1006070|title=No Russian air defense missile systems crossed Russia-Ukraine border \u2013 top brass|work=TASS|access-date=25 May 2018|language=ru}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-29140593|title=Ukraine crisis: Poroshenko offers rebels more autonomy|date=10 September 2014|work=BBC News|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/europe/putin-claims-no-proof-russians-downed-mh17-20190621-p51ztv.html|title=Russians made a 'scapegoat' after MH17 report released, says Malaysia PM|last=Sipalan|first=Joseph|date=21 June 2019|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2019-06-23}}</ref> and holds the Ukrainian government at fault for [[Air traffic control|allowing civilian flights]] in a war zone.<ref>{{Citation|title=Putin Dismisses MH17 Charges|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/russia-putin-mh17/30010707.html|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Immediately after contact with the aircraft was lost, the rebel militia in Donetsk claimed to have shot down a Ukrainian [[Antonov An-26|An-26]] military transporter.<ref name=\"VK Wall\"/> When it became apparent that the wreckage that fell near Hrabove was from a civilian airliner, the separatists withdrew this claim and denied shooting down any aircraft.<ref name=\"vk.com\"/><ref name=\"Arthur Bright\"/><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/20/three-pro-russia-rebel-leaders-suspects-over-downed-mh17 |title=The Guardian 20 July 2014 |author=Alec Luhn |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=8 September 2014|date=20 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\nThe findings by the DSB and JIT are consistent with the earlier claims by American and German intelligence sources<ref name=\"LAtimes\"/><ref name=\"WaPoJuly22\">{{cite news |title=The evidence that may prove pro-Russian separatists shot down MH17 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/07/20/the-evidence-that-may-prove-pro-russian-separatists-shot-down-mh17/ |accessdate=8 September 2014 |work=The Washington Post |date=22 July 2014}}</ref> and claims by the Ukrainian government.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/yatsenyuk-russia-is-not-planning-to-conduct-any-humanitarian-mission-live-361699.html|title=Yatsenyuk: 'We need to survive first'|date=22 August 2014|work=Kyiv Post}}</ref>\n\n==Aircraft==\nFlight 17, which was also marketed as [[KLM]] Flight 4103 (KL4103) through a [[codeshare agreement]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Statement Malaysia Airlines MH17 |url=http://news.klm.com/en/incident-with-malaysia-airlines-flight-mh017-e/ |website=[[KLM]] |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> was operated with a Boeing 777-2H6ER,{{efn|The aircraft is a Boeing 777-200ER (for Extended Range) model; Boeing assigns a [[List of Boeing customer codes|unique customer code]] for each company that buys one of its aircraft, which is applied as an [[infix]] in the model number at the time the aircraft is built. The code for Malaysia Airlines is \"H6\", hence \"777-2H6ER\".}} serial number 28411, registration 9M-MRD.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|30}} The 84th Boeing 777 produced, it first flew on 17 July 1997, exactly 17 years before the incident, and was delivered new to Malaysia Airlines on 29 July 1997.<ref name=\"airfleets1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.airfleets.net/ficheapp/plane-b777-28411.htm# |title=Malaysia Airlines 9M-MRD (Boeing 777&nbsp;\u2013 MSN 28411) &#124; Airfleets aviation |publisher=Airfleets.net |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Powered by two [[Rolls-Royce Trent 800|Rolls-Royce Trent 892]] engines and carrying 280 seats (33 [[Business class|business]] and 247 [[Economy class|economy]]), the aircraft had recorded more than 76,300 hours in 11,430 cycles before the crash.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|30}} The aircraft was in an airworthy condition at departure.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|31}}\n\nThe Boeing 777, which entered commercial service on 7 June 1995, has one of the best safety records among commercial aircraft.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/07/17/boeing-777-safe-track-record/12786181/ |title=Boeing 777 has excellent track record, experts say |author=Larry Copeland |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> In June 2014 there were about 1,212 aircraft in service, with 340 more on order.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://active.boeing.com/commercial/orders/displaystandardreport.cfm?cboCurrentModel=777&optReportType=AllModels&cboAllModel=777&ViewReportF=View+Report |title=777 Model Orders and Deliveries summary |publisher=Boeing |date=June 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Passengers and crew==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"margin:0 0 0.5em 1em; float:right;\"\n|-\n|+People on board by nationality<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|27}}\n|-\n!Nation||data-sort-type=\"number\"|Number<!-- OFFICIAL LIST PER THE OFFICIAL DSB REPORT, DON'T MODIFY -->\n|-\n|Australia || style=\"text-align:center;\"|27\n|-\n|Belgium || style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|Canada{{efn|Including:\n* 1 dual Canadian-Romanian citizen}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Germany{{efn|Including:\n* 1 dual German-Dutch citizen}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|Indonesia || style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|-\n|Malaysia{{efn|28 passengers and 15 crew}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|43\n|-\n|Netherlands{{efn|Including:\n* 1 dual Dutch-Belgian citizen\n* 1 dual Dutch-Israeli citizen\n* 1 dual Dutch-Italian citizen\n* 1 dual Dutch-American citizen\n* 1 dual Dutch-Malaysian citizen<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2014/09/09/remains-of-shell-worker-and-baby-coming-home-so-far-35-victims-have-been-brought-back/|title=Remains of Shell worker and baby coming home|newspaper=[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]|date=9 September 2014|accessdate=25 September 2017|quote=The 35, he added, included restaurateur Jenny Loh Yan Hwa, a passenger with dual citizenship, along with Dutch citizens Fan Shun Po and Paul Goes.}} \u2013 The Dutch-Malaysian <!--LOH/YANHWA MRS--> is counted as Dutch on [https://www.malaysiaairlines.com/content/dam/malaysia-airlines/mas/PDF/MH17/MH17%20PAX%20AND%20CREW%20MANIFEST%20200714.pdf the manifest]</ref>\n* 3 Dutch-Vietnamese citizen <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thanhniennews.com/society/vietnamese-family-friends-mourn-as-remains-of-mh17-victims-arrive-home-33948.html|title=Vietnamese family, friends mourn as remains of MH17 victims arrive home|date=13 November 2014|website=Thanh Nien Daily}}</ref>|name=|group=}}|| style=\"text-align:center;\" |193\n|-\n|New Zealand || style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|Philippines || style=\"text-align:center;\"|3\n|-\n|United Kingdom{{efn|Including:\n* 1 dual British-South African citizen\n* 1 dual British-New Zealand citizen}} || style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n| '''Total''' || style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''298'''\n|}\n\nThe incident is the deadliest airliner shootdown incident to date.<ref name=reuters>{{cite news |url=http://www.financialexpress.com/news/malaysia-airlines-mh17-shot-down-top-5-deadliest-attacks-on-airliners/1271130 |title=Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17: Top 5 deadliest airliner shootdowns |agency=Reuters |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> All 283 passengers and 15 crew died.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|27}} By 19 July, the airline had determined the nationalities of all 298 passengers and crew.<ref name=\"Official nationalities\"/>\n\nThe crew were all Malaysian, while over two-thirds (68%) of the passengers were Dutch. Most of the other passengers were Malaysians and Australians, the remainder were citizens of seven other countries.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|27}}\n\nAmong the passengers were delegates en route to the [[XX International AIDS Conference, 2014|20th International AIDS Conference]] in Melbourne, including [[Joep Lange]], a former president of the [[International AIDS Society]], which organised the conference.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/crash-claims-top-aids-researchers-heading-to-melbourne-20140718-zuaw3.html |title=Crash claims top AIDS researchers heading to Melbourne |last=Lillebuen |first=Steve |date=18 July 2014 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Many initial reports had erroneously indicated that around 100 delegates to the conference were aboard, but this was later revised to six.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robin |first1=Myriam |title=100 AIDS researchers on MH17? Why and how the media got it wrong |url=http://www.crikey.com.au/2014/07/23/100-aids-researchers-on-mh17-why-and-how-the-media-got-it-wrong/ |website=[[Crikey]] |accessdate=23 July 2014 |date=23 July 2014}}</ref> Also on board were [[Senate (Netherlands)|Dutch Senator]] [[Willem Witteveen]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/2686/Binnenland/article/detail/3691664/2014/07/18/Senator-Witteveen-PvdA-omgekomen-bij-crash.dhtml |title=Senator Witteveen (PvdA) omgekomen bij crash \u2013 Binnenland \u2013 VK |work=De Volkskrant |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Australian author [[Liam Davison]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Victorians among those killed in MH17 crash: Premier |url=http://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/story/2426085/victorians-among-those-killed-in-mh17-crash-premier/?cs=80 |work=[[Bendigo Advertiser]] |accessdate=19 July 2014|date=18 July 2014 }}</ref> and Malaysian actress [[Shuba Jay]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Malaysian actress, Dutch hubby and baby die with MH17 |url=http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/malaysian-actress-dutch-hubby-and-baby-die-with-mh17 |newspaper=The Malaysian Insider |accessdate=19 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140722064912/http://www.themalaysianinsider.com/malaysia/article/malaysian-actress-dutch-hubby-and-baby-die-with-mh17 |archivedate=22 July 2014 }}</ref>\n\nAt least twenty family groups were on the aircraft and eighty passengers were under the age of 18.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/news/asia/south-east-asia/story/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-20-families-gone-one-shot-20140721 |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 crash: 20 families gone in one shot |newspaper=[[The Straits Times]] |date=21 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RF430C7G?url=http://www.straitstimes.com/news/asia/south-east-asia/story/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-20-families-gone-one-shot-20140721 |archivedate=21 July 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Miranda |first1=Charles |first2=Cindy |last2=Wockner |first3=Ian |last3=McPhedran |author-link3=Ian McPhedran|first4=Jacquelin |last4=Magnay |url=http://www.news.com.au/world/mh17-train-in-kharkiv-as-tony-abbott-says-mh17-aftermath-is-evidence-tampering-on-industrial-scale/story-fndir2ev-1226996838429 |title=MH17 train in Kharkiv as Tony Abbott says MH17 aftermath is evidence tampering on industrial scale |publisher=[[News Corp Australia]] |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150724092335/http://www.news.com.au/world/mh17-train-in-kharkiv-as-tony-abbott-says-mh17-aftermath-is-evidence-tampering-on-industrial-scale/story-fndir2ev-1226996838429|archivedate=24 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe flightcrew were captains Wan Amran Wan Hussin and Eugene Choo Jin Leong, and first officers Ahmad Hakimi Hanapi and Muhd Firdaus Abdul Rahim.<ref>\"[http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/08/22/The-crew-of-MH17/ The crew of MH17]\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6S0tSU9RB?url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/08/22/The-crew-of-MH17/ Archive]). ''[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]''. 22 August 2014. Retrieved 22 August 2014.</ref>{{efn|The family name is Choo, as the Chinese name is Choo Jin Leong ({{zh|c=\u6731\u4ec1\u9686|p=Zh\u016b R\u00e9nl\u00f3ng}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.sina.com.cn/w/2014-07-18/170430543109.shtml |script-title=zh:MH17\u822a\u73ed\u534e\u88d4\u673a\u957f\u7236\u59bb\u5747\u66fe\u5c31\u804c\u9a6c\u822a |publisher=[[Sina Corp|Sina]] News |date=18 July 2014 |language=zh-hans <!--|archivelink=https://www.webcitation.org/6RWlHmVgT?url=http://news.sina.com.cn/w/2014-07-18/170430543109.shtml-->}} - The reference contains Choo's name in Chinese characters.</ref> - note that Ethnic Malays do not have family names.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2014/08/22/the-crew-of-mh17|title=The crew of MH17 &#124; The Star Online|website=www.thestar.com.my}}</ref>}}\n\n==Background==\n{{See also|2014 pro-Russian unrest in Ukraine|War in Donbass}}\n\nAn [[War in Donbass|armed conflict in Eastern Ukraine]] led some [[airlines]] to avoid eastern Ukrainian airspace in early March 2014 due to safety concerns.<ref name=20140718BBC>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-28356745 |title=MH17 crash: Airlines divert flights from eastern Ukraine |publisher=BBC |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/18/airlines-avoid-ukraine-airspace-mh17|title=Many airlines have avoided Ukrainian airspace for months|last=Neate|first=Rupert|last2=Glenza|first2=Jessica|date=18 July 2014|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> In the months prior to 17 July, reports also circulated in the media on the presence of weapons, including surface-to-air missiles, in the hands of the armes groups that were fighting the Ukrainian government in the eastern part of Ukraine. Ukrainian military aircraft were also deployed in the conflict. On 26 May a spokesperson of the Ukrainian Armed Forces revealed in the media that a surface-to-air missile systems that was being used by armed groups near Donetsk airport had been destroyed from a helicopter by the Ukrainian army. On 6 June 2014 ''[[The International New York Times]]'' reported that surface-to-air missiles had been seized from military bases. On 11 June the newspaper ''[[Argumenty nedeli]]'' reported that a Buk-M1 missile launcher had been present in an area under the armed groups' control. In late June the Russian news agencies reported that insurgents had obtained a [[Buk missile system]] after having taken control of a Ukrainian military unit A-1402;<ref name=\"vor-20140629\">{{cite news|url=http://voiceofrussia.com/news/2014_06_29/Donetsk-militia-takes-control-of-Ukrainian-anti-air-installation-1561/|title=Donetsk militia takes control of Ukrainian anti-air installation|date=29 June 2014|newspaper=Voice of Russia|accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"itar290614\">{{cite news|url=http://itar-tass.com/mezhdunarodnaya-panorama/1287030|date=29 June 2014|accessdate=21 July 2014|agency=[[Information Telegraph Agency of Russia]]|language=Russian|script-title=ru:\u041e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b \u0414\u041d\u0420 \u0432\u0437\u044f\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0442\u0440\u043e\u043b\u044c \u0432\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c \u041f\u0412\u041e \u0441 \u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043d\u043e-\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043c\u0438 \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\"|trans-title=DNR militias seized an air defence base with anti-aircraft missile systems \"Buk\"}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ntv.ru/novosti/1085256/|date=17 July 2014|work=NTV News|publisher=[[NTV (Russia)|NTV]]|language=Russian|script-title=ru:\u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b \u043e\u0431\u0437\u0430\u0432\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u0437\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0442\u043d\u043e-\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u043d\u044b\u043c\u0438 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043c\u0438 \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\"|trans-title=Donetsk militias acquired anti-aircraft missile systems \"Buk\"|accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> the [[Donetsk People's Republic]] claimed possession of such a system in a since-deleted [[Twitter|tweet]].<ref name=\"itar290614\" /><ref name=\"thediplomat\">{{cite news|last=Panda|first=Ankit|url=http://thediplomat.com/2014/07/malaysian-airlines-flight-mh17-shot-down-over-donetsk-ukraine/|title=Malaysian Airlines Flight MH17 Shot Down Over Donetsk, Ukraine|date=17 July 2014|work=The Diplomat|accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Such air defense systems cannot reliably identify and avoid civilian aircraft if present in the zone of conflict.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/2014/07/18/12951/how-can-a-civilian-plane-accidentally-be-shot-down/|title=How Can a Civilian Plane Accidentally Be Shot Down?|website=MIT Technology Review|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2014/07/18/did-the-ukrainian-rebels-even-know-they-were-shooting-at-a-civilian-aircraft/|title=Did the Ukrainian rebels even know they were shooting at a civilian aircraft?|last=telecommunications|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref> The Ukrainian authorities declared in the media that this system was not operational.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\" />{{rp|187\u2013188}} According to the subsequent statement of the [[Security Service of Ukraine]] three Buk missile systems were located on Ukrainian territory controlled by militia at the time that Malaysia Airlines Boeing-777 was shot down. On the night following the downing of MH17 three Buk missile launchers along with a [[Buk missile system#Description|Buk command vehicle]] were moved into Russia.<ref>[https://uacrisis.org/en/6364-v-sbu-eh-dokazi-bezposerednoyi-priche Ukraine\u2019s Security Service Counterintelligence Chief presents photo evidence of Russia\u2019s direct involvement in the downing of Malaysian Flight MH17 that resulted in the deaths of 298 passengers]</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PWtH8AA42Fc&t=257 (English) Vitaly Nayda. UCMC, 19th of July 2014 ]</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20140721205539/http://www.sbu.gov.ua/sbu/control/uk/publish/article?art_id=129099&cat_id=39574 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0456\u044f \u0440\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0441\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0431\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0445\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0442\u0438 \u0434\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0438 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0454\u0457 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0456 \u0434\u043e \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0443 \u0432 \u043d\u0435\u0431\u0456 \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u043e\u044e]</ref>\n\nSeveral aircraft from [[List of Ukrainian aircraft losses during the Ukrainian crisis|the Ukrainian airforce were shot down in the months and days preceding the MH17 incident]]. On 14 June 2014, a [[Ukrainian Air Force]] [[Ilyushin Il-76]] military airlifter [[Ukrainian Air Force Ilyushin Il-76 shoot-down|was shot down]] on approach to [[Luhansk International Airport]], with loss of nine crew members and forty troops.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|183}} On 14 July 2014, a Ukrainian Air Force [[Antonov-26|An-26]] transport airplane flying at {{convert|6500|m|ft|abbr=on}} was shot down.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|183}} The militia reportedly claimed via social media that a Buk missile launcher, which they had previously seized and made operational, had been used to bring down the aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.vz.ru/news/2014/7/14/695525.html |title=\u041e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043b\u0438, \u0438\u0437 \u0447\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0441\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0410\u043d-26 |publisher=Vzglyad |quote=Today the self-defence destroyed An-26 airplane using SAM \"9\u041a37\u041c1\" (better known as 'Buk') ... said the militia, distributed in social networks [translation after ellipsis from Google translate] |date=14 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> American officials later said evidence suggested the aircraft had been shot down from [[Russia|Russian territory]].<ref name=\"BakerNYT\">[[Peter Baker (author)|Peter Baker]] (18 July 2014), [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/19/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-plane-ukraine.html U.S. Sees Evidence of Russian Links to Jet's Downing] ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref> \n\nOn 16 July, two Ukrainian [[Sukhoi Su-25]] [[close air support]] aircraft were shot at. The Ministry of Defense of Ukraine reported that at about 13:00 local time the militia used [[MANPAD]]s against Sukhoi Su-25 and damaged the aircraft which was performing a flight mission in the [[Anti-Terrorist Operation Zone (Ukraine)|ATO zone]]. According to the report, the plane received minor damage but was forced to make an emergency landing.<ref>[http://www.mil.gov.ua/news/2014/07/16/bojovi-litaki-povitryanih-sil-zs-ukraini-v-ramkah-vidnovlennya-bojovih-zavdan-nanesli-dekilka-tochkovih-aviaudariv-po-viznachenih-obektah-protivnika/ \u0411\u043e\u0439\u043e\u0432\u0456 \u043b\u0456\u0442\u0430\u043a\u0438 \u041f\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0442\u0440\u044f\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u0421\u0438\u043b \u0417\u0421 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0438 \u0432 \u0440\u0430\u043c\u043a\u0430\u0445 \u0432\u0456\u0434\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044f \u0431\u043e\u0439\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0445 \u0437\u0430\u0432\u0434\u0430\u043d\u044c \u043d\u0430\u043d\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u0434\u0435\u043a\u0456\u043b\u044c\u043a\u0430 \u0442\u043e\u0447\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0445 \u0430\u0432\u0456\u0430\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0456\u0432 \u043f\u043e \u0432\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0445 \u043e\u0431\u2019\u0454\u043a\u0442\u0430\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430]</ref> Later, the Ministry of Defense of Ukraine reported on the second Su-25 that was attacked on the same day at about 19:00 local time near the Ukrainian-Russian border in the area of the city of [[Amvrosiivka]].<ref>[http://www.mil.gov.ua/news/2014/07/17/rosijskij-vijskovij-litak-zbiv-ukrainskij-su-25-v-nebi-donbasu/ \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0439 \u043b\u0456\u0442\u0430\u043a \u0437\u0431\u0438\u0432 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0421\u0443-25 \u0432 \u043d\u0435\u0431\u0456 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0443]</ref> According to the details reported by Ukraine's [[RNBO]] spokesperson Andriy Lysenko, the Ukrainian Su-25 was shot down by [[R-27 (air-to-air missile)|an R-27T]] medium range air-to-air missile fired by a [[Mikoyan MiG-29|MiG-29]] jet from Russian territory while the Su-25 was at an altitude of 8,250 m.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7ifB7TgAZYU \u041b\u0438\u0441\u0435\u043d\u043a\u043e \u0440\u043e\u0437\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0432, \u044f\u043a \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0432\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0449\u0443\u0432\u0430\u0447 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u044e\u0432\u0430\u0432 \u0437\u0430 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0457\u043d\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u043c \u0421\u0443 25]</ref><ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\" />{{rp|185}} The [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Russian Defence Ministry]] said that the accusations were false.<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28345039 |title=Ukraine conflict: Russia accused of shooting down jet |date=17 July 2014 |work=BBC News |location=London |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"rfe/rl on rejection of accusation\">{{cite news |url=http://www.rferl.org/content/ukraine-russia-jet-shot-down-blame/25460575.html |title=Russia Rejects 'Absurd' Accusation Over Downed Ukrainian Jet |date=17 July 2014 |work=[[RFE/RL]] |publisher=RFE/RL |location=Prague |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Subsequently, in response to additional questions by the Dutch Safety Board, the Ukrainian authorities reported that a \"provisional investigation\" had revealed that the plane had been shot down while flying at an altitude of 6,250 m. It was not stated when this provisional investigation had been completed. Ukrainian authorities also thought that the Su-25 could have been shot down with a [[Pantsir missile system]] from Russian territory, though they thought this less likely.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\" />{{rp|185}}\n\nOn 17 July, an [[Associated Press]] journalist saw a Buk launcher in [[Snizhne]], a town in [[Donetsk Oblast]], {{convert|16|km|mi|0}} southeast of the crash site. The reporter also saw seven separatist [[tank]]s near the town.<ref name=\"leonard\">{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/ukraine-air-force-jet-downed-russian-missile-102817809.html |author=Peter Leonard |title=Ukraine: Air Force jet downed by Russian missile |publisher=ABC News |agency=Associated Press |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113123101/http://news.yahoo.com/ukraine-air-force-jet-downed-russian-missile-102817809.html |archivedate=13 January 2016}}</ref> [[Associated Press]] journalists reported that the Buk M-1 was operated by a man \"with unfamiliar fatigues and a distinctive Russian accent\" escorted by two civilian vehicles.<ref name=Karmanau>{{cite news |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/what-happened-day-flight-17-was-downed |title=What happened? The day Flight 17 was downed |author1=Yuras Karmanau  |author2=Peter Leonard  |lastauthoramp=yes |work=Associated Press |date=25 July 2014 |accessdate=13 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141009123439/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/what-happened-day-flight-17-was-downed |archivedate=9 October 2014}}</ref> The battle around [[Savur-Mohyla]] has been suggested as the possible context within which the missile that brought down MH17 was fired, as separatists deployed increasingly sophisticated [[anti-aircraft warfare|anti-aircraft weaponry]] in this battle, and had brought down several Ukrainian [[jet aircraft|jets]] in July.<ref>Daily Telegraph, 14 November 2014,[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/11231333/The-unlikely-pilgrimage-site-of-Saur-Mogila.html the unlikely pilgrimage site of saur mogila]</ref>\n\nBack in April, the [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] warned governments that there was a risk to commercial passenger flights over south-eastern Ukraine.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|217}} The American [[Federal Aviation Administration]] issued restrictions on flights over [[Crimea]], to the south of MH17's route, and advised airlines flying over some other parts of Ukraine to \"exercise extreme caution\". This warning did not include the MH17 crash region.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/17/us-ukraine-crisis-airplane-warnings-idUSKBN0FM2BV20140717 |title=U.S. air carriers to avoid Russia-Ukraine border airspace |agency=Reuters |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-20140717>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/law-and-order/10974823/Air-operators-belatedly-avoid-Ukraine-war-zone.html |title=Air operators belatedly avoid Ukraine war zone |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |first=Tom |last=Whitehead}}</ref> 37 airlines continued overflying eastern Ukraine and about 900 flights crossed the [[Donetsk Oblast|Donetsk region]] in the seven days before the Boeing 777 was shot down.<ref name=spiegel-981813>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/panorama/malaysia-airlines-mh17-lufthansa-ueberflog-ost-ukraine-56-mal-a-981813.html |title=Absturz von Flug MH17: Lufthansa flog zuletzt 56-mal \u00fcber Kriegsgebiet |trans-title=Crash of Flight MH17: Lufthansa lately flew 56 times over crisis region |work=Der Spiegel |language=German |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref> On 17 July at 00:00 Russian [[Air traffic control|air traffic controllers]] closed the [[airspace]] in the adjacent area over Russia below {{convert|53000|feet}}. Long-distance flights typically travel at altitudes of 33,000 to 44,000 feet,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://traveltips.usatoday.com/altitude-plane-flight-100359.html|title=What Is the Altitude of a Plane in Flight?|website=traveltips.usatoday.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-24}}</ref> so this restriction effectively closed their airspace to civilian overflights. The reason given was \"armed conflict in Ukraine\". The Dutch Safety Board asked for, but did not receive, a more detailed explanation for this restriction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/media/attachment/2018/7/10/debcd724fe7breport_mh17_crash.pdf |title=MH17 Crash|website=Dutch Safety Board|pages=180|access-date=16 July 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT Maps\">{{cite news |title=Maps of the Crash of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/07/17/world/europe/maps-of-the-crash-of-malaysian-airlines-flight-mh17.html |date=21 July 2014 |work=The New York Times |accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref> \n\nThe airspace above Donetsk was managed by Ukraine. The Ukrainian authorities imposed restrictions for flights under 32,000 feet (9,800 m), but did not consider closing the airspace to civil aviation completely.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\" />{{rp|10}}<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.novayagazeta.ru/inquests/68762.html|title=17 \u0438\u044e\u043b\u044f \u0432 \u0437\u043e\u043d\u0443 \u0410\u0422\u041e \u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0435\u043d \u0431\u044b\u043b \u0432\u044b\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0442\u044c \u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0410\u043d-26 \u0441 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u043c\u0438 \u0434\u0435\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0438|date=10 June 2015|language=Russian|trans-title=On 17 July an An-26 transport was to fly with Ukrainian paratroopers|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref> <ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/20/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-plane-ukraine.html Ukraine Says It Can Prove Russia Supplied Arms System That Felled Jet]</ref> As with other countries, Ukraine receives [[Freedoms of the air|overflight fees]] for commercial aircraft that fly through their borders and this may have contributed to the continued availability of civilian flight paths through the conflict zone.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/aviation/ukraine-responsible-for-airspace-safety-iata-20140720-zuzmp.html |title=Ukraine responsible for airspace safety: IATA |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |first=Jamie |last=Freed |date=20 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"smh-20140718\">{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/aviation/mh17-disaster-flights-over-war-zones-because-its-cheaper-20140718-zua0y.html |title=MH17 disaster: Flights over war zones 'because it's cheaper |author1=Tom Whitehead |author2=Nick Collins |author3=Martin Evans |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nAccording to Vadim Lukashevich in an interview to ''[[Novaya Gazeta]]'', on the day of MH17 incident, a Ukrainian [[Antonov-26|An-26]] was scheduled to deliver [[paratrooper]]s to the battle arena.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.novayagazeta.ru/inquests/68762.html|title=17 \u0438\u044e\u043b\u044f \u0432 \u0437\u043e\u043d\u0443 \u0410\u0422\u041e \u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0435\u043d \u0431\u044b\u043b \u0432\u044b\u043b\u0435\u0442\u0435\u0442\u044c \u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0410\u043d-26 \u0441 \u0443\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u043c\u0438 \u0434\u0435\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043c\u0438|date=10 June 2015|language=Russian|trans-title=On 17 July an An-26 transport was to fly with Ukrainian paratroopers|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref>{{Importance inline|reason=unnamed source of the statement of some private person}}\n\n==Crash==\n[[File:MH17 map-en.svg|thumb|upright=1.364|Route of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17]]\n[[File:MH17 Flight Route (en).svg|thumb|upright=1.364|Routes of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 (MH17) and Singapore Airlines Flight 351 (SQ351), including airspace restrictions]]\n\nOn Thursday, 17 July 2014, Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 departed from [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol]] Gate G3 at 12:13&nbsp;[[Central European Summer Time|CEST]] (10:13&nbsp;[[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]])<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|23}} and took off at 12:31 local time (10:31 UTC). It was due to arrive at [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport]] at 06:10 [[Time in Malaysia|MYT]], Friday, 18 July (22:10 UTC, 17 July).<ref name=BBCbothsides/>\n\nAccording to the original flight plan, MH17 was to fly over Ukraine at [[flight level]] 330 (33,000&nbsp;feet or 10,060&nbsp;metres) and then change to FL 350 around the Ukrainian city of [[Dnipropetrovsk]]. When it reached the area as planned, at 15:53 [[Eastern European Summer Time|local time]] (12:53&nbsp;UTC), [[Dnipropetrovsk]] Air Control (''Dnipro Control'') asked MH17 if they could climb to FL 350 as planned, and also to avoid a potential [[Conflict (air traffic control)|separation conflict]] with another flight, [[Singapore Airlines]] Flight 351 (SQ351), also at FL 330. The crew asked to remain at FL 330 and the air traffic controller approved this request, moving the other flight to FL 350. At 16:00 local time (13:00&nbsp;UTC), the crew asked for a deviation of {{convert|20|nmi|km}} to the left (north) off course, on [[Airway (aviation)|airway]] L980, due to weather conditions. This request was also approved by ''Dnipro Control'' [[Air traffic control|ATC]]. The crew then asked if they could climb to FL 340, which was rejected as this flight level was not available, so MH17 remained at FL 330. At 16:19 local time (13:19 UTC), ''Dnipro Control'' noticed that the flight was {{convert|3.6|nmi|km}} north of the centreline of approved airway and instructed MH17 to return to the track. At 16:19 local time (13:19&nbsp;UTC), ''Dnipro Control'' contacted Russian ATC in [[Rostov-on-Don]] (''RND Control'') by telephone and requested clearance to transfer the flight to Russian [[airspace]]. After obtaining the permission, ''Dnipro Control'' attempted to contact MH17 for handing them off to ''RND Control'' at 16:20 local time (13:20&nbsp;UTC), but the aircraft did not respond. When MH17 did not respond to several calls, ''Dnipro Control'' contacted ''RND Control'' again to check if they could see the aircraft on their radar. ''RND Control'' confirmed that the airplane had disappeared.<ref name=\"dsb1\"/>\n\nThe Dutch Safety Board reported a last flight data recording at 16:20 local time (13:20&nbsp;UTC), located west of the [[urban-type settlement]] Rozsypne (\u0420\u043e\u0437\u0441\u0438\u043f\u043d\u0435), near [[Hrabove, Donetsk Oblast|Hrabove]] heading [[Points of the compass|east-southeast]] (ESE, 115\u00b0) at {{convert|494|kn|km/h mph}}.<ref name=\"dsb1\"/>\n\nAt exactly 16:20:03 local time (13:20:03 UTC) a [[Buk missile system|Buk]] [[surface-to-air|ground-to-air missile]], which had been launched from an area east from the aircraft, detonated outside the aircraft just above the cockpit to the left. An [[Uncontrolled decompression|explosive decompression]] occurred, resulting in both the cockpit and tail sections tearing away from the middle portion of the fuselage. All three sections disintegrated as they fell rapidly towards the ground.\n\nThe majority of debris landed near [[Hrabove, Donetsk Oblast|Hrabove]], a village located north of [[Torez]] in eastern Ukraine's [[Donetsk Oblast]]. The debris spread over a {{convert|50|km2|mi2}} area to the southwest of Hrabove.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\" />{{rp|53}} The fireball on impact is believed to have been captured on video.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10975094/Malaysia-Airlines-crash-video-believed-to-show-moment-of-planes-impact.html |title=Malaysia Airlines crash: video believed to show moment of plane's impact |work=The Telegraph |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Photographs from the site of the crash show scattered pieces of broken [[fuselage]] and [[Aircraft engine|engine]] parts, bodies, and passports.<ref name=\"huffington\">{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/07/17/malaysia-airlines-mh17-passenger-jet-crashes-ukraine-near-russian-border_n_5595450.html |title=Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 'Shot Down in Ukraine Near Russian Border' |first=Sara C |last=Nelson |date=17 July 2014 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |location=United Kingdom |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Some of the wreckage fell close to houses.<ref name=\"Telegraaf22866550\">{{cite web |url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/buitenland/22866550/__Vliegtuig_crasht_in_Oekraine__.html |title=Maleisisch passagiersvliegtuig in Oekra\u00efne neergestort |trans-title=Malaysian passenger aircraft shot down in Ukraine |work=[[De Telegraaf]] |language=Dutch |accessdate=17 July 2014 |date=17 July 2014}}</ref> Dozens of bodies fell into crop fields, and some fell into houses.<ref>{{cite news |author=Cahal Milmo |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-no-forensic-investigators-coordination-or-body-bags-as-locals-are-left-to-scour-the-gruesome-scene-9615895.html |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 crash: No forensic investigators, co-ordination or body bags as Ukraine locals are left to scour gruesome scene |work=The Independent |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThree other commercial aircraft were in the same area when the Malaysian airplane crashed: [[Air India]] Flight 113 (AI113), a [[Boeing 787]] en route from [[Delhi]] to [[Birmingham]], [[EVA Air]] Flight 88 (BR88), a [[Boeing 777]] en route from [[Paris]] to [[Taipei]], and the closest aircraft [[Singapore Airlines]] Flight 351 (SQ351) was {{convert|33|km|mi}} away, a Boeing 777 en route from [[Copenhagen]] to [[Singapore]].<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|41}}\n\n==Recovery of bodies==\n[[File:Arrival of corpses from MH17 at Eindhoven Airport.jpg|thumb|First arrival of bodies at [[Eindhoven Airport]]]]\nA Ukraine Foreign Ministry representative said that the bodies found at the crash site would be taken to [[Kharkiv]] for identification, {{convert|270|km|mi}} to the north. By the day after the crash, 181 of the 298 bodies had been found.<ref name=ap-20140718>{{cite news |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/world/official-181-bodies-found-at-mh17-crash-site/article6225245.ece |title=Official: 181 bodies found at MH17 crash site |agency=Associated Press |work=The Hindu |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> Some were observed being placed in [[body bag]]s and loaded onto trucks.<ref name=APBodies>{{cite news |title=Raw: Crews begin moving bodies at jet crash site |url=https://www.usatoday.com/videos/news/nation/2014/07/19/12883715/ |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=Associated Press |date=19 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=SMHBodies>{{cite news |last1=Miller |first1=Nick |title=MH17: 'Unknown groups' use body bags |url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/mh17-unknown-groups-use-body-bags-20140719-3c8dl.html |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=19 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=GuardianBodies>{{cite news |last1=Grytsenko |first1=Oksana |title=MH17: armed rebels fuel chaos as rotting corpses pile up on the roadside |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/19/mh17-armed-rebels-chaos-corpses-ukraine |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\nDutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte complained about the lack of respect shown to the personal belongings of the dead which were reportedly being looted. He initially announced his disgust about the handling of the bodies that were reportedly being \"dragged around\" and \"thrown\", but later stated they had been handled with more care than originally thought.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nu.nl/vliegramp-oekraine/3832485/rutte-geschokt-respectloos-gedrag-rampplek.html |title=Rutte geschokt over 'respectloos gedrag' op rampplek |publisher=[[Nu.nl]] |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |language=Dutch}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/31522/Vliegtuigcrash-in-Oekraine/article/detail/3693688/2014/07/21/Rutte-Zorgvuldiger-met-lichamen-omgegaan-dan-werd-gevreesd.dhtml |title=Rutte: 'Zorgvuldiger met lichamen omgegaan dan werd gevreesd' |author=Laura de Jong |date=21 July 2014 |website=[[de Volkskrant]] |language=Dutch}}</ref> On 20 July, Ukrainian emergency workers, observed by armed separatists, began loading the remains of the passengers of MH17 into [[Refrigerated van|refrigerated railway wagons]] for transport and identification.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/some-bodies-removed-from-mh17-crash-site-1405849163 |title=Bodies Removed From MH17 Crash Site Human Remains Moved to Railcars at Torez Station |last=Sonne |first=Paul |author2=Alexander Kolyandr, Margaret Coker |date=20 July 2014 |work=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 July, pro-Russian rebels allowed Dutch investigators to examine the bodies. By this time, 272 bodies had been recovered, according to Ukrainian officials.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28399406 |title=MH17 plane crash: Dutch experts examine bodies |publisher=BBC |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> Remains left Torez on a train on the evening of 21 July, en route to Kharkiv to be flown to the Netherlands for identification.<ref name=bbc-train>{{cite news |title=MH17 plane crash: Train with bodies leaves Ukraine station |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28411225 |work=BBC News |accessdate=21 July 2014 |date=21 July 2014}}</ref> On the same day, Malaysian Prime Minister [[Najib Razak]] announced that the Malaysian government had reached a tentative agreement to retrieve the remains of the Malaysians who died in the crash, following any necessary forensic work.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marlow |first1=Iain |title=MH17: Malaysia reaches 'behind the scenes' deal to recover bodies |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/world/mh17-malaysia-reaches-deal-to-recover-bodies-in-race-for-muslim-burials/article19692413/ |accessdate=21 July 2014 |work=The Globe and Mail |date=21 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Convoy of MH-17 victims on the highway.jpg|thumb|Convoy of 40 hearses heading to [[Hilversum]], while other traffic stopped]]\nIt was reported on 21 July that with 282 bodies and 87 body fragments found, there were still 16 bodies missing.<ref name=\"AljazeeraObama7-21\">{{cite news |title=Obama calls for Russia 'pivot' on Ukraine as MH17 investigation begins |url=http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2014/7/21/obama-ukraine-russia.html |accessdate=21 July 2014 |publisher=Al Jazeera |date=21 July 2014}}</ref> An agreement had been reached that the Netherlands would co-ordinate the identification effort. A train carrying the bodies arrived at the [[Malyshev Factory]], Kharkiv on 22 July.<ref name=nyt-20140722>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/23/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-jet-ukraine.html |title=Bodies of Crash Victims Safely Moved Out of Combat Area |first=Andrew |last=Higgins |newspaper=The New York Times |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> Dutch authorities stated that they found 200 bodies on the train when it arrived at Kharkhiv, leaving almost 100 unaccounted for.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/world/mh17-crash-families-worst-fears-realised-as-bodies-go-missing-20140723-zvv9x.html |title=MH17 crash: families' worst fears realised as bodies go missing |work=The Age |first=Paul |last=McGeough |date=23 July 2014 |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> In late July, the UK [[Metropolitan Police]] sent specialist officers to Ukraine to assist with the recovery, identification and repatriation of bodies.<ref name=hp-20140719 />\n\nThe first remains were flown to [[Eindhoven]] in the Netherlands on 23 July,<ref name=\"bbc-bodies-kharkiv\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28416973 |title=MH17 bodies leave Ukraine rebel area and reach Kharkiv |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |work=BBC News}}</ref> moved there with Dutch air force [[Lockheed C-130 Hercules|C-130]] and Australian [[Boeing C-17 Globemaster III|C-17]] transport aircraft,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/netherlands-to-coordinate-mh17-victim-identification-efforts-114072100077_1.html |title=Netherlands to coordinate MH17 victim identification efforts &#124; Business Standard News |work=Business Standard |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-22/operation-launched-to-recover-and-identify-mh17-victims/5615332 |title=MH17: Tony Abbott announces Operation Bring Them Home to secure and identify victims of Malaysia Airlines disaster \u2013 ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> which landed at [[Eindhoven Airport]] just before 16:00 local time.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/mh17-crash-social-media--blackout-tribute-continues-as-first-bodies-are-to-be-flown-to-netherlands-from-ukraine-9622288.html |title=MH17 crash victims: First bodies arrive in Netherlands from Ukraine |author=Heather Saul |date=23 July 2014 |website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> The day after, another 74 bodies arrived.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nos.nl/artikel/679047-weer-74-kisten-naar-hilversum.html |title=Weer 74 kisten naar Hilversum |date=24 July 2014 |work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]] |language=Dutch}}</ref> The examination and identification of the bodies was conducted at the [[Royal Netherlands Army#Services|Netherlands Army]] medical regiment training facility in [[Hilversum]] and was coordinated by a Dutch forensic team.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140722/hilversum-treft-voorbereidingen-voor-lichamen-mh17/ |title=Hilversum treft voorbereidingen voor lichamen MH17 |work=Nieuws.nl |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140723204451/http://www.nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140722/Hilversum-treft-voorbereidingen-voor-lichamen-MH17 |archive-date=23 July 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nOn 1 August it was announced that a search and recovery mission, including about 80 forensic police specialists from the Netherlands, Malaysia and Australia, and led by Colonel Cornelis Kuijs of the [[Royal Marechaussee]], would use [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drones]], [[Detection dog|sniffer dogs]], [[Underwater search and recovery|divers]] and [[Satellite imagery|satellite mapping]] to search for missing body parts at the crash site.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/11005039/Dutch-and-Australian-police-to-use-drones-divers-and-sniffer-dogs-in-perilous-search-for-victims.html |title=Dutch and Australian police to use drones, divers and sniffer dogs in perilous search for victims |publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph]] (London) |date=1 August 2014 |accessdate=3 August 2014 |first=Tom |last=Parfitt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/05/mh17-investigators-frustrated-at-limited-access-due-to-fighting |title=MH17 investigators frustrated at limited access due to fighting |work=The Guardian |accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> Australian officials had believed that as many as 80 bodies were still at the site,<ref name=\"Guardian AP\" /> but after some days of searching the international team had \"found remains of only a few victims\" and concluded that \"the recovery effort undertaken by local authorities immediately after the crash was more thorough than initially thought.\"<ref name=\"FortunatelyMoreWasDone\">Toby Sterling, [http://bigstory.ap.org/article/dutch-premier-halts-search-ukraine-victims \"Dutch premier halts search for Ukraine victims,\"] Associated Press, 6 August 2014. Retrieved 6 August 2014. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141118080619/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/dutch-premier-halts-search-ukraine-victims|date=18 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August the Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte announced that the recovery operation would be temporarily halted due to an upsurge in fighting around the crash site threatening the safety of crash investigators and recovery specialists, and that all international investigators and humanitarian forces conducting searches would leave the country leaving behind a small communications and liaison team.<ref>{{cite web |author=Helen Davidson and agencies |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/07/mh17-crash-search-for-remains-halted |title=MH17 crash: search for remains halted as Australia begins day of mourning |work=The Guardian |date=6 August 2014 |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 August the bodies of 20 Malaysians (of 43 killed in the incident) arrived in Malaysia.<ref name=MH17Guardian>{{cite news |title=MH17 bodies arrive in Malaysia |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/22/mh17-bodies-arrive-in-malaysia |accessdate=22 August 2014 |agency=Agence France-Presse in Kuala Lumpur |date=21 August 2014}}</ref> The government announced a National Mourning Day, with a ceremony broadcast live on radio and television.<ref>{{cite news |author=TheStar |title=MH17 day of mourning: White hearses arrive at KLIA |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/08/22/MH17-Day-of-mourning-white-hearses-at-KLIA/ |date=22 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 October a spokesman for the Dutch national prosecutor's office stated that one victim had been found with an oxygen mask around his neck; a forensic investigation of the mask for fingerprints, saliva and DNA did not produce any results and it is therefore not known how or when that mask got around the neck of the victim.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|99}}\n\nBy 5 December 2014, the Dutch-led forensic team had identified the bodies of 292 out of 298 victims of the crash.<ref>{{cite news |last=Grindstad |first=Ingrid |title=Six MH17 victims remain unidentified |url=http://www.nltimes.nl/2014/12/05/six-mh17-victims-remain-unidentified/ |date=5 December 2014 |accessdate=6 December 2014 |newspaper=NL Times}}</ref> In February and April 2015 new remains were found on the site,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/02/02/ukraine-crisis-mh-idUSL6N0VC3GC20150202 |title=Dutch search team recovers remains, MH17 wreckage in Ukraine |author=Anthony Deutsch |agency=Reuters |date=2 February 2015 |accessdate=16 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=Remains2015>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/dutch-investigators-recover-human-remains-mh17-crash-110138676.html |title=Dutch investigators recover human remains from MH17 crash site |date=21 April 2015 |accessdate=23 April 2015 |agency=Agence France-Presse}}</ref> after which only 2 victims, both Dutch citizens, had not been identified.<ref name=Remains2015 />\n\n== Reporting in the mass media ==\n''[[De Telegraaf]]'', a large-circulation Dutch tabloid, published on 19 July a front-page photo-collage of pro-Russian rebel leaders, including Igor Girkin, under the one-word headline \"Murderers\" (\"Moordenaars\").<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-dutch-newspapers-respond-with-anger-and-despair-as-wait-for-return-of-bodies-continues-9618753.html|title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 crash: Dutch newspapers respond with anger and despair as wait for return of bodies continues \u2013 Europe \u2013 World|author=Adam Withnall|date=21 July 2014|accessdate=22 July 2014|newspaper=The Independent}}</ref>\n\nIt was suggested on other media that credit and debit cards may have been looted from the bodies of the victims, and the Dutch Banking Association said it would take \"preventative measures\" against any possible fraud.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/ukraine-plane-crash/dutch-banks-respond-reports-mh17-victims-looted-credit-cards-n160246|title=Dutch Banks Respond to Reports of MH17 Victims' Looted Credit Cards|date=19 July 2014|accessdate=20 July 2014|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> There were also accusations that other possessions had been removed and that evidence at the crash site had been destroyed.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10978577/MH17-Malaysia-Airlines-crash-victims-robbed-of-their-dignity-by-rebels.html|title=MH17: Malaysia Airlines crash victims robbed of their dignity by rebels|last1=Mendick|first1=Robert|date=19 July 2014|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=20 July 2014|last2=Sawer|first2=Patrick|last3=Ross|first3=Time}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/world/heartless-looters-raid-malaysian-airlines-flight-mh17-crash-site-article-1.1872047|title=Heartless looters raid Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 crash site, swipe victims' luggage, personal items|last1=Wagner|first1=Meg|date=18 July 2014|work=Daily News|accessdate=20 July 2014|location=New York}}</ref> Dutch prime minister [[Mark Rutte]] acknowledged on 6 August that early reports of chaos and criminality around the site may have been exaggerated.<ref name=\"FortunatelyMoreWasDone\" /> One eyewitness observed that valuable items like shoes and bottles of alcohol were untouched in the wreckage.<ref>Shaun Walker with Harriet Salem and Josh Halliday, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/20/mh17-victims-crash-site-anger-russia-grows \"MH17: world's anger at Russia grows as bodies pile on to train at crash site,\"] ''The Guardian'', 21 July 2014. Retrieved 6 August 2014.</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nAbout 90 minutes after the incident, Ukraine closed all routes in Eastern Ukrainian airspace, at all altitudes.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|101}} The incident dramatically heightened fears about airliner shootdowns,<ref>{{cite news |title=Air India flight with 126 on board was right behind MH 17 |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Air-India-flight-with-126-on-board-was-right-behind-MH-17/articleshow/38601142.cms |date=18 July 2014 |work=The Times of India |accessdate=12 November 2014 |quote=<!--\"But such fears did not exist over Europe, at least till Terrible Thursday.\"-->}}</ref> leading to some airlines announcing they would avoid overflying conflict zones.\n\nShortly after the crash, it was announced that Malaysia Airlines would retire [[flight number]] MH17 and change the Amsterdam\u2013Kuala Lumpur route to flight number MH19 beginning on 25 July 2014, with the outbound flight unchanged.<ref name=\"usatoday\">{{cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/business/2014/07/18/malaysia-flight-17-retired-numbers/12827633/ |title=Malaysia will stop using No. 17 next week |first=Bart |last=Jansen |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |work=[[USA Today]]}}</ref><ref name=\"ABCAust001\">{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-21/mh17-malaysia-airlines-retires-flight-number-out-of-respect-/5610864 |title=MH17: Malaysia Airlines retires flight number after Ukraine crash |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> In association with the retirement of the Boeing 777 aircraft type from Malaysia Airlines' fleet, Malaysia Airlines terminated service to Amsterdam, opting to codeshare with [[KLM Royal Dutch Airlines|KLM]] on the KUL-AMS route for service beyond 25 January 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://airlineroute.net/2015/12/03/mh-amscdg-jan16cxld/ |title=Malaysia Airlines Cancels Amsterdam / Paris Routes from late-Jan 2016 |work=Airlineroute.net |date=3 December 2015 |accessdate=26 December 2015}}</ref> On 18 July 2014, shares in Malaysia Airlines dropped by nearly 16%.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/malaysia-airlines-shares-tank-2014-7 |title=Malaysia Airlines Shares Tank |website=Business Insider |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 July 2014, two Ukrainian military jets were hit by missiles at the altitude of {{convert|17000|ft}} close to the area of the MH17 crash. According to the [[National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine|Ukrainian Security Council]], preliminary information indicated that the missiles came from Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.trust.org/item/20140723154118-im9dy |title=Ukraine: missiles that brought down jets may have been fired from Russia |accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, Malaysia proposed that the [[United Nations Security Council]] set up an international tribunal to prosecute those deemed responsible for the downing of the airplane. The Malaysian resolution received the support of 11 of the 15 nation security council, with three abstentions, but the resolution was vetoed by Russia.<ref name=\"churkin\" /> Russia proposed an alternative draft resolution, which would not have set up a tribunal.<ref>{{cite news|url=Russia submits rival MH17 resolution draft|title=https://www.dw.com/en/russia-submits-rival-mh17-resolution-draft/a-18596856}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/news/russia-makes-rival-un-move-on-mh17-probe|title=Russia makes rival UN move on MH17 probe}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-33710088|title=Russia vetoes MH17 tribunal at UN|date=2015-07-29|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-04-23|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\"veto\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/russia-opposes-un-mh17-tribunal/27139710.html|title=Russia Opposes UN MH17 Tribunal|website=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|language=en|access-date=2020-04-25}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 June 2016, a Russian businessman claimed that the shooting down of the airplane put an end to [[Novorossiya (confederation)|hopes of a Russian nation in Ukraine]] and prolonged the War in Donbass.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Loiko|first1=Sergei|title=The Unraveling of Moscow's 'Novorossia' Dream|url=http://www.rferl.mobi/a/unraveling-moscow-novorossia-dream/27772641.html|website=Radio Free Liberty}}</ref>\n\n==Investigation==\nTwo parallel investigations were led by the Dutch, one into the technical cause of the crash, and a separate criminal inquiry.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/11/us-ukraine-mh17-bodies-idUSKCN0IV1NJ20141111?feedType=RSS&virtualBrandChannel=11563 |title=Where are the bodies, MH17 families ask |author=Anthony Deutsch |agency=Reuters |accessdate=11 November 2014 |date=11 November 2014}}</ref> The technical report was released on 13 October 2015,<ref name=\"FinalReportDate\">{{cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/final-report-on-downing-of-malaysia-airlines-flight-mh17-due-october-1440675525 |title=Final Report on Downing of Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 Due October |last=Wall |first=Robert |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=27 August 2015}}</ref> while the criminal investigation reported some of their findings in September 2016.<ref name=\"BBC News 28 September 2016\"/><ref name=\"NLTimesJIT\"/> According to the [[Convention on International Civil Aviation]], the country in which an aviation incident occurs is responsible for the investigation, but that country may delegate the investigation to another state; Ukraine has delegated the leadership of both investigations to the Netherlands.<ref>{{cite news |title=MH17 investigation \u2013 why is Malaysia excluded? |first=Julie |last=L\u00e9vesque |newspaper=eTN Global Travel Industry News |date=3 December 2014 |accessdate=21 December 2014 |url=http://www.eturbonews.com/53217/mh17-investigation-why-malaysia-excluded}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Parker |first1=Andrew |last2=Olearchyk |first2=Roman |title=Netherlands to lead MH17 investigation |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/19c29f34-10e1-11e4-b116-00144feabdc0,Authorised=false.html?_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2F19c29f34-10e1-11e4-b116-00144feabdc0.html%3Fsiteedition%3Duk&siteedition=uk&_i_referer= |accessdate=22 July 2014 |work=Financial Times |agency=Financial Times Ltd |date=21 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Bewerkt door: redactie |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/31522/Vliegtuigcrash-in-Oekraine/article/detail/3698000/2014/07/24/Nederlandse-leidersrol-krijgt-juridische-basis.dhtml |title=Nederlandse leidersrol krijgt juridische basis \u22120 Vliegtuigcrash in Oekra\u00efne \u2013 VK |work=De Volkskrant |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dutch Safety Board heads investigation: investigation effort in full swing, black boxes currently being read out |url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/uploads/fm/2014_07_23_PB_OVV_neemt_leiding_over_ENG_DEF.pdf |website=onderzoeksraad.nl |publisher=[[Dutch Safety Board]], The Hague |accessdate=24 July 2014 |date=23 July 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ShCuUTie?url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/uploads/fm/2014_07_23_PB_OVV_neemt_leiding_over_ENG_DEF.pdf |archivedate=19 September 2014 }} ()</ref>\n\n===On-site investigation===\n<!--{{2013\u20132014 unrest in Ukraine}} Already covered and more appropriate at bottom of article in a collapsible bar anyway -->\nIn the hours following the crash, a meeting was convened of the [[Trilateral Contact Group on Ukraine|Trilateral Contact Group]]. After they had held a video conference with representatives of insurgents affiliated with the Donetsk People's Republic (who controlled the area where the aircraft crashed), the rebels promised to \"provide safe access and security guarantees\" to \"the national investigation commission\" by co-operating with Ukrainian authorities and OSCE ([[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]]) monitors.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.osce.org/home/121390 |title=Press statement by the Trilateral Contact Group |publisher=Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140908053442/http://www.osce.org/home/121390 |archivedate=8 September 2014 }}</ref> During the first two days of investigation, the militants prevented the OSCE and the workers of [[State Emergency Service of Ukraine|Ukrainian Emergencies Ministry]] from freely working at the crash site. [[Andrei Purgin]], a leader of the Donetsk People's Republic, declared later that \"we will guarantee the safety of international experts on the scene as soon as Kiev concludes a ceasefire agreement\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Shaun |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/20/mh17-pro-russia-rebels-crash-site-kiev-ceasefire |title=MH17: pro-Russia rebels will allow access to crash site if ceasefire agreed |work=The Guardian |accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Investigation of the crash site of MH-17.jpg|thumb|Dutch and Australian police at the crash site on 3 August 2014]]\nBy 18 July 2014, the [[flight data recorder]] and the [[cockpit voice recorder]] had been recovered by separatists,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/07/18/malaysia-airlines-mh17-black-boxes-reportedly-recovered-russia-denies-it-will-take-them-from-rebels/ |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 black boxes reportedly recovered, Russia denies it will take them from rebels |work=National Post |date=22 May 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> and three days later were handed over to Malaysian officials in [[Donetsk]].<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|44}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Shaun |last2=Salem |first2=Harriet |title=Ukraine rebels hand over MH17 black boxes and let train carrying bodies leave |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/22/mh17-black-boxes-handed-over-pro-russia-rebels |accessdate=21 February 2019 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> The voice recorder was damaged but there was no evidence that data had been tampered with.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|45}}\n\nThe [[National Bureau of Air Accidents Investigation of Ukraine]], which led investigations, both off-site and on-site, during the first days after the crash,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nbaai.gov.ua/news.html?id=6&lang=ua |title=\u0420\u043e\u0437\u0441\u043b\u0456\u0434\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044f \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0438 \u043b\u0456\u0442\u0430\u043a\u0430 Boeing 777 |publisher=NBAAI |date=18\u201325 August 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref> had by August 2014 delegated the investigation to the DSB because of the large number of Dutch passengers and the flight having originated in [[Amsterdam]].<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|14}}<ref>\"[http://onderzoeksraad.nl/en/onderzoek/2049/investigation-crash-mh17-17-july-2014/onderzoek/1559/questions-and-answers-concerning-the-investigation-into-flight-mh17#fasen Investigation crash MH17, 17 July 2014].\" [[Dutch Safety Board]]. Retrieved 22 August 2014. \"Ukraine has transferred responsibility for investigating the cause of the crash to the Dutch Safety Board. The request came from Ukraine. This request was made because the flight departed from the Netherlands, and due to the large number of Dutch nationals who died in the crash\"</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://nos.nl/nieuwsuur/artikel/2139769-mh17-misbruikt-voor-opvoeren-spanning-met-rusland.html |title=MH17 misbruikt voor opvoeren spanning met Rusland |access-date=17 July 2019 |work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]] |date=26 October 2016 |language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 July 2014, a Malaysian team of 133 officials, search and recovery personnel, and forensics, technical and medical experts arrived in Ukraine.<ref>{{cite news |title=MH17 plane crash: Dutch experts examine bodies |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-28399406 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |publisher=BBC |date=21 July 2014}}</ref> Also Australia sent a 45-member panel headed by former [[Air chief marshal (Australia)|Air Chief Marshal]] [[Angus Houston]], who had earlier supervised the [[Malaysia Airlines Flight 370|MH 370 probe]].<ref>{{cite news |title=MH370 search coordinator to lead Australia's MH17 probe Panel |url=http://news.biharprabha.com/2014/07/mh370-search-coordinator-to-lead-australias-mh17-probe-panel/ |agency=Indo-Asian News Service |publisher=news.biharprabha.com |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> Approximately 200 special forces soldiers from Australia were also deployed to provide support for the JIT investigators.<ref name=\"smhabbotttroops\">{{cite web|last1=Wroe|first1=David|title=Tony Abbott's office floated sending Australian troops into Ukraine conflict, defence expert claims|url=https://www.smh.com.au/federal-politics/federal-election-2016/tony-abbotts-office-floated-sending-australian-troops-into-ukraine-conflict-defence-expert-claims-20160612-gphbab.html|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|publisher=Fairfax Media|accessdate=13 October 2017|date=13 June 2017|quote=In the end, Australia quietly deployed about 200 special forces soldiers in a low-key role supporting police investigators.}}</ref> The United Kingdom sent six investigators from the [[Air Accidents Investigation Branch]] (AAIB) and the UK [[Foreign Office]] sent extra consular staff to Ukraine.<ref name=hp-20140719>{{cite news |title=Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17: British Investigators Join Probe in Ukraine Amid Fears of Evidence Tampering |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2014/07/19/malaysia-airlines-flight-mh17_n_5601582.html |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=19 July 2014}}</ref> It took until late July before the full international team could start working at the crash site,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/01/mh17-investigators-reach-crash-site-ukraine-search-bodies |title=MH17 investigators reach crash site two weeks after plane brought down |work=The Guardian |date=1 August 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref> under the leadership of the [[Ministry of Defence (Netherlands)|Dutch Ministry of Defence]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.houseofrepresentatives.nl/sites/www.houseofrepresentatives.nl/files/news_items/140728ambtelijke_briefing_mh17_beknopt_engels_1.doc |title=Summary Report of a Briefing at Civil Service Level |publisher=[[House of Representatives (Netherlands)|House of Representatives]] |date=28 July 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 July 2014, a Ukrainian representative said that pro-Russian rebels had mined approaches to the crash site and moved heavy artillery.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/still-no-safe-passage-to-malaysia-airlines-crash-site-1406714025 |title=Still No Safe Passage to Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 Crash Site in Eastern Ukraine |first1=Alexander |last1=Kolyandr |first2=Gabriele |last2=Steinhauser |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal |date=30 July 2014 |accessdate=2 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 August 2014, the experts left the crash site due to concerns about their safety.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Outlook India |agency=Press Trust of India |title=21 More MH17 Crash Victims Identified, Experts Leave Site |url=http://www.outlookindia.com/news/article/21-More-MH17-Crash-Victims-Identified-Experts-Leave-Site/854102 |date=8 August 2014 |accessdate=17 August 2014}}</ref> In mid-September they unsuccessfully attempted to regain access to the site.<ref>{{cite news |author=<!-- no author--> |title=Netherlands deploys more experts to probe MH17 crash |url=http://ibnlive.in.com/news/netherlands-deploys-more-experts-to-probe-mh17-crash/498540-2.html |agency=Press Trust of India |newspaper=CNN-IBNLive |date=13 September 2014 |accessdate=14 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.oneindia.in/international/additional-mh17-crash-investigators-return-to-netherlands-1525660.html#infinite-scroll-1 |title=Additional MH17 crash investigators return to Netherlands |publisher=[[Oneindia.in]] |date=20 September 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014}}</ref> On 13 October 2014, a Dutch-Ukrainian team resumed recovery of victims' personal belongings.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.newsweek.com/dutch-experts-help-recover-mh17-crash-items-despite-nearby-clashes-277024 |title=Dutch Experts Help Recover MH17 Crash Items Despite Nearby Clashes |work=Newsweek |date=13 October 2014 |accessdate=13 October 2014}}</ref> In mid-November 2014, work was undertaken to remove part of the wreckage from the crash site. Earlier efforts by the recovery team to salvage the MH17 wreckage had been frustrated by disagreements with the local rebels.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-30000967 |title=MH17 crash: Dutch salvage team 'unable to start' |accessdate=2 December 2014 |publisher=BBC |date=11 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-26248275 |title=Ukraine crisis: Timeline |accessdate=2 December 2014 |publisher=BBC |date=13 November 2014}}</ref> The recovery operation took one week to complete. The debris was transported to the Netherlands where investigators reconstructed parts of the airplane.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-11-24/dutch-complete-mh17-wreckage-recovery-in-ukraine/5912572 |title=MH17: Dutch complete recovery of Malaysia Airlines wreckage in eastern Ukraine |date=24 November 2014 |accessdate=24 November 2014 |agency=Agence France-Presse |publisher=ABC News}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, possible [[Buk missile system|Buk missile launcher]] parts were found at the crash site by the Dutch led [[#Criminal investigation|joint investigation team]] (JIT).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dearden |first1=Lizzie |title=MH17 crash: Investigators find possible parts of Buk missile used to shoot plane down |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/mh17-crash-investigators-find-parts-of-buk-missile-possibly-used-to-shoot-plane-down-10450053.html |accessdate=11 August 2015 |work=The Independent |date=11 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Investigation into possible Buk-missile-parts |url=https://www.om.nl/vaste-onderdelen/zoeken/@90384/investigation-into/ | work=Landelijk Parket |publisher=Openbaar Ministerie (Dutch public prosecution service) |accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Cause of the crash===\n[[File:Buk-M1-2 9A310M1-2.jpg|thumb|upright|A mobile [[Buk missile system|Buk surface-to-air missile]] launcher, similar to that concluded to have been used in the incident]]\n<!-- The audio has been widely published/played in media coverage and is a significant & noteworthy piece of evidence. Discuss on the talk page section: \"Deletion of External Link to Wiretaps Audio\" and \"YouTube ref\" -->\n{{external media| float  = right| width  =| image1 =| audio1 = {{YouTube|BbyZYgSXdyw|Pro-Russian rebels discuss the shooting down of an aircraft}} Intercepted phone calls, verified with voice recognition by the National Security Agency,<ref name=\"Landay\">{{cite web |last=Landay |first=Jonathan S. |url=http://www.bellinghamherald.com/2014/07/22/3762980/us-officials-we-still-dont-know.html |title=WASHINGTON: U.S. officials still don't know who shot down Malaysian airliner &#124; World |work=The Bellingham Herald |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> between rebels discussing which rebel group shot down the aircraft and initial reports that it was a civilian aircraft. Audio (in Russian) released by [[Security Service of Ukraine]] with English subtitles.<ref name=\"ONE News\">{{cite web |url=http://tvnz.co.nz/world-news/militants-admit-shooting-down-mh17-reports-6031634 |title=Militants admit to shooting down MH17 \u2013 reports |publisher=ONE News |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Demirjian\">{{cite news |last=Demirjian |first=Karoun |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/07/20/watch-ukraines-pro-russian-rebels-discuss-mh17s-black-box-in-secret-recording/ |title=Watch: Ukraine's pro-Russian rebels discuss MH17\u2032s black box in secret recording |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref>}}\n\nSoon after the crash both American and Ukrainian officials said that a 9M38 series surface-to-air missile strike was the most likely cause.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ensor |first=Josie |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10977644/MH17-what-we-know-two-days-after-Malaysia-Airlines-crash-over-Ukraine.html |title=MH17: what we know two days after Malaysia Airlines crash over Ukraine |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> If so, then the missile was fired from a mobile Soviet-designed [[Buk missile system]] ([[NATO reporting name]]: SA-11 \"Gadfly\"). At the time, Buk was the only surface-to-air missile system known to be deployed in the region that was capable of reaching the cruising altitude of commercial air traffic.<ref name=\"BakerNYT\"/><ref>{{cite web |first=Wil |last=Thijssen |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/31522/Vliegtuigcrash-in-Oekraine/article/detail/3692229/2014/07/19/De-bewijsstukken-Wie-schoot-MH17-neer.dhtml |title=De bewijsstukken: Wie schoot MH17 neer? |newspaper=[[de Volkskrant]] |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |language=Dutch}}</ref><ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\">{{cite news |first1=Ralph |last1=Vartabedian |first2=W.J. |last2=Hennigan |title=High-tech spycraft tracked missile's path to Malaysia Airlines jet |url=https://www.latimes.com/nation/nationnow/la-fg-satellites-ukraine-missile-20140717-story.html |accessdate=21 July 2014 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">Robert Mendick (27 July 2014) [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10993020/MH17-why-the-culprits-may-never-be-caught.html MH17: why the culprits may never be caught] ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]''</ref><ref name=\"Aust-ABC002\">{{cite web |title=MH17 likely shot down by mistake by Russian separatists, US intelligence official says |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-23/mh17-likely-shot-down-by-accident-by-russian-separatists/5616748 |publisher=ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |date=23 July 2014 |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"kyivpost1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/sbu-releases-more-conversations-implicating-russia-in-shooting-down-malaysia-airlines-flight-video-transcript-2-356778.html |title=SBU releases more conversations implicating Russia in shooting down Malaysia Airlines flight (VIDEO, TRANSCRIPT) |work=Kyiv Post |date=14 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Such systems, unless they receive information from larger networks, have limited capacity to distinguish between military and civilian airplanes. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technologyreview.com/s/529156/how-can-a-civilian-plane-accidentally-be-shot-down/|title=Design of Surface-to-Air Missile Systems Makes Accidents Far from Improbable|last=Majumdar|first=Dave|website=MIT Technology Review|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/the-flaw-in-the-buk-missile-system-2014-7|title=This Flaw In The Buk Missile System Makes It Really Easy To Accidentally Shoot Down A Passenger Jet|last=Rosen|first=Armin|website=Business Insider|access-date=2020-03-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-switch/wp/2014/07/18/did-the-ukrainian-rebels-even-know-they-were-shooting-at-a-civilian-aircraft/|title=Did the Ukrainian rebels even know they were shooting at a civilian aircraft?|last=Fung|first=Brian|last2=|date=|website=Washington Post|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-12|last3=}}</ref> \n\nAccording to defence analyst Reed Foster (from [[Jane's Information Group]]), the contour of the aluminium and the blistering of the paint around many of the holes on the aircraft fragments indicate that small, high-velocity [[Fragmentation (weaponry)|fragments]] entered the aircraft externally, a damage pattern indicative of an SA-11.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/07/21/world/europe/wreckage-offers-clues-on-why-flight-17-went-down.html |title=Wreckage Offers Clues on Why Flight 17 Went Down |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> Ballistics specialist Stephan Fruhling of the [[Australian National University]]'s [[Strategic and Defence Studies Centre]] concurred with this, explaining that since it struck the cockpit rather than an engine it was probably a radar guided, rather than heat seeking, missile equipped with a [[proximity fuze]]d [[warhead]] such as an SA-11.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/photo-of-mh17-wreckage-proves-missile-attack-claims-report-20140722-zvjur.html |title=Photo of MH17 wreckage proves missile attack, claims report |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |author=Rose Powell |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> \n\nShortly after the crash, [[Igor Girkin]], leader of the Donbass separatists, was reported to have posted on social media network [[VKontakte]], taking credit for downing a Ukrainian An-26.<ref name=\"VK Wall\">{{cite web|url=https://vk.com/wall-57424472_7256 |title=Wall \u2013 VK |date=17 July 2014 |work=archive.org |accessdate=22 October 2016 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717155720/https://vk.com/wall-57424472_7256 |archivedate=17 July 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.interpretermag.com/evidence-of-separatists-possession-of-buk-system-before-downing-of-mh17/ |title=Evidence of Separatists' Possession of Buk System Before Downing of MH17 |work=The Interpreter Magazine |date=27 July 2014 |accessdate=25 February 2015 |author=Catherine A. Fitzpatrick}}</ref><ref name=\"Boroday20140813\"/> This news was repeated by channels in Russia, with LifeNews reporting \"a new victory of Donetsk self-defence who shot down yet another Ukrainian airplane\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bbc.com/russian/features-37496581|title=\u041a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0430 MH17: \u043a\u0430\u043a \u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u043b\u0438\u0441\u044c \u0432\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0445 \u0421\u041c\u0418|last=\u0411\u0443\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430|first=\u041e\u043b\u044c\u0433\u0430|date=28 September 2016|newspaper=BBC \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430|language=en-GB|access-date=29 September 2016}}</ref> Russian news agency [[TASS]] also reported eyewitness accounts claiming that the Donbass militia had just shot down a Ukrainian An-26 military airplane with a missile.<ref name=tassan26/> The separatists later denied involvement, saying they did not have the equipment or training to hit a target at that altitude.<ref>{{cite news |author=Rick Feneley |url=https://www.smh.com.au/national/attack-on-flight-mh17-after-the-tragedy-the-accusations-rain-down-20140718-zumq4.html |title=Attack on Flight MH17: After the tragedy, the accusations rain down |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/comment/smh-editorial/mh17-ultimate-responsibility-lies-with-putin-20140718-zuc0v.html |title=MH17: Ultimate responsibility lies with Putin |work=The Age |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Europe/2014/0717/Web-evidence-points-to-pro-Russia-rebels-in-downing-of-MH17-video |title=Web evidence points to pro-Russia rebels in downing of MH17 (+video) |work=The Christian Science Monitor |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref> Russian media also reported that [[Alexander Borodai]] called one of the Moscow media managers 40 minutes after the crash, saying that \"likely we shot down a civilian airliner\".<ref name=\"Boroday20140813\">{{cite web |url=http://www.interpretermag.com/novaya-gazeta-editor-boroday-called-moscow-press-about-downing-of-civilian-airliner/ |title=Novaya Gazeta Editor: Boroday Called Moscow Press About Downing of Civilian Airliner |work=The Interpreter Magazine |date=13 August 2014 |accessdate=25 February 2015 |author=Catherine A. Fitzpatrick}}</ref>\n\nWitnesses in [[Torez]] reported sightings on the day of the incident of what appeared to be a [[Buk missile system|Buk missile launcher]],<ref name=walker>{{cite web |last1=Walker |first1=Shaun |title=Ukrainians report sightings of missile launcher on day of MH17 crash |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/22/ukraine-sightings-missile-launcher-mh17?CMP=twt_gu |work=The Guardian |accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> and [[Associated Press|AP]] journalists reported sightings of a Buk system in separatist controlled [[Snizhne]].<ref name=Karmanau/> The witness reports backed up photographs and videos which had been posted online, of the Buk launcher in rebel-held territory.<ref name=walker/>\n\nOn 19 July 2014, Vitaly Nayda, the chief of the Counter Intelligence Department of the [[Security Service of Ukraine]] (SBU), told a news conference, \"We have compelling evidence that this terrorist act was committed with the help of the Russian Federation. We know clearly that the crew of this system were Russian citizens.\"<ref>{{cite news |agency=Reuters |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/19/us-ukraine-crisis-intelligence-idUSKBN0FO0GD20140719 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |date=19 July 2014 |title=Ukraine says has 'compelling evidence' Russian crew shot down Malaysian plane |first1=Pavel |last1=Polityuk |first2=Elizabeth |last2=Piper|editor1-first=Louise|editor1-last=Ireland |archivedate=19 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140719125225/https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/19/us-ukraine-crisis-intelligence-idUSKBN0FO0GD20140719}}</ref><ref name=espreso-20140719>{{cite news |url=http://espreso.tv/news/2014/07/19/raketnym_kompleksom_buk_yakyy_zbyv_boeing_777_keruvaly_rosiyany___sbu |title=\u0420\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0442\u043d\u0438\u043c \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u043e\u043c \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\", \u044f\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0437\u0431\u0438\u0432 Boeing-777 \u043a\u0435\u0440\u0443\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0438 \u0440\u043e\u0441\u0456\u044f\u043d\u0438, \u2013 \u0421\u0411\u0423 (Missile complex \"BUK\", that shot Boeing-777 was managed by Russian citizens) \u2013 Espreso.tv (leading Ukrainian news agency) |agency=[[Espreso.tv]] |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Schofield |first=Matthew |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2014/07/19/233825/ukraine-video-claims-proof-of.html?sp=/99/100/&ihp=1 |title=Ukraine video claims proof of Russia-supplied anti-aircraft system |publisher=Mcclatchydc.com |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> He cited what he said were recorded conversations in which separatists expressed satisfaction to Russian intelligence agents that they brought down an aircraft.<ref name=\"ForbesPRG1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paulroderickgregory/2014/07/18/smoking-guns-russian-separatists-shot-down-malaysian-plane/ |work=[[Forbes]] |title=Smoking Guns: Russian Separatists Shot Down Malaysian Flight MH17; Putin Must Be Held Responsible |first=Paul Roderick |last=Gregory |date=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ForbesPRG2\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paulroderickgregory/2014/07/19/what-more-smoking-guns-are-needed-for-mh17-the-worlds-first-sam-terrorism/ |title=Here Are The Intercepted Transcripts Indicating Russian Rebels Shot Down Malaysian Flight MH17 |work=Forbes |first=Paul Roderick |last=Gregory |date=19 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> While one of the involved persons acknowledged that these conversations took place, the separatists denied that they were related to the crash of MH17 and blamed the Ukrainian government for shooting it down.<ref name=BBCbothsides>{{cite news |title=MH17 Malaysia plane crash in Ukraine: What we know |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28357880 |work=BBC News |accessdate=21 July 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718121104/http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-28357880 |archivedate=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u0411\u0435\u0441 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0433 \u043e\u0431\u0432\u0438\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u0443\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0442\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \"\u0411\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430\" |url=http://lenta.ru/news/2014/07/18/bezler/ |publisher=[[Lenta.ru]] |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=APbothsides>{{cite news |title=Both sides in Ukraine deny shooting down plane |url=http://hosted2.ap.org/PASCR/a5050f4ad4f44dafab85bb41a15281cf/Article_2014-07-17-EU--Ukraine-Plane/id-080a6229c3e249c3b05226215d0da426 |work=Associated Press |accessdate=21 July 2014 |first1=Peter |last1=Leonard |first2=Mstyslav |last2=Chernov}}</ref><ref name=\"nationalpost1\">{{cite news |url=http://news.nationalpost.com/2014/07/17/malaysian-passenger-plane-was-shot-down-by-rebels-intercepted-phone-calls-prove-ukraines-president-says/ |title=Malaysian plane was shot down by rebels, intercepted phone calls prove, Ukraine's president says |work=[[National Post]] |publisher=Associated Press via [[Postmedia Network]] |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> According to Nayda, a Buk launcher used in the shootdown was moved back into Russia the night after the attack.<ref name=Karmanau/> The SBU released another recording, which they said was of pro-Russian-separatist leader [[Igor Bezler]] being told of an approaching aircraft two minutes before MH17 was shot down. Bezler said the recording was real, but referred to a different incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/29/-sp-ukraine-rebel-igor-bezler-interview-demon |title=The Guardian 29 July 2014 |work=The Guardian |accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> The head of the SBU, [[Valentyn Nalyvaichenko]], later concluded that rebels intended to shoot down a Russian airliner in a [[false flag|false flag operation]] to give Russia a pretext to invade Ukraine, but shot down MH17 by mistake.<ref>{{citation |title=Separatists planned terrorist attacks against Aeroflot aircraft on day of MH17 crash as pretext for Russian invasion into Ukraine- SBU chief |work=[[Radio Ukraine International]] |date=7 August 2014 |accessdate=21 November 2014 |url=http://www.nrcu.gov.ua/en/148/573400/ |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129041421/http://www.nrcu.gov.ua/en/148/573400/ |archivedate=29 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ukraine Says Rebels Mistook Doomed Flight MH17 for Aeroflot Plane |first=Anna |last=Dolgov |newspaper=Moscow Times |date=8 August 2014 |accessdate=21 November 2014 |url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/ukraine-says-rebels-mistook-doomed-flight-mh17-for-aeroflot-plane/504793.html}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Terrorists and militants planned cynical terrorist attack at Aeroflot civil aircraft |work=[[Security Service of Ukraine]] |date=7 August 2014 |accessdate=7 June 2015 |url=http://www.sbu.gov.ua/sbu/control/en/publish/article?art_id=129860 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150721074226/http://www.sbu.gov.ua/sbu/control/en/publish/article?art_id=129860 |archive-date=21 July 2015 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\nJournalists from the [[Associated Press]] in Snizhne, Ukraine reported seeing a Buk M-1 enter the town operated by a man \"with unfamiliar fatigues and a distinctive Russian accent\" escorted by two civilian vehicles, which then moved off in the direction where the shootdown later occurred.  According to Ukrainian counterterrorism chief, Vitaly Nayda, after downing the airplane under separatist direction, the launcher's Russian crew quickly moved it back across the border into Russia.<ref name=\"Karmanau\"/>\n\nOn 22 July 2014, a rebel fighter revealed to an Italian reporter that fellow separatists had told his unit the aircraft had been shot down under the assumption that it was Ukrainian.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.corriere.it/esteri/14_luglio_22/cosi-stato-colpito-l-aereo-0a7e5f9e-115f-11e4-affb-3320a03d21e8.shtml |title=Cos\u00ec \u00e8 stato colpito l'aereo |trans-title=So the plane was struck |language=Italian |newspaper=[[Corriere della Sera]] |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |first=Lorenzo |last=Cremonesi}}</ref> This information was verified and confirmed on the same day by a German newspaper.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.faz.net/aktuell/politik/ausland/europa/separatisten-sollten-piloten-der-mh17-festnehmen-13059009.html |title=Separatisten am Abschussort sollten Piloten festnehmen |trans-title=Separatists at the crash site should capture pilots |work=[[Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung]] |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=2 October 2014 |author=Konrad Schuller}}</ref> Unnamed American intelligence officials stated that sensors that traced the path of the missile, [[Fragmentation (weaponry)|shrapnel]] patterns in the wreckage, voice print analysis of separatists' conversations in which they claimed credit for the strike, and photos and other data from social media sites all indicated that Russian-backed separatists had fired the missile.<ref name=\"WaPoJuly22\"/>\n\nAmerican officials said that satellite data from infrared sensors detected the explosion of Flight MH17.<ref name=\"ReutersIndia\">{{cite news |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/idINKBN0FN2QK20140718 |title=U.S scrambles to determine who fired Russian-made missile at jet |first=Phil |last=Stewart |first2=Mark |last2=Hosenball |date=19 July 2014 |agency=[[Reuters]] |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref> American intelligence agencies said that analysis of the launch plume and trajectory suggested the missile was fired from an area near Torez and Snizhne.<ref name=\"BakerNYT\"/><ref name=\"Los Angeles Times\"/> The British ''[[The Daily Telegraph|Daily Telegraph]]'' said: \"''The Telegraph''{{'}}s own inquiries suggest the missile, an SA-11 from a Buk mobile rocket launcher, was possibly fired from a cornfield about {{convert|12|mi|km|order=flip}} to the south of the epicentre of the crash site.\"<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\"/> Other sources suggest the missile was launched from the separatist-controlled town of Chernukhino.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/easternapproaches/2014/07/flight-mh17 |title=Flight MH17: The Evidence |author=M.J.S. |work=The Economist |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref> Several other media outlets including ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'' and the ''[[Sydney Morning Herald]]'' reported that the aeroplane is believed to have been downed by a rebel-fired missile.<ref name=\"Guardian AP\">{{cite news |agency=Australian Associated Press |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/aug/01/australia-mh17-bodies-retrieved-from-crash-site-within-days |title=Australia says all MH17 bodies should be retrieved from crash site within days |work=The Guardian |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Washington Post Tharoor\">Ishaan Tharoor \u2013 [https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/worldviews/wp/2014/07/20/the-evidence-that-may-prove-pro-russian-separatists-shot-down-mh17/ The evidence that may prove pro-Russian separatists shot down MH17] \u2013 The Washington Post \u2013 20 July 2014. Retrieved 3 August 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Paul McGeough |url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/ukraine-war-zone-tempers-federal-police-attempts-to-access-mh17-crash-site-20140801-zzkxy.html |title=Ukraine war zone tempers Federal Police attempts to access MH17 crash site |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=14 June 2012 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nAn unnamed American intelligence official stated that Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 may have been shot down in error by pro-Russian separatists, citing evidence that separatists launched an SA-11 surface-to-air missile that blew up the Malaysian airliner. They said it was possible the rebel was a former member of the [[Armed Forces of Ukraine]] who had [[Defection|defected]] to the pro-Russian separatists.<ref name=\"LAtimes\">{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/world/europe/la-fg-ukraine-intelligence-us-20140722-story.html |title=U.S. officials believe attack against Malaysian plane was mistake |work=Los Angeles Times |date=22 July 2014}}</ref> The official dismissed Russian allegations that MH17 took evasive action and said the claim that the Ukrainian government had shot down MH17 was not realistic, as Kiev had no such missile systems in that area, which was rebel-controlled.<ref name=\"Aust-ABC002\"/> American intelligence officials also said that Russia was attempting to disguise the flow of weaponry it was delivering to the rebels by sending older weapons that matched Ukraine's inventory.<ref name=\"WaPoJuly22\"/> The British [[Foreign Office]] stated that it was \"highly likely\" that the missile was fired from an area controlled by Russian-backed separatists.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2014/07/26/ukraine-crisis-britain-mh17-plane-idINKBN0FV0J720140726 |title=Britain says highly likely MH17 shot down by Russian-supplied missile |agency=Reuters |date=26 July 2014 |accessdate=4 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Russian Ministry of Defence]] has maintained that American claims of separatist responsibility were \"unfounded\", and said that the American intelligence agencies have not released any of the data on which they based their conclusions.<ref>{{cite news |title=US Claims of Flight MH17 Downing by Militia Remain Unfounded \u2013 Russia's Defense Ministry |url=http://en.ria.ru/russia/20140724/191186319/US-Claims-of-Flight-MH17-Downing-by-Militia-Remain-Unfounded-.html |agency=RIA Novosti |date=24 July 2014 |quote=The United States has not yet provided any documented evidence to prove that the rocket that brought down the Malaysia Airlines Boeing 777 was launched from militia-controlled territory, Russian Deputy Defence Minister Anatoly Antonov said on Thursday.}}</ref> According to the Russian military, in what the ''[[New York Magazine]]'' called \"Russia's Conspiracy Theory\", MH17 was shot down by the Ukrainians, using either a surface-to-air missile or a fighter aircraft.<ref name=newyork>{{citation |title=Russia's 'Conspiracy Theory': MH17 Shot Down by Ukrainian Fighter Jet or Missile |work=New York |first=Margaret |last=Hartmann |url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2014/07/russia-mh17-downed-by-ukrainian-jet-missile.html |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=20 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Russia Presents Its Account of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 Crash |first=Olga |last=Razumovskaya |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=20 September 2014 |url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/russia-presents-its-account-of-malaysia-airlines-flight-17-crash-1405952441?mod=e2tw}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 July 2014, the Russian Ministry of Defence (MoD) held a press conference and claimed that satellite photographs showed that the Ukrainian army moved a Buk SAM battery to the area close to the territory controlled by the rebels on the morning of 17 July, hours before the crash. They said the installation was then moved away again by 18 July. The Russian MoD also stated that, about 1,5 minutes after the airliner began to fall apart, \"supposedly a Ukrainian Su-25\" was detected by two Russian military on-duty radars and was being observed by the radars for four minutes.<ref>[https://function.mil.ru/news_page/country/more.htm?id=11970654%40egNews Briefing with the media, dedicated to the newly identified facts which relate to the aviation disaster of Malaysian aircraft \"Boeing 777\".]</ref> It was also said that this ground-attack aircraft approached to within {{convert|3|to|5|km|mi}} of the Malaysian airliner.<ref name=\"wsj russian version\">{{cite news |author=Razumovskaya, Olga |title=Russia Presents Its Account of Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 Crash |url=https://online.wsj.com/articles/russia-presents-its-account-of-malaysia-airlines-flight-17-crash-1405952441 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Promoted by Russian media, the idea that a Su-25 could have downed the Boeing 777 with an [[air-to-air missile]] was dismissed by chief designer of the Su-25, Vladimir Babak.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://uatoday.tv/news/general-designer-of-su-25-says-aircraft-couldn-t-have-shot-down-mh17-414628.html |title=General designer of Su-25 says aircraft couldn't have shot down MH17 |publisher=Ukraine Today |date=11 March 2015 |accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref> In 2015 [[Bellingcat]] purchased satellite photos from the same area and time as used by the MoD and demonstrated that they had used older photos (May and June 2014) in their presentation that were edited to make a Ukrainian Buk launcher appear as if it was removed after the attack.<ref>{{cite news |title=MH17-Absturz kontert Kritik mit neuen Satellitenbildern |url=http://www.zeit.de/politik/ausland/2015-06/bellingcat-russland-mh17-satellitenfotos-manipulation |language=German |date=12 June 2015 |accessdate=17 June 2015 |newspaper=De Zeit}}</ref> In the report published by the Dutch Safety Board, an air-to-air missile strike was ruled out.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nIn an interview with [[Reuters]] on 23 July 2014, [[Alexander Khodakovsky]], the commander of the pro-Russian [[Vostok Battalion (Donbass)#Vostok Battalion|Vostok Battalion]], acknowledged that the separatists had an anti-aircraft missile of the type the Americans had said was used to shoot down the aircraft, and said that it could have been sent back to Russia to remove proof of its presence;<ref name=\"ReutersKho\">{{cite news |agency=Reuters |date=23 July 2014 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/23/us-ukraine-crisis-commander-exclusive-idUSKBN0FS1V920140723 |title=Ukraine rebel commander acknowledges fighters had Buk missile |author=Anton Zverev}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Shaun Walker in Donetsk |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/23/mh17-ukraine-separatists-buk-missile-system |title=MH17: Ukraine separatist commander 'admits' rebels had Buk missile system |work=The Guardian |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Buckley |first=Neil |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/26fe789c-126e-11e4-a581-00144feabdc0.html |title=Separatist leader admits Ukraine rebels held Buk missile system |work=Financial Times |date=4 July 2014 |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> he later retracted his comments, saying that he had been misquoted and stating that rebels never had a Buk.<ref name=\"GuardianKho\">{{cite web |last1=Walker |first1=Shaun |title=MH17: Ukraine separatist commander 'admits' rebels had Buk missile system |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/23/mh17-ukraine-separatists-buk-missile-system |work=The Guardian |accessdate=24 July 2014}}</ref> In November 2014 he repeated that the separatists had a Buk launcher at the time, but stated that the vehicle, under control of fighters from Luhansk, had still been on its way to Donetsk when MH17 crashed. It was then withdrawn to avoid being blamed.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lanting |first=Bert |title=Wij hadden raket, maar haalden MH17 niet neer |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/dossier-rampvlucht-mh17/wij-hadden-raket-maar-haalden-mh17-niet-neer~a3782013 |language=Dutch |newspaper=de Volkskrant |date=4 November 2014 |accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 July 2014, Ukrainian security official Andriy Lysenko announced, at a press conference, that black box recorder analysis had revealed that the aircraft had been brought down by shrapnel that caused \"massive explosive decompression.\" Dutch officials were reported to be \"stunned\" by what they saw as a \"premature announcement\" and said that they had not provided this information.<ref>{{cite news |author=Natasha Culzac |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/mh17-crash-black-boxes-show-plane-suffered-massive-explosive-decompression-following-shrapnel-hit-9632881.html |title=MH17 crash: Black boxes show plane suffered 'massive explosive decompression' following shrapnel hit \u2013 Europe \u2013 World |work=[[The Independent]] |date=28 July 2014 |accessdate=28 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 September 2014, the [[BBC]] released new material by [[John Sweeney (journalist)|John Sweeney]] who cited three civilian witnesses from Donbass who saw the Buk launcher in the rebel-controlled territory on the day when MH17 crashed. Two witnesses said the crew of the launcher and a military vehicle escorting it did not have local accents and spoke with [[Moscow|Muscovite]] accents.<ref name=bbc29109398>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-29109398 |title=MH17 disaster: Russians 'controlled Buk missile system' |work=BBC News |date=8 September 2014 |accessdate=9 September 2014 |author=Sweeney, John}}</ref> On the same day Ignat Ostanin, a Russian journalist, published an analysis of photos and films of Buk units moving in Russia and Ukraine in the days before and after the MH17 crash. According to Ostanin, the markings on the specific launcher suspected of being used to shoot MH17, together with the number plates of the [[large goods vehicle]] that carried the launcher, suggested that it belonged to the 53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade of the Air Defence Forces of the [[Russian Ground Forces]].<ref name=\"FBS2APRIL\">{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/paulroderickgregory/2015/04/02/is-the-mh17-joint-investigation-team-avoiding-the-question-of-kremlin-guilt/ |title=Is The MH17 Joint Investigation Team Avoiding The Question of Kremlin Guilt? |work=Forbes |date=2 April 2015 |accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"ostanin\">{{cite web |url=https://bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2014/09/08/images-show-the-buk-that-downed-flight-mh17-inside-russia-controlled-by-russian-troops/ |title=Images Show the Buk that Downed Flight MH17, Inside Russia, Controlled by Russian Troops |publisher=[[Bellingcat]] |date=8 September 2014 |accessdate=9 September 2014 |last=Ostanin |first=Iggy}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 October 2014 the president of the German [[Bundesnachrichtendienst|Federal Intelligence Service]] (BND) gave a presentation about MH17 to a German parliamentary committee overseeing intelligence activities.  According to ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', the report contained a detailed analysis which concluded that pro-Russian separatists had used a captured Ukrainian Buk system to shoot down Flight MH17. The report also noted that \"Russian claims the missile had been fired by Ukrainian soldiers and that a Ukrainian fighter jet had been flying close to the passenger jet were false\".<ref name=spiegel-bnd-de>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/politik/ausland/mh17-laut-bnd-waren-separatisten-fuer-absturz-verantwortlich-a-997885.html |title=Ostukraine: BND macht Separatisten f\u00fcr MH17-Absturz verantwortlich|trans-title=Eastern Ukraine: BND says separatists are responsible for MH17 crash |work=Der Spiegel |language=German |date=19 October 2014 |accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/10/20/world/germany-says-ukraine-rebels-downed-mh17-seized-missiles-report/ |title=Germany says Ukraine rebels downed MH17 with seized missiles: report |agency=Agence France-Presse |date=20 October 2014 |accessdate=20 October 2014}} \"He also said Ukrainian photos had been \"manipulated\", the magazine reported but did not elaborate on what the pictures showed, who had provided them or altered them.\"</ref> The [[Attorney General of Germany]] opened an investigation against unknown persons due to a suspected [[war crime]].<ref name=spiegel-bnd>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/europe/german-intelligence-blames-pro-russian-separatists-for-mh17-downing-a-997972.html |title=Deadly Ukraine Crash: German Intelligence Claims Pro-Russian Separatists Downed MH17 |work=[[Der Spiegel]] |date=19 October 2014 |accessdate=19 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nBetween November 2014 and May 2016, UK-based investigative collective [[Bellingcat]] made a series of conclusions, based on their examination of photos in social media and other open-source information. Bellingcat said that the launcher used to shoot down the aircraft was a Buk 332 of the Russian [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]] based in [[Kursk]], Russia, which had been transported from [[Donetsk]] to [[Snizhne]] and was controlled by separatists in Ukraine on the day of the attack.<ref name=\"Bellingcat\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Origin-of-the-Separatists-Buk-A-Bellingcat-Investigation1.pdf|title=MH17: Source of the Separatists' Buk|author=Bellingcat MH17 Investigation Team|date=8 November 2014|publisher=Bellingcat|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109132619/https://www.bellingcat.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/Origin-of-the-Separatists-Buk-A-Bellingcat-Investigation1.pdf|archive-date=9 November 2014|url-status=live|access-date=16 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/ukraine/journalists-find-solid-russian-ties-to-missile-that-hit-mh17-371161.html|title=Journalists find 'solid' Russian ties to missile that hit MH17|last=Gorchinskaya|first=Katya|date=9 November 2014|work=Kyiv Post|accessdate=18 June 2015|last2=Lavrov|first2=Vlad}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/meet-eliot-higgins-putins-mh17-nemesis-345485|title=Meet Eliot Higgins, Putin's MH17 Nemesis|last=Tucker|first=Maxim|date=22 June 2015|work=Newsweek|accessdate=24 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/bellingcat-new-evidence-against-russian-soldiers-on-mh17/a-18959585|title=Bellingcat: New evidence against Russian soldiers on MH17|work=DW.COM|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2016/05/03/the_lost_digit/|title=bellingcat \u2013 The Lost Digit: Buk 3x2 \u2013 bellingcat|work=bellingcat|accessdate=4 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 December 2014 the Dutch news service [[RTL Nieuws]] published a statement of an unnamed local resident who witnessed the shooting down of MH17, indicating that the aircraft was shot down by a missile from rebel territory. He took photographs of what appeared to be the vapour trail of a ground-launched missile which he passed to the [[Security Service of Ukraine|SBU]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/binnenland/ooggetuige-mh17-mijn-doel-rechtvaardigheid |title=Ooggetuige MH17: 'Mijn doel is rechtvaardigheid' |trans-title=Eyewitness of MH17: \"My goal is justice\" |newspaper=RTL News |date=22 December 2014 |accessdate=23 December 2014 |language=Dutch}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New Competing Claims on Downing of MH17 |publisher=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date=24 December 2014 |url=http://www.rferl.org/content/new-competing-claims-on-downing-of-mh17/26760591.html}}</ref> On 24 December Russia's state-operated domestic news agency [[RIA Novosti]] quoted the leader of the self-proclaimed Donetsk People's Republic, [[Alexander Zakharchenko]], saying he saw MH17 shot out of the sky by two Ukrainian jets.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0413\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u0414\u041d\u0420 \u043e \u043a\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 MH17: \"\u042f \u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043b, \u043a\u0430\u043a \u044d\u0442\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0441\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043b\u043e\" |trans-title=Head of the DPR about the crash of MH17: \"I saw how it happened\" |date=25 December 2014 |accessdate=26 December 2014 |language=Russian |newspaper=RIA News |url=http://ria.ru/mh17/20141225/1040130183.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Kremlin-backed insurgent leader claims personally witnessing Ukrainian aircraft shooting down MH17 |newspaper=Ukraine Today |date=25 December 2014 |url=http://uatoday.tv/news/kremlin-backed-insurgent-leader-claims-personally-witnessing-ukrainian-aircraft-shooting-down-mh17-399664.html}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015 a report produced by the German investigative team CORRECT!V concluded a Buk surface-to-air missile launcher operated by the [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]] shot down MH17.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kyivpost.com/content/kyiv-post-plus/new-report-says-it-proves-russian-forces-downed-flight-mh17-377063.html |title=New report says it proves Russian forces downed flight MH17 |date=10 January 2015 |first=Maxim |last=Tucker |work=Kyiv Post |accessdate=9 February 2015}}</ref> Large amounts of other [[circumstantial evidence]] were presented separately by various parties that supports this version, identifying specific launcher vehicle, operator name, truck transporting it and its alleged route through Russia and Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/evidence-mounts-that-russia-supplied-the-missiles-that-shot-down-mh17-in-ukraine-2015-5?IR=T |title=Evidence mounts that Russia supplied the missiles that shot down MH17 in Ukraine |website=Business Insider |date=13 May 2015 |accessdate=13 June 2015 |author=Robert Coalson}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2015 Reuters published statements from named witnesses from Chervonyi Zhovten ({{lang-uk|[[:uk:\u0427\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0416\u043e\u0432\u0442\u0435\u043d\u044c|\u0427\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u0416\u043e\u0432\u0442\u0435\u043d\u044c]]}}), a village close to Torez and Snizhne, who said they saw the Buk rocket passing over the village when it was fired from a field around 1.5&nbsp;km away. It also published a statement from a witness who was said to be a separatist fighter (referred to by first name only) who confirmed that the launcher was placed in that area on the day of the Boeing crash to prevent Ukrainian airstrikes.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/03/12/us-ukraine-crisis-airliner-idUSKBN0M81XF20150312 |title=Exclusive: From 'Red October' village, new evidence on downing of Malaysian plane over Ukraine |agency=Reuters |accessdate=12 March 2015 |author=Anton Zverev}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015, [[News Corp Australia]] published the transcript of a 17-minute video recorded at the scene shortly after the crash. The transcript and published segments of the video indicated that Russian-backed rebels arrived at the crash site in the expectation of finding the wreckage of a military aircraft and of locating crew that had parachuted from the aircraft.<ref name=\"NC150717\">{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/national/full-transcript-russian-backed-rebels-ransack-the-wreckage-of-mh17-in-shocking-17-minute-video/story-e6frfkp9-1227444629703|title=Full transcript: Russian-backed rebels ransack the wreckage of MH17 in shocking 17-minute video|date=17 July 2015|accessdate=17 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717004444/http://www.news.com.au/national/full-transcript-russian-backed-rebels-ransack-the-wreckage-of-mh17-in-shocking-17-minute-video/story-e6frfkp9-1227444629703|archive-date=17 July 2015|url-status=dead|work=[[news.com.au]]}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2016, [[Stratfor]] released satellite imagery taken 5 hours before the crash which showed a Russian Buk system travelling on a flatbed truck east through the town of [[Makiivka]], 40&nbsp;km away from Snizhne. Stratfor's concluded that a Buk system had moved from the Russian border toward Donetsk on 15 July 2014, and then moved back to the east on the afternoon of 17 July 2014, hours before Flight MH17 was shot down.<ref>{{cite news|title=Examining the Evidence of Russia's Involvement in a Malaysia Airlines Crash|url=https://www.stratfor.com/analysis/examining-evidence-russias-involvement-malaysia-airlines-crash|accessdate=16 May 2016|publisher=Stratfor}}</ref>\n\n===Dutch Safety Board reports===\n====Preliminary report====\nOn 9 September 2014, the preliminary report was released by the Dutch Safety Board (DSB).<ref name=\"dsb1\">{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2014/09/09/world/europe/netherlands-ukraine-mh17-report/index.html?hpt=hp_t2 |title=Report: MH17 hit by burst of 'high-energy objects' from outside |date=9 September 2014 |publisher=CNN |accessdate=25 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"dsbprelim\">{{citation |title=Preliminary report \u2013 Crash involving Malaysia Airlines Boeing 777-200 Flight MH17 |work=DSB |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=24 September 2014 |url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/uploads/phase-docs/701/b3923acad0ceprem-rapport-mh-17-en-interactief.pdf}}</ref>{{rp|16}} This preliminary report concluded that there was no evidence of any technical or operational failure in the aircraft or from the crew prior to the ending of the [[Flight recorder|CVR and FDR]] recordings at 13.20:03 hrs (UTC). The report also said that \"damage observed on the forward fuselage and cockpit section of the aircraft appears to indicate that there were impacts from a large number of high-energy objects from outside the aircraft\". According to the investigators, this damage probably led to a loss of structural integrity that caused an in-flight break-up first of the forward parts of the aircraft and then of the remainder with an expansive geographic spread of the aircraft's pieces.\n\n[[Tjibbe Joustra]], Chairman of the Dutch Safety Board, explained that the investigation thus far pointed \"towards an external cause of the MH17 crash\", but determining the exact cause required further investigation. They also said that they aimed to publish the final report within a year of the crash date.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Prof. mr. dr. Erwin Muller |title=Investigation crash MH17, 17 July 2014 Donetsk |url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/onderzoek/2049/investigation-crash-mh17-17-july-2014/preliminary-report/1562/preliminary-report-points-towards-external-cause-of-mh17-crash#fasen |website=Dutch Safety Board |publisher=Onderzoeksraad voor Veiligheid |accessdate=14 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Final report====\n[[File:MH17 Missile Impact.webm|thumb|thumbtime=43|right|upright=1.273|Narrated reconstruction of the missile impact, produced by the [[Dutch Safety Board]]]]\nThe Dutch Safety Board (DSB) issued its final report on the crash on 13 October 2015. The report concluded that the crash was caused by a [[Buk missile system|Buk 9M38-series surface-to-air missile]] with a 9N314M [[warhead]]. The warhead detonated outside and above the left-hand side of the cockpit. The impact killed the three people in the cockpit and caused structural damage to the airplane leading to an in-flight break-up resulting in a wreckage area of 50 square kilometres and loss of the lives of all 298 occupants.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/> Based on evidence they were able to exclude meteor strikes, the airplane having technical defects, a bomb, and an air-to-air attack as causes of the crash. The DSB calculated the trajectory of the missile and found it was fired within a {{convert|320|km2|sqmi|adj=on}} area southeast of [[Torez]]. Narrowing down a specific launch site was outside the DSB's mandate.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\">{{cite report|url=https://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/media/attachment/2018/7/10/debcd724fe7breport_mh17_crash.pdf |title=Crash of Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 |publisher=[[Dutch Safety Board]] |date=13 October 2015 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6cFSGnsRg?url=http://cdn.onderzoeksraad.nl/documents/report-mh17-crash-en.pdf |archivedate=13 October 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref>{{rp|147}} The findings did not specify who launched the Buk missile but according to Al Jazeera, the area identified by the DSB was controlled by separatists at the time of the downing.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2015/10/dutch-board-russian-missile-downed-mh17-151013112210934.html |title=Dutch board says Russian-made missile downed MH17 |date=13 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the technical investigation, the selection of the flight route was also investigated by the DSB.<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigation crash MH17, 17 July 2014 |url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/onderzoek/2049/investigation-crash-mh17-17-july-2014/onderzoek/1543/dutch-safety-board-heads-investigation-investigation-effort-in-full-swing-black-boxes-currently-being-read-out |website=onderzoeksraad.nl |publisher=[[Dutch Safety Board]] |accessdate=24 July 2014 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6ShD1V2ae?url=http://www.onderzoeksraad.nl/en/onderzoek/2049/investigation-crash-mh17-17-july-2014/onderzoek/1543/dutch-safety-board-heads-investigation-investigation-effort-in-full-swing-black-boxes-currently-being-read-out |archivedate=19 September 2014 }} ()</ref> Some airlines had avoided the Eastern Ukrainian airspace prior to the MH17 disaster. Many others, including 62 operators from 32 countries, continued to use this route.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\"/>{{rp|224}}<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Abeyratne|first1=Ruwantissa|title=Flight MH 17 and State Responsibility for Ensuring Safety and Security of Air Transport|journal=Journal of Transportation Security|date=1 December 2014|volume=7|issue=4|pages=347\u2013348|doi=10.1007/s12198-014-0148-0|language=en|issn=1938-7741}}</ref> The DSB judged that the Ukrainian authorities should have closed the airspace above eastern Ukraine prior to the incident due to the ongoing conflict and earlier military shootdowns,<ref name=\"AvSaf151013\">{{cite news |title=Dutch Safety Board: MH17 brought down by missile in airspace that should have been closed |url=https://news.aviation-safety.net/2015/10/13/dutch-safety-board-mh17-brought-down-by-missile-in-airspace-that-should-have-been-closed/ |accessdate=4 October 2019 |publisher=ASN News |date=13 October 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\" />{{rp|10}} but noted that states involved in armed conflicts rarely did so.<ref name=\"DSB_Final_Report\" />{{rp|11}} It recommended that states involved in such armed conflicts should exercise more caution when evaluating their airspace, and that operators should more thoroughly assess the risks when selecting routes over conflict areas.<ref name=\"BBC13OCT15_1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-34518473 |title=MH17 report: Five key findings from the Dutch Safety Board |newspaper=BBC News |accessdate=13 October 2015|date=13 October 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"AvSaf151013\" />\n\n===Criminal investigation===\nThe criminal investigation into the downing of MH17 is being led by the [[Openbaar Ministerie|Public Prosecution Service]] of the [[Dutch Ministry of Justice]], and is the largest in Dutch history, involving dozens of prosecutors and 200 investigators.<ref name=\":0\">{{citation |title=MH17 criminal investigation largest ever in the Netherlands |agency=Xinhua News Agency |date=15 August 2014 |accessdate=27 October 2014 |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/world/2014-08/15/c_126873336.htm |editor=Mu Xuequan |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140826002055/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/world/2014-08/15/c_126873336.htm |archive-date=26 August 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Investigators interviewed witnesses and examined forensic samples, satellite data, intercepted communications, and information on the Web.<ref>{{citation |title=MH17 crash: Investigation focuses on '25 metal shards' |publisher=BBC News |date=12 September 2014 |accessdate=27 October 2014 |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-29180887}}</ref> Participating in the investigation along with the Netherlands, are the four other members of the [[joint investigation team]] (JIT),<ref name=\"TheStarJIT\" /> Belgium, Ukraine, Australia, and lastly, Malaysia,<ref>{{cite news |title=Speculation on MH17 is damaging to investigations |newspaper=Free Malaysia Today |agency=[[Bernama]] |date=22 November 2014 |accessdate=22 November 2014 |url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2014/11/22/speculation-on-mh17-is-damaging-to-investigations/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129091900/http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2014/11/22/speculation-on-mh17-is-damaging-to-investigations/ |archive-date=29 November 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> which joined in November 2014.<ref name=\"TheStarJIT\">{{cite news |url=http://www.thestar.com.my/News/Nation/2014/12/01/mh17-malaysia-to-be-part-of-investigating-team/ |title=MH17: Malaysia accepted as full member of probe team |newspaper=The Star |location=Petaling Jaya, Malaysia |date=1 December 2014 |accessdate=2 December 2014}}</ref> Early in the investigation, the JIT eliminated accident, internal terrorist attack or air-to-air attack from another aircraft as the cause of the crash.<ref name=\"SMH JIT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/world/malaysia-airlines-flight-mh17-was-shot-down-from-prorussian-rebel-controlled-territory-investigation-finds-20160928-grqter.html|title=Malaysia Airlines Flight MH17 was shot down from pro-Russian rebel controlled territory, investigation finds|first=Nick|last=Miller|date=29 September 2016|work=Sydney Morning Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, in a letter to the [[United Nations Security Council|Security Council]], the Netherlands [[United Nations|UN]] representative wrote that \"The Dutch government is deliberately refraining from any speculation or accusations regarding legal responsibility for the downing of MH17.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Letter to President of the UNSC |first=Karel J.G |last=van Oosterom |date=16 December 2014 |accessdate=21 December 2014 |url=http://www.tweedekamer.nl/downloads/document?id=adbae747-b7f0-4713-ad97-1a7e1b75dcd2&title=Brief%20van%20Permanent%20Representative%20of%20the%20Kingdom%20of%20the%20Netherlands.pdf }}</ref> Also in December, the assistant secretary of the [[United States Department of State]]'s European and Eurasian Affairs said America had given all of its information, including classified information to the Dutch investigators and to the [[ICAO]].<ref>{{cite news |title=US Submits Classified Information on MH17 to Investigators: State Dep't |newspaper=[[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]] |date=17 December 2014 |accessdate=21 December 2014 |url=http://sputniknews.com/military/20141217/1015956748.html}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2015, the JIT released a Russian-language video calling for witnesses in the [[Donetsk Oblast|Donetsk]] and [[Luhansk Oblast|Luhansk regions]] who might have seen a [[Buk missile system]].<ref name=\"JITMH17\">{{cite web |url=http://jitmh17.com/ |title=Call for witnesses |publisher=Joint Investigation Team |accessdate=30 March 2015}}</ref> The video included some previously undisclosed recordings allegedly of tapped phone conversations between rebel fighters about the Buk. In one recording, of a conversation a few hours after the shoot down, a fighter says that a member of the Buk's accompanying crew had been left behind at a checkpoint. In another recording, dated the day after the shootdown, a rebel allegedly says the Buk system and its crew had been brought from Russia by \"the Librarian.\"  The video presents a \"scenario\" whereby a Buk missile was transported on a [[Volvo]] low loader truck from Sievernyi (\u0421\u0454\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0438\u0439), a town located within a kilometre of the Russian border (near [[Krasnodon]]), to [[Donetsk]] during the night of 16/17 July.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=olQNpTxSnTo MH17] ''Politie [Police]''  International Joint Investigation Team</ref>\nIn the week following the public appeal, the JIT received more than 300 responses resulting in dozens of \"serious witnesses\".<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/binnenland/23903198/__Bruikbare_tips_over_daders_MH17__.html|trans-title=Dozens of useful tips about MH17 |title=Tientallen bruikbare tips over MH17 |last=van der Graaf |first=Jolande |language=Dutch |newspaper=De Telegraaf |date=9 April 2015 |accessdate=17 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nltimes.nl/2015/04/09/hundreds-respond-to-call-for-mh17-witnesses-tips/ |title=Hundreds respond to call for MH17 witnesses |last=Van Jaarsveldt |first=Janene |date=9 April 2015 |accessdate=17 June 2015 |newspaper=NL Times}}</ref> In 2016 the presence of the [[transloading|transloader]] of matching color with a Buk missile was confirmed on a satellite photo of the area taken just a few hours before the downing of the airplane, which was described as \"correlating with other evidence\" by [[Stratfor]] who found the photo in [[DigitalGlobe]] archive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stratfor.com/analysis/examining-evidence-russias-involvement-malaysia-airlines-crash|title=Examining the Evidence of Russia's Involvement in a Malaysia Airlines Crash|website=Stratfor|access-date=13 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-updates/incidents/mh17-the-satellite-images-russia-doesnt-want-us-to-see/news-story/8c03f8e87971d36f70b5402ffbda16ff|title=The image Russia doesn't want the world to see|website=NewsComAu|access-date=16 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 April 2015 Dutch authorities made available 569 documents concerning the shoot-down. Personal information and official interviews had been redacted. A further 147 documents were not made public.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rtlnieuws.nl/nieuws/binnenland/wat-we-niet-mogen-zien-147-documenten-mh17-blijven-geheim |title=Wat we niet mogen zien: 147 documenten MH17 blijven geheim |work=RTL Nieuws |accessdate=30 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Findings of the joint investigation team (JIT)====\nOn 28 September 2016, the JIT gave a press conference in which it concluded that the aircraft was shot down with a [[Buk missile system|9M38 Buk missile]] fired from a rebel-controlled field near Pervomaisky (\u041f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u043c\u0430\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439), a town {{convert|6|km|mi|abbr=on}} south of [[Snizhne]].<ref name=\"NLTimesJIT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nltimes.nl/2016/09/28/jit-mh17-shot-down-by-a-9m38-buk-missile-from-russian-origin/|title=JIT: MH17 shot down with missile fired from pro-Russian rebel controlled field}}</ref> It also found the Buk missile system used had been transported from Russia into Ukraine on the day of the crash, and then back into Russia after the crash, with one missile less than it arrived with.<ref name=\"SMH JIT\"/><ref name=\"BBC News 28 September 2016\">{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-37495067 |title= MH17 missile 'came from Russia', Dutch-led investigators say |author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date= 28 September 2016|website= [[BBC News Online]] |publisher= [[BBC]] | accessdate= 2 October 2016 }}</ref> The JIT said they had identified 100 people, witnesses as well as suspects, who were involved in the movement of the Buk launcher, though they had not yet identified a clear chain of command to assess culpability, which was a matter for ongoing investigation. The Dutch chief prosecutor said \"the evidence must stand before a court\" which would render final judgement.<ref name=\"SMH JIT\"/> During the investigation, the JIT recorded and assessed five billion internet pages, interviewed 200 witnesses, collected half a million photos and videos, and analysed 150,000 intercepted phone calls.<ref name=\"NLTimesJIT\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.om.nl/onderwerpen/mh17-crash/@96066/presentation/|title=Presentation preliminary results criminal investigation MH17 28-09-2016}}</ref> According to JIT head prosecutor Fred Westerbeke the criminal investigation is based on \"immense body of evidence,\" including testimonies of live witnesses who saw the \"Buk\" launcher, primary radar data, original photos and videos.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.novayagazeta.ru/articles/2017/10/16/74192-the-purpose-is-to-bring-this-matter-to-court|title=\"The purpose is to bring MH17 matter to court\"|work=\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u2013 Novayagazeta.ru|access-date=16 October 2017|language=ru-RU}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Engineering Technologies 2010 Part3 0031 copy.jpg|thumb|A Buk SAM of the type used by the [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]]]]\nOn 24 May 2018, after extensive comparative research, the JIT concluded that the Buk that shot down the flight came from the Russian [[53rd Anti-Aircraft Missile Brigade]] in [[Kursk]].<ref name=\"jit\">{{cite web | url =https://www.om.nl/onderwerpen/mh17-crash/@103196/update-criminal-0/ |title=Update in criminal investigation MH17 disaster|publisher=[[Openbaar Ministerie]]| date=24 May 2018| accessdate =24 May 2018}}</ref> The head of the National Investigation Service of the Dutch police asked the eyewitnesses and insiders to share information about the identities of the Buk crew members, the instruction the crew members followed and persons responsible for the operational deployment of the involved Buk on 17 July 2014.<ref name=\"jit\"/> According to Dutch [[Openbaar Ministerie|Public Prosecution Service]], by 24 May 2018 \"the authorities of the Russian Federation have ... not reported to the JIT that a Buk of the 53rd Brigade was deployed in Eastern Ukraine and that this Buk downed flight MH17.\"<ref name=\"jit\"/> In response, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] stated that Russia will analyze the JIT conclusion, but will acknowledge it only if it becomes a party in the investigation.<ref name=\"kommersant\">{{cite web | url = https://www.kommersant.ru/doc/3638260|title=\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043f\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0435\u0449\u0430\u043b \u0438\u0437\u0443\u0447\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0432\u044b\u0432\u043e\u0434\u044b \u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u044f \u043e \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435 Boeing MH17|work=[[Kommersant]]| language=Russian|date=24 May 2018| accessdate =24 May 2018}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Defence (Russia)|Russian Ministry of Defence]] in turn stated that no Russian Buk crossed the border with Ukraine.<ref name=\"kommersant\"/>\n\nOn 25 May 2018 the governments of the Netherlands and Australia issued a joint statement in which they laid responsibility on Russia \"for its part\" in the crash.<ref name=\":1\" /> The Netherlands and Australian foreign ministers stated that they would hold Russia legally responsible for shooting the airliner down. Netherlands Foreign Minister [[Stef Blok]] stated that \"the government is now taking the next step by formally holding Russia accountable,\" and, \"The Netherlands and Australia today asked Russia to enter into talks aimed at finding a solution that would do justice to the tremendous suffering and damage caused by the downing of MH17. A possible next step is to present the case to an international court or organization for their judgment.\"<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/netherlands-australia-flight17-statement-russia-1.4677473|title = Netherlands, Australia holding Russia 'accountable' for downing of MH17|access-date = 25 May 2018|author=[[The Associated Press]] |work = [[CBC News]]|date = 25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nSeveral other countries and international organisations expressed their support for the JIT's conclusions and the joint statement by the Netherlands and Australia.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2233506-internationale-reacties-op-mh17-rusland-moet-verantwoordelijkheid-nemen.html |title=Internationale reacties op MH17: Rusland moet verantwoordelijkheid nemen |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]] |date=25 May 2018 |language=Dutch}}</ref> UK Foreign Secretary [[Boris Johnson]] said the United Kingdom \"fully supports Australia and the Netherlands,\" calling on Russia to cooperate.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/foreign-secretary-statement-on-the-mh17-investigation |title=Foreign Secretary statement on the MH17 investigation |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[Foreign & Commonwealth Office]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref> High Representative [[Federica Mogherini]] of the EU stated that the European Union \"calls on the Russian Federation to accept its responsibility\" and to cooperate as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.consilium.europa.eu/en/press/press-releases/2018/05/25/declaration-by-the-high-representative-on-behalf-of-the-eu-on-the-findings-of-the-joint-investigation-team-on-the-downing-of-flight-mh17/ |title=Declaration by the High Representative on behalf of the EU on the findings of the Joint Investigation Team on the downing of flight MH17 |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[European Council]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref> The German government called on Russia to \"fully explain the tragedy.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bundesregierung.de/Content/DE/Artikel/2018/05/2018-05-25-ukraine-mh17-gutachten.html |title=Die Schuldigen ermitteln |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[Bundesregierung]] |date=25 May 2018 |language=German}}</ref> The US Department of State issued a statement saying that the United States \"strongly support the decisions by the Netherlands and Australia,\" requesting Russia to acknowledge its involvement and to \"cease its callous disinformation campaign.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2018/05/282502.htm |title=Calling Russia To Account for Malaysia Airlines Flight MH-17 |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[United States Department of State]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref> NATO Secretary General [[Jens Stoltenberg]] called on Russia to \"accept responsibility and fully cooperate ... in line with [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 2166]].\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nato.int/cps/en/natohq/news_154585.htm |title=Statement by the NATO Secretary General on MH17 investigation |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[NATO]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the JIT's conclusions, Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] reiterated that the Russians are \"not involved in it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/news/57556 |title=St Petersburg International Economic Forum plenary session |access-date=29 May 2018 |work=[[Kremlin]] |date=25 May 2018}}</ref> Following release of the JIT report, Malaysian Prime Minister [[Mahathir Mohamad|Mahathir]] said the JIT was making Russia a \"scapegoat\" and that he did not believe the Russians whom the JIT had charged were involved. Conversely the Malaysian prosecutor supported the investigation by saying the findings \"are based on extensive investigations and also legal research\".<ref name=\"reuters_20-06-2019\">{{cite news |last1=Sipalan |first1=Joseph |title=Malaysian PM says Russia being made a scapegoat for downing of flight MH17 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ukraine-crisis-mh17-malaysia/malaysian-pm-says-russia-being-made-a-scapegoat-for-downing-of-flight-mh17-idUSKCN1TL0OW |accessdate=5 July 2019 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Proposed international tribunal====\nIn June 2015, the Netherlands, supported by the other JIT members, sought to create an international tribunal to prosecute those suspected of downing the Malaysian airliner, which would take up the case after the closing of the criminal investigation. The Dutch hoped that an international tribunal would induce Russian cooperation, which was considered critical.<ref>{{cite news |title=Exclusive: International tribunal looks like best chance for MH17 justice \u2013 Dutch sources |agency=Reuters |date=23 June 2015 |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/06/23/us-ukraine-crisis-mh-idUSKBN0P326E20150623 |first=Anthony |last=Deutsch |accessdate=25 June 2015}}</ref> In late June 2015, the Russian government rejected a request by the five countries on the investigative committee to form a UN tribunal which would try those responsible for the shooting down of the aircraft, calling it \"not timely and counterproductive.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/jun/26/russia-rejects-calls-for-un-tribunal-malaysia-airlines-flight-mh17 |title=Russia rejects calls for UN tribunal to prosecute MH17 suspects |work=The Guardian |agency=Agence France-Presse |accessdate=28 June 2015 |date=26 June 2015}}</ref> On 8 July 2015, Malaysia, a member of the [[UN Security Council]], distributed a draft resolution to establish such a tribunal. This resolution was jointly proposed by the five JIT member countries. Russian UN Ambassador [[Vitaly Churkin]] responded, \"I don't see any future for this resolution. Unfortunately, it seems that this is an attempt to organize a grandiose, political show, which only damages efforts to find the guilty parties.\"<ref name=churkin>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/malaysia-airlines-mh17-russia-rebukes-push-for-un-tribunal-1.3146029 |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17: Russia rebukes push for UN tribunal |date=10 July 2015 |publisher=[[CBC News]] |accessdate=10 July 2015}}</ref> Russia later circulated a rival resolution which criticised the international investigation's lack of \"due transparency\" and demanded those responsible be brought to justice, but which did not call for a tribunal.<ref>{{cite news|title=Russia's UN Draft on MH17 Crash Doesn't Call for Tribunal |url=http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/russias-draft-mh17-crash-call-tribunal-32575088 |agency=Associated Press |date=20 July 2015 |author=Edith M. Lederer |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722201823/http://abcnews.go.com/US/wireStory/russias-draft-mh17-crash-call-tribunal-32575088 |archivedate=22 July 2015 }}</ref> In a vote, Malaysia's resolution gained majority support of the UNSC, but was [[United Nations Security Council veto power|vetoed]] by Russia.<ref name=veto>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/07/29/us-ukraine-crisis-mh17-un-idUSKCN0Q32GS20150729 |title=Russia vetoes bid to set up tribunal for downed Flight MH17 |author=Michelle Nichols |agency=Reuters |date=29 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Criminal prosecution====\nIn a statement made on 5 July 2017 by the Dutch Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Bert Koenders]], it was announced that the JIT countries would prosecute any suspects identified in the downing of flight MH17 in the Netherlands and under Dutch law.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.government.nl/latest/news/2017/07/05/statement-by-the-minister-of-foreign-affairs-on-mh17-5-july-2017 |title=Statement by the minister of Foreign Affairs on MH17, 5 July 2017 |work=Government of the Kingdom of the Netherlands |agency=Ministry of Foreign Affairs |date= 7 July 2017}}</ref> A treaty between the Netherlands and Ukraine made it possible for the Netherlands to prosecute in the cases of all 298 victims, regardless of their nationality. This treaty was signed on 7 July 2017,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.government.nl/topics/mh17-incident/news/2017/07/07/minister-of-security-and-justice-signs-mh17-treaty-with-ukraine |title=Minister of Security and Justice signs MH17 treaty with Ukraine |work=Government of the Kingdom of the Netherlands |agency=Ministry of Security and Justice |date= 7 July 2017}}</ref> and went into force on 28 August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://zoek.officielebekendmakingen.nl/trb-2018-162.HTML|title=Verdrag tussen het Koninkrijk der Nederlanden en Oekra\u00efne inzake internationale juridische samenwerking met betrekking tot misdrijven die verband houden met het neerhalen van vlucht MH17 van Malaysia Airlines op 17 juli 2014|date=7 September 2018|website=Tractatenblad van het Koninkrijk der Nederlanden}}</ref> On 21 March 2018, the Dutch government sent legislation to the parliament, allowing the suspects involved to be prosecuted in the Netherlands under [[Law of the Netherlands|Dutch law]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-21/legislation-clears-way-for-mh17-trials-in-the-netherlands|title=Legislation Clears Way for MH17 Trials in the Netherlands|agency=[[Associated Press]]|date=21 March 2018|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=22 March 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.unian.info/world/10052111-dutch-court-may-be-allowed-to-prosecute-those-involved-in-mh17-crash-by-video-link.html|title=Dutch court may be allowed to prosecute those involved in MH17 crash by video link|agency=[[Ukrainian Independent Information Agency|UNIAN]]|access-date=13 April 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 June 2019, the [[Dutch Public Prosecution Service]] charged four people with murder in connection with the shooting down of the aircraft: three Russians, [[Igor Strelkov (officer)|Igor Girkin]], Sergey Dubinsky, and Oleg Pulatov, and one Ukrainian, Leonid Kharchenko. International arrest warrants were issued in respect of each of the accused.<ref name=\"BBC48691488\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-48691488|title=Four charged with shooting down MH17 plane|work=BBC News Online|accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref> One of the suspects, Lieutenant Colonel Oleg Pulatov, expressed his intention to join the legal process by being represented in court. The trial began on 9 March 2020, with none of the accused in attendance.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-polytics/2868589-netherlands-public-prosecution-service-brings-charges-against-four-suspects-in-mh17-case.html|title=Netherlands Public Prosecution Service brings charges against four suspects in MH17 case|date=3 February 2020|work=Ukrinform|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ukrinform.net/rubric-polytics/2863987-one-of-suspects-in-mh17-case-wants-to-join-legal-proceedings.html|title=One of suspects in MH17 case wants to join legal proceedings|date=4 February 2020|work=Ukrinform|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/mh17-trial-start-accused-facing-murder-charges-200309000652546.html|title=MH17 trial starts with four accused facing murder charges|date=9 March 2020|work=Al Jazeera|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref> Igor Girking gave an interview to an independent journalist Graham Phillips. In this interview, Girkin said that he would not attent the trial because he did not recognize that the court had jurisdiction over Russian citizens. He said that he was not involved in the shootdown, and that he considered the government of Ukraine responsible for the loss of life in the shootdown, because \"only a moron or a criminal would send an airliner into a zone of active hostilities\".<ref>{{Cite news|last=Phillips|first=Graham|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5dArwTCTWfY|title=MH17: Igor Girkin / Strelkov Response to MH17 Accusations|date=2019-06-19|work=|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019 SBU arrested Vladimir Tsemakh, head of air-defence in DPR-controlled Snizhne during the attack on MH17. [[Bellingcat]] described him as an important eye-witness to the events surrounding the downing of flight MH17. Bellingcat analysed his possible role and said that a video showed Tsemakh making \"what appears to be a damning admission to his personal involvement in hiding the Buk missile launcher in the aftermath of its use on 17 July 2014\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2019/07/09/the-arrest-of-vladimir-tsemakh-and-its-implications-for-the-mh17-investigation/|title=The Arrest of Vladimir Tsemakh and Its Implications for the MH17 Investigation|date=9 July 2019|website=bellingcat|language=en-GB|access-date=31 August 2019}}</ref> In August 2019 Russia reportedly added Tsemakh to its list in a previously agreed exchange of prisoners of war with Ukraine. In an article, ''The Insider'' website commented on Russia's motives in requesting the exchange of a Ukrainian citizen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theins.ru/politika/173069|title=\u041a\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043b\u044c \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043b \"\u0441\u0432\u043e\u0438\u043c\" \u0432\u043e\u0434\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044f \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\u0430\" \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u0426\u0435\u043c\u0430\u0445\u0430 \u0438 \u0442\u0440\u0435\u0431\u0443\u0435\u0442 \u043e\u0431\u043c\u0435\u043d\u044f\u0442\u044c \u0435\u0433\u043e \u043d\u0430 \u0421\u0435\u043d\u0446\u043e\u0432\u0430|date=30 August 2019|website=The Insider|language=ru-RU|access-date=31 August 2019}}</ref> On 4 September 2019, an appeals court in Kiev ruled to release Tsemakh.<ref name=MoscowTimes20190907>{{cite news|url=https://www.themoscowtimes.com/2019/09/07/signaling-readiness-for-thaw-russia-and-ukraine-swap-prisoners-a67090|title=Signaling Readiness for Thaw, Russia and Ukraine Swap Prisoners: The exchange brings peace talks between the neighboring countries closer, analysts say.|newspaper=[[The Moscow Times]]|last=Gershkovich|first=Evan|date=7 September 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> On 7 September 2019, Volodymyr Tsemakh was released during a Ukraine-Russia prisoner exchange.<ref name=CNN20190907>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/09/07/europe/ukraine-russia-prisoner-swap-intl/index.html|title=Film director Oleg Sentsov and MH17 suspect among those freed in Russia-Ukraine prisoner swap|work=[[CNN]]|last1=Lapin|first1=Denis|last2=Pavlova|first2=Olga|last3=Britton|first3=Bianca|last4=Dean|first4=Sarah|date=7 September 2019|access-date=7 September 2019}}</ref> According to the [[List of Ministers of Foreign Affairs of the Netherlands|Dutch Foreign Minister]] [[Stef Blok]], the exchange had been delayed for a week so that Vladimir Tsemakh could be questioned by the Dutch Public Prosecution Service as a witness about the events surrounding the downing of flight MH17.<ref name=CNN20190907/> The [[Dutch Prime Minister]] [[Mark Rutte]], the [[List of Ministers of Justice of the Netherlands|Minister of Justice and Security]] [[Ferdinand Grapperhaus|Ferd Grapperhaus]], the JIT, and Blok added that the Netherlands regretted Tsemakh, who is a 'person of interest', being included in the exchange due to pressure on Ukraine from Russia.<ref name=MoscowTimes20190907/><ref name=CNN20190907/><ref>{{cite news| last1=Olearchyk| first1=Roman | last2=Foy| first2=Henry| url=https://www.ft.com/content/1cf7478e-cfbf-11e9-99a4-b5ded7a7fe3f| title=Ukraine court releases man of interest to MH17 probe on bail: Move raises speculation he could be part of imminent prisoner swap between Kiev and Moscow| work=[[Financial Times]]| date=5 September 2019| access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=AD20190907>{{cite news| url=https://www.ad.nl/buitenland/nederland-vraagt-rusland-om-mh17-verdachte~a953df4d/| title=Nederland vraagt Rusland om MH17-verdachte: Het Openbaar Ministerie heeft Rusland gevraagd MH17-verdachte Vladimir Tsemach uit te leveren. Dat liet het OM de nabestaanden van de vliegramp vanmiddag weten. Nederland betreurt zeer dat Oekra\u00efne de Oekra\u00efense separatist \u00fcberhaupt aan Rusland heeft overgedragen| trans-title=The Netherlands asks Russia for MH17 suspect: The Public Prosecution Service has asked Russia to extradite MH17 suspect Vladimir Tsemach. The OM informed the relatives of the plane crash this afternoon. The Netherlands deeply regrets that Ukraine has handed over the Ukrainian separatist to Russia at all.| work=[[Algemeen Dagblad|AD.nl]]| language=Dutch| date=7 September 2019| access-date=13 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dutch did question MH17 witness before he was returned to Russia: minister |url=https://www.dutchnews.nl/news/2019/09/dutch-did-question-mh17-witness-before-he-was-returned-to-russia-minister/ |accessdate=9 September 2019 |work=DutcNews.nl |date=8 September 2019}}</ref> Others including Chairman Piet Ploeg of Stichting Vliegramp MH17 which is the organization of the victims' relatives called the release of Tsemach \"unacceptable\".<ref name=AD20190907/> The Dutch Public Prosecution Service (OM) requested that Tsemach, who is not a Russian citizen, be extradited from Russia to the Netherlands.<ref name=AD20190907/> On 14 November 2019 the JIT published a new witnesses appeal and simultaneously released a number of recorded conversations of rebel leaders. JIT was particularly interested in \"the command structure and the role that Russian government officials may have played.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=MH17 Witness Appeal November 2019 |url=https://www.politie.nl/themas/flight-mh17/witness-appeal-crash-mh17.html |website=politie.nl |accessdate=14 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=MH17 disaster: Phone-taps 'show Russia directed Ukraine rebels' |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-50419669 |accessdate=15 November 2019 |work=BBC News |date=14 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nA number of witness statements, especially from the DPR armed forces, were presented anonymously due to fear of reprisal from Russia.<ref name=\":3\" /> Although the Russian secret service attempted to hack into the Malaysian [[Attorney General of Malaysia|Attorney-General]]'s office, investigation files of the [[Australian Federal Police]] and offices at The Hague, prosecutors say the identities of the witnesses still remain secure.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theaustralian.com.au/world/russians-hacked-our-mh17-evidence-dutch-court-hears/news-story/d61101fd4f37f261ba63dedf07627c3d|title=Russians hacked our MH17 evidence, Dutch court hears}}</ref>\n\n==British ISC report==\nOn 20 December 2017, the [[Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament|Intelligence and Security Committee]] of the UK Parliament published its annual report. It contains a short section entitled \"Russian objectives and activity against UK and allied interests\" which quotes MI6 as stating: \"Russia conducts information warfare on a massive scale... An early example of this was a hugely intensive, multichannel propaganda effort to persuade the world that Russia bore no responsibility for the shooting down of [Malaysian Airlines flight] MH-17 (an outright falsehood: we know beyond any reasonable doubt that the Russian military supplied and subsequently recovered the missile launcher)\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Toler|first1=Aric|title=British Intelligence Report Confirms Russian Military Origin of MH17 Murder Weapon|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2017/12/20/british-intelligence-report-confirms-russian-military-origin-mh17-murder-weapon/|website=Bellingcat|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=ISCP Annual Report 2016-2017|url=https://b1cba9b3-a-5e6631fd-s-sites.googlegroups.com/a/independent.gov.uk/isc/files/2016-2017_ISC_AR.pdf?attachauth=ANoY7cqS8WVJqzXucCjkPcD1PkT4M4RJspBV9tHBYEJAZLobTFw2rG67hpLh55zoZsZ9_9Xrmtqiq4CzbwmhAUpzCTh3AW-lBjOdmWFYJds1-EYzBgJGRmPWubVpg_Yl0SrMUrYTcKGn-8HtPvf5AARiu60msxtT2SpjJfdv78EEeqkINZBUythVem1KHFtKbbziZLQNdiiOymaCinv1pUa1FIpSVaHOkjNwmyfFteiMvnTRX00Qz_0%3D&attredirects=0}}</ref>\n\n==Civil cases==\nIn July 2015 a writ was filed in an American court by families of 18 victims accusing the separatist leader Igor Girkin of \"orchestrating the shootdown\" and the Russian government of being complicit in the act. The writ was brought under the [[Torture Victim Protection Act of 1991]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/11742865/MH-17-Russian-separatist-leader-sued-for-900-million-by-crash-victims.html]. MH-17-Russian-separatist-leader-sued-for-900-million-by-crash-victims</ref> In May 2016 families of 33 victims of the crash filed a claim against Russia and president Vladimir Putin in the [[European Court of Human Rights]], arguing Russian actions violated the passengers' right to life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-36350520|title=MH17 crash: Victims' families sue Putin and Russia|website=BBC News|access-date=22 May 2016}}</ref><ref>Blakkarly, Jarni (22 May 2016). [http://in.reuters.com/article/australia-mh-idINL3N18J00O UPDATE 1-Australian firm names Russia, Putin in MH17 compensation claim -report.] ''Reuters.'' Retrieved: 22 May 2016.</ref> A group of 270 relatives of Dutch victims joined the claim in May 2018 after the JIT concluded that Russia was involved.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2233480-nabestaanden-mh17-naar-europees-hof-voor-schadeclaim-tegen-rusland.html|title=Nabestaanden MH17 naar Europees Hof voor schadeclaim tegen Rusland|work=NOS|access-date=30 May 2018|date=25 May 2018|language=Dutch}}</ref> In July 2016, Malaysia Airlines was sued in Malaysia by 15 passengers' families in two separate writs, each brought under the [[Montreal Convention]], arguing that the airline should not have chosen that route.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.themalaymailonline.com/malaysia/article/mh17-kin-sue-malaysia-airlines-seek-damages-ahead-of-lawsuit-deadline|title=MH17 kin sue Malaysia Airlines, seek damages ahead of lawsuit deadline|author=Yap Tzu Ging|date=15 July 2016|newspaper=Malay Mail Online}}</ref> A month earlier, a separate lawsuit was brought by the families of 6 crew members who alleged negligence and breach of contract by the airline.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/world/missing-malaysia-plane-crew-lawsuit-1.3612177|title=Malaysia Airlines sued by relatives of MH17 crew shot down over Ukraine|agency=The Associated Press|date=2 June 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Reactions==\n{{main|International reactions to the Malaysia Airlines Flight 17 shootdown}}\n<!--PLEASE DON'T ADD ANY PICTURES OF WORLD LEADERS IN THIS SECTION A/P TALK PAGE DISCUSSION AND ARCHIVES-->\n<!-- Please don't add \"condolences\" per WP:MEMORIAL. Please don't add tiny flags or bullet points; consensus is that it is better as prose. Thanks. -->\n\n===Countries===\nUkrainian President [[Petro Poroshenko]] called the crash the result of an act of terrorism, and also called for an international investigation into the crash.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10974784/Malaysia-Airlines-crash-President-Poroshenko-calls-shooting-down-of-Malaysian-plane-an-act-of-terrorism.html |work=The Daily Telegraph |title=Malaysia Airlines crash: President Poroshenko calls shooting down of Malaysian plane an 'act of terrorism' |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nMalaysian Deputy Foreign Minister [[Hamzah Zainuddin]] said that the foreign ministry would be working with the Russian and Ukrainian governments with regard to the incident.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.cri.cn/12394/2014/07/18/2941s836537.htm |title=Malaysia to Work with Russia, Ukrainian Governments on MH17 |publisher=English.cri.cn |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Prime Minister [[Najib Razak]] said that Malaysia was unable yet to verify the cause of the crash but that, if the airplane was shot down, the perpetrators should be swiftly punished.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.voanews.com/east-asia/malaysian-pm-demands-swift-justice-if-plane-was-shot-down |title=Malaysian PM Demands Swift Justice if Plane Was Shot Down |publisher=[[Voice of America]] |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref> The [[Government of Malaysia|Malaysian government]] flew the [[Flag of Malaysia|national flag]] at [[half-mast]] from 18 July until 21 July.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stasiareport.com/news/asia/south-east-asia/story/malaysia-airlines-mh17-crash-flags-fly-half-mast-over-next-three-day |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 crash: Flags to fly at half-mast over next three days, says Najib |author=Yong Yen Nie |publisher=Straits Times Asia Report |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Nederlandse vlag halfstok voor stadhuis Hoorn.jpg|thumb|upright|Flag at half mast in front of [[Hoorn]] city hall during the national day of mourning on 23 July]]\n\nDutch Prime Minister [[Mark Rutte]] and King [[Willem-Alexander]] voiced their shock at the crash,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.telegraaf.nl/binnenland/22867019/__Verklaring_Rutte_over_MH17__.html |title=Verklaring premier Rutte over crash MH17 &#124; Binnenland |language=Dutch |work=De Telegraaf |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://dc.the-netherlands.org/news/2014/07/statement-king-willem-alexander.html |title=Statement of His Majesty King Willem-Alexander on Malaysian Flight MH17 |work=Kingdom of the Netherlands |publisher=The Netherlands Embassy in Washington, D.C., United States |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718002846/http://dc.the-netherlands.org/news/2014/07/statement-king-willem-alexander.html |archive-date=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and Minister of Foreign Affairs [[Frans Timmermans]] joined the Dutch investigation team sent to Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/2668/Buitenland/article/detail/3691806/2014/07/18/Timmermans-mee-met-onderzoekers-naar-Oekraine.dhtml |title=Timmermans mee met onderzoekers naar Oekra\u00efne |language=Dutch |work=ANP |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Dutch government buildings flew the flag at half-mast on 18 July.<ref name=\"nieuws.nl\">{{cite web |url=http://nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140717/vlaggen-overheidsgebouwen-halfstok-na-vliegramp/ |title=Vlaggen overheidsgebouwen halfstok na vliegramp |language=Dutch |author=Novum |publisher=Nieuws.nl |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140726214011/http://www.nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140717/Vlaggen-overheidsgebouwen-halfstok-na-vliegramp |archive-date=26 July 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Music was cancelled and festivities were toned down on the last day of the [[Nijmegen Marches]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140718/vierdaagse-nijmegen-muziek-geschrapt-wegens-vliegramp/ |title=Vierdaagse Nijmegen: muziek geschrapt wegens vliegramp |language=Dutch |author=Novum |publisher=nieuws.nl |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402114956/http://nieuws.nl/algemeen/20140718/vierdaagse-nijmegen-muziek-geschrapt-wegens-vliegramp/ |archive-date=2 April 2015 |url-status=dead}}</ref> On 21 July the Netherlands opened a war crimes investigation on the downing of the aircraft and a Netherlands public prosecutor went to Ukraine as part of this investigation. Rutte threatened tough action against Russia if it did not help in the investigation.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/netherlands-opens-investigation-airliner-shoot-down-131650202.html |title=Netherlands opens war crimes investigation into airliner downing |author1=Thomas Escritt |author2=Angus MacSwan |date=21 July 2014 |website=[[Yahoo! News]]}}</ref> On the same day, Timmermans spoke at the UN Security Council Meeting, after the Council had unanimously condemned the shooting down of MH17.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2014/07/22/terugluisteren-en-lezen-de-bewogen-speech-van-timmermans-a1423587|title=Terugluisteren en -lezen: de indrukwekkende speech van Timmermans |author=Marije Willems |date=22 July 2014 |website=[[NRC Handelsblad|NRC]]}}</ref> An increase in negative emotions and somatic complaints was observed in the Dutch population during the first four days after the MH17 crash.<ref>{{Cite journal |author= Jeronimus|display-authors=etal| year = 2018 | title = Acute stress responses after indirect exposure to the MH17 airplane crash| journal = British Journal of Psychology| volume = 0 | pages = 1\u201324 | doi=10.1111/bjop.12358| doi-access = free}}</ref>\n\nAustralian Prime Minister [[Tony Abbott]] said in an address to parliament that the aircraft was downed by a missile which seemed to have been launched by Russian-backed rebels.<ref name=DT>{{cite news |last1=Maiden |first1=Samantha |title=MH17: Russia says Tony Abbott 'operating only on speculation' in his tough stance over separatist involvement in plane tragedy |url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/news/nsw/mh17-russia-says-tony-abbott-operating-only-on-speculation-in-his-tough-stance-over-separatist-involvement-in-plane-tragedy/story-fni0cx12-1226994356506 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=Australia |date=19 July 2014}}</ref> [[Julie Bishop]], the Australian Minister for Foreign Affairs, said in an interview on an Australian television programme that it was \"extraordinary\" that her Russian counterparts had refused to speak to her over the shootdown after the Russian ambassador was summoned to meet her.<ref name=DT/> The Russian government was critical of Abbott's response; Abbott was one of the first world leaders to publicly connect the shootdown to Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-19/russia-says-abbott-comments-mh17-downing-unacceptable/5608852?pfm=ms |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17: Russia says Tony Abbott's comments blaming separatists are 'unacceptable', Julie Bishop criticises Moscow for lack of talks \u2013 ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> Abbott later criticised the recovery efforts as \"shambolic\", and \"more like a garden clean-up than a forensic investigation\"; Bishop publicly warned separatist forces against treating the victims' bodies as hostages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-07-21/government-considers-declaring-mh17-disaster-a-terrorist-act/5610908?pfm=ms |title=MH17: Prime Minister Tony Abbott hits out at 'shambolic' recovery effort; Government considers listing outrage as terrorist act; rebels move bodies to refrigerated train \u2013 ABC News (Australian Broadcasting Corporation) |publisher=Australian Broadcasting Corporation |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> Abbott also said in an interview on 13 October 2014, in anticipation of Russia's President [[Vladimir Putin]]'s attendance at the [[2014 G20 Brisbane summit|2014 G20 summit]], scheduled for mid-November 2014 in [[Brisbane]], Australia: \"Australians were murdered. They were murdered by Russian-backed rebels using Russian-supplied equipment. We are very unhappy about this.\"<ref>{{cite news |author1=Sabra Lane |title=Tony Abbott promises to 'shirtfront' Putin at G20 Summit |url=http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2014/s4106143.htm |accessdate=14 October 2014 |work=7:30 |date=13 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nRussian President Putin said that Ukraine bore responsibility for the incident which happened in its territory, which he said would not have happened if hostilities had not resumed in the south-east of Ukraine.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://ria.ru/society/20140718/1016472533.html|script-title=ru:\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d: \u0437\u0430 \u0430\u0432\u0438\u0430\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0443 \u043d\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0442 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0430 |trans-title=Putin: Ukraine responsible for the crash |language=Russian |date=18 July 2014 |agency=RIA Novosti |quote=\"\u0411\u0435\u0437\u0443\u0441\u043b\u043e\u0432\u043d\u043e, \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e, \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0442\u0435\u0440\u0440\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0435\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0433\u043e \u044d\u0442\u043e \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u043e\u0448\u043b\u043e, \u043d\u0435\u0441\u0435\u0442 \u043e\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u0437\u0430 \u044d\u0442\u0443 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0448\u043d\u0443\u044e \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0433\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044e\", \u2013 \u0441\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u043b \u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u0420\u0424 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"biden\">{{cite news |url=https://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/biden-malaysia-airlines-crash |publisher=MSNBC |title=Joe Biden: Malaysia Airlines flight 'apparently' shot down |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> He also said that it was important to refrain from reaching hasty conclusions and politicised statements before the end of the investigation. He said that Russia would help an international inquiry led by the ICAO.<ref name=RT-live>{{cite news |title=Malaysia Airlines MH17 plane crash in Ukraine LIVE UPDATES |url=http://rt.com/news/173628-malaysian-plane-crash-ukraine/ |accessdate=21 July 2014 |publisher=RT |date=17 July 2014}}</ref> At the end of July a [[Duma]] deputy [[Ilya Ponomarev]] said in an interview for ''[[Die Welt]]'' that the separatists had shot down the airplane by mistake and that Putin now realised he had supplied the weapon to the \"wrong people\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.welt.de/politik/ausland/article130579514/Putin-realisiert-dass-er-die-Falschen-bewaffnete.html |title=Putin realisiert, dass er die Falschen bewaffnete |work=Die Welt |language=German |date=26 July 2014 |accessdate=1 August 2014 |author=Silke M\u00fclherr und Inga Pylypchuk}}</ref> The [[Danish Institute for International Studies]] has pointed out to the similarities of Russian reaction to the downing of [[Korean Air Lines Flight 007|Korean Airlines flight KAL-007]] in 1983 where the USSR initially denied any involvement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pure.diis.dk/ws/files/950041/DIIS_RP_2017_6_web.pdf|title=Russian Hybrid Warfare|website=Danish Institute for International Studies|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170824221700/http://pure.diis.dk/ws/files/950041/DIIS_RP_2017_6_web.pdf|archive-date=24 August 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nUnited States President [[Barack Obama]] said the United States would help determine the cause.<ref name=\"telegraph\"/> In a press statement, White House spokesman [[Josh Earnest]] called for an immediate ceasefire in Ukraine to allow for a full investigation.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mason |first1=Jeff |last2=Holland |first2=Steve |title=White House urges Ukraine ceasefire for plane probe, Obama talks to Putin |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/18/us-ukraine-crisis-obama-idUSKBN0FN0D420140718 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |agency=Reuters |date=18 July 2014}}</ref> Vice-President [[Joe Biden]] said the airplane appeared to have been deliberately shot down, and offered American assistance for the investigation into the crash.<ref name=\"biden\"/> [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations|American&nbsp;Ambassador to the United Nations]] [[Samantha Power]] called on Russia to end the war.<ref name=nytimes1>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/19/world/europe/malaysia-airlines-plane-ukraine.html |title=Obama Points to Pro-Russia Separatists in Downing of Malaysia Airlines Plane |first=Michael D. |last=Shear |first2=Somini |last2=Sengupta |first3=Sabrina |last3=Tavernise |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> The British government requested an emergency meeting of the [[United Nations Security Council]] and called an emergency [[Cabinet Office Briefing Room|Cobra]] meeting after the incident.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Leonard |first1=Peter |title=Ukraine: 295 on Malaysia plane shot down over east |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/official-malaysian-plane-shot-down-over-ukraine |work=Associated Press |publisher=The Big Story |accessdate=17 July 2014 |ref=APBigStory |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717190514/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/official-malaysian-plane-shot-down-over-ukraine |archivedate=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10975874/MH17-plane-crash-David-Cameron-urges-those-responsible-for-downing-jet-to-be-held-to-account.html |title=MH17 plane crash: David Cameron urges those responsible for downing jet to be 'held to account' |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref> Chairman of the US [[Joint Chiefs of Staff]] [[Martin E. Dempsey]] said that instead of backing away from supporting the rebels in the wake of the airliner shootdown, Putin had \"taken a decision to escalate.\"<ref>David M. Herszenhorn (25 July 2014), [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/26/world/europe/russian-artillery-fires-into-ukraine-kiev-says.html ''Russia Steps Up Help for Rebels in Ukraine War,''] ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref>\n\n[[File:Nationaal Monument MH17.jpg|thumb|Memorial for the victims of Flight MH17 located in [[Vijfhuizen]], the Netherlands]]\n\nOn 17 July 2017, exactly three years after the crash, a [[memorial]] in memory of the victims was unveiled in [[Vijfhuizen]], the Netherlands. The opening of the memorial, which is located just outside Schiphol Airport, was attended by more than 2000 relatives of victims, King Willem-Alexander and his wife [[Queen M\u00e1xima of the Netherlands|Queen M\u00e1xima]], Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte, Minister of Security and Justice [[Stef Blok]] and the speakers of the Dutch Senate and House of Representatives. The memorial includes 298 trees, one tree for each victim.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nos.nl/artikel/2183659-onthulling-nationaal-monument-mh17-deze-dag-sloeg-een-gat-in-ons-leven.html |title=Onthulling Nationaal Monument MH17: 'Deze dag sloeg een gat in ons leven' |access-date=17 July 2019 |work=[[Nederlandse Omroep Stichting|NOS]] |date=17 July 2017 |language=Dutch}}</ref>\n\n===Organisations===\nOn 17 July the European Union's representatives [[Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso]] and [[Herman Van Rompuy]] released a joint statement calling for an immediate and thorough investigation.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://europa.eu/rapid/press-release_STATEMENT-14-231_en.htm?locale=en |title=EUROPA PRESS RELEASES \u2013 Press release \u2013 Joint statement by the President of the European Commission, Jos\u00e9 Manuel Barroso, and the President of the European Council, Herman Van Rompuy, on the crash of the Malaysian airliner in Ukraine |publisher=Europa (web portal) |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> The EU officials also said that Ukraine has first claim on the aircraft's black boxes.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/malaysian-plane-mh17-crash-investigators-face-struggle/1/373127.html |title=Malaysian plane MH17 crash investigators face struggle : Asia, News |work=India Today |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe [[International Civil Aviation Organization]] announced, on 18 July, that it was sending its team of experts to assist the [[National Bureau of Air Accidents Investigation of Ukraine]] (NBAAI), under Article 26 of the [[Convention on International Civil Aviation]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.icao.int/Newsroom/Pages/Ukraine-requests-ICAO-assistance-in-MH17-accident-investigation.aspx |title=Ukraine Requests ICAO Assistance in MH17 Accident Investigation |publisher=ICAO |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=20 July 2014}}</ref> The [[United Nations Security Council]] adopted [[United Nations Security Council Resolution 2166|Resolution 2166]] on 21 July, regarding an official crime investigation into the incident. On 24 July 2014 the ICAO issued a State Letter reminding signatory states of their responsibilities with respect to the safety and security of civil aircraft operating in airspace affected by conflict.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.icao.int/Newsroom/Pages/ICAO-clarifies-State-responsibilities-arising-from-conflict-zones.aspx |title=ICAO Clarifies State Responsibilities Arising from Conflict Zones |publisher=ICAO |date=24 July 2014 |accessdate=10 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Amsterdam Airport- Flight MH17 Memorial (14675744526).jpg|thumb|A makeshift memorial at [[Schiphol Airport]] for the victims of Flight MH17]]\nAfter the crash, memorial services were held in Australia<ref name=\"itv-memorial\">{{cite news |url=http://www.itv.com/news/update/2014-07-20/memorial-service-held-for-mh17-victims-in-australia/ |title=Australia mourns MH17 victims at memorial service |work=ITV News |date=20 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> and in the Netherlands, which declared 23 July, the day when the first victims arrived in the country, a [[national day of mourning]], the first since 1962.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nu.nl/binnenland/3834822/woensdag-23-juli-dag-van-nationale-rouw.html |title=Woensdag 23 juli dag van nationale rouw &#124; nu.nl/binnenland &#124; Het laatste nieuws het eerst op |publisher=Nu.nl |accessdate=22 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"ibt-mourning\">{{cite news |url=http://www.ibtimes.co.uk/netherlands-declares-national-day-mourning-mh17-victims-1457454 |title=Malaysian Airlines Flight MH17: Netherlands Declares National Day of Mourning For MH17 Victims |work=International Business Times |date=20 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> The opening ceremony of the AIDS 2014 conference, on 20 July, of which several delegates had been on board Flight MH17, began with a tribute to the victims of the crash.<ref name=\"starobserver\">{{cite news |url=http://www.starobserver.com.au/news/local-news/aids-2014-opening-ceremony-tinged-with-sombre-mood/125442 |title=AIDS 2014 opening ceremony tinged with sombre mood |first=Elias |last=Jahshan |work=Star Observer |date=20 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> In Malaysia, makeshift memorials were created in the capital city of [[Kuala Lumpur]].<ref name=\"bbc memorials\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-28397889 |title=MH17 crash: Malaysians mourn at makeshift memorials |work=BBC News |first=Sharanjit |last=Leyl |date=21 July 2014 |accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Russian media coverage==\n{{See also|Media portrayal of the Ukrainian crisis}}\nIn July 2014, shortly after the crash, the liberal Russian opposition newspaper ''[[Novaya Gazeta]]'' published a headline in Dutch that read \"Vergeef ons, Nederland\" (\"Forgive Us, Netherlands\").<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/world/russian-newspaper-novaya-gazeta-prints-frontpage-apology-for-mh17-disaster-in-dutch/story-fndir2ev-1227001958997|title=Russian newspaper Novaya Gazeta prints front-page apology for MH17 disaster in Dutch|date=25 July 2014|accessdate=25 July 2014|work=News.com.au}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.foreignpolicy.com/posts/2014/07/25/russian_paper_issues_front_page_apology_to_netherlands_for_mh17|title=Russian Paper Issues Front Page Apology to Netherlands for MH17|last1=Groll|first1=Elias|date=25 July 2014|website=Foreign Policy|accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nCoverage by Russian media has however differed from coverage in most other countries<ref>{{cite news |title=Russia offers alternate scenarios for Malaysia Airlines crash |url=http://www.upi.com/Top_News/World-News/2014/07/22/Russia-offers-alternate-scenarios-for-Malaysia-Airlines-crash/2701406045751/ |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=2 November 2014 |first=Ed |last=Adamczyk |agency=United Press International |quote=Russian media offers explanations conflicting with the information provided by the rest of the world.}}</ref> and has changed significantly over time.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ioffe |first1=Julia |title=The Russian Public Has a Totally Different Understanding of What Happened to Malaysia Airlines Flight 17: And it's more of a problem than you think |url=https://newrepublic.com/node/118782 |accessdate=21 July 2014 |work=New Republic |date=20 July 2014 |quote=The picture of the catastrophe that the Russian people are seeing on their television screens is very different from that on screens in much of the rest of the world, and the discrepancy does not bode well for a sane resolution to this stand-off |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140721015346/http://www.newrepublic.com/node/118782 |archive-date=21 July 2014 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> According to [[Bellingcat]], these changes have usually been in response to new evidence published by DSB and the investigation team.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2018/01/05/kremlins-shifting-self-contradicting-narratives-mh17/|title=The Kremlin's Shifting, Self-Contradicting Narratives on MH17 - bellingcat|date=5 January 2018|work=bellingcat|access-date=5 January 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the poll conducted by the [[Levada Center]] between 18 and 24 July in 2014, 80% of Russians surveyed believed that the crash of MH17 was caused by the Ukrainian military. Only 3% of respondents to the poll blamed the disaster on pro-Russian separatists in eastern Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.levada.ru/30-07-2014/katastrofa-boinga-pod-donetskom|title=\u041a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0430 \"\u0411\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430\" \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u043e\u043c|date=30 July 2014|publisher=Levada.ru|accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/30/mh17-vast-majority-russians-believe-ukraine-downed-plane-poll|title=MH17: vast majority of Russians believe Ukraine downed plane, poll finds|last1=Luhn|first1=Alec|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2 August 2014|agency=Guardian News and Media Limited}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/more-than-80-of-russians-blame-ukrainian-army-for-malaysia-airlines-crash/504333.html|title=More Than 80% of Russians Blame Ukrainian Army for MH17 Crash|work=The Moscow Times|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2017, the Russian portal ''The Insider'', the news agency [[McClatchyDC]], and Bellingcat performed a joint investigation that confirmed the identity of a high-rank military officer using a call-sign \"Dolphin\" to be colonel general Nikolai Fedorovich Tkachev. Tkachev is frequently heard in the wiretaps acquired by JIT supervising the operation of \"Buk\" delivery and set-up.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2017/12/08/russian-colonel-general-delfin/|title=Russian Colonel General Identified as Key MH17 Figure \u2013 bellingcat|date=8 December 2017|work=bellingcat|access-date=8 December 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcclatchydc.com/news/nation-world/world/article188720184.html|title=Russian general ID'd in activity around shootdown of Malaysian passenger jet|website=mcclatchydc|accessdate=30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Initial reactions and \"An-26 downing\" version ===\nOn the evening of the crash, the [[Life (news agency, Russia)|LifeNews]] portal released a statement from the separatists saying that a \"Ukrainian Air Force [[An-26]] transport plane\" had been shot down by a missile and crashed.<ref name=\"lifenews 136801\">{{cite news|script-title=ru:\u041e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0446\u044b \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043e \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442\u043e\u043c \u0410\u043d-26 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0435 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u044b |url=http://lifenews.ru/news/136801 |quote=On July 17 near the village of Rassypnoye over the Torez city in Donetsk region an An-26 transport plane of Ukrainian Air Force was taken down, said the militia. According to them, the plane crashed somewhere near the \"Progress\" mine, away from residential areas. According to one of the militias, at about 17:30 local time an An-26 flew over the city. It was hit by a rocket, there was an explosion and the plane went to the ground, leaving a black smoke. Debris fell from the sky |accessdate=17 July 2014 |date=17 July 2014 |language=Russian}}</ref> [[ITAR-TASS]] and [[RIA Novosti]] also reported that an An-26 had been shot down by the separatist militia near Torez at around 16:00 local time in what it described as \"yet another victory of DPR self-defence\".<ref name=\"tassan26\">{{cite news|title=Donetsk People's Republic militia downs another Ukraine's An-26 plane \u2013 eyewitnesses |url=http://en.itar-tass.com/world/741164 |accessdate=18 July 2014 |agency=[[Information Telegraph Agency of Russia]] |date=17 July 2014 |ref=TASS2 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RA3m6ZDd?url=http://en.itar-tass.com/world/741164 |archivedate=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=\u0422\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0410\u043d-26 \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0435 \u0423\u043a\u0440\u0430\u0438\u043d\u044b, \u0437\u0430\u044f\u0432\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0447\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0446\u044b |url=http://ria.ru/world/20140717/1016409306.html |website=ria.ru |agency=RIA Novosti |date=17 July 2014 |accessdate=13 October 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RR2Ynt9a?url=http://ria.ru/world/20140717/1016409306.html |archivedate=29 July 2014 }}</ref> Around the same time Leonid Kharchenko, who was responsible for the Buk launcher convoy through DPR, reported to his commander Sergei Dubinsky that the launcher is \"on the spot and has already downed one\" Ukrainian ground-attack plane.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2020/04/20/the-mh17-trial-part-1-new-materials-from-the-four-defendants/|title=The MH17 Trial Part 1: New Material From The Four Defendants|date=2020-04-20|website=bellingcat|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-21}}</ref>\n\nShortly after it became evident that it was a civilian aircraft which had crashed, the separatist media denied any responsibility and possession of anti-aircraft missiles capable of reaching the necessary altitude.<ref name=\"vk.com\">{{cite web |title=\u0421\u0432\u043e\u0434\u043a\u0438 \u043e\u0442 \u0421\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044f \u0418\u0432\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447\u0430 |url=http://vk.com/strelkov_info |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140717152222/http://vk.com/strelkov_info |archivedate=17 July 2014 |website=VKontakte |accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Arthur Bright\">{{cite web |url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Europe/2014/0717/Web-evidence-points-to-pro-Russia-rebels-in-downing-of-MH17-video |title=Web evidence points to pro-Russia rebels in downing of MH17 (+video) |author=Arthur Bright |date=17 July 2014 |website=[[The Christian Science Monitor]]}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\" />\n\n=== Conspiracy theories ===\nOn 18 July, Commander of the [[Donbass People's Militia]] [[Igor Strelkov (officer)|Igor Girkin]] was quoted as stating that \"a significant number of the bodies weren't fresh\". He followed up by saying \"Ukrainian authorities are capable of any baseness\"; and also claimed that blood serum and medications were found in the airplane's wreckage in large quantities.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.yahoo.com/rebel-leader-gives-bizarre-account-plane-crash-182256709.html|title=Rebel leader gives bizarre account of plane crash|date=18 July 2014|accessdate=18 July 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140721032149/http://bigstory.ap.org/article/rebel-suggests-malaysia-plane-victims-long-dead|archivedate=21 July 2014|url-status=dead|work=Yahoo! News|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Girkin also claimed that some of the passengers had died a few days before the crash.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rusvesna.su/news/1405676334|author=\u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044c \u0421\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0432|date=18 July 2014|publisher=RusVesna|language=Russian|script-title=ru:\u0418\u0433\u043e\u0440\u044c \u0421\u0442\u0440\u0435\u043b\u043a\u043e\u0432: \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0435\u0439 \u0438\u0437 \u0411\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430 \u0443\u043c\u0435\u0440\u043b\u0438 \u0437\u0430 \u043d\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u0441\u0443\u0442\u043e\u043a \u0434\u043e \u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0444\u044b|trans-title=Some of the Boeing's passengers died a few days before the crash|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6RBLozt4P?url=http://rusvesna.su/news/1405676334|archivedate=19 July 2014|url-status=live|accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe Russian government-funded<ref>{{cite news |last=Squires |first=Nick |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/ukraine/10976920/British-journalist-working-for-Russian-TV-resigns-over-bias-in-Ukraine-MH17-coverage.html |title=British journalist working for Russian TV resigns over bias in Ukraine MH17 coverage |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014}}</ref> outlet [[RT (TV network)|RT]] initially said that the airplane may have been shot down by Ukraine in a failed attempt to assassinate Vladimir Putin, in a plot which was organised by Ukraine's \"Western backers\". This was quickly dismissed as Putin's flight route was hundreds of kilometres north of Ukraine.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wyborcza.pl/1,75477,16347795,Moskwa_obwinia_Ukraine.html?piano_t=1 |title='Zamach na Putina', 'Ile odszkodowa\u0144 zap\u0142ac\u0105 Ukrai\u0144cy' i zmiany w Wikipedii. Ofensywa propagandowa Moskwy |language=Polish|trans-title=\"The attempt on Putin\", \"How much compensation will pay Ukrainians\" and changes in Wikipedia. Moscow's propaganda offensive |url-access=subscription  |work=Gazeta Wyborcza |date=18 July 2014 |accessdate=19 July 2014 |first=Wac\u0142aw |last=Radziwinowicz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.co.id/rt-malaysia-airlines-ukraine-2014-7/ |title=Here's The Ridiculous Way Russia's Propaganda Channel Is Covering The Malaysia Airlines Crash |last1=Szoldra |first1=Paul |website=Business Insider |date=18 July 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140720054152/http://www.businessinsider.co.id/rt-malaysia-airlines-ukraine-2014-7/ |archivedate=20 July 2014  }}</ref>\n\nOther conspiracy theories propagated by Russian media included that the Ukrainians shot down the airplane by mistake, drawing parallels to downing [[Siberia Airlines Flight 1812]] in 2001 (reported in July{{citation needed|date=November 2019}} and in December 2014<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-30597555 |title=MH17: Russia reveals 'witness' who blames Ukraine pilot |publisher=BBC |date=24 December 2014 |accessdate=27 December 2014}}</ref>); that Ukrainian air traffic controllers purposefully redirected the flight to fly over the war zone (proven false by the DSB investigation); and that the Ukrainian government organised the attack on the airplane to bring infamy upon the pro-Russian rebels.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.yahoo.com/russians-fed-conspiracy-theories-ukraine-crash-064400429.html |title=Russians Fed Conspiracy Theories on Ukraine Crash |work=Yahoo News |date=22 July 2014 |accessdate=22 July 2014 |first=Laura |last=Mills |agency=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref>\n\nThe number of alternative theories disseminated in Russian mass media started growing as the DSB and JIT investigations increasingly pointed towards the separatists.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://buran.ru/htm/mh17.htm|title=\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0447\u0435\u043c\u0443 \u043f\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0431 \u0440\u0435\u0439\u0441 \u041c\u041d17 \u043d\u0430\u0434 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0441\u043e\u043c? \u0411\u0440\u0438\u0444\u0438\u043d\u0433 \u041c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u044b \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|website=buran.ru|access-date=6 August 2016}}</ref> On 15 November 2014, Russia's [[Channel One Russia|Channel One]] reported on a supposedly leaked spy satellite photo which showed the airplane being shot from behind by a Ukrainian Su-25 fighter jet.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.1tv.ru/news/social/271864 |title=\u0421\u043d\u0438\u043c\u043e\u043a \u043c\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0439\u0437\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \"\u0411\u043e\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0430\", \u0441\u0431\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043f\u043e\u0434 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u0446\u043a\u043e\u043c, \u043e\u0431\u0441\u0443\u0436\u0434\u0430\u044e\u0442 \u0432\u043e \u0432\u0441\u0435\u043c \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0435 |date=15 November 2014 |website=Channel One Russia}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=Russia's Channel One show satellite photo evidencing MH17 was downed by fighter jet |work=TASS |date=14 November 2014 |accessdate=15 November 2014 |url=http://en.itar-tass.com/world/759835}}</ref> Many other Russian media reprinted the photo but its authenticity was immediately dismissed as the airplanes were out of scale which indicated poor copy-and-paste.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/world/sensational-russian-photo-of-mh17-being-shot-debunked-by-citizen-journalist-group-20141115-11nbqs.html |title='Sensational' Russian photo of MH17 being shot debunked by citizen journalist group |last=Miller |first=Nick |date=15 November 2014 |accessdate=15 November 2014 |newspaper=The Age}}</ref> Later it was disclosed, that the photo had been initially emailed to the Vice-President of the [[Russian Union of Engineers]] by a self-described aviation expert who had found it on a Russian online forum.<ref name=\"BUZZnov2014\">{{citation |title=Russian TV Airs Clearly Fake Image To Claim Ukraine Shot Down MH17 |first=Max |last=Seddon |date=15 November 2014 |accessdate=15 October 2014 |work=BuzzFeed |url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/maxseddon/russian-tv-airs-clearly-fake-image-to-claim-ukraine-shot-dow}}</ref> The aviation expert later apologised, saying that he was unhappy with how the information had been used.<ref name=\"BUZZnov2014\" /> In a later interview by magazine ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Channel One CEO [[Konstantin Ernst]] admitted that reporting on the satellite photo was a \"simple error\", saying that it was a human mistake not made on purpose.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/12/16/the-kremlins-creative-director|title=The Kremlin\u2019s Creative Director|date=9 December 2019|work=The New Yorker|first=Joshua|last=Yaffa|accessdate=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2014, Sara Firth, who had worked as a correspondent with RT for the previous five years, resigned in protest at the channel's coverage of the crash, which she described as \"lies\".<ref name=\"sarafirth\">{{cite news|url=http://www.news.com.au/travel/travel-updates/mh17-fallout-russian-reporter-sara-firth-quits-over-ukraine-lies/story-fnizu68q-1226994372531|title=MH17 fallout: Russian reporter Sara Firth quits over Ukraine 'lies'|date=28 March 2014|work=News.com.au|accessdate=21 July 2014}}</ref> RT said Firth had left to take another job.<ref name=\"ReporterResigns\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2014/jul/18/mh17-russia-today-reporter-resigns-sara-firth-kremlin-malaysia|title=Russia Today reporter resigns in protest at MH17 coverage|work=The Guardian|accessdate=18 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 Dutch newspaper ''[[NRC Handelsblad]]'' described how false stories about the MH17 crash had been propagated with the support of [[Christian Democratic Appeal]] politician [[Pieter Omtzigt]], who introduced a Russian-speaking Ukrainian man as an \"eyewitness\" to the crash on a public expert debate in May 2017. The man, who was an asylum-seeker from Ukraine, did not witness the crash and his speech, texted to him by Omtzigt prior to the interview, repeated the Russian-promoted version that Ukrainian jets downed the Boeing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2017/11/10/hoe-twijfel-rond-mh17-in-de-hand-wordt-gewerkt-13959091-a1580806|title=Hoe twijfel rond MH17 in de hand wordt gewerkt|work=NRC|access-date=13 November 2017|language=nl}}</ref>\n\n=== The \"Ukrainian Buk\" version ===\nIn May 2015, ''Novaya Gazeta'' published a report by \"a group of Russian military engineers\" that came to the conclusion that the airplane was shot down by a [[Buk missile system|Buk-M1 launcher]] with 9M38M1 missile. The authors also analysed the visible impact traces on the surface of the airplane and suggested that the missile could not have been fired from [[Snizhne]], but was instead fired from [[Zaroshchenske]] and claimed that a Ukrainian anti-air unit was located there at that time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.novayagazeta.ru/inquests/68332.html |title=\u042d\u0442\u043e \u0431\u044b\u043b \"\u0411\u0443\u043a-\u041c1\" |publisher=Novaya Gazeta |date=5 May 2015 |accessdate=5 May 2015 |trans-title=This was \"Buk-M1\"}}</ref> In June 2015, the report was the subject of a press conference and was attributed to Mikhail Malisevskiy, chief engineer at Moscow-headquartered [[Almaz-Antey]], the Buk missile manufacturer.<ref name=\"TheAgeAlmaz\">{{cite news |url=http://www.theage.com.au/world/mh17-plane-was-shot-down-by-a-buk-missile-russian-weapons-manufacturer-says-20150602-ghfdco.html |title=MH17 plane was shot down by a Buk missile, Russian weapons manufacturer says |author=Nick Miller |date=2 June 2015}}</ref> The [[Security Service of Ukraine]] said that there were inaccuracies in this version, and called part of the report a fake.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stopfake.org/sbu-novye-dokazatelstva-krusheniya-boeing-na-donbasse-osnovany-na-fejkovyh-snimkah/ |title=\u0421\u0411\u0423: \u041d\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0435 \"\u0434\u043e\u043a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\" \u043a\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f Boeing \u043d\u0430 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0441\u0441\u0435 \u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u044b \u043d\u0430 \u0444\u0435\u0439\u043a\u043e\u0432\u044b\u0445 \u0441\u043d\u0438\u043c\u043a\u0430\u0445 |date=6 May 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2015 |website= |publisher=StopFake.org|trans-title = SBU called the Russian analysis on Boeing based on fake photos}}</ref> Russian military expert Vadim Lukashevich argued on [[TV Rain]] that the spatial orientation of the rocket at the moment of explosion did not exclude the possibility that it was launched from Snizhne, as the report claimed. Lukashevich also noted that the report admitted a Buk missile as the cause of the crash, discrediting the previous theories about the crash (Su-25 etc.) circulated in Russian media.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://m.tvrain.ru/teleshow/here_and_now/ja_ne_uvidel_v_etom_doklade_ekspertov_vpk_aviatsio-386961/ |title=\u042f \u043d\u0435 \u0443\u0432\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043b \u0432 \u044d\u0442\u043e\u043c \u0434\u043e\u043a\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0435 \u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u041f\u041a\". \u0410\u0432\u0438\u0430\u0446\u0438\u043e\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0442 \u041b\u0443\u043a\u0430\u0448\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u043e \u0442\u043e\u043c, \u043a\u0442\u043e \u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043c \u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0438\u043b \u0434\u043e\u043a\u0443\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442, \u0440\u0430\u0437\u0434\u043e\u0431\u044b\u0442\u044b\u0439 \"\u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u043e\u0439 |date=6 May 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2015 |website= |publisher=TV Rain |last=Lukashevich |first=Vadim|trans-title = \"I haven't seen military experts in that report\", aviation expert Lukashevich who and why published the report leaked by Novaya Gazeta}}</ref> ''[[Ukrainska Pravda]]'' questioned claims about the Ukrainian anti-aircraft unit and stated that Zaroshchenske was under control of pro-Russian forces on the day of shootdown.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pravda.com.ua/news/2015/05/6/7066943/ |title=\u0417\u041c\u0406: \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0456\u0439\u0441\u044c\u043a\u0456 \u0435\u043a\u0441\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0442\u0438 \u0432 \u0441\u0435\u043a\u0440\u0435\u0442\u043d\u0456\u0439 \u0434\u043e\u043f\u043e\u0432\u0456\u0434\u0456 \u043f\u0456\u0434\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0434\u0438\u043b\u0438, \u0449\u043e \u0411\u043e\u0457\u043d\u0433 \u0437\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0437 \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\u0430\" |date=6 May 2015 |accessdate=6 May 2015 |website= |publisher=Ukrainska Pravda|trans-title = Media: Russian experts confirmed in secret report, that Boeing was shot by \"Buk\"}}</ref> ''Novaya Gazeta'' published a long analysis by Mark Solonin, also denying the Almaz-Antey version,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.novayagazeta.ru/inquests/68376.html |title=\u0421\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043c \u0442\u0440\u0430\u0435\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0438 |date=12 May 2015 |website=Novaya Gazeta |last=Solonin |first=Mark}}</ref> interviewed inhabitants of Zaroshchenske who denied claims that Ukrainian forces and Buk launchers were present in the village at that time.<ref>{{cite web |title=There Was No Buk in Our Field |url=http://www.interpretermag.com/there-was-no-buk-in-our-field/ |website=The Interpreter |accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u041d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0448\u0435\u043c \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0435 \"\u0411\u0443\u043a\u0430\" \u043d\u0435 \u0431\u044b\u043b\u043e. \u041d\u0438 \u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u0430 \u2013 \u043d\u0438 \u043e\u0442 \u0433\u0443\u0441\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0446, \u043d\u0438 \u043e\u0442 \u0432\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0441\u0438\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0430 |url=http://www.novayagazeta.ru/inquests/68728.html |accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref> According to [[Bellingcat]], Russia's satellite images were from June and showed signs of editing.<ref name=\"Bell150531\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bellingcat.com/news/uk-and-europe/2015/05/31/mh17-forensic-analysis-of-satellite-images-released-by-the-russian-ministry-of-defence/ |title=MH17 \u2013 Forensic Analysis of Satellite Images Released by the Russian Ministry of Defence |work=Bellingcat |date=31 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"DW150601\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dw.de/forensic-report-russia-faked-mh17-satellite-photos/a-18490259 |title=Forensic report: Russia faked MH17 satellite photos |first=Conor |last=Dillon |publisher=[[Deutsche Welle]] |date=1 June 2015}}</ref> ''[[Bild]]'' described the Russian satellite image as \"fake\".<ref name=\"Bild150508\">{{cite news |url=http://www.bild.de/politik/ausland/flug-mh-17/russische-beweise-gefaelscht-40861842.bild.html |title=BILD entlarvt falsche Satellitenaufnahme |language=German |trans-title= BILD exposes false satellite image |first=Julian |last=R\u00f6pcke |work=[[Bild]] |date=8 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 September 2018, Russia's Ministry of Defence held a press conference that aimed to cast doubt on Moscow's culpability for the tragedy. Lt. Gen. Nikolai Parshin, chief of the Missile and Artillery Directorate, said that after Dutch investigators displayed parts of the missile and their serial numbers, they studied and declassified archives at the research center that produced the Buk missiles. Parshin said the Russian archives show that the missile that was made of these parts was transported to a military unit in western Ukraine in 1986, and to Russia's knowledge never left Ukraine. Officials also claimed that video evidence presented by the Joint Investigation Team (JIT), in which the missile that allegedly shot down the airplane was shown being moved from Russia into Ukraine, was fabricated.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/aponline/2018/09/17/world/europe/ap-eu-russia-mh17.html |title= Russia: Missile That Shot Down Flight MH17 Was Ukrainian |date= 17 September 2018 |work= The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nJIT responded that it had requested details about recovered missile parts from Russia in May 2018, but had received no answer. It said, information from the Russian Ministry of Defence would be carefully studied as soon as the documents were made available, as requested in May 2018 and required by [[United Nations Security Council|UNSC]] in 2016. JIT stated it had always carefully analysed information provided by Russia, but information presented to the public was inaccurate on several points. Russia had given differing accounts over time of how MH17 was shot down; for example claiming to have evidence (radar images) that a Ukrainian fighter fired an air-to-air missile at MH17.<ref>{{cite news |title=MH17 crash: Dutch ask Russia to submit new claims |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-45546611 |accessdate=18 September 2018 |work=BBC News |date=18 September 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author= Landelijk Parket |title=Reaction JIT to press conference of Russian Ministry of Defense |url=https://www.om.nl/actueel/nieuwsberichten/@104053/reaction-jit-to/ |website=Openbaar Ministerie |accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Oleksandr Turchynov]], secretary of [[National Security and Defense Council of Ukraine]], said in September 2018 that Russia's claim was \"yet another failed fake report that the Kremlin made up in order to cover up their crime that has been proven by the official investigation as well as independent experts.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.newsweek.com/russian-propaganda-moscow-releases-audio-blaming-ukraine-downing-mh17-flight-1124371 |title= Russian propaganda? Moscow releases audio blaming Ukraine downing MH17 flight that killed almost 300 |date= 17 September 2018 |work= Newsweek}}</ref>\n\n==Maps==\n{{col-float|width=320px}}\n{{Location map many\n| Afro-Eurasia\n| relief      = 1\n| width       = 300\n| float       = none\n| caption     = Location of departure, crash site and destination\n| alt         = Location of crash site; departure and destination airports\n| <!--first label/marker-->\n| label1      = {{nowrap|Amsterdam Airport Schiphol}}\n| label1_size = <!-- or: label_size -->\n| position1   = <!-- or: position, pos1, pos -->\n| background1 = <!-- or: background, bg1, bg -->\n| mark1       = Green pog.svg\n| mark1size   =\n| link1       = <!-- or: link -->\n| lat1_deg    = 52\n| lat1_min    = 18\n| lat1_sec    = 29\n| lat1_dir    = N\n| lon1_deg    = 4\n| lon1_min    = 45\n| lon1_sec    = 51\n| lon1_dir    = E\n| <!--second label/marker-->\n| label2      = Crash site\n| label2_size =\n| position2   = bottom\n| background2 = <!-- or: bg2 -->\n| mark2       = Airplane Crash.svg\n| mark2size   = 10\n| link2       =\n| lat2_deg    = 48\n| lat2_min    = 8\n| lat2_sec    = 17\n| lat2_dir    = N\n| lon2_deg    = 38\n| lon2_min    = 38\n| lon2_sec    = 20\n| lon2_dir    = E\n| <!--third label/marker-->\n| label3      = {{nowrap|Kuala Lumpur}} {{nowrap|International Airport}}\n| label3_size =\n| position3   =\n| background3 = <!-- or: bg2 -->\n| mark3       =\n| mark3size   =\n| link3       =\n| lat3_deg    = 2\n| lat3_min    = 44\n| lat3_sec    = 36\n| lat3_dir    = N\n| lon3_deg    = 101\n| lon3_min    = 41\n| lon3_sec    = 53\n| lon3_dir    = E\n}}\n{{col-float-break|width=320px}}\n{{Location map many\n| Europe\n| relief      = 1\n| width       = 300\n| float       = none\n| caption     = Location of departure and crash site\n| alt         = Location of departure and crash site\n| <!--first label/marker-->\n| label1      = {{nowrap|Amsterdam Airport Schiphol}}\n| label1_size = <!-- or: label_size -->\n| position1   = <!-- or